<html><head></head>
<title>STRENGTHENING NON-FORMAL PRE-SCHOOLING AND CAREGIVER EDUCATION
WITHIN THE INTEGRATED CHILD DEVELOPMENT SERVICE</title>
<body>
<center><b>STRENGTHENING NON-FORMAL PRE-SCHOOLING<br>
AND CAREGIVER EDUCATION<br>
WITHIN THE INTEGRATED CHILD DEVELOPMENT SERVICE</b><br>
<p>
A CONSULTANT REPORT<p>
<p>
Prepared for the World Bank, and<p>
<p>
The Governnent of India, Ministry of<p>
Social Welfare, Women and Child Development Section<p>
<p>
by<p>
<p>
Robert G. Myers<p>
Cassie Landers<p>
<p>
of<p>
<p>
The Consultative Group on<p>
Early Childhood Care and Education<p>
<p>
New York, September, 1989</center><p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Preface</b><p>
<p>
	This report was prepared at the request of the World Bank as part of a mission
to assist the Government of India and concerned state governments in preparing
two projects for support by the IDA. The purpose of the projects under
discussion is to strengthen and expand the Integrated Child Development Service
(ICDS) in Andra Pradesh, Bihar, Madaya Pradesh, Orissa, and Tamil Nadu. The
specific purpose of our consultancy was to assist in the design of a project
component intended to improve the quality, efficiency, and effectiveness of pre-school
education within ICDS. That charge was broadened, in conversations with ICDS
and the Bank, to include discussion of ways to strengthen the education,
socialization, and stimulation dimensions of early childhood development for
children under age 3, in conjunction with the health and nutrition education
being provided for caregivers.<p>
<p>
	We would like to thank the staff of the Women and Child Development Section of
the Ministry of Social Welfare for taking time at a particularly busy moment to
discuss issues, and for facilitating conversations with others in New Delhi and
in Orissa (see Annexure 2 reporting on a visit to Orissa by Landers). Our
conversations were held with individuals in the GOI and in technical support
institutions (the National Institute of Public Cooperation and Child
Development -- NIPCCD; the National Council of Educational Research and Training -- NCERT; the Indian Council for Child Welfare -- ICCW);
with independent Indian scholars and practioners; and with individuals in
international assistance organizations (UNICEF, CARE, the Aga Khan foundation).
Annexure 1 lists the institutions and individuals with when we spoke during our
visit.<p>
<p>
	The comments that follow are not only based on what we saw and heard during
this visit, but also during previous visits to India. We have drawn as well on
our reading of manuals and of a portion of the extensive literature that exists
dealing with ICDS and the non-formal
pre-school/child development component. We hope that the reflections offered will be
constructive and well-informed,
and that they will serve as a basis for further discussion as the process
proceeds, of arriving at a specific set of proposals.<p>
<p>

							Robert Myers<p>
							Cassie Landers<p>

<p>
September 4, 1989<p>
<p>
<b>Introduction</b><p>
<p>
	Within a holistic view of child development, the ICDS seeks to "lay the
foundation for proper psychological, physical, and social development of the
child". In addition to reducing mortality,<p>
morbidity, and malnutrition, it seeks also to reduce school dropouts. In this
report, we will emphasize two components of ICDS directed toward achieving
these goals:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	  Non-formal
education for children ages 3 to 8, helping to prepare children mentally and
socially for school and for a changing world.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Family and community education for child care and development, helping to
increase their ability to provide stimulating and educative experiences
responding to psychological and social as well as health and nutritional needs
of their children, from birth to age 6, but particularly in the period from 0
to 3.</ul>
	Giving greater attention to stimulation, socialization, and education of the
young child through these components within ICDS is essential because:<p>
<p>
<ol>	1. Early months and years of a child's life are critical in formation of
intelligence, personality, and social behaviour.<p>
<p>
	2. Stimulation and education activities will affect health and nutrition as
well as cognitive and social developnent. An active, alert, inquisitive,
secure, and communicative child will be<p>
healthier, better nourished, and more likely to survive than a passive, inert,
reticent, insecure and uncommunicative child. He or she will also be more
likely to succeed in school and life.<p>
<p>
	3. Interventions combining education/stimulation with health and nutrition
activities can more significantly affect the development of a child and
readiness for schooling than any one of
these interventions applied in isolation.<p>
	4. Strengthening caregiver education and the non-formal
pre-school
component can help to improve the situation of "the girl child," affecting both
parental attitudes and the girl child's
preparation for schooling.</ol>
	With these justifications in mind, we will set out some general principles
providing a guide to actions, present the issues and concerns most often
mentioned as obstacles to strengthening both the pre-school
and parental education components, and discuss specific actions that were
mentioned as ways of helping to overcome these obstacles.<p>
<p>
	Rather than try to report separately on each of our visits and conversations,
we will incorporate ideas gleaned from them within the discussion of various
issues and actions, as appropriate. This general organization will be followed
first for the non-formal
pre-school
component, then for caregiver education.<p>
<p>
<b><center>Non-Formal Preschool Education</center></b><br>
<p>
	As might be expected in a system as large and varied as the ICDS, the non-formal
preschool service for children ages 3 to 6 functions well in some centres, in a
perfunctory way in many others, and barely at all in still others. According to
a pilot study of ICDS social components carried out by NIPCCD (Sharma, 1987)*,
a relatively high proportion of Anganwadi Centres (AWC) are perceived first as
feeding centres, with little or no attention given to the
non-formal
pre-school
education component. In some places, therefore, the first task of ICDS is to
build in the preschool component; in others it will be to strengthen the
component.<p>
<p>
	The apparent neglect of pre-schooling
by some communities and the generally weak condition of the component occurs in
spite of conditions that, in theory, should support and strengthen it. For
example:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 Many innovative demonstration projects have been carried out showing how the
preschool component might be strengthened, and repeated attempts have been made
to incorporate (sometimes successfully) the fruits of this experimentation into
the administrative guidelines and manuals of ICDS.  (NIPCCD, August, 1988)<p>
<p>
	 <li>There is a relatively high level of agreement among professionals concerning
the obstacles to proper implementation and about the form the preschool
component should take.</ul>

Moreover:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 The organization of non-formal
preschool education occupies a prominent place and is detailed in the
description of  job responsibilities and tasks of an AWW found in the
pre-service job training syllabus INIPCCD, 1989, pp. 3-11).<p>
<p>
	 <li>In the syllabus, 83 of 432 hours are scheduled for preschool education (p.
15). This compares favorably, for instance, with 94 hours for nutrition and
health activities, including nutrition and health education.<p>
<p>
	 <li>The preschool responsibility confers prestige on the AWW, allowing her to be
seen within the community as a "teacher."<p>
<p>
	 <li>When the AWW is questioned about what aspect of their work  she likes best, the pre-school
component is often identified as the most satisfying.</ul>
	Against this background, the problem, as we see it, is not so much to to invent
new possible solutions (most have been tried out somewhere), or to establish
new principles, or to identify issues, bottlenecks and obstacles (most of which
are known). Rather, operational solutions must be found to facilitate the
continuing translation of existing principles and knowledge and experience into
action at the local level, and to motivate people sufficiently to
act vigorously at various levels of the system. Accordingly, even though we
will cite principles, discuss issues, and comment on specific actions below,
the main challenge is organizational and
motivational.<p>
<p>
*Adarsh Sharma, Monitoring Social Components of Integrated Child Development
Services: A Pilot Project, New Delhi, NIPCCD, 1987, This study covered a sample
of  blocks, including tribal, rural and urban blocks. In addition to drawing on
records and reports available at the AWC, information was obtained from census
data of the project areas, a household survey, interviews with ICDS
functionaries, representatives of local organizations and community members,
and actual observation of programme implementation using an Observation
Proforma, The study contains a wealth of information about how AWCs are
actually organized and function, about the perceptions and actions of the AWWs,
supervisors, and CDPOs, and about such matters of interest as the distribution
of AWW time, the frequency of visits, the perceptions of beneficiaries, etc. We
have found the study very useful in broadening our own understanding of
the preschool components of ICDS.<p>
<p>
<b>Principles: Some areas of relative agreement</b><p>
<p>
	From conversations held with Indian professionals and practioners, a
relatively high degree of consensus appears suggesting that:<p>
<p>
<ul><li> A more interactive, participatory approach should permeate the non-formal
preschool component of the ICDS system based on the principle of guided
learning through active experience (whether at the level of the child or in the
training of functionaries) in which individuals are helped to construct their
own knowledge.<p>
<p>
	To achieve this shift, most of the people consulted thought it would be
necessary to continue the move away from a highly structured and directive
curricula for children, and away from an over-emphasis
on learning letters and numbers, to greater emphasis on learning basic concepts
through discovery  and play. It would be necessary, also, to move away
lecturing functionaries in time-bounded
programmes of pre-service
training and refresher courses with few links to daily practice, to a system of
continuous training and learning on the job, guided by
supervisor/facilitators.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Promoting imagination and creativity is a key to improving quality. In pre-school
education programmes, imagination and creativity, together with mastery of some
general principles of working with children and knowing how to take advantage
of existing materials in the environment are more important than providing a
particular set of toys and materials or mastering a specific curriculum.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Improving quality is more a matter of using AWW time more effectively than of
extending hours to be used for education and socialization activities.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Motivating functionaries at all levels is as important  improving their
competency in particular skills.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Flexibility and decentralization are crucial. The vast differences in
geography and culture within India require flexibility and variety in structure
as well as content, so that generic programme principles can be adapted to
local circumstances. This suggests a need to decentralize actions as much as
possible.</ul>

<b>Some Issues and Concerns</b><p>
<p>
	<b>Training and Supervision</b><p>
<p>
	Wherever our conversations began, they seemed to wind up with a disussion of
training/supervision. Therefore, more of this report will be devoted to
training and supervision (which we feel are inseperable) than to other issues
raised during these conversations. To help structure the discussion, we will
pose, and comment on several questions.<p>
<p>
	<b>1.  Who is to be trained?</b><p>
<p>
	This may be the most important question of all. The selection of individuals
for training will influence both the organization and content of training, and
will have an effect on the
outcomes of training as well.<p>
<p>
	During our visit, we heard a range of opinions about the selection of AWW.
NIPCCD's study of social components concluded that married AWW between the ages
of 25 and 44 years were less likely to turn over (and therefore to use the
training they receive). However, the fact that many women in this age range
have very young children and additional household responsibilities makes it
difficult to recruit them. The study also identified a positive
relationship between educational level and worker performance, A more
subjective opinion was that the most successful AW are those who are creative
and musically-inclined
and empathetic, regardless of their level of education.<p>
<p>
	In some places, AWW from tribal areas are trained in special programmes rather
than in the regular centres using the regular syllabus. This is at least in
part because of the generally lower
level of formal education of the tribal girls, but it is also related to other
cultural differences. Tribal groups have particular beliefs and child rearing
practices as well as forms of community
organization that should be respected and built upon in the training and
implementation of the programme.<p>
<p>
	As one moves up the ladder in the ICDS hierarchy to supervisors and CDPOs, a
major consideration for trainers is whether or not these individuals are
promoted from within the ICDS system or whether they come from outside and so
have not had previous exposure
to ICDS. To the extent that they are promoted, they will bring with them the
cumulative benefits of both experience and previous training. This would make
it easier to link training and practice.<p>
<p>
	An important implication of the above is that it may be necessary to relax
some qualifications in order to select motivated, creative, and empathetic
individuals, and to build a "career line" within ICDS allowing advancement for
those who show ability on the
job (regardless, for instance, of their formal educational qualifications).<p>
<p>
	Another issue related to the question of who should be trained was related to
the recognized value of joint training (see below). The ANM and the local dai,
and the helper should have some knowledge of the pre-school
component. Additional thought needs to be given to both the content and the
logistics of training these supportive individuals in ways that would allow
them to be more supportive of the AWW. For the most part, that probably means
incorporating them
into selected in-service
training sessions.<p>
<p>
	<b>2.  Who will do the training?</b><p>
<p>
	The 300-plus
institutions now charged with training the AWW are known to vary widely in the
quality and content of the training provided. We encountered some
dissatisfaction with the present system, related in part to structural
problems. Trainers have little job security (contracts are for one year) and
lack incentives. To provide greater security and incentives, a variety
of suggestions were made including the extension of contracts to five years,
holding periodic meetings and workshops for trainers, constructing residential
accomodations, and selecting trainers from within the system.<p>
<p>
	There is a tendency to turn to academic specialists for training, assuming
that they know better how non-formal
pre-schools
should be organized and run. This is reflected in the current
procedures for pre-service
training in which specialists on a particular theme are often brought in to
lecture on that particular topic. It is reflected in a desire by some to
involve university
faculties of social welfare, child development, and education more prominently
in the training.<p>
<p>
	At the same time, we constantly heard the need to tie training more closely to
field experience and to make it more practical. To do that not only requires
changes in the content and organization of training; sore importantly, it
implies selection of trainers with practical ICDS field experience. It is
consistent with the idea that each training institution should also have
responsibility for overseeing the implementation of programmes in at least one
block. By so doing, trainers would be more in touch with the realities faced by
grassroots workers and supervisors.<p>
<p>
	The need to tie training to experience also reinforces the idea that
supervisors should be much more prominent in the training of AWWs .<p>
<p>
	<b>Supervisor as Trainer.</b> If supervisors are to be expected to do more of
the training than they have done in the past, a major effort will need to be
made to assist the supervisor in that role. A number of suggestions were made
with that in mind.<p>
<p>
<ul><li> First, the training of supervisors should be adjusted to include additional
attention to group organization and to such techniques as role playing,
eliciting exchanges of experience, and use of questions, in order to overcome
the natural tendency to train through lecturing.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Second, supervisors should be provided with a set of materials that would
facilitate discussion at the circle level as well as transmit information (see
below).<p>
<p>
	 <li>Third, a monthly training/discussion meeting of supervisors could be organized.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Fourth, a master supervisor's post should be created specifically to help
supervisors in their facilitating/training capacity.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Fifth, the AWW/supervisor role should be reduced so that contact with AWWs
can be more frequent and the training function more prominent. The present load
of 18 to 20 AWW per supervisor makes it difficult for a supervisor to make two
visits per month to each AWW, particularly when the AWW are scattered. At least
in some places (dispersed areas, new areas, areas where the pre-school
component has not yet taken hold, for instance), the ratio should be closer to
10 or 12 AWW per supervisor.</ul>
	CDPOs, At present, CDPOs are brought to Delhi for their initial orientation? A
question was raised as to whether their pre-service
as well as in-service
training might be at the state level, with a State Resource Centre taking
responsibility for the training. This was consistent with the idea that
training should be as close to the job as possible.<p>
<p>
	<b>3.  What should be the length, periodicity, and balance of pre-
and in-service training?</b><p>
<p>
	We encountered a range of opinions about the most appropriate length of pre-service
training. These differences were related to different ideas about how much
content a grassroots worker should be provided and could absorb in a first
sitting, to questions of the location of training away from home and the
corresponding need for time of adjustment (implying a longer stay) vs.
homesickness (implying a shorter stay), and to ideas about how in-service
training should occur.<p>
<p>
	Although it is possible to imagine reducing further the current 3-month
pre-service
training could be further reduced, if supported by a strong follow-on
system of in-service
training, the 3-month
period already represents a compromise from the original four months. This
compromise seems to have evolved over time as the result of a long process
involving system participants at all levels. It is necessary, therefore, to
demonstrate clearly that a shorter, or reorganized, pre-service
alternative can produce equivalent or better results. To do so requires
experimentation with a range of alternative training schemes on a scale that
has
not yet been done.<p>
<p>
	<b>"Sandwich" training.</b> The Working Group on Early Childhood Education and
Elementary Education has proposed experimentation with the "sandwich" principle
for pre-service
training of AWWs and supervisors, using various mixes. [For AWWs, for example,
a 1 month "orientation" (basic competencies and understanding) followed by 6
months of field placement accompanied by on-the-job
supervision, followed by 1 month of skills training (which could be at the
circle level using mobile extension training) based on field experience,
followed by another 2 months of field placement, with a final months training
to "sum up." This system would keep the three month period of training, but
distribute it over an 11-month period.]<p>
<p>
	Each state could set its own experimental system, to be tried out as part of
the project. Built into the experimentation should be a system for evaluating
results.<p>
<p>
	<b>In-service training.</b> In some of our conversations we found a tendency to equate
"refresher training" and "in-service
training." While it is true that refresher training occurs while a person is
"in service," such courses are, typically, not "on-the-job"
and they represent only one form of training while in service. Usually, ICDS
refresher courses, like the pre-service
courses, take workers away from their places of work to provide them with a
chance to learn something new and/or to go over old topics in light of their
experience on the job. It is our experience that most refresher training has
relatively little lasting effect, even though it does, in the short term, help
to motivate workers and provide them with something of value.<p>
<p>
	In our opinion, training on-the-job
that occurs through supervision and through periodic meetings at the local
level, and through forms of mobile training should have a much higher priority
than refresher courses away from the job.<p>
<p>
	On several occasions, we were told of the apparent success of mobile training
at the district level. These included experiences in Maharastra, in the USAID-assisted
programme, and in Orissa. This form of training can be equally useful for
helpers and AWW and other local workers such as the ANM. The model seems to
have some cost benefits as well. It can be supportive of training on-the-job
by supervisors.<p>
<p>
	<b>Training at the circle level.</b> We also heard considerable interest, both
inside the ICDS and in the technical institutions, in the idea of using the
monthly circle meetings as training opportunities in which a topic could be
discussed at each session, and time given also for discussion of the AWW's own
situation. These sessions could be backed by "booster" materials --
pamphlets and posters, for example -- or even by radio broadcasts. They could be organized in such a way that a
particular AWW or two took the lead each month in presenting the topic. Topics
might be chosen well in advance or might be selected each time for the
subsequent meeting, according to the needs of the AWWs. The sessions could
provide an opportunity for a trainer from the training institution to
participate. The location of the sessions could be rotated among AWCs.
Certificates could be given after participation in a certain number of circle-level
training meetings, as they are given for participation in a refresher course.<p>
<p>
	To a certain degree, block meetings, as well as circle meetings, could also be
used to provide training, rather than to serve simply as days to compile
statistics. The feasibility of this alternative depends in part on distances
involved and on transportation.<p>

<p>
	<b>4.  What training methods and content should be used?</b><p>
<p>
	<b>Method.</b> The revised Guidelines for Instructors for organising job
training of AWW suggests that, "Instructors must avoid use of the chalk and
talk method. Theory in all sessions must be kept to a bare minimum and should
be mainly in the way of introducing the
topic and giving basic information." (p. 7) Further, "The method of training to
be used has been indicated wherever possible by using words like: discuss with,
elicit from, trainees perception of, role play, conduct meeting, arrange a
display, etc." (p. 8)<p>
<p>
	Both the guidelines and the syllabus for the AWW are filled with suggestions
for specific activities and games. Several sessions are devoted to preparation
of aids and play materials - for physical, cognitive, language, and social-emotional
development. Play is given an important place in the curriculum and time is
alloted in the training programme for field applications.<p>
<p>
	In brief, the officially published training materials suggest a holistic,
active approach, very much in line with the general principle suggested above.
The challenge is to select and train trainers who will in fact follow that
approach. That puts considerable pressure on the importance of the training of
trainers and of breaking the lecture habit. Even more, the challenge is to
link the field work to the particular situation faced by the AWW once she
returns to her village and centre. That can only be done through strong follow-up
of pre-service
activities in training on-the-job.<p>
<p>
	<b>Content.</b> In the last few years, several ideas have been promoted in
India to improve the non-formal
pre-school
curriculum of ICDS and the activities of AWW. Two particularly prominent
approaches have been the "Cognitively Oriented" approach of Indira Swaminathan
and the "Thematic" approach originating in Kerala. These two approaches both
have merit and are complementary to each other. Either one can serve as a
starting point for activities. The current attempts to combine these two should
be encouraged.<p>
<p>
	To the extent possible, the content of the training should be adjusted to
local customs and should incorporate songs, games, stories, riddles, etc. that
are local. Both the syllabus for job
training and the guidelines for trainers make some provision for this. Here,
the most important challenge may be to link the songs and games to principles
of child development<p>
<p>
	(This topic will be picked up again under the discussion of materials.)<p>
<p>
<b>Materials/Resources</b><p>
<p>
	Materials for use in the pre-school.
The following description comes from the NIPCCD study examining social
components of ICDS:<p>
<p>
<ul>	"The investigators observations on availability of teaching aids and play
material at the AW revealed that such a provision was there only in 45 percent
AWs of thesample. However, the material was adeguate only in 33 percent AWs,
i.e., enough for the number of children enrolled or present. Further the aids
and play material were appropriate only in 42 percent AWs, the articles in most
cases were made out of waste/indigenous material  devoid of durability and thus
unable to withstand any handling. As a result, these were kept as show pieces,
either locked in cupboards or far away from the reach  the children. In some
instances, attractive blocks and toys were provided to the AWs, the workers
were hesitant in letting children use these to prevent loss and damage and
avoid problems at the time or stock checking."<p>
<p>
	"Faded charts of birds, animals,...adorned the walls In most cases these were
stuck far above the eye level children, thus failing to even provide any visual
stimulation...The drab, dull and unstimulating surroundings could only be
attributed to the workers limited inability to be imaginative and creative;
possibly  the training provides limited experience in preparation of
appropriate material. The kit items made during the job training get exhausted
and are not substituted." (p. 57)<p>
<p>
	"Interestingly, most of the AWs (78%) had printers, blackboards, charts and
books. Their daily routine included teaching of numbers through rote method.
The AW was thus turned into a primary school, the concept of non-formal
preschool education was obviously not followed..." (p. 58)</ul>
	This assessment conforms with our own observations, with case study materials,
and with repeated comments of others with whom we have talked. It is consistent
with the comments made by AWW trainees from tribal areas in Orissa (see
annexure 2) who identified as problems the absence of toys and child learning
materials, and the inadequate training in the use of existing materials.<p>
<p>
	We see, then, at least three problems: the presence or absence of materials,
their quality and durability (and/or ease of replacement), and attitudes about
their use. Of these three, the
last is probably the most important.<p>
<p>
	With imagination, no pre-school
should lack materials that can be used for play and learning. These may be of
virtually no cost, or of very low cost, and as simple as the use of pebbles or
bottle caps for sorting and counting. Bottle caps can be made into musical
instruments. These materials are durable, and can be replaced. Usually, enough
can be found for all children to use. Or, as in the case of the simple
"cognitive kit" of the COPCC programme, they say include a home-made
doll, a rope, a stethoscope made out of a small piece of rope and a bead, etc.
A home-made
doll can be made from any of many local materials and need not be very fancy.
It too can be replaced with relative ease. (For other ideas about the use of low-cost
materials to make toys, and more importantly, for many play activities that
require no materials at all, see Mina Swaminathan, UNICEF, 1986.)<p>
<p>
	In their training, AWW are asked to make some materials and aids. These are
usually not very durable (e.g., a paper puppet), but they are easy to replace.
However, the idea that these can, and should, be replaced when they wear out or
that there are alternative materials that night be used, does not seem to be
internalized. Rather, there still seems to be an idea that materials should be
provided, not made.<p>
<p>
	The making and use of toys and teaching aids is an area in which the
supervisor could be of great help to AWW, and AWW could be encouraged to share
their ideas with each other. It is a topic that could be discussed regularly at
circle meetings, or to which one or more meetings might be devoted, to
gathering ideas from the group as well as from outside sources. In addition,
the community could be called on to help provide materials.<p>
<p>
	The above comments must be moderated to recognize the intense levels of
poverty that characterize some of the AWW environments, in which there are few
"waste" materials to be appropriated for the school. Both the conditions of
poverty and the prestige attached to colorful, pre-made
toys may justify purchase and supply of some such toys to AWCs.(1.) However,
these cannot be expensive, and it must be made clear that such toys are for
use, not decoration, and that other toys and materials from the environment can
be equally effective.<p>
<p>
	A host of other materials and aids exist. These include the Centre for Media
Learning materials developed by NCERT, among which is a science kit for
children 3 to 6, and the learning kit developed by the Centre for Learning
Resources in Pune. In Orissa, the SCERT has developed and field tested
materials, adapted to the local context (see comments in Annexure 2).<p>
<p>
	If it has not already been done, a useful task would be to review existing
play materials and to put the results of the review in a form that would help
each state to make choices about the
materials to subsidize. Several years ago, the Centre for Media Learning made
such a review for Tamil Nadu, Gujarat, Manipur, Karnataka, Andhra Pradesh and
Maharasta, and published manuals for each state giving details of local
availability and suggestions about how to use the materials in a centre. These
publications are now out of stock (and probably out of date in some 
respects). It might be worthwhile to update and revise these publications as a
starting point for a larger effort. The materials reviewed could be brought
together in one place and/or, an attempt could be made tosee that one set was
available in each State Resource Centre.<p>
<p>
	While giving some attention to the production and distribution of pre-made
toys and materials, our own bias would be to put greater effort into promoting
the local construction of play materials by AWWs and community members. With
some supervision and quality
control, this could develop into an income-generating
activity for certain villagers. Accordingly, the first investment would be in
providing trainees with the few basic materials they eight need to
create a "starter set" as part of their own training (see Annexure IV of the
Eighth Plan Working Group for an example of what might be done for Rs.300.)<p>
<p>
	With the exception of the materials reviewed in Orissa, we were not able to
give much attention to printed materials for children during our short visit.
But we would endorse the need, present in the Eight Plan working Group
recommendations, for a review of existing materials, undertaken in
collaboration with publishers, and the need for production of children's
literature at the pre-school
level and in regional languages on a larger scale.<p>
<p>
	<b>Training materials.</b> It Is our impression that a wide variety of printed
and visual aid materials exist to support the training process. These have been
produced by NCERT, NIPCCD, and others. In general, however, these seem to be
directed toward pre-service
training rather than focussing on in-service
training by supervisors and at the circle level. There is also a continuing
need for adaptation to local ideas and circumstances. For instance, we found
that even though the SCERT in Orissa has carried out excellent work in this
regard, adapatation to needs of tribal areas was still required.<p>
<p>
	Consistent with the idea of strengthening in-service,
on-the-job
training, greater attention should be given to developing materials for use by
supervisors in circle meetings. One such set of
pamphlets has already been developed for use in the Mobile Creche programme and
these might be examined for their relevance on a larger scale. However, in-service
materials should, for the most part, be created at the State or District level
in order to facilitate adjustment to local circumstances and to the expressed
needs of particular groups of trainees.<p>
<p>
	An excellent video has been prepared by NIPCCD that includes information about
making and using materials, but as part of a more general presentation of
various kinds of activities that AWW might carry out with children in their
centres. This, and similar training materials, should be distributed to all
training centres and an effort should be made to be sure that all have the
equipment necessary to use such materials.
                             <p>
<p>
	<b>The AWW Guidebook.</b> Although the AWW training Syllabus gives a
proportionate treatment to the non-formal
pre-school
component of ICDS, the Guidebook (1986 version) does not. Nutrition and health
are given 107 pages in the Guidebook and the section on record
keeping and reporting fills 68 pages, while pre-school
is handled in 16 pages.. Although a great deal is packed into the 16 pages, the
pre-school
suggestions and activities do not have the same level of specificity as the
health and nutritional activities. There is nosection, for instance, indicating
how activities might be organizedaround a theme. There is nothing about the use
of children's names. Whereas four pages are given over to pictures of examples
from various food groups, there are no diagrams of how space night be set up to
encourage play and guided activities in a non-formal
pre-school programme. The importance of play is not made as clear in
the Guidebook as in the revised training syllabus.<p>
<p>
	<b>An Activities Guide.</b> In press is an Activities Guide that may be useful
as a supplement to the AWW Guidebook. This resource, which has been produced by
Amita Verma, with funding from UNICEF, sets out activities in five
categories:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 Information (about the natural and physical environment, self and family, and
animals) <p>
<p>
	 <li>Problem solving (related to immediate and long-term
memory, to similarities and differences, and the concept of part-whole
<p>
<p>
	 <li>Language development (Listening, speaking, understanding, creative self-expression,
verbal fluency)<p>
<p>
	 <li>Visual and auditory discrimination<p>
<p>
	 <li>Cognitive development (concepts such as shape, size, sound, colour, number,
weight, texture, direction, time, living and non-living)</ul>
<p>
1. During our visit we were shown part of a particular set of toys made in
Madaya Pradesh by a non-governmental
organization. It was difficult to judge the value of the set because not all
pieces were present and we did not have information about the paint used, and
the cost of different combinations, or about the quality control (we saw part
of one set only). At first glance, the set appeared to be of moderate quality
and reasonably durable. Some pieces seemed more more appropriate for children
below age 3. The cost is relatively high if compared with such alternatives as
the cognitive kit of COPCC, but only a little higher than the set suggested in
the Annexure I of the Eighth Plan working group. (However, the materials in the
Eighth Plan listing are more varied.)<p>
<p>
<b>Time Allocation</b><p>
<p>
	The job responsibilities of the AWW have been classified into 4 main
categories: preparatory work, service delivery (including non-formal
preschool activities and health and nutrition activities), community contact
and education, and management and administration. In carrying out these
responsibilities, the AWW can draw on the assistance of a helper, can cooperate
with other individuals such as the dai and the ANM, and can call upon
organizations such as the Mahila Mandels. We will focus here on the pre-school
component, recognizing the need to balance this time with that required for
other duties and the sharing of those duties with
helpers, ANMs, etc.<p>
<p>
	According to the social monitoring study carried out by NIPCCD, the way in
which AWW divide their time among these responsibilities varies significantly
from place to place. For instance, in one tribal block in Rajasthan, 8 of 15 AWW reported spending only 3 to 5 hours per
week on preschool activities, with the remaining 7 blocks, preschool time was
between 6 and 10 hours per week. By way of contrast, in another Rajasthani
tribal block, 13 of 15 AWWs reported spending between 11 and 15 hours per week
on pre-school
activities. (The distribution of time spent on feeding was virtually the same
for these two blocks, with most spending between 6 and 10 hours per week.)
According to the study, however, spending 11 to 15 hours per week on preschool
activities did not necessarily mean that the activities were being carried out
more effectively. In some cases, then, the challenge is to make effective use
of the time already being devoted to the pre-school
component; in others, the challenge is to increase pre-school
time as well as to use that time effectively.<p>
<p>
	It is difficult to say, with any degree of confidence, that a certain fixed
number of hours each week is the "minimum" that should be spent on non-formal
pre-school
activities. The minimum time allocation will depend on: local goals, the
characteristics of the children involved, the ratio of adults to children in
the preschool, and the effectiveness of time use. In our opinion, however, if
time is well used, approximately eight hours a week spent by the AWW on child
development activities for children ages 3 to 5 in the Anganwadi should be
sufficient to make a significant difference in most children's abilities to
create and cope and master pre-literacy
and numeracy concepts and skills that will be needed for school.<p>
<p>
	Accepting this rough figure of 8 hours as reasonable, implies that an AWW
could devote 2 hours each morning during 4 mornings a week to pre-school
activities. This arrangement would leave the AWW time during two mornings and
during the afternoons for liaison with local officials and health personal, for
home visiting, for group meetings, and for growth monitoring. The AW helper, in
combination with adolescent girls and/or volunteer community members could be
responsible for the two mornings when the AWW is not present at the AWC. with
some training for the helper in organizing play for the children, activities to
complement feeding could be implemented.<p>
<p>
	By asking explicit that the AWW is to spend two mornings a week in the
community, working with families and with children O to 3, the ICDS programme
would provide a needed signal regarding the importance of this younger target
group, would free time for the activities related to the 0-to-3s
as well as pregnant and lactating mothers, and would still allow adequate time
for feeding and the non-formal
pre-school
component.<p>
<p>
	Other observations related to time use follow:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 The radio experiment being carried out in Rajasthan in which programmes for
ICDS children are presented for 15 minutes each morning should help the AWW to
organize her time as well as to provide her with a continuing source of
information and new activities.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Asking the AWW to perform additional responsibilities such as literacy
instruction could place an additional burden on the AWW, affecting negatively
her attention to the pre-school
and nutritional activities.<p>
<p>
	 <li>The inclusion of adolescent girls in the ICDS programme may be a good idea
but should probably not be looked upon as a major time-saving
scheme because these young girls will  require supervision, increasing the
responsibility of the AWW. (Nevertheless, we were told by Orissa AWWs in
training, that the idea of involving adolescent girls was a good one.)</ul>

<b>Motivation</b><p>
<p>
	In the brainstorming session held during our visit (see list of participants
in Annexure 1), an issue of major concern to those present was that of
motivation, or, "the human factor." The quality of the pre-school
(and other) components of ICDS is directly affected by the motivation and self-confidence
of the programme implementers. The desire to work, and to work well, involves
more than acquiring a set of skills. It requires feedback and an occasional pat
on the back, so one knows one is doing well, or, is at least making advances.
It requires listening and guiding by supervisors rather than just informing. It
requires opportunities to participate in a supportive group where one can share
successes and raise questions.<p>
<p>
    It was pointed out that ICDS has instituted a system of snail increments in
pay to recognize time in service -- as one incentive for AWW workers. Fortunately, however, monetary incentives,
although important, are only part of the motivational picture.<p>
<p>
    ICDS also has experimented with a system of prizes. While it has not
functioned regularly, it could be implemented in a more systematic way. Also,
it would be possible to establish various
systems of recognition (with or without a prize). For instance, AWW might be
asked to contribute stories in a contest. The stories judged to be the best
could be published and distributed on a wide
scale. The same might be done for songs.<p>
<p>
	Perhaps the most important way to reward performance is through promotion -- from AWW to supervisor, from supervisor to a master supervisor and/or to become
a CDPO. This provides personal challenge as well as the prospect of higher pay.
This kind of promotion too rarely happens, however. As suggested above,
increasing the amount of promotion from within the system could strengthen the
system considerably, not only by incorporating more practical experience, but
by increasing motivation.<p>
<p>
	Motivation can come also from continuing in-service
training that includes the possibility of group discussion -- at circle meetings for AWWs and at monthly meetings at the block level for
supervisors. As suggested that these meetings could be opportunities for
training; but at least as important is their potential role in providing a
regular source of motivation to grassroots workers. Motivating through on-going
in-service
training and support does not require any major budget increases, but it does
enter into planning, particularly as part of the training of supervisors.
Providing certification for the skills obtained through such in-service
training is also a source of motivation.<p>
<p>
	The suggestion to reduce the AWW/Supervisor ratio can also be justified, in
part, in terms of the additional motivation that can be provided through more
frequent and regular visits with a reduced load.<p>
<p>
<b>Organization</b><p>
<p>
	The need to strengthen state and local levels of ICDS was identified as a
challenge. Some clear moves in that direction have already been taken. In
Orissa, for instance, the SCERT has been active in both training and materials
development, and is looking to establish District Institutes for Education and
Training (DIET) in 13 Districts. It is possible to foresee an Early Childhood
Development Unit at each DIET. These units could function as resource centres
responsible for coordination of training, materials development, research, and
dissemination at the District level. In addition, an AWW could be attached to
each DIET as a kind of "laboratory" which would provide opportunities for AWW
training.<p>
<p>
	Clearly, strengthening of State Resource Centers should be written into the
plans of the states that are to participate in the two projects. An early
education/child development person should be
part of those centres.<p>
<p>
	It was suggested that more should be done to bring the talents of Home
Economics, Education, and Social Welfare faculties of universities into ICDS,
perhaps assigning to participating organizations the responsibility for
overseeing implementation of on-going
programmes as well as for programme monitoring and evaluation.<p>
<p>
	From several sides came the repeated suggestion that sore non-governmental
institutions could be involved in ICDS.<p>
<p>
<b>Monitoring and Evaluation</b><p>
	Health and nutrition components of ICDS have been endlessly monitored, giving
visibility to these components. Now, NIPCCD has demonstrated both the value and
feasibility of monitoring the social components of ICDS, including the pre-school
component. This NIPCCD initiative deserves to be supported and extended to
include periodic evaluation of the impact of the ICDS programme on children and
other participants. This could, and in our opinion, should be written into the
project proposals.<p>
<p>
Additional support could be given to attempts to move monitoring and analysis
functions froa the central level to the state and district levels by
strengthening monitoring cells at these levels. This requires a concerted
training effort, and probably a technical assistance arrangement with NIPCCD
and a local university-based
group.<p>
<p>
    NIPCCD has proposed:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 A half-yearly
Pro-forma
to be completed by AWW dealing with: physical facilities, amenities, and the
worker's background, and<p>
<p>
	 <li>A Quarterly Report that would include information about:<p>
<p>
<ul>beneficiaries (by the AWW)<br>
work performance of functionaries (by Supervisors)<br>
quality of services (by a technical institution), and<br>
observations of 3 women from the community (by a technical
institution).</ul><br>
</ul>
	This proposal deserves serious consideration and action to bring together this
proposal with the nutrition and health monitoring.<p>
<p>
As far as we can tell, there is no system for evaluating the impact of ICDS on
the cognitive and social aspects of child development, as there is for
nutrition and health, using mortality, mobidity, and nutritional indicators.
Instruments exist that could be used to evaluate the effect of ICDS on pre-literacy
and pre-numeracy
skills. It would also be possible to evaluate the effect on school enrollment,
progress, and performance (see, for instance, Chaturvedi, 1987, or, Balaji and
Arya, 1987).<p>
<p>
	In our conversations we have sensed a hesitancy to carry out such impact
evaluations, which we think would show a positive effect in areas where the
programme is being implemented reasonably well, and would provide an argument
for helping to upgrade the pre-school
component in areas where implementation is not as good.<p>

<p>
<center><b>Community Education for Child Care</b></center><p>
<p>
	In the syllabus and guidebook, a section dealing with the education of parents
and other caregivers is called, "Community Education for Child Care." These
words suggest a heavy emphasis on health and on custodial care. We would prefer
to see the section labeled, "Community Education for Child Devel6pment,"
consistent with the ICDS name.<p>
<p>
	Enhancement of early childhood development by working with parents and other
caregivers is important because such support and education:<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 Is necessary to reach children in their earliest months and years (ages O to 3).<p>
<p>
	 <li>Builds and reinforces family responsibility for child development.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Adds continuity and support to centre-based
services.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Promotes an integrated approach.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Helps sustain improvements In the long term by empowering parents and other
caregivers.</ul>
<b>Principles</b><p>
<p>
	There is broad agreement that ICDS has not been as successful in reaching
children under age 3 as it has been in reaching children in the 3 to 5 age
group. It may not be surprising, therefore, that whereas the path to improving
the quality of non-formal
pre-school programmes is reasonably clear, there is much less clarity about how
to design the equivalent developmental component for children under three. It
Is clear that community education for child care has to be central, but that
education is presently discussed only in terms of nutrition and health. Indeed,
one whole part of community education for child development --
that relating to the cognitive,
linguistic, social and emotional development of the child under the age of 3 -- seems to be missing. There is little or no attention in the official material
we saw dealing with child care education, to information or activities designed
to develop the senses through stimulation or that help to develop a child's
mind and respond to a child's need for security, interaction, exploration and
love. This part of child development is left until age 3.<p>
<p>
	Further, the idea of child care education seems to revolve around the simple
presentation of basic messages. This rather impersonal approach is not one we
find congenial, nor is it a position shared by all the people with whom we
spoke. Consequently, The principles suggested below for child care education
are not ones that we heard articulated frequently (as was the case for pre-school),
but, rather, represent our own thinking and that of a few individuals with whom
we spoke. (For one treatment, see: Sharma, Infant stimulation, May, l989.)<p>
<p>
<ul><li>	 Child care education should be integrated in its content. There is a need to
include information about the mental and social development of children in the
earliest years as well as about their survival and physical growth. As
indicated at the outset, an alert, inquisitive, secure and communicative child
will be healthier, better nourished, and more likely to survive than a passive,
inert, reticent, insecure and uncommunicative child.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Child care education should draw on existing knowledge and experience as well
as provide new information. It is important to recognize that many caregivers,
even in so-called
disadvantaged environments, are competent and effective caregivers who have a
store of traditional wisdom to draw upon. Positive behaviours need to be
supported, even as negative practices are being corrected through the
presentation of new knowledge.<p>
<p>
	<li>Child care education should allow for support through periodic home visits or
through group discussion and action. It is not enough simply to get messages to
people. The purpose of caregiver education is to change attitudes, improve
behaviour and have an impact on the child, not just to transfer knowledge.
Experience suggests that changes in attitudes and practices require a fore of
education that reinforces individual messages with interpersonal forms of
communication on a recurring basis. A one-shot
educational effort does not innoculate, and impersonal media communica tions,
alone, will rarely be sufficient to change behaviour.<p>
<p>
	 <li>Child care education should be set within the context of, and help to
promote, other activities that make fundamental changes in the environment in
which a child develops. From the education should come community organization
for action that helps to change unsanitary conditions, provides income
generating activities, and attacks other general problems in the community
affecting development.</ul>
<b>Issues and Concerns</b><p>
<p>
	<b>The need for integration</b>. Because community child care education is
presently framed in terms of health and nutrition and does not include a psycho-social
dimension, a first task is to integrate that dimension into the general process
of child care education. To do so, it will be necessary to build awareness of
the importance of this dimension, to re-examine
training materials to see that this theme is included, to create materials for
use at the grassroots and in circle meetings, and to experiment with inclusion
of the component in specific child care education programmes.<p>
<p>
	Subsumed under this issue are many details related to training and materials
development which remain to be worked out.<p>
<p>
<b>Time</b><p>
<p>
We have already discussed in relation to the pre-school
component a time reallocation that would give more time to the AWW for child
care education. Incorporating a psycho-social
dimension within this education would not demand much additional time from the
AWW. What is implied is a few minutes during each home visit or in group
meetings to discuss stimulation, interaction, and socialization themes,
supporting positive practices, and suggesting new or different activities. An
occasional group meeting devoted to this theme would also be called for, in
which emphasis would be place on drawing out the positive practices and
activities that some families are using and that could be adopted by others.<p>
<p>
	It would be advisable for the developmental component to be phased in over
time. It could be handled in the main as part of in-service
training, and by providing only a general orientation within the pre-service
training. Phasing in this dimension would avoid overloading the AWW with
additional knowledge during the pre-service
training.<p>
<p>
<b>An Experiment to Watch</b><p>
<p>
	In Orissa, the NCERT has been carrying out an experiment with a home-based
programme of child development for tribal and urban children over the last
several years. (Muralidharan and Mishra, 1989) The experiment involves work
with selected families through home visits and in groups organized by trained
para-professionals
from the community (not, in the first instance AWWs). In the training
programme, these para-professional
workers were given fundamental principles of child development, child care and
desirable child rearing practices through slide showings, songs, and
activities, and were exposed to supporting materials (produced by the CML) and
to examples of stimulating activities for parents and their very young
children. Over the course of a year, weekly home visits were carried out.<p>
<p>
	The appproach taken is an integrated one. Home discussions and small group
meetings deal with immunization, ORT, weaning, etc., as well as with stimulation-related
activities. Immunization camps were held in conjunction with Primary Health
Care and the Women's Welfare Centre as part of the project.<p>
<p>
	To help create the content for the materials and visits, a baseline study was
carried out in 1986 that included, among other things, information about
health, nutrition, sanitation, and stimulation practices. This study was
carried out by THREAD (Team of Human Resource Education and Action for
Development), an NGO based in Orissa.<p>
<p>
	When experimental and control groups in the experiment were compared,
experimental mothers were found to be much more aware of the need for
stimulation than non-experimental
mothers. More importantly, experimental children in the tribal area (but not in
the urban area) performed significantly better on tests of motor, personal-social,
language, and cognitive development, at all developmental levels.<p>
<p>
	Based on this initial success, the project is now being carried out within the
ICDS programme, with hose visiting being done by AWWs. The results of this
extension of the original idea bear
watching closely.<p>
<p>
<b>Some Specific Suggestions:</b><p>
<p>
	1. There is a need for NIPCCD to follow up its meeting earlier this year on
traditional (including tribal) child rearing practices, to extract from the
results of that meeting specific implications for the content of materials to
be used in training and in community child care activities by supervisors and
AWW (NIPCCD, 1989).<p>
<p>
	2. A pamphlet should be developed for use in in-service
training of AWW at the circle level, and with parents, that would help parents
to recognize the highly-developed
condition of a child's senses at birth and the importance of helping a child to
exercise these capacities if they are to develop properly. The pamphlet might
give an important place to such existing (but declining) practices as
massage.<p>
<p>
	3. A pamphlet might be created that links development to the rituals that now
mark various milestones in the early life of a child.<p>
<p>
	4. If it has not already been done, AIR should be encouraged to work with
NCERT or NIPCCD on the development of a set of "spots" or short programmes that
would be directed toward parents of children O to 3 that draw on the
information to be included in the two publications suggested above. The
presentation of these spots might be coordinated with group meetings in
communities, much as the Rajasthan experiment now coordinates its programmes
with programming in the pre-schools.
An example of such a model is available from Southern Chile.<p>
<p>
	5. The NCERT experiment in Orissa, described above, should be followed
closely.<p>
<p>
	6. An elaborate training effort is being tried out in several states where
CARE is providing food, begining with training of CDPOs and ending the
"cascade" with the training of mothers by AWWs. One of the experimental states
is Orissa. This programme has focussed on health and nutrition; it does not
include a component mother-child interaction and education. A repeat round of training is envisioned for
next year to reinforce what have been given. In the repeat, the training should
be broadened to integrate in the additional dimension of child development.<p>
<p>
	7. There are undoubtedly other experimental home-based
projects being carried out in India that take an integrated perspective, that
include stimulation/education/socialization components and that include, or
focuss on, birth to age 3. It may be appropriate to organize a national meeting
to present results from innovative home-visiting
or parental education programmes, similar to the meeting organized in 1983
dealing with cognitive development in early childhood programmes.<p>
<p>
<b>Postscript on Child Development Education</b><p>
<p>
	Because our original charge was to look at the non-formal
pre-school
component of ICDS and because our time was relatively short during this
consultancy, we do not feel we have been able to do justice to the area of
child care education focussing on children O to 3. At the same time we feel
strongly that this is a crucial area and that a concerted effort should be made
now to incorporate the stimulation/interaction/education content into
programmes of health and nutrition education. We hope that it will be possible
for someone, within the context of the project discussions, to examine this
area in greater depth and to incorporate the component into the final project
plan.<p>
<p>
