<head>
   <title>The Culture of Infancy: An Analysis of Infant
 Behavior and Child Rearing Practices in
 South India </title>
   </head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">

<div align=center><h3>The Culture of Infancy: An Analysis of Infant 
<div align=center><p>Behavior and Child Rearing Practices in</p></div>

<div align=center><p>South India </p></div>

<div align=center><p>Prepared for 
<br>The 3rd International Ethnography of Childhood Workshop Cambridge,
England 
<br>July 3- 6, 1988 
<br></p></div>

<div align=center><p>Cassie Landers, Ed.D., MPH 
<br>Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care 
<br>and Development c/o UNICEF/NY 
<br></p></div>
</h3></div>

<p><b>ABSTRACT: 
<br>Culture of Infancy: An Analysis of Infant Behaviour and Child Rearing
Practices in South India 
<br></b>Cassie Landers, Ed.D., MPH 
<br>Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care 
<br>and Development c/o UNICEF/NY 
<br></p>

<p>Prepared for 
<br>The 3rd International Ethnography of Childhood Workshop 
<br>Cambridge, England July 3- 6, 1988 
<br></p>

<p>In an effort to contribute to the growing body of comparative child
development research, a psycho- biological model useful in the analysis
of early child development was applied to a group of infants in a South
Indian fishing community. The application of this model generated both
quantitative baseline data from which infant behaviour, development and
physiology can be understood as well as an ethnographic exploration of
the knowledge, attitudes, and beliefs which structure caregiving behaviours
and define the wider cultural setting.</p>

<p>The specific aims of this investigation were to: (1) describe and document
the behavioural profile of this group of infants, (2) illustrate the complex
set of relationships between biomedical and social variables, and (3) discover
the mechanisms through which these relationships vary in different cultures.
The data generated led to the analysis of three major perspectives including:
(1) the biological efficacy and adaptability of the infant to overcome
the demands of a stressful environment, (2) the effectiveness of culturally
adapted infant- rearing patterns, and (3) the unique psychological make-
up and identity development of the Indian woman. In addition, the insights
drawn from this research addressed several critical social policy issues
related to the design and implementation of early intervention programmes
for infants at- risk.</p>

<p>Table I. Selected Measures For Cross- Cultural Infancy Research.</p>

