<p>control are described and recorded. The reflex items are scored as:
O = absent, 1 e low, 2- medium, 3 P high, With a 2 considered normal for
most of the reflexes, while the 26 behavioral items are rated on a nine-
point scale. The BNBAS uncovers the infant's major capacities to organize
himself when confronted with the intense physiological demands for recovery
from labor, delivery, and exposure to the environment outside of the uterus,
The infant is manipulated in such a fashion that within the half- hour
examination he demonstrates his ability for physical, cognitive, social,
and temperamental function, as well as psycho- physiological intactness.

<br></p>

<p>To analyze the data, the individual items were grouped according to
the behavioral clusters developed by Lester, Ale, and Brazelton (1982).
This system, which seeks to preserve the dynamic Conceptualization of the
infant, combines the 26 behavioral items into six behavioral clusters and
uses the 16 reflexes to generate a seventh cluster (Table II). To derive
the six behavioral clusters, the curvilinear scale items are rescored as
linear. The cluster score is the mean of the rescored items used to define
the cluster, with higher scores indicating &quot;better&quot; performance.
The six behavioral clusters are: Habituation, response decrement to repeated
auditory, visual, and tactile stimulation; Orientation, response to animate
and inanimate stimuli and overall alertness; Motor, integrated motor acts
and overall muscle tonus; Range of State, which assess the rapidity, peak
and lability of state changes; Regulation of State, efforts to modulate
the infant's o~m state control; and Autonomic Regulation, signs of physiological
stress seen as tremors, startles, and changes in skin color. The seventh
or Reflex cluster is the total number of deviant reflex scores so that
higher</p>

