Child Devel692.</p>

<p>scores indicate a greater number of deviant reflexes. Performance on
the BNBAS for each of the 30 Indian infants will be presented and discussed
under two major headings; (1) group analysis of cluster scores and their
pattern of change during the first month of life and, (2) correlational
analysis between selected material infant biomedical factors and BNBAS
performance.</p>

<p>Medical Assessments. Maternal medical information consisted of obstetrical
and reproductive histories and the anthropometric indicators of height,
weight, and arm circumference. For the infant the anthropometric indicators,
length, weight, and head circumference were measured at birth, 1, and 3
months with the additional measurements of chest and arm circumference
at 3 months.</p>

<p>Socio- Cultural Data. Through a series of both formal and informal interviews,
an attempt was made to describe the particular socio- cultural setting
surrounding each mother and infant. Information of the family support system
and kinship structure and educational level of the parents was obtained.
Based on the work of Levinson (1974), an overall index of family wealth
was calculated, which included the following parameters: housing, occupation,
sanitation, and the number of various household possessions.</p>

<p>Psychometric Functioning. The Bayley Scale of Infant Development was
administered to each infant at 3 months (Bayley, 1969). The primary value
of this tool for infant development lies in its ability to determine a
child's current level of functioning and the degree of deviation from normality.
The scale is divided into two complementary areas of developmental functioning,
namely Mental ability and Psychomotor ability. The mental scale is designed
to assess sensory- perceptual activities, discrimination and the ability
to respond to these; the early acquisition of object constancy and memory,
learning, and problem solving, vocalizations and the beginning of verbal
communication; and early evidence of the ability to form generalizations
and classifications which is the basis of abstract thought. The motor scale
assesses both gross and fine motor control, the degree of balance, tone,
and flexibility through the administration of motor tasks.</p>

<p>Norms for the Bayley Scale are based on 1,262 children ranging in age
from 2- 30 months. In standardizing the scale, the mental and motor items
were arranged in approximate order by age placement (the age at which %
of the children passed a given item). The Mental Development Index (MDI)
and the Psychomotor Development Index (PDI) were derived by administration
of the respective scales, The distribution of raw scores at each age level
was converted to a set of normalized standard scores with a mean value
of 100 and a standard deviation of 16. The standard score range of 50 through
150 covers more than three standard deviations on either side of the average
MDI or PDZ for each of the chosen 14 age groups tested In the standardization
design.</p>

<p><b>SAMPLE CHARACTERISTICS</b></p>

<p>Delivery Characteristics and Early Infant Environment. Of the 30 infants,
12 were delivered by a physician at the Kasturba Hospital, while the remaining
births took place at a rural health center with a midwife attending the
delivery. Infants were delivered without medication and placed alongside
the mothers immediately after birth. Mothers at the rural health center
had the option of placing their infant in a cradle located at the foot
of each bed. The average length of hospital stay was 5- 7 days, while mothers
who delivered at the center returned home between the 3rd and 5th days.
The new mother was constantly surrounded by female members of her extended
family throughout the duration of her stay. Breast feeding was initiated
usually within 24- 48 hours of birth. Initial feeds were supplemented on
the first through third days with jaggery water administered by spoon.
The tradition of not giving colostrum, recommended by ancient Indian physicians
and still practiced by 85- 902 of rural mothers (Agarwal b Agarwal, 1981),
was not widely practiced among this population of women. Breastfeeding
is frequent and on demand at all times of the day and night.</p>

<p>The 1Oth day of the infant's life is a memorable one. It is at this
time that the infant is named and a cradle made out of wood or straw hung
from the center of the hut. A silver belt, or piece of string in poorer
families, is placed around the infant's waist and used to measure and monitor
the child's growth. Children are named after their grandparents, the patron
deity of the family, or some object known for its strength and purity.
It is usually selected jointly by the elder members of the family. Until
the IOTA or IST day following delivery, mothers are considered impure.
This state of impurity is remedied by the bath, as running water is considered
the great purification agent. This task was traditionally assigned to the
washerwoman, who in virtue of her functions finds herself living permanently
in a state bordering upon that which others enter temporarily (Dumont,
1970). At present, this task is performed by the maternal grandmother,
Following the purification bath, the new mother is reintegrated into the
family. For the infant as well the bath plays a major role. An elaborate
bath and oil massage is followed by tightly wrapping the infant with an
old piece of sari.</p>

<p>Throughout the first month of life, infant and mother can be found resting
in one corner of the hut. As women in India often return to their native
home for delivery, remaining there from 3 to 5 months, the maternal grandmother
plays a major role in the early life of the infant. In such cases where
the maternal grandmother was absent, she was replaced by a female relative
or, in two cases, an elderly woman from the community, It is a time when
all of the new mother's energies are directed towards the care of her infant
and she is comforted and strengthened by the security of her familial environment.
From the moment of birth, the Indian infant is greeted and surrounded by
unyielding physical ministrations and the Indian mother is inclined towards
a total indulgence of her infant's wishes and demands (Kakar, 1978). Reflecting
the stoicism, endurance and dedication of her culture, the Indian woman
gives to infancy its mystical aura and marked impact on development.</p>

<pre>TABLE III.

MEAN, RANGE, AND STANDARD DEVIATION
OF SELECTED MATERNAL CHARACTERISTICS

                                                                       
        Variable        Mean    S.D.     Range
                                                                       

