<p>1See Appendix B for calculation of Index.</p>

<p>2Literacy: 1 = illiterate; 2 = semiliterate; 3 = literate</p>

<p>Maternal Characteristics. The characteristics of the Indian mothers
are shown in Table III. The mean height was 155.6 cm (59.0 inches), with
a weight of 47.2 kgs (103.8 pounds) and an arm circumference of 23.0 cm
(8.8 inches). Both mean height and mean weight were below the 5th percentile
of American standards for women aged 25- 34 years (Nation Center for Health
Statistics, 1979a). However, when weight was assessed in terms of height
(weight for height), the mean fell between the IOTA and 25th percentile.
The range of weight for height was from the 3rd to 75th percentiles (National
Center for Health Statistics 1979b). Since the stature of women is influenced
strongly by malnutrition, infection, and other types of stress centered
in infancy and childhood and extending into adulthood, the low values for
height and weight are indicative of suboptimal maternal health and nutrition
and are likely to influence weight gain during pregnancy (Mata &amp; Wyatt,
1971). The diets of these women were typical of a South Indian community
and consisted of rice, ragi, wheat, pulses, vegetables, buttermilk, and
coconut milk, Rice and fish characterized the diets of the nonvegetarian
mothers from the fishing community.</p>

<p>Their ages ranged from 19 to 45, with a mean maternal age of 28.2 years.
The women were distributed across the age ranges as follows: 1 woman 19
or less; 7 women each within the age ranges 20- 24, 25- 29; 9 women 30-
34 years, and 1 woman over 35 years. Gravida and parity were found to be
3,7 and 2.4, respectively, with 17% of the mothers delivering their first
child. in terms of educational status, 18.5% were illiterate, 29.7% were
semi- literate, and 51.8% were literate.</p>

<p>Measurement of selected host and environmental variables permitted computation
of the Family Wealth index useful in separating families into categories
of differing socio- economic status. The observed limits of dispersion
ranged between 51.8 and 294.8, with a mean of 149 and a standard deviation
of 57.7. As indicated by the wide range of scores, the families included
in the study represented the poor, lower middle, and middle socio- economic
classifications.</p>

<p>Several of the maternal characteristics were significantly interrelated
as indicated in Table IV. Weight and height were positively related, as
were weight and arm circumference. Age, parity, and gravida are highly
interrelated and suggest that older mothers have a greater number of children.
The maternal anthropometric characteristics were also examined with respect
to Family Wealth Index and maternal literacy rate, Maternal literacy was
positively related to the Family Wealth Index, but not significantly related
to any of the maternal medical factors. Literacy, on the other hand, was
related to maternal factors of gravida and parity and suggested that multiparous
mothers were more illiterate.</p>

<p>Newborn Characteristics. Infants less than 2500 gms were included in
the study and not considered low birthweight as according to the criteria
laid down by the World Health Organization. As the average birth weight
of full term infants in India is about 500 gms less than that of Western
countries, the international low birthweight (LBW) criterion cannot be
accepted for the Indian infant, Various Indian investigators have suggested
1800- 2500 gms as the criteria for LBW infants with the majority approving
2000 gms as the cut- off point (Ghosh, 1970; Bhargava L Ghosh, 1974; Datta
Banik, 1978).</p>

<p>The newborn characteristics are presented in Table V. All infants were
between 37 and 40 weeks gestation. The birthweights ranged from 2000 gms
to 3550- gms with a mean of 2777 gms. Male infants were slightly heavier
than female infants; 2834 and 2773, respectively. These findings are in
agreement with the mean birthweights reported by various investigators
throughout India (8hargava, Kumari, Coudhury, Lall, 1980). According to
the U.S. birthweight standards for males, 60% of the Indian infants were
at or below the IOth percentile, while 40% were at or below the 50th percentile,
The corresponding figures for females are 41% at or below the lOth percentile
and 59% at or</p>

