</pre>

<p>(ems) of 49.1 is in agreement with that reported by other Indian investigators
(Uklonskaya, Purl,Choudhari, Luthra, Kumar, 1961; Ghaf &amp; Sandhu, 1968).
This figure corresponds to the 50th percentile of U.S. standards (Gairdner
4 Pearson,1971). The mean head circumference was 33.7 (ems), a figure slightly
less than that reported by Ghai et al. (1468) and is below the IOth percentile
for U.S. newborns (Gairdner &amp; Pearson, 1971).</p>

<p>The ponderal index, a ratio of birthweight to body length, can be used
to define the end results of fetal growth and nutrition. It is a rather
unique and useful measure for, unlike birthweight, the ponderal index is
not confounded by race, sex, fetal age, or parity when defining malnutrition.
By taking length into consideration, babies who are long, with a relatively
small amount of soft tissue mass, can be seen as having experienced a late
gestation nutritional insult (Brazelton, Parker, Zuckerman, 1976). Based
on research in the Western world, a ponderal index less than 2.3 has been
used to define fetal malnutrition in term infants. The mean ponderal index
for the Indian infant in the present study was 2.36 with a range from 1.88
to 3.28. Using 2.3 as the cut- off point, 45% of the infants would be defined
as malnourished or alternately termed small for gestational age (SGA).
An important question is to determine whether the behavioral characteristics
typical of a SGA infant are manifested by these Indian infants who, be
means of a low P.I., would be defined as such.</p>

<p>Several of the newborn medical factors were interrelated and the significant
correlations between them are shown in Table VI. As may be expected, the
heavier infants are also longer and have larger head circumferences. Infant
length at birth was also negatively related to the ponderal index, which
suggests that low ponderal index infants have a longer birth length. The
ponderal index, however was not significantly correlated with weight gain
at one month. The anthropometric measures of birth weight, length, and
head circumference were positively correlated with weight at one month.
Thus infants who were larger at birth are also larger at one month, which
supports the notion the growth in the early months is a biological function
of infant status at birth.</p>

