State Regulation6.5 1.2   5.8 1.4   6.3 1.1   6.1 1.5   6.2 1.3   4.9 1.6  
Auto regulation 7.0 .7    7.2  .7   7.4 .5    7.6  .5   7.5  .6   7.5  .6
Reflexes        2.2 1.6   1.5 1.5   1.5 1.3   1.9 2.0   1.4 1.5    .5 1.2


</pre>

<p>Habituation. The newborn is equipped at birth with a capacity to shut
out repitious, disturbing, visual, auditory, and tactile stimulation that
might otherwise make excessive demands on his immature physiologic system.
The BNBAS assesses this capacity be measuring the decrement that occurs
in response to a flashlight, bell, rattle, and pinprick. The pinprick,
however, was not administered to the Indian infant. As evident from the
mean scores for the habituation cluster presented in Table VII, this sample
of Indian infants is performing in the optimal range. Their behavior could
be characterized by shutdown of body movements, diminution in blinks and</p>

<pre> TABLE VIII.  

 SUMMARY OF REPEATED MEASURE ANALYSIS OF VARIANCE  

 BNBAS CLUSTER SCORES ON DAYS I, 3, 5, 7, 10 and 30  

 BNBAS Cluster          SS Error      DF       F          P  

 Habituation            141.57        175     13.17      .0001  

 Orientation            371.19        175      2.03      .07  

 Motor                   85.25        175     21.69      .0001  

 Range of State         150.18        175      1.81      .1132  

 Regulation of State    267.93        175      7.58      .0001  

 Autonomic Stability     43.00        175      8.03      .0001  

 Reflexes               381.45        175      4.31      .001  
</pre>

<p>respiratory changes after 4- 6 presentations of stimuli. Moreover, their
performance changes significantly throughout the first month, as identified
from the results of the ANOVA on this cluster presented in Table VIII.
The pattern of mean scores indicates that the scores increase over time
but as well as being linear, the quadratic function indicates that the
scores remain the same on days 5, 7, increase on day 10, and remain the
same on day 30. The linear component accounts for 48.9% of the change,
while the quadratic component accounts for 45.82 of the variation in scores.</p>

<p>The Indian infant's capacity to shut out disturbing visual and auditory
stimulation serves him well when confronting the demands of his environment,
From the moment of birth these infants are exposed to a continuous stream
of intense animate and inanimate stimulation, which characterizes their
small, crowded, and open huts. Their optimal performance on this cluster
reflects the adequacy of their habituation center to adapt to the demands
of a stimulation- rich environment. In interpreting these results it is
proposed that the use of swaddling, a technique practiced by this community,
is related to their optimal habituation response. It is generally believed
that swaddling has a calming, restraining influenced on infants which induces
and extends sleep by reducing the number of startles which may lead to
waking (Chisholm, 1978). Perhaps the most significant medical research
on the effects of swaddling with or without the use of the cradleboard
has been conducted by Lipton, Steinschneider, Richmond, (1965). Based on
experimental evidence they reported that infants who were swaddled slept
more, had reduced levels of motor activity in response to stimulation,
fewer startles, and lower heart rate variability than non- swaddled infants.
According to these authors, the motor restraint imposed by swaddling reduces
the overall arousal level by decreasing afferent proprioceptive stimuli
to the central reticular formation of the brain stem. It appears that the
findings from this investigation support the hypothesis that both the effects
of swaddling and the constant stimulation provided by their environment
are related to these infants' exceptional ability to shut out disturbing
and physiologically threatening environmental stimulation.</p>

<p>Orientation. At birth the infant is equipped with a capacity for processing
complex visual information and for demonstrating visual motor movements
which enable him to follow and fixate on an appealing stimulus. The BNBAS
items used to measure this capacity are the visual and auditory orientation
to inanimate objects (bell, ball) and responsivity to the examiner's face
and/or voice. Although a large within group variation was found, their
overall scores fell at the low- to mid- range level of the scale. Their
behavior can be characterized by stilled and quiet alerting to the stimulus
with smooth or jerky visual tracking for at least 300 are, Only a few of
the infants were able to follow the stimulus with eyes and head 60&quot;
horizontally and 30&quot; vertically, which is characteristic of a more
optimal orientation response. As identified in Table XV the items comprising
this cluster show no significant change over the first 30 days of life
(p(.07). There is, however, a slight increase over time with the means
fluctuating between a low of 4.7 on day 1 and a high score of 5.5 on day
10.</p>

<p>In interpreting the low- to mid- range orientation performance of these
infants which does not improve significantly over time, two hypotheses
may be offered. One difficulty in applying the BNBAS in cross cultural
research is the experimenter's lack of control over environmental circumstances
(de Vries &amp; Super, 1978). For example, the administration manual explicitly
states that the exam should be performed in between feedings and within
a quiet and dimly lit environment (Brazelton, 1973). As the Indian infant
is fed on demand and the exams were often performed in small dark huts,
amidst the confusion of daily activities and the enthusiastic support of
as many as 20 observers, the atmosphere was less than ideal. Thus it may
be suggested that the demands of the environment made it more difficult
for the examiner to bring the infant to the quiet alert state needed to
elicit the infant's optimal orientation response. Perhaps with greater
control over the conditions under which the exam is performed, the overall
mean scores would show some improvement. A second hypothesis offered in
explanation of the consistently low orientation scores speaks to the set
of maternal expectations for the social responsivity of her infant. In
the first month of life there was little evidence of &quot;en face&quot;
behaviors between a mother and her infant. Particularly noteworthy was
the absence of maternal vocalizations towards the infant during any of
the caregiving activities. Even during feedings when the mother would observe
her infant, her glances were perfunctory and without any expectation of
response. Moreover, the typical feeding position, the infant seated sideways
against the mother's outstretched legs, exacerbated the lack of visual
en face regard. The maternal energy seemed to be directed towards ministering
to her infant's physiologic needs with little emphasis placed upon his
emerging social capacities, It is suggested that the type of maternal responsivity
observed during the first month coupled with dark huts, did not create
an environment conducive to the intimate verbal or visual conversations
characterizing mother- infant early interaction in the Western world.</p>

<p>Motor. An illuminating source of information about the newborn can be
obtained through the simple observation of motoric behavior. During the
neonatal exam, motor behavior is assessed by the maturity, tone,and vigor
of motoric movements as well as his capacity for head and neck control.
The repeated measure ANOVA for the motor cluster found a significant increase
in motor performance throughout the first month (p(.0001). The linear,
quadratic and cubic components were significant and accounted for 72.162,162
and 4.9% of the variation, respectively. There is an overall increase from
a mean of 4,3 on day 1 to 5.9 on day 30, The variation in scores between
days 3 and 10 accounts for the quadratic and cubic variation, The type
and kind of motor activity exhibited by this group could be qualitatively
described as mature,somewhat hypertonic and resistant with an air of deliberate
intensity. Their movements were not jerky with restricted arcs characteristic
of the immature infant, nor were they the smooth, well- controlled movements
typifying the healthy, full- term infant, Rather, their vigorous, intensely
driving responses were indicative of the strong motoric potential of these
infants.Largely controlled by state behavior, most motor activity was seen
when the infant was roused to an active state 5 or 6. When resting or in
quiet alert states, random, non- purposeful activity was rarely seen, and
a position of flexion for both arms and legs was the preferred position.
These intensely motorically active infants could be easily consoled through
appropriately supportive tactile maneuvers. Once in a high arousal state
they were easily brought back to the resting position of flexion in both
upper and lower extremities through the restraining tactile responses of
the examiner. Thus, through these motor responses the infants would communicate
their preference for the type and kind of handling they needed to stabilize
their physiologic state.</p>

<p>Mothers typically administered to the infants' needs with quick,abrupt,
and vigorous movements. Grandmothers, who provided most of the care during
the first month of life, were especially rough in their handling of these
small but- motorically active infants. This type of motor stimulation was
most noticeable during the bathing of these infants. Described as well
by other investigators (Hopkins, 1976, Le Boyer, 197~), the Indian bath
is an elaborate, formal routine of daily massage which begins in the first
few days of life and continues throughout the first year. (Photo I) It
begins by placing the infant prone on the mother's outstretched legs and
in turn each part of the body is individually stretched and prodded. Using
tepid water and soap, the lower extremities are massaged first, and are
followed by the arms, back, abdomen, neck, and face. Exhausted from the
intensity of this stimulation, the infants are swaddled and enter into
a prolonged sleep. The abrupt handling of the infant was only observed
during caregiving activities; at other times no efforts were made to stimulate
the infant motorically. Infants were not played with, jazzed- up, nor engaged
in en face play behaviors. Moreover, their motor activity was usually interpreted
as a signal of distress to which the mothers responded with feeding and/or
rocking. To console by rocking, the infant was placed upright on the mother's
outstretched legs. Continuous rocking movements were instigated by tapping
the infant's back, and the infants were required to maintain adequate head
and neck control, The effect of early and constant motor stimulation on
the pattern of development is apparent from comparative data from a group
of Caucasian American middle- class infants. (Landers, 1983). On the individual
item pull- to- sit, which measures girdle strength as well as the degree
of balance between flexor and extensor muscles, the U.S. infant performed
significantly better than the Indian infant on day 1. By day 10, however,
this pattern was reversed, with the Indian infants' mean reaching a high
of 7.1 in comparison to a U.S. mean of 6.0 (pt .005). It was suggested
that the superior performance of the Indian infants by day 10 is evidence
for the interval between their given biologic potential for early motor
development and the type and quality of environmental stimulation they
received.(Photo II).</p>

<p>Range of State. The items comprising this cluster assess the difficulty
in rousing certain Infants from sleep states to an alert state with disturbing
stimuli, the rapidity which they go from sleep to crying, and the lability
that certain infants demonstrate as they move rapidly from one stage to
another, The ANOVA for this sample did not show any significant change
in the Range of State cluster. The overall mean score of 3.5 suggests that
these infants are performing on the lower end of the scale on the rapidity,
peak and lability of state changes. Generally speaking, the infants were
somewhat irritable, and hypersensitive to stimulation as they moved rapidly
into an intense cry state where they were unavailable to respond and interact
with the external environment. Particularly disturbing is the lack of improvement
in the mean scores of this cluster over time. However, one must note the
large standard deviation for this cluster, which speaks to the potential
of strong within- group differences which may be operative. An analysis
of the infant and biomedical factors which may account for these differences
will be presented.</p>

<p>Regulation of State. This cluster assesses the neonate's use of state
behavior and the infant is assessed for his capacity to shut out disturbing
stimulation. The ANOVA for this cluster was significant and shows a decreasing
linear trend over time from a mean score of 6.5 on day 1 to a scare of
4.9 on day 30. The decrease in mean score on day 30 may speak to the scale's
upper limit for this cluster which was reached for these infants on day
10. Perhaps at one month the infant requires increasingly complex and demanding
stimulation from the environment In order to maintain an alert and active
state. Throughout the first 10 days of the infants' life, they are performing
in the mid- to upper range of the scale. They reacted almost instantly
to being cuddled by the examiner by leaning forward and moulding on the
examiner's shoulder and nestling their heads in a crook of the examiner's
neck. Less optimal behaviors would have been characterized by active resistance
or passive involvement to being held by the examiner. This warm responsivity
to the examiner is an important source of rewarding feedback and indicative
of his positive contribution to the infant- caregiver relationship. An
additional indicator of state regulation is the infant's capacity to exhibit
self- quieting behaviors. Even during the first or second exam an infant
would spontaneously bring his state under control by hand to mouth movements.</p>

<p>Autonomic Regulation. This cluster assesses how the infant is responding
to the physiological demands of his immaturity and the stresses of labor
and delivery. In this exam autonomic stability is measured by (1)tremulousness,(2)
amount of startle during an exam, (3) lability of skin color. As seen in
Table VIII, the ANOVA for this cluster was significant and the difference
in mean scores accounted for by both the linear and quadratic trends. Scores
were in the optimal range on day 1 and increased throughout the first 7
days.</p>

<p>By day 7 the scores had stabilized and reached a mean of 7.6. In general
these infants showed few startles and tremors and had good healthy skin
color which changed only minimally throughout the exam. As suggested by
the results of the Habituation cluster, the optimal autonomic regulation
exhibited by these infants may be related to the practice of swaddling.
These data support the results of previous investigators (Lipton, et al.,
1975; Brackbill, 1973; Giacoman, 1971) and suggests that the technique
of swaddling is related to a decrease in the number of startles seen in
the newborn period. It is suggested that this occurs because of the decreased
afferent proprioceptive stimuli to the central reticular formation of the
brain stem which reduces the overall arousal level. It is further argued
that the constant tactile proprioceptive stimulation of the swaddling material
may be an important motor restraint.</p>

<p>Reflex. The reflex cluster, which sums the total number of abnormal
reflex scores so that a higher score indicates a greater number of deviant
reflexes, shows a significant linear trend (p(.001). The decrease in mean
scores from a high of 2.2 to a low of .5 shows the pattern of recovery
in reflex activity during the first month of life, Of the 16 elicited reflexes
an increased sucking, rooting response, as well as decreased walking stepping,
and incurvation response, accounted for most of the deviation in the early
days of life. The exaggerated sucking and rooting response can be related
to hunger and rate of milk flow (Brazelton, et al., 1976), and in the early
exams these infants did show signs of hunger. The hypotonic walking and
stepping responses seen early on may also be the result of depleted nutritional
stores as a result of poor intrauterine growth. Incurvation of the trunk
often did not appear until the 5th or 7th day exam. Asymmetry was also
apparent with the response first emerging on one side only. According to
Prechtl Beintema,(1964), this response is often absent in the first few
days and thus this decreased response was not indicative of any abnormality.
In general,the reflex activity of these infants was evidence in favor of
an intact central nervous system.</p>

<p>In summary, the repeated measure analysis of variance provided a description
of the BNBAS performance of a group of 30 healthy South Indian newborns
in the first month of life, The most salient finding is the increase in
performance over time on the Habituation, Motor, Autonomic Stability, and
Reflex clusters. For each of these clusters, optimal performance was seen
on day 30, following a general systematic up and down pattern on days 5,
7, 10. On two of the seven clusters, Habituation and Autonomic Regulation,
the infants performed in the optimal range. Mid- range performance was
seen initially on both the Orientation and Range of State clusters and
showed no significant improvement throughout the first month. This behavioral
profile was interpreted as an interactive effect of environment forces
and cultural practices on early infant behavioral and neurological development.
In particular the analysis focused on the following three aspects of their
environments and included (1) the effects of swaddling on infant development,(2)
the type and quality of motor stimulation, and (3)mother- infant interaction
and its effect on the infant's social responsivity. It was suggested that
the optimal performance on the habituation and Autonomic Regulation clusters
was related to the restraining and calming influences of the swaddling
techniques employed by this community. Specific maternal behaviors were
hypothesized to contribute to the development of infant motor activity,
specifically the combination of vigorous motor, stimulation coupled with
constraining and consoling behaviors. Finally, it was suggested that the
poor orientation responses exhibited by these infants was related to the
lack of maternal expectations for social responsivity and the less than
ideal circumstances under which the exam was performed.</p>

<p><b>MATERNAL FACTORS AND BRAZELTON SCALE PERFORMANCE</b></p>

<p>It has been suggested that BNBAS performance is affected by several
infant and maternal biomedical factors and that these relationships may
vary within different cultural groups (Lester &amp; Brazelton, 1982). In
an effort to determine the extent to which these forces are operative within
this sample of infants their BNBAS performance was correlated with a number
of maternal and infant variables. Maternal factors included in the analysis
were age, parity, height, weight, arm circumference, family wealth, and
literacy. Infant behavior was measured by performance on BNBAS cluster
scores at three time periods throughout the first month. Exams performed
on the 1st and 3rd days characterized an early exam, the middle period
consisted of exams on days 5,7, and 10 with the final or late exam performed
on day 30. Several of these correlations were significant and the results
are presented in Table IX.</p>

<pre>Table IX.
Correlations: Maternal Medical/Social Factors
And Infant Behavior (BNBAS)

                                        
                                                Arm     Family
                                                Circum- Wealth
