<pre>                     
* Head Circumference was not significant.
**Early Exam. Performed on Days 1, 3.
   Middle Exam. Performed on Days 5, 7, 10.
   Late Exam. Performed on Day 30.
` p&lt;.05
`'p&lt;.01


</pre>

<p>Birth weight had the most effect on BNBAS outcome, and an interesting
behavioral profile typifying the smaller infants began to emerge. Negative
associations were found for the Habituation and Range of State clusters.
This suggests more optimal performance by the lower weight infant in the
ability to shut out disturbing stimuli and the capacity to move slowly
from one state to another. Thus the lower weight infants could both maintain
deep sleep states and are somewhat less vulnerable to the manipulations
and ministrations of the examiner. Because of their optimal state regulation
they were less easily excited and came to and maintained an alert state
4 for longer periods of time. An increase in the number of deviant reflexes
was related to low birthweight, an association which was significant on
both middle and late exams.</p>

<p>The association between motor performance and birthweight was positive,
which suggests that the heavier infants had more optimal motor behavior,
as assessed by tone, maturity, pull- to- see behavior, defensive movements,
and activity, An enhanced motor performance was also positively related
to birth length during the middle examination periods. There were no significant
associations between head circumference and infant behavior. Weight at
one month was positively correlated to the Orientation cluster on the final
exam and negatively correlated to the reflex cluster during the middle
examination period. Thus, those infants who weighed the most at one month
exhibited better alerting, orienting, and following responses to both inanimate
and animate stimulation. The relationship to the Reflex cluster implies
that the number of deviant reflexes seen in the middle examination period
was greater for those infants who weighed less at one month. The Ponderal
Index (P.I.), which is a length for weight ration, was computed for each
infant and correlated with BNBAS cluster scores (Brazelton et al., 1976).
The P.T. was used in the assessment of fetal malnutrition such that a Low
score indicates thinness and a high score obesity. The P.I. was associated
in the early exam period with the reflex cluster and with the State Regulation
cluster in the middle exam period. These correlations suggested that a
P.I., indicative of thinness, was associated with an increased number of
deviant reflex scores and a decreased capacity for state regulation. These
infants were somewhat more irritable, hyper responsive to stimulation,
and less able to console themselves when upset.</p>

<p>These data suggest that the low P.I. and lighter weight infants in the
sample are somewhat, although not dramatically, distinct and rather curiously
so, as their associations to INBAS cluster scores were not always in the
direction anticipated. It appears that the low P.I. infants had less capacity
for state regulation and an increased number of deviant reflex scores.
The smaller weight infant had better habituation and range of state performance
with an increased number of deviant reflexes and poorer motor performance
than the heavier infants in this sample.</p>

<p>In order to obtain a more complete understanding of the effects of birthweight
and the ponderal index on infant behavior, a one- way repeated measure
analysis of variance (ANOVA) was performed to see if either birthweight
or P.I. had any effect BNBAS performance. The sample was divided into 3
groups according to the 75th, 50th and 25th percentile distribution for
birthweight and ponderal index. The percentile distribution for birthweight
defined the following groups: Group I included those infants weighing below
the 25th percentile of 2,525 gms, Group 2 consisted of infants with a birthweight
of or below the 50th percentile, while Group 3 included those infants falling
above or below the 75th percentile, which was calculated at 3,030 gms.
The sample, when divided according to the distribution of P.I. scores,
was classified as follows: Group 1 had an index on or below the 25th percentile
of 2.11, Group 2 consisted of those infants with a P.I. of or below the
50th percentile of 2.24, while Group 3 had a P.I. below or above the 2.50
which was the 75th Percentile Rating, the BNBAS outcome was measured by
the rate of change in performance as estimated by the slope of the best
fitting regression line for each of the clusters.(Landers, 1983) The slope
of the best fitting regression line, computed for each of the 7 BNBAS clusters
was used to indicate the rate of change on that cluster over the first
month of life for each of the 3 birthweight groups as well as each of the
3 P.Z. groups. As a result of these two analyses, it was found that neither
birthweight nor P.I. had any significant effects on the rate of change
in BNBAS cluster scores. It appears that the trends observed from the correlational
analysis between BNBAS performance and infant factors were not apparent
upon further inspection of the data. In light of this information, one
may conclude that the variability in BNBAS performance as measured by the
rate of change in cluster scores exhibited by this sample of infants cannot
be accounted for by the singular effects of either birthweight or ponderal
index.</p>

<p>The simple correlation analysis of maternal, infant, and environmental
factors on infant outcome in the first three months presented in the preceding
discussion, indicated several important relationships which may be operating
within this sample. Such an analysis however was based on the assumption
that there are clear sequences of linear causality between variables of
infant risk status and later developmental outcome, Based on the extensive
reviews of single- factor studies and their inability to explain relations
between risk factors, one is well aware of the limitations inherent in
this approach.(Clarke and Clarke, 1976; McCall et al., 1972; Sameroff and
Chandler, 1975). By contrast, risk scores that are based on multiple factors
produce clearer results (Hobel,'et al., 1973; Prechtl, 1968). It is hypothesized
that the combination of risk variables will account for a greater amount
of the neonatal variability exhibited by this sample. For a more complete
understanding of the interaction between the biologic, cultural and social
factors, the reader is referred to the multiple factor analysis performed
on this data set. (Landers, 1983).</p>

<p><b>INFANT DEVELOPMENT AT THREE MONTHS</b></p>

<p>Anthropometric Indicators. In an effort to monitor the path of early
infant growth anthropometric data and Bayley scores were obtained at 3
months. All assessment procedures were performed within the home environment.
The means,standard deviations, and range for these items are presented
in Table XI.</p>

<pre>
TABLE XI.
MEAN, STANDARD DEVIATION, AND RANGE OF OUTCOME
MEASURES AT 3 MONTHS

                                Mean            S.D.         Range
Weight (kg)                     5.92            1.0          4 - 8
Length (cm)                     61.3            2.5         55.0-66.0
Head Circumference (cm)         40.3            2.2          37-47
Bayley Mental Develop-
mental Index (MDI)              108.6          13.9          72 - 131
Bayley Motor Develop-
mental Index (PDI)              129.2          20.5          50 - 151

</pre>

<p>The weight at 3 months ranged from 4.0 kg - 8.0 kg with a mean of 5.92
kg. Males were slightly heavier than females with a mean of 6.0 kg and
5.84 respectively. When the weights of the Indian infants were compared
to U.S. standards the following picture emerged. For boys, 12% were above
the 90th percentile, 332 fell between 50th and 90th percentile; 22% fell
between 50th and IOth percentile while 22% fell below the 1Oth percentile.
For girls the weight distribution according to U.S. standards was as follows;
33% fell above the 90th percentile, 33% fell between 50th and 90th percentile,
while one child fell below the 1Oth percentile. Figures I and II graphically
display this distribution.</p>

<p><img src="culfig1.gif" border=0  height=225 width =293 >Boys Weight
at Birth, One and Three Months <img src="culfig2.gif" border=0  height=221 width =318 >Girls
Weight at Birth, One and Three Months </p>

<p><i>Charts based on Western standards. Prepared by Drs. D. Gairdner and
J. Pearson. Published and distributed by Castleread Publications, Castleread,
Hertford, England, 1971.</i></p>

<p>As the graphs portray, the velocity of growth from birth to 3 months
is quite remarkable. The average gain in weight was 3.16 kg which is compared
to an average gain of 2.5 kg for U.S. infants (Lowery, 1973). According
to Western pediatric standards, birthweight should double by 5 months (Lowery,
1973). For this sample, 65% of the infants had doubled their birth weights
by three months. The two additional measures of infant growth, length and
head circumference, showed similar increases throughout the first 3 months,
The mean crown- heel length was 61.3 cm which corresponds to the 90th percentile
of U.S. standards. Similarly, the mean head circumference for this group
(40.3 cm) corresponded to the 50th percentile. By comparison, it is interesting
to note that at birth, the mean head circumference for this sample fell
below the U.S. 1Oth percentile.</p>

<p>The mean weight for this sample is slightly higher than the weights
reported by various investigators throughout India (Udani, 1963; Currimbhoy,
1963; Swaminathan, Jyothi, Singh, Madhavad, and Gopalan, 1964; Ghai &amp;
Sandhu, 1968; ZCMR, 1972). The All India mean weight for 3 month old infants
is 4.0 kg, while the mean reported for this sample stems in part from the
selection of only healthy full term infants and its longitudinal design.
Moreover the majority of Indian investigations have been cross- sectional
and include infants of all birth weights.</p>

<p>Bayley Performance. The Bayley Scale was administered to each infant
and the Mental Development Index (MDI) and Psychomotor Development Index
(PDI) were calculated (Bayley, 1969). These indices are a normalized standard
score with a mean of 100 and a range from 50- 150 which covers more than
3 standard deviations on either side of the mean. For this sample, the
mean MDT was 108.6 with a range of 72- 131. The motor index yielded a slightly
higher mean score of 129.2 and a range which spanned the entire scale.
It was further noted that 23% of the Indian infants had a motor index of
140 or above, a score achieved by less than 10% of the U.S. infants. While
Indian infants performed similarly to U.S. infants in tasks of cognitive
development, specific items on the motor scale were in advance of the norms.
These included the gross motor abilities such as head balance, sits along
momentarily, and the ability to roll over from back to stomach. More than
50% of the Indian infants at 3 months of age passed these items in comparison
to the mean age of 4.2, 5.3 and 6,4 months for the standardized U.S. sample.
In fine motor performance, partial thumb opposition while holding a cube
was more advanced for the Indian sample. These data add support to the
notion of an enhanced motor development suggested by the analysis of Brazelton
data in the first month of life.</p>

<p>Table XII presents the correlations between the 3 months outcome measures.
</p>

<pre>CORRELATION MATRIX OF 3 MONTH OUTCOME MEASURES

                                           Head
                        Weight  Length  Circumference   MDI     PDI

                                                
