</pre>

<p>As indicated in the table, the MDI and PDI were highly correlated at
.64 which supports the premise that early motor and cognitive development
are highly correlated. It is argued that motor development, through its
emphasis on and concern with the development of sensory and motor processes
associated with active movement and physical exploration of the external
environment, provides the basic foundation for the development of a higher
ordered information processing system upon which more sophisticated perceptual
and cognitive processes are ultimately built. The evidence suggests that
the feedback provided to the young infant as a result of its active exploration
and interaction with the environment is a stimulation for continued perceptual
and cognitive growth.(Williams, 1983). While there were no significant
correlations between the MID and anthropometric variables, the PDI was
correlated with both the infant's weight(.53) and length (.39) at 3 months
and suggests that the larger infants were more motorically advanced than
the smaller infants. Furthermore, the PDI was significantly correlated
to weight at one month (.50) and positively although not significantly
related to weight at birth.</p>

<p>In summary, the data described the growth of a group of healthy infants
which can be characterized by a dramatic rate of physical growth, advanced
motor performance and patterns of cognitive development similar to the
standards defined by U.S. infants. This pattern of development mirrors
the course of adaption witnessed in the first month of life.</p>

<p><b>DISCUSSION</b></p>

<p>Based on conceptions of high risk perinatal factors in pregnancy developed
in this country (Prechtl, et al. 1968; Hobel, Hyvarinen, and Okada,1973)
many of the mothers in this sample would have been placed in a high risk
category. The factors, such as low weight, small stature, high parity,
poor pregnancy weight gain, non- antiseptic techniques, and unmonitored
deliveries, coupled with the environmental conditions of crowded, poor,
dark huts would have defined them at risk. In spite of these circumstances
the infants produced were small but motorically organized and physically
intact. Those infants with a low P.I. indicative of intrauterine malnutrition
did not exhibit to the same degree the hypersensitive, irritable behaviors
characterizing the full term but undernourished infant from this country.
The pattern of recovery exhibited by this group of infants throughout the
first month of life was even more dramatic by 3 months of age. Their developmental
profile was characterized by an increased velocity of physical growth,
advanced motor development and patterns of cognitive performance which
were similar to standards set by U.S. infants at three months of age. The
data presented here bring to the forefront a number of increasingly complex
and important issues in infancy research. Although exploratory in nature,
these findings challenge a number of widely accepted assumptions concerning
the relationship between pre- and perinatal circumstances and infant growth.
In accepting this challenge one is required to acknowledge a number of
models that may be operative. These data lend themselves to the consideration
of three perspectives which include, (I) the efficacy and adaptability
of the biological organism to overcome the demands of a stressful environment,
(2) the effectiveness of culturally adapted infant rearing patterns, and
(3) the unique psychological make- up and identity development of the Indian
woman. The insights provided by these perspectives will be discussed.</p>

<p>Biological Adaptability. In the first instance it is suggested that
the behavior of this group of infants exemplifies the adaptability of the
human infant when confronted with continued and persistent stress to return
to a predetermined developmental pathway. In this perspective one does
not wish to underemphasize the stressful nutritonal, obstetrical, and social
factors of the maternal pre- and perinatal environment but rather to underscore
the awesome capacity of the species to adjust in accordance with the degree
of stress imposed, The developmental pattern described by this group of
infants emphasizes the preadapted variability in the human infant, especially
as it functions to overcome the obstacles to growth under less than ideal
circumstances. They demonstrated the ability of the human species to over
come deflection and to return to a predetermined developmental pathway
which, as Waddington (1962) has suggested, is in itself a biological goal.
This process was particularly salient in the dramatic catch- up weight
gain exhibited by this sample during the first three months of life. By
three months of age 58% of the infants were above the 50th percentile of
weight based on U.S. standards as compared to the birth weights where only
one infant was above the 50th percentile and 48.22 fell below the 1Oth
percentile.</p>

<p>The pattern of infant feeding displayed by this community was characterized
by constant maternal proximity and availability which enabled breast feeding
on demand. It is argued that the biologic capacity for catch- up growth
is inherent in our species, and the maternal feeding practices described
allowed this preprogrammed adaptability to unfold. For example the antibodies,
lysozomes, lympocytes, macrophanes and other components of colostrum and
transitional breast milk, serve to defend against infection which may have
been the major 'predator' during evolution (Stohiar, Pelley, Kaniecki-
Green, and Klaus, 1976; Jelliffe &amp; Jelliffe, 1971; Gyorgy, 1967; Goldman&amp;
Smith, 1973; Lozoff, Brittenham, Trause, Kennell, and Klaus, 1977). Because
of these properties, a significantly enhanced resistance to enteric infection
has been observed among breast fed babies not only when the environment
is favorable but also when the environmental sanitation was at less than
acceptable levels (Mata, 1978; Mata b Wyatt, 1971). In addition the composition
of breast milk is particularly well suited to the pattern of feeding exhibited
by the mothers of this community, In species which nest or cache their
infants, breast milk is high in protein and fat,mother- infant contact
is intermittent and feedings are spaced from 2 to 15 hours apart (Dumond,
1975). Be receiving their total nutritional requirements in short periods
these infants are adapted for long separations. In contrast, species which
are carried by, hibernate with, or follow their mothers have low fat,low
protein breast milk, constant maternal- infant contact, and essentially
continuous feeding (Ben- Shaw~62). Human milk is low in fat and extremely
low in proteins. Since human infant is immobile at birth, the insights
of comparative physiology have identified the pattern of human care as
that of carrying and continuous feeding (Blurton- Jones, 1972). Thus the
cultural patterns of continuous feeds, made possible through constant maternal
availability, support, reinforce, and enhance the biologic pre- adaptability
of our species. When viewed in this light the ability of these small infants
to exhibit catch- up growth is simply part of the developmental script
of the human species. The more enlightening issue raised by these data
relates to our understanding of developmental deviations. It suggests that
early deviations from expected patterns of growth occur from environmental
forces which constrain and defeat the organism's selfrighting tendencies
and inherent ability to return to the path of normality (Sameroff, 1975).</p>

<p>Child Rearing Patterns. A second conceptual issue raised by the data
relates to the role of the child rearing environment and its ability to
influence the developmental pathway. It is proposed that in this highly
supportive environment even the most vulnerable infants were integrated
into the family in a manner which fostered- their capacity for recovery.
In commenting on this issue LeVine (1977, p. 16) states, &quot;. . . that
cultural evolution within human populations also produces standardized
strategies of survival for infants and children, strategies reflecting
environmental pressures from a more recent past, encoded in customs rather
than genes and transmitted socially rather than biologically.&quot; The
patterns of infant rearing exhibited by this community and their effects
on development address specifically the quality and quantity of tactile-
kinesthetic stimulation and the degree and kind of maternal social responsivity.
A review of the possible effects of these behaviors on early infant development
follows.</p>

<p>As described earlier, the motoric stimulation received by these infants,
reflected in the elaborate daily bath and massage, seemed particularly
well- suited to these motorically precocious infants and paved the way
for increasingly complex motor organization. At three months of age they
were above U.S. standards for motor development as measured on the Bayley,
with certain items involving head control 2- 3 months ahead of U.S. norms.
Active motoric stimulation was complemented by swaddling techniques which
seemed to be related to an increased capacity to habituate to disturbing
stimulation and maintain autonomic regulation as measured by the Brazelton
scale throughout the first month. It was suggested that these tactile-
kinethestic ministrations are directly related to the advanced motor performance
characterizing this group of infants in the early months of life. Rapid
motor development in infancy has been reported by other cross cultural
investigators (Super, 1981a; 1981b). Fundamental to all these cultures
is the increased amount of kinesthet stimulation, maternal proximity, and
rapid response to distress signals.</p>

<p>Experimental studies of the human infant given supplemental kinesthetic
stimulation confirm these findings. Kinesthetic stimulation was found to
exert a reinforcing effect on the smiling response of four to five month
old infants (Brossard &amp; DeCarie, 1968) and to be more effective than
tactile stimulation in soothing the neonate (Korner &amp; Thoman,1972).
In another study, premature in supplementary kinesthetic stimulation by
rocking for 30 minutes each day had significant weight gains when compared
to matched controls (Freedman, cited in Ambrose, 1969). Scarr- Salapatek
and Williams (1973), investigating the effects of early stimulation on
low birth weight infants, found that infants who received increased visual
tactile and kinesthetic stimulation in the first year had better grasp
reflexes, greater alertness, and increased weight gain at 4 weeks of age
and higher Cartel scores at one year. In a study of six month old infants,
Yarrow,Rubenstein, and Pedersen, (1975) found that among all the sensory
modes investigated, kinesthetic vestibular stimulation was of singular
importance.</p>

<p>A second area in which the culture of Indian infancy exhibits an adaptive
pattern of response, focuses on the type and quality of maternal social
responsivity. Mothers, following rather than leading while interacting
with their infants, responded instantly to the slightest indication of
infant distress. In the early months of life distress hunger call and the
infants pacified by feeding, Particularly apparent was the paucity of maternal
vocalizations directed towards the infant in conjunction with caregiving
behaviors. Although their environments exposed them to a constant stream
of human speech, they were rarely the direct recipients of vocal exchange.
The adaptive element of maternal behaviors concealed in patterns of child
rearing is suggested by these observations. One may assume that the Indian
mother's immediate response to her infant's distress is an adaptive reaction
to the pressures of a harsh physical environment and threats of high rates
of infant mortality. At the same time,her behavior conforms to the culture's
emphasis and value for dependency at the expense of behaviors which shape
the infant towards autonomous, creative and individualized functioning.</p>

<p>A number of investigators have been concerned with the specific effects
of contingent responsiveness distress on infant development. Lewin and
Goldberg (1969) suggested that the infant's awareness of a contingent relationship
with his caregiver promotes cognitive development and reported a significant
relationship between maternal contingent behavior and the infant's habituation
to a redundant stimulus, a measure believed to be a primary indicator of
cognitive development. in a study of the maternal responsiveness to an
infant's cry, it was found that a decreased latency of response resulted
in a decreased amount of crying in the first year. Speculating that the
infant's use of the cry as social communication is enhanced by the maternal
contingent response, the authors rejected the notion that a rapid response
to crying may interfere with the child's level of competence (Yarrow et
al.,1975). A study of 6 month old infants reported by Yarrow et al.(1975)
found that a high level of maternal contingent response to distress was
associated with higher scores on the Bayley scale. In addition, three measures
of cognitive motivation were positively associated and included goal directedness,
reaching and grasping, and secondary circular relations. In interpreting
these results the authors speculated that immediate response to an infant's
distr$ss may facilitate the infant's motivation to interact with the environment.
Goal directedness, a measure indexing persistent attempts to secure objects
not immediately available, and secondary circular reactions, behaviors
involving the repetitionof actions to produce feedback, may be early expressions
ofthe infant's~attempt to master the environment. The observations of the
present study support the results of past investigators, and suggest that
the rapid maternal responsivity to an infant's cry reinforces active coping
with his environment and enhances his persistance in eliciting feedback.</p>

<p>In describing the beliefs and practices typifying early infant care
in this South Indian community, the analytical framework of childrearing
as cultural adaptation defined by LeVine (1977) is particularly applicable.
The data presented here support his conclusion that culture no less than
biology contributes to the way in which parents perceive the tasks of childrearing.
Moreover these ways are rational, and contain information about environmental
contingencies previously experienced by the population and assimilated
into its cultural tradition. parents who ridgidly conform to customary
prescriptions may be unaware of their past or present efficacy but may
view them as religiously or ethically ordained. Finally as LeVine states,
if we are to understand the constraints within which cultural values operate
and to assess the prospects of change, the adaptive component concealed
in childrearing customs must be clarified (LeVine, 1977, p. 17).</p>

<p>Maternal Commitment. Finally, the ability of these infants to meet the
demands of their environment warrants the investigation of the powerful
psychosocial commitment of the Indian mother to the survival of her infant
and the confidence with which she ministers to his needs. The maternal
behaviors defined a pattern of responsivity rather striking to the Western
observer. From the moment of birth the infant is greeted and surrounded
by unyielding physical ministrations, and the Indian mother is inclined
towards total indulgence of her infant's wishes and demands. As previously
described, this deference and indulgence in Indian motherhood has psychological
origins in the identity development of the Indian woman (Kakar, 1978).
It is argued that this psyche- social development evolves from the interplay
between universal processes of human development and the set historical
trends,religious ideals and social institutions unique to the Indian culture.
It is further suggested that the maternal response to the demands of her
infant reflect both her deeply rooted emotional stance towards her infant
and the culture's perception of and value for che child. The Indian mothers'
psyche- social commitment to her child emerges out of an extended family
system which instructs, rewards, and supports her in these efforts. According
to Kakar's (1978) analysis, this deference and indulgence in Indian motherhood
has psychological origins in the identity development of the Indian woman.
As a daughter, an Indian girl is but a sojourner in her own family, and
in marriage her status is changed to daughter- in- law rather than wife.
It is only with motherhood that she comes into her own and can establish
her position within the family, community and the life cycle. Her role
from thence forward is a powerful one. According to the teachings of her
culture and reflected in the popular devotional Krishna mythology, the
child has been traditionally perceived as a completely innocent being,
a gift of the gods, towards whom one is expected to shower their deepest
protection, affection and indulgence (Kakar, 1979). According to traditional
Hindu thought, it is the child, in his spontaneity and intense capacity
for sorrow and joy, who comes closest to the divine state. It is the adult
who must learn what it is the child has to teach (Kinsley,1977).</p>

<p>As these data emphasize, the application of universal risk factors in
development muse be viewed with caution for the mechanisms through which
they exert their effect varies both between and within cultures. For a
given factor, the degree of risk imposed is directly related to the culturally
defined structures and institutions which have evolved to buffer its impact.
Thus, we must continue in~our efforts to construct paradigms that allow
for the systematic analysis of the contexts which directly and indirectly
influence the developmental pathway.</p>

