<html><head>
<title>SECOND INTER-AGENCY
MEETING ON COMMUNITY-BASED
APPROACHES
FOR CHILD DEVELOPMENT
</title></head>
<body> 
<h3 align=center>
SECOND INTER-

AGENCY
MEETING ON COMMUNITY-

BASED
APPROACHES<p>
FOR CHILD DEVELOPMENT<p>
(New York, 29-

31
October 1984)<p>
<p>
<u>MOVING TO SCALE:</u><p>
<u></u><p>
<u></u><p>
<u>Early Childhood Education Project in Kenya</u>
</h3><p>
<u></u><p>
<u>A note for discussion from the Bernard van Leer Foundation</u><p>
<p>
<p>
For more than a decade the Kenya Institute of Education within the Ministry of
Education has collaborated with the Bernard van Leer Foundation in a project to
enhance the quality of pre-

school
education in Kenya. Starting in 1972, this project launched in Nairobi a small,
intensive man-

power
and curriculum development programme. After gradual changes in strategy, the
project was operating, by 1982, in five districts of Kenya varying from central
urban to coastal and isolated mountain environments. From this evolved
strategies for mutual support between pre-

school
and community, in-

service
training, localized curricula and materials. Based on the experience of the
project, the Ministry of Education is now setting up a national programme for
training and support of pre-

school
teachers and other kinds of child workers. For this a national centre for early
childhood education is being created within the institute of Education with
small satellite centres being set up in various districts.<p>
<p>
This paper attempts to describe the project history to allow for a thorough
understanding of most of the processes underlying its growth, of which many
were planned but many were unforeseen. Thus the Kenyan case provides a vivid
backdrop against which a number of questions pertinent to this conference can
be posed.<p>
<p>
How can a controlled exercise in educational innovation in an area which is not
a top national priority develop both as a technically sound undertaking in
itself and as a mechanism for influencing evolution of policy in directions
favourable to low-

cost
early education for the deprived child?<p>
<p>
What are the criteria used in recruiting project staff, what weight should be
given to formal education as opposed to non-

formal
education, socio-

economic
background and personality features such as creativity and flexibility?<p>
<p>
As chance and unforeseen factors play important roles in evolution of projects
how, then, should projects be designed as to allow for unplanned
developments?<p>
<p>
Under what conditions and for what purposes should projects be assisted by
external or expatriate advisers?<p>
<p>
What sort of relationship should be pursued in working with local authorities
and communities to permit optimal cooperation and sustainability?<p>
<p>
What measures should be taken to successfully include the elusive poorest of
the poor into social intervention programmes ?<p>
<p>
<u>The term pre-

school
education</u> is used in this paper to describe early childhood education
structures for children up to 6 years. In urban areas there are private nursery
schools which charge high fees and also day nurseries run by the Nairobi City
Council which cater for children of parents from all socio-

economic
levels. In rural Kenya the structures are somewhat different. The pre-

school
education system has its origin in the self-

help
movement known as harambee, where the community is responsible for building the
nursery schools and employing the teachers and other workers.<p>
<p>
Construction and maintenance of the physical plant lies almost entirely with
the community. The parents as well as professionals who support these pre-

schools
largely perceive their benefit not only in academic preparation for primary
schooling but also in provision of health and care for their children as many
parents are involved in development activities which leaves them little time to
take care of their children.<p>
<p>
What is significant to observe here is the expansion of the pre-

school
movement in Kenya within the harambee paradigm. In 1968 the number of children
enrolled in self-

help
pre-

school
institutions was nearly 180,000. Now enrolment has risen to roughly 500,000.
However, the proportion of children between 3 and 6 years in early childhood
frameworks still remains<p>
slightly less than 20% of the total age group. This represents only 10% of the
total child population estimated at 4.5 million. Considering that Kenya's
population growth rate is 4%, a major effort is indeed required to provide
adequate services for all children.<p>
<p>
<u>Start-

up
of the project</u><p>
<p>
For the Kenyan educators who would soon be involved in the project supported by
the Bernard van Leer Foundation, the essential challenge was to enhance
dramatically the quality of nursery schools which had been created. They felt
this challenge was closely linked to the staff's lack of training and to the
limited training resources in the country. A number of agencies and ministries
were involved in providing training for pre-

school
teachers. However the output from these efforts was small and training
opportunities by-

passed
the nursery school workers who lacked basic educational qualifications needed
to enter formal training programmes.<p>
<p>
In 1969, first contacts between Kenyan authorities and the Bernard van Leer
Foundation took place they agreed on cooperating on developing a cognitively-

oriented
experimental training programme in early childhood education. The intended
programme was very modest in scope: to train a small cadre of supervisors who
might in turn give training to others. From this point, however, the
Foundation, the Ministry of Education and, in particular, the Kenya Institute
of Education which carried out the project, has taken it through many
metamorphoses.<p>
<p>
The six year project proposal agreed on in 1971 called for the development of a
teacher training programme, a model nursery school curriculum and the training
of personnel to serve as nursery school supervisors.<p>
<p>
<u>Nairobi Project 1972-

1976</u><p>
<p>
At the outset it was decided to place the project within the Kenya Institute of
Education (KIE), a department of the Ministry of Education. This decision meant
that some time and effort would be required initially to build resources-

-
human
and material-

-
in
the early childhood domain as the<p>
Ministry of Education had not previously been involved in this field.<p>
<p>
A second important decision was to mount the project in Nairobi as it was
argued that the necessary infrastructure for early childhood education was
strongest in and around the capital. It turned out however that due to
difficulty in eliciting local cooperation the project did not succeed in
entering the poorer areas of the city.<p>
<p>
Project activities began in 1972 at the Kenya Institute of Education and up to
1975 the project trained 45 teachers and supervisors from the city, education
and public health departments. All participants were trained primary school
teachers drawn from various schools in the city. Although they were qualified
teachers they tended to be rigid and formal in their practices -


a result of their previous experiences. That this added further challenges to
the project trainers is implied in the comment of one participant:<p>
<p>
I still remember some (participants) refusing to make materials, such as papier
mache, since it looked messy. When we were digging the small shamba near the
Institute some refused to hold jembes (hoes) or to carry things to the store or
sweep the classroom.<p>
<p>
These obviously were activities not done in primary schools.<p>
<p>
The two year training programme for Nairobi teachers had two major components:
one year of residential training and one year of internship. The residential
course dealt with child development, educational psychology, play and physical
activities, language skills, number work, and environmental activities, music
and movement, creative abilities, health and safety and the development of
materials. The course unintentionally focused on work with 5 year olds only.
The scope of the course has however widened significantly later on. During the
internship year the teachers worked in day nurseries or pre-

school
units attached to some primary schools.<p>
<p>
The training programme succeeded in bringing about major, positive changes in
the teachers' skills and behaviours. Their placement in pre-

school
units after completion of the training programme helped stimulate the expansion
of pre-

school
units from four in 1974 to forty-

one
in 1984. Over the subsequent five years, many of the teachers remained active
in the field of early childhood education and care, some of them taking up
training or supervisory roles as originally envisaged.<p>
<p>
The period of the Nairobi project provided an excellent opportunity to build
capacities of-

the
project unit not only in training, but also in planning and evaluation. A
dedicated core staff was formed. They have remained with the project for more
than a decade -

-

providing remarkable continuity, technical excellence and field knowledge. This
group participated in all aspects of project development including training,
evaluation, planning and the alteration of plans. This cadre also started
developing new strategies for project implementation. For example, as they
have described it:<p>
<p>
At this stage, the project staff decided to depart from the usual curriculum
development procedures which rarely involve teachers and children. Instead the
project staff drew heavily on the experience of the teachers and involved them
in actually writing the books. The staff considered this an important step
because teachers can communicate with other teachers through examples of what
they themselves have carried out successfully and through their knowledge of
the problems they have encountered.<p>
<p>
<u>Curriculum</u><p>
<p>
The books and manuals produced at this time had an urban bias and were too
sophisticated linguistically for use in rural areas. Nonetheless, the materials
eschewed a "canned" approach to curricula, emphasized the development of
curriculum materials together with the training process, and emphasized the
well rounded development of children presenting approaches that stimulate
children's ideas and interests through manipulation of the local environment.<p>
<p>
The project has conscientiously avoided developing a prescriptive national
curriculum for pre-

school
education in view of the University of cultures, language and environment which
would be the main sources of curriculum. In lieu of this, it has collected,
organized or produced learning and teaching materials. Teachers guides and
resource books have been developed, and so have children's books in three local languages. Proto-

types
of concrete and manipulative materials have also been developed with the
teachers/parents manual on how to make them. Throughout, the project has linked
training and curriculum development processes closely. The training
has aimed to stimulate the teacher to be major source of suitable curriculum in
that she relates the activities to her environment. During the training the
teachers and trainers have to draw heavily on their own experiences and
environment to build up a store of methods and materials.<p>
<p>
In part, this strategy may have derived from making a so-

called
virtue out of a necessity as there is no established system for distribution of
educational materials for pre-

schools
and nurseries around the country. Furthermore, the task of providing curricula
or other printed materials in
major local languages would be formidable.<p>
<p>
<u>Move to Rural Areas 1976-

1978</u><p>
<p>
As pointed out the main aim of the project was the development of pre-school
education manpower. Training was therefore the main component of the total
project. After the two training programmes were completed the need to move to
the rural areas was evident if the project was to come out with a viable
training programme that could be replicated throughout the country.  These
would have facilitated the experimentation of materials and training styles in
the rural setting where a majority of the community nursery schools are to be
found.  Surveys were  conducted in a number of districts and municipalities and
Kiambu and Murang'a were selected as both councils had shown great interest in
pre-

schools
and had employed a large number of teachers from which the project could select
trainees for its training programme. Between them there were, in 1975, about
650 pre-

school
teachers working largely supported by the County Councils or parents'
communities.<p>
<p>
As project staff expected, they found that the rural teachers, without training
and with limited reading skills or experience in using printed materials,
tended to "teach" little children in ways unrelated to their needs. As a staff
member of the project noted:<p>
<p>
Teaching is mainly verbal and little attempt is made to help children develop a
basic understanding of concepts that lay the foundation for future learning. A
lot of time is spent on memorising letters and numerals and on rote counting.
Singing is a major part of the daily programme. Many songs are in English. The
teachers generally have no specific aim in teaching these songs and are not
concerned about whether the songs are meaningful to the children. In language
activities, children memorise English words with their meanings in the mother
tongue. The teacher places great emphasis on training in English, as this is
equated with education. Despite these shortcomings, children who have been to
nursery school settle down quickly when they enter primary school because they
have learned to listen to the teacher, to concentrate for a period of time and
to interact with other children. (A-

p.9-
10)<p>
<p>
Little had been done to analyse the needs of children and teachers. With this
in mind, the team reformulated project objectives to emphasize: the assessment
of existing rural pre-

school
services, the development of ideas which would make maximum use of available
resources; the development of training programmes by providing assistance to
the teachers themselves to acquire skills in devising appropriate materials and
curricula for their children; motivating teachers to cooperate and share their
knowledge with other teachers in their area. This basic restructuring of
project objectives eventually led to the development of a wide range of
strategies for in-

service
training.<p>
<p>
Another new aspect was that the project took considerable pains from the start
to gain the commitment of rural authorities and set up mechanisms for
collaboration with rural County Councils and parent groups. Discussions were
held with the local leaders and Council officials where the project's aims and
intended operations were spelled out while taking into account the Council's
needs and their abilities to participate in this joint venture. The County
Councils, for example, agreed to provide assistance by releasing selected
teachers, providing suitable training sites, providing some materials and
transportation.<p>
<p>
During the same period the induction of district trainers began whereby able
teachers who has been identified as capable of in-

servicing
other teachers were picked from the former Nairobi trainees to join the project
in Murang&#146;a and Kiambu.<p>
<p>
A major change in the project was the dramatic redesigning of the training
programme. The one year residential training course provided in Nairobi was too
costly and impractical for rural teachers, therefore, a six month in-

service
course was designed in which residential training alternated with pre-

school
teaching practice. The Residential sessions were held during the holidays so
that schools would not be without teachers during the term. The organisation of
the six month training programme is shown in the following diagram.<p>
<p>
<i>The inter-

relationship
of the residential and the field components.</i><p>
<center>
<img src=boxes.gif alt="Diagram">
</center>


<p>
<p>
The training methodology has also altered for these rural courses. As the
project staff noted:<p>
<p>
The majority of these teachers did not terminate their education prematurely
because they were incapable of continuing; rather there are many socio-

economic
factors which contributed to their dropping out of school. These teachers are
highly respected in their communities and they have a very warm and friendly
relation with the community. Many of these teachers have a very high degree of
commitment to their job. This is exemplified by the fact that in some cases
they go for long periods without salary and when they get it, it is only a
small amount. These teachers have a wealth of knowledge on how children grow
and develop.<p>
<p>
The programme was practical, taking off from problems identified by the
trainees themselves. A great emphasis was placed on alternative uses for local
materials, on stimulating the development of language skills in the local
language, and on providing more time for health, nutrition and agricultural
subjects.<p>
<p>
A new perspective began to emerge among project staff which was subsequently
reflected in their programming style. In the words of one project staff
member:<p>
<p>
How would you like to train someone who has not acquired basic skills in
literacy and numeracy to become a pre-

school
teacher and hence charged with the difficult task of preparing children for the
skills of literacy and numeracy? Would you imagine training people who can not
do written assignments because they just cannot communicate in the medium of
literacy?<p>
<p>
This is the situation that the project has been attempting to deal with. Using
a participatory approach we formulated an on-

job
training programme whereby the project staff interacted with the teachers in
given contexts within the country. The project staff helped these teachers to
acquire basic pedagogical skills and professional skills which were geared
toward increasing their understanding of how children grow and learn. In the
course of working with these teachers, we found many positive things about them
which made our experiences with them very fascinating.<p>
<p>
The courses for each group of teachers last about six months. An important
paint to lay emphasis on is the fact that the project has categorically adopted
the view that the in-service
course should be organised within the context in which the participants are
working. In other words, courses should take place in the home district of
those attending teachers. This means the project team has to move from the
Headquarters to the project site whenever there is a course taking place. -

-
This
operational model has illuminated a lot of interesting observations
particularly in the areas of centre/peripheral and change agent/client system
relationships.<p>
<p>
<p>
Modifications were made in the programme as a result of the experience gained
in each of the training courses in Murang'a and Kiambu. For example, it soon
became obvious that organised follow-

up
with the trainees was needed after the end of the courses. Secondly, and
importantly, a
system gradually evolved whereby trainers were selected from the group of
trainees in each course. These trainers, after receiving more training
themselves, subsequently came to design and conduct in-

service
courses for other teachers in their areas. Thus, although only 35 teachers
participated in the initial Kiambu course in 1977, a small number of trainers
drawn from this group subsequently provided seminars and six month courses for
300 other teachers. Murang'a likewise started with 20 teachers and by now a
further 282 teachers have been in-serviced
since 1980.<p>
<p>
By 1978 when the first stage of Foundation funding was coming to an end,
flexible strategies had obviously emerged for upgrading pre-school
education. Furthermore, the emphasis had gradually shifted from the provision
of training per se to providing experiences for skills development together
with mutual support among teachers in using new skills. Project evaluation
indicated that, while in terms of the number of teachers thus far trained
(about 100) and the materials produced, this had not been a low-

cost
project, the strategies were apparently effective and could, over the long run,
result in low-

cost
programming. At this time the agreed period of funding came to an end. The
project in the meantime felt that further activities in the rural programme
would result in more effective strategies for developing of pre-school
work drew up a proposal for continued collaboration with the Foundation for
another three years. This constituted phase II of the project.<p>
<p>
Central components of project activities were to be: the preparation of
trainers, provision of district-

level
training programmes, community involvement and expansion of the project to two
rural districts.<p>
<p>
<u>Training of Trainees and District Courses 1979-1982</u><p>
<p>
A further two rural districts were: Keiyo/Marakwet, and Kilifi were involved
during this phase of operations. The proposal had called for preparation of
trainers as a central component of the project activities. It was hoped that
through further training the trainers would develop the skills and competence
in organising and running in-service
courses for teachers in their own districts. These potential trainers were
trained through;<p>
<p>
a.	attachment - this means that the trainers who are attached to the project staff for a period
of time ranging from a few weeks to four years. For some trainers it meant
working with project staff on a full time basis participating in the planning
and executing of all project activities. For others they came in on a more part-

time
training involving working with a member of the project but without resuming
full responsibility for the tasks at hand.<p>
<p>
b.	seminars and workshops -


this was another approach to the preparation of the trainers. Seminars and
workshops were held in the project districts. During these seminars/workshops
the problems encountered by the trainers in the course of their duties were
discussed and solved. Trainers were also given further guidance in planning
their in-service
courses and in making field observations of the teachers at work.<p>
<p>
c.	on-the-job training -


a more informal way of training was through joint participation with the
project staff in the training programme organised for teachers in the
participating districts.<p>
<p>
These trainers in turn organized and provided in-

service
courses for untrained teachers as the diagram below shows.<p>
<p>
<p>
DURATION OF THE DISTRICT COURSES 1979-

1984<p>


<pre>
DISTRICT              DURATION              NO. TEACHERS          TRAINERS              
Nairobi               2-9 months                    152           5 trainers 1 school   
                                                                  advisor               
Murang&#146;a              4-5 months Seminars           282           4 trainers 1          
                                                                  district              
                                                                  supervisor            
Kiambu                6 months Seminars             300           12 trainers 6         
                                                                  supervisors           
Kilifi                Seminars,                      78           5 trainers 2          
                      Attachment-                                 district              
                      undefined length*                           supervisors           

</pre>
<p>
* In Kilifi, the trainers decided not to organize formal in-
                                                                                        
service
courses. Instead, they developed a system of attachment in which a group of
untrained teachers is attached to a trainer for a period of apprenticeship.
This apprenticeship is augmented by consultations between the trainer and
teachers. Most of the trained teachers in the district have, through this
apprenticeship system, assisted in training others.<p>
<p>
In addition to the flexible training strategies, another aspect of the
programme was the attempt to involve the sponsors of early childhood centres as
<u>partners</u> in the training programme. This was necessary to ensure
sustainability and quality at the end of the project intervention. Thus local
authorities provide support for the training, payment of salaries; or some
teachers and provision of materials. The communities also participated in
provision of physical facilities, feeding programmes in some schools and in the
day to day running of the centres.<p>
<p>
<u>Assessment</u><p>
<p>
Assessments of the project have demonstrated that a shift has occurred in
teaching practices away from rote learning to varied participatory approaches.
Teachers are extraordinarily successful at collecting and using local materials
in imaginative ways. Project evaluation suggested that there may be a need for
some further guidelines for self-
                                                                                        
assessment
for use by teachers and trainers.<p>
<p>
About half the teachers and trainers had seven years of formal schooling. Those
with more, particularly from Nairobi, tended to be less flexible in adopting
new teaching styles. Specialized training on-
                                                                                        
the-                                                                                        
job
is more important than the formal educational qualifications of the pre-
                                                                                        
school
teacher.<p>
<p>
Children who attended pre-
                                                                                        
school
perform better in their first year of primary school. Children whose teachers
have been trained by the project, appear to exhibit more exploratory behaviour
and have greater command of their local language.<p>
<p>
Evaluation has shown that the project has elicited continued involvement and
commitment from parents and teachers extending far beyond the period of direct
interaction with project staff. In several cases, the project has freed mothers
for economic/agricultural activities and older siblings to attend school.<p>
<p>
The project evaluation is also demonstrated that certain minimal conditions are
required in order for the educational strategies to be effective. These pre-
                                                                                        
conditions
include basic transportation infrastructure enabling movement of teachers,
trainers and materials.<p>
<p>
<u>Development of a Nationwide Programme</u><p>
<p>
By 1984 the project had trained 800 teachers who work with about 32,000
children in five districts. The experience in programme development had been
extensive. Furthermore a critical core of project staff and trainers had grown
over the years and remained remarkably stable, without the staff transfers and
attrition that affect many programmes. The project had demonstrated that:<p>
<p>
-A narrow vision of early childhood education as the domain of the small group
of expert curriculum planners and training specialists can be replaced by a
more realistic strategy of programme development drawing on the knowledge and
skills of all those involved in the education process;<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
To
develop methods of early childhood education which are culturally, politically
and socio-
                                                                                        
economically
relevant, local workers and the community must be intensively involved in
design and decision-
                                                                                        
making;<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
To
reach teachers effectively strategies should focus on the acquisition of skills
without removing the teacher from the working context. The strategies should be
based on participation, peer-
                                                                                        
to-                                                                                        

peer teaching, and the development of locally relevant curricula
simultaneously. The approaches also bring local authorities, the community and
pre-
                                                                                        
schools
together as partners.<p>
<p>
<p>
In terms of policy, in 1980 the Ministry of Basic Education was vested with the
responsibility for the coordination of pre-
                                                                                        
school
programmes. Furthermore, departments of early childhood education were set up
within the Ministry headquarters and the Schools Inspectorate. The two
departments cooperate closely with the Kenya Institute of Education.<p>
<p>
The Ministry prepared the proposal for the dissemination of district-
                                                                                        
based
in-
                                                                                        
service
training strategies for early childhood education. The plan called for the
setting up of a National Centre for Early Childhood Education within the KIE.
This will form the hub of a network of subcentres in districts throughout the
country. These will work to enhance services for the pre-
                                                                                        
school
child by:<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
establishing
a nationwide network of on-
                                                                                        
the-                                                                                        
job
training for teachers in the pre-
                                                                                        
schools
and the local communities;<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
continuing
to develop localized curricula;<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
enhancing
current training models to include other components related to the development
of the child (such as primary health care and nutrition);<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
conducting
and disseminating research and offering services for the dissemination of
resources, training and materials.<p>
<p>
<p>
It is planned that the programme will be developed, as before, in deliberate
stages drawing on the training resources and experience from the current KIE
early childhood programme. Some new elements will be added; while others will
be expanded or modified. Among the latter are strategies which build on early
childhood education as an entry point for community development. The project
has considerable in empowering and mobilising parents and community members.
New actions will be stimulated in relation to health, nutrition, community well-
                                                                                        
being.
Another challenge for the programme will be to reach out beyond the 20% of the
children in the 3 to 6 year age group to involve those who would benefit, but
have been unable to do so thus far.<p>
<p>
Financial support for this large-
                                                                                        
scale
programme is being provided from various institutions, hopefully working in
collaboration. The Foundation, after receiving the proposal, for example, has held several discussions with UNICEF staff. The Foundation is providing support
for the Nasitonal Centre within the KIE which will develop its programme for
the training of trainers and will serve to help support and coordinate
activities among the district centres in the network. Other agencies are (or
are considering) providing support for the development of district-
                                                                                   
level
activities and the
district centres.<p>
<p>
<u>Reflections on "moving to scale" in the Kenyan programme</u><p>
<u>Start-
                                                                                        
up
of the project</u><p>
-
                                                                                        
The
initiation of the project with the Ministry of Education which had not
previously been involved in early childhood education implied that part of
project resources and time would be devoted to building the capacities and
building on the potential of the Ministry. It also introduced some political
constraints against which the new project had to contend in eliciting the
cooperation of other agencies. The fact that the Ministry of Education was
assigned responsibility for pre-
                                                                                        
schools
by the government in 1980 has resolved many of the problems.<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
Selecting
Nairobi as the starting point for the project, as had been suggested by the
Foundation may have caused some delays. Some observers suggest that the donor's
decision may not have been correct and, in part led the project to begin on too
small a scale, possibly below the critical mass needed for an experimental
programme, Others argue that it was essential to start in Nairobi on a small
scale and expand carefully from there.<p>
<p>
<u>Elements of programme development</u><p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        

The success of this project seems to derive in part from its administrative
flexibility and the foresight of its staff in trying out less orthodox
approaches and capitalising on all manner of local resources. A case in point
is the careful selection of potential pre-
                                                                                        
school
trainers with some bias toward performance rather than formal qualitifications.
The project developed as a process, as a result of planning-
                                                                                        
trial-                                                                                        
replanning,
rather than as a blueprint scheme. Thus, in the future it is expected and
indeed planned that there will be variation, innovation and change in the
programme as it enters new districts. The strategy remains flexible.<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
Another
important factor in project development was serendipity; which permitted a
relatively slow metamorphosis from a small, rather costly urban model to a low-
                                                                                        
cost
wide-
                                                                                        
reaching
programme. The project was initially envisaged this project as a small,
experimental effort with only a nebulous idea of moving to a national scale.
This presents challenges to those who believe in detailed advance planning.<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
It
also present challenges to those who believe in long-
                                                                                        
term
expatriate technical assistance for programme development. In keeping with the
policy of the Bernard van Leer Foundation, no outside personnel were attached
to the project. Nor does the Foundation have a representative or field office
in Kenya or Africa. Of course, this cuts costs. However, far more important is
the point that the project would probably not have developed as subtly or along
what might be called such 'relevant' lines had outsiders been in or near
decision-
                                                                                        
making
positions.<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
Another
key to the growth of the project was its ability to draw upon the demand for pre-
                                                                                        
school
education, Indeed all project districts were selected on the basis of having
already a high level of demand as implied by their relatively extensive early
childhood centre infrastructure.<p>
<p>
Coupled to this, but somewhat distinct, was the capacity of the project to draw
upon traditional Kenyan experience in self-
                                                                                        
help.
It should be noted that in some areas programme development was side-
                                                                                        
tracked
by local elites; however, in general Harambee provided essential contributions
to the programme.<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
Another
important element in project development is its essentially <u>contractual</u>
basis with local authorities. Local committees and district councils must first
indicate, not only a willingness to collaborate, but must allocate resources
for training and follow-
                                                                                        
up
activities. One obvious<p>
implication is that the project must expand gradually. A second point is that
it would be almost impossible to <u>impose</u> the programme nationally by
fiat. These are features that arguably have enhanced the sustainability and
growth of the programme, avoiding the 'flash-
                                                                                        
in-                                                                                        
the-                                                                                        
pan'
syndrome that affects some projects. Thus, this is not a national programme,
but a programme which is expanding across the nation.<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
"Goodness
of fit" has been a key element in the development of this project. Community-
                                                                                        
based
education efforts such as this may, in most instances, require deliberate,
staged expansion fitting with the interests, perceived needs and resources of
the community.<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
With
a range of government and private agencies involved in early childhood
education, collaboration among them was essential. In fact, however, lack of
inter-
                                                                                        
agency
collaboration was a political constraint particularly in the early years of
project development. This is not unusual of course. In many situations, both
project implementers and donors require patience and time-
                                                                                        
-                                                                                        
something
which also has financial implications.<p>
<p>
<u>Costs</u><p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
Foundation
donations to the project up through 1982 amounted roughly to US$100,000
annually at current prices. In practice most inputs were local, however; and
the tilt toward local input increased as the project developed. The district
councils and parents committees provide teacher<p>
salaries; the communities build and maintain the centres. In some cases they
also provide food. The teachers and trainers, who receive very small salaries,
must be very dedicated indeed to undertake training and carry out their daily
work-
                                                                                        
-                                                                                        
this
is also an uncosted input. It is exceptionally
difficult to attach monetary figures to these inputs.<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
Local
costs and inputs are relative. It appears that when the relative local costs
are too high the project can not and perhaps should not be implemented. In the
face of famine, community disorganisation and the absence of infrastructure,
the strategies collapse. However, it appears to provide greatest benefits to
children as self-
                                                                                        
sustaining
model in rural areas where certain threshold conditions prevail, where there is
a basic transportation infrastructure, and minimal but adequate levels of
nutrition are attainable and where the local community is already seeking ways
of
improvement. Where these conditions are met, within a fairly broad range of
environments, the project seems to have a high potential for diffusion and
sustainability. Thus, for example, local training programmes have continued in
four out of five of the project districts, funded by district
government or parents, after the withdrawal of the project.<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
On
the other hand, the long-
                                                                                        
term
implications of this proviso deserve careful consideration. Roughly 20% of the
children aged 3 to 6 years are involved in pre-
                                                                                        
school/nursery
structure. Some, though not all, of the 80% live in marginal areas or come from
families too poor to participate. The Hon. Dr. E. Gachukia has noted:<p>
<p>
...it was also currently argued that this take-
                                                                                        
over
or assistance (of Government to Harambee schools) would bring about uneven
development or utilisation of government resources, since some regions had more
harambee schools and projects than others. Regional imbalance is here seen as a
negative consequence or implication of the harambee movement. Other negative
views see the harambee movement as benefiting only the elite. ... Whatever the
merit or lack of it of the Harambee self-
                                                                                        
help
movement in Kenya, however, we would perhaps not be here discussing partnership
in the development of pre-
                                                                                        
school
education in Kenya today, if it had not been for the harambee effort of Kenyans
at the grass roots level.<p>
<p>
<u>Donor Agencies</u><p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
Various
donor agencies have a role in the development of this project. In a few cases
some inputs such  -
                                                                                        
as
food for a few centres has been provided from other resources. Other agencies
have committed themselves or are contemplating support for the development of
the district level centres and the strengthening of health and nutrition
components in the programme. It will be essential that donor agencies
collaborate effectively in the future.<p>
<p>
-
                                                                                        
"Moving
to scale" implies a need for long-
                                                                                        
term
support and long-
                                                                                        
term
vision of goals and outcomes on the part of all parties-
                                                                                        
-                                                                                        
government,
programme implementers and, of course, donors.<p>
<p>
<img src=2ndiag.gif alt="Figure"><p><hr>
