<html><head>
</head>
<title>Early Childhood Development in
Countries of the Andres Bello Agreement</title>
<body>
<p>
<center>
<b>Early Childhood Development in</b><p>
<b>Countries of the Andres Bello Agreement</b><p>

<p>
(with implications for action)<p>
<p>

<p>
A paper prepared for the Executive Secretariat<p>
of the Andres Bello Agreement<p>
<p>
by<p>
<p>
Robert G. Myers<p>
The Secretariat of<p>
The Consultative Group on<p>
Early Childhood Care and Development<p>
</center>
June 1993<p>
<p>
<b>TABLE OF CONTENTS</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
	  I	KEY CONCEPTS<p>
<p>
	 II	A PROGRAM FRAMEWORK<p>
<p>
	III	COUNTRY CONTEXTS<p>
<p>
	 IV	THE SITUATION OF YOUNG CHILDREN IN CONVENIO COUNTRIES<p>
<p>
	  V	PROGRAMS OF ATTENTION TO THE YOUNG CHILD<p>
<p>
		A.  Center-based services<p>
		B.  Parental education and enablement<p>
		C.  Child-centered community-based programs<p>
		D.  Institution building<p>
		E.  Communication<p>
<p>
	 VI	SOURCES OF PROGRAM SUPPORT<p>
<p>
		A.  National<p>
		B.  International<p>
		<p>
<p>
	 VII	OPENINGS FOR ASSISTANCE BY SECAB<p>
<p>
		REFERENCES<p>
<p>
		APPENDICES<p>
<p>
		A.  Program Guidelines <p>
		B.  Pre-school Enrollments: Selected Countries, by Age<p>
		C.  International Assistance for Programs of Early 			Childhood Development
in Countries of the Convenio 			Andres Bello<p>
<p>
<p>
	The purpose of this paper is to provide the Secretariat of the Convenio Andres
Bello with suggestions for possible work that would help to improve the
integral development of the 17 to 18 million young children under the age of 6
years<b>[1]</b> who are living in the participating
countries of the Convenio.  Special attention will be given to children living
in conditions that put them "at risk".  In order to arrive at those suggestions
in a systematic and grounded way, it seems appropriate, first, to clarify some
basic concepts, to establish a framework for analysis and to describe, as best
as possible, the situation of children in the region.  Suggestions will also
take into account what is already being done in the region, including
activities that are funded by other international organizations in support of
child development in the region.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>I  KEY CONCEPTS</b><p>
<p>
	Although the focus of this paper is on learning and education during the
pre-school years, the key phrase to be used will be "child care and
development."  This requires some clarification of the terms and of their
relationship.<p>
<p>
	<b>Learning</b> is a process of acquiring knowledge, skills, habits and values
through experience and experimentation, observation, reflection and/or study
and instruction.  <b>Education</b> is the process of fostering learning.
<b>Schooling</b> is one form of education.<p>
   <p>
	<b>Pre-school education</b> is used in common parlance to identify educational
programs occurring outside the home and provided to children <b>during their
immediate preschool years</b>, usually from ages 4 through 6.  This education
focusses typically on cognitive development and the preparation of children for
school.  During the last decade or so, formal preschool programs have been
complemented by experiments in "non-formal" preschool education.  Often, these
non-formal programs share methodologies and contents with formal preschooling
and, as formal preschools, are located in a center outside the home.  They are
characterized as "non-formal", however, because the program workers are not
paid for their work as part of the formal system of education.<p>
<p>
	<b>Initial education</b> is a broader concept than preschool education, as
described above.  The term refers to programs intended to enhance early
learning through some kind of guided educational process directed to children
throughout their pre-school years, i.e., <b>from birth until entrance into
primary school</b>.  Initial education can include programs that focus on
enabling parents to be better educators of their young children as well as on
programs directly involving children.  Therefore programs of initial education
need not be center-based but can occur through, for instance, home-visiting.
This term is not in common use in all countries of the Convenio does not serve
our purposes as well as it might.<p>
<p>
  <b> </b>	<b>Child development</b> is understood as a holistic process of
change in which a child learns to manage ever more complex levels of moving,
thinking, feeling and relating to others.  This definition goes beyond
cognitive or mental development to include physical, social and emotional
development.  These dimensions of a child's development are distinct but are
organically interrelated.  Learning is a crucial part of development.  General
development involves both 1) a gradual unfolding of biologically determined
characteristics and 2) a process of learning that occurs as children interact
with the people and things that make up their environment.<p>
<p>
	A program of <b>integrated child development</b> attends to physical, mental,
social and emotional needs of a child.  In so doing, it incorporates attention
to nutrition and health status as well as to the psycho-social well being of
children.  Often, however, programs labeled as child development programs are
not comprehensive or integrated, concentrating instead on mental development
and leaving aside attention to physical or social developmental needs.  These
narrow programs are very similar to most pre-school programs.<p>
<p>
	<b>Child care</b> consists of the actions necessary to promote survival,
growth and development<b>[2]</b>.  Care includes
attention to health and nutrition as well as to psychological and social needs
of children.  In theory, a child care program should go beyond protection or
custodial care of children to include all elements of an integrated child
development program, including stimulation and attention to mental and social
development.  In fact, many child care programs are purely custodial, providing
shelter, food, protection from accidents and monitoring of health, but little
else.<p>
<p>
<p>
	In brief, the phrase, "child care and development"  (defined in an integral
way) is favored in this discussion of programs over "pre-school education" in
order to promote a broader view of learn-ing and education than is usually
captured when talking about "pre-schools" or even about "initial education".
Moreover, this is the phrase adopted at the World Conference on Education for
All (WCEFA) in its "Framework for Action to Meet Basic Learning Needs".  Among
the goals that countries were urged to pursue, within a broadened concept of
"basic education," was:<p>
<p>
"Expansion of early childhood care and development activities, including family
and community interventions, especially for poor, disadvantaged and disabled
children." (Paragraph 8).   <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>II  A PROGRAM FRAMEWORK</b><b>[3]</b> <p>
<p>
	Because child development and learning occur as children interact with their
environment, it is essential to take into con-sideration in programming both
the changing condition of the child (at birth and along the way), and the
changing condition of the various environments affecting the child's
development.  According-ly, the framework to be presented below has two
dimensions, one referring to changes in the child, the other to complementary
programs that are related to different levels of environment affecting a
child's development.  <p>
<p>
	<b>The changing child.</b>  The condition of the child at birth depends on
genetic endowment, but also on the health and  nutri-tional status and habits
of the mother during pregnancy.  Similar-ly, the developmental status of a
child in the early years depends both on the natural unfolding of abilities as
a child matures physically and on health and nutritional conditions affecting
that maturation.  <p>
<p>
	The changing condition of children during the early years requires changes in
the kinds of programs directed to children as a child matures, in accordance
with their developmental stage.  A newborn child is obviously not the same
child as a child who has just developed the ability to walk and talk or as a
child in the immediate pre-school years.  If a child development strategy is to
be comprehensive, it should respond to changing needs throughout the
development process.  It is not enough to begin programming for child
development when the child reaches age three of four.<p>
<p>
	Because child development follows a general pattern (even though the process
will vary from individual to individual and culture to culture), it is possible
to establish program activities appropriate to general stages or levels of a
child's development.  These stages, which define the first dimension of the
framework, correspond roughly to certain age periods and might be distinguished
as follows:<p>
<p>
    	a prenatal period.<p>
    	infancy (up to about 18 months) that encompasses weaning, learning to walk
and early language development.<p>
    	a toddler and post-toddler period (about 18 to 48 months) during which a
child's coordination, language, ability to think and social skills advance
rapidly.<p>
    	a preschool period (approximately ages 4 and 5) when coordination is
relatively well developed, and when cognitive development and development of
pr-literacy and pre-numeracy skills occurs quickly, along with greater
attention to relationships with peers.<p>
    	a period of accommodation to school and the world at large (roughly ages 6
to 8).<p>
<p>
	Within governments, the organizational responsibility for programs of early
childhood development is usually divided and tends to follow developmental
stages and/or the age of children.  Responsibility for the first three stages
described often falls to the health sector or to organizations concerned with
family welfare.  Form age three or four onward, child development is more
likely to be associated with education and preschools.<p>
<p>
	This division is logical in the sense that survival and the early months of
development are closely tied to the biophysical conditions and maturation of
the child, and, during this time, most children are cared for within the
family.  In the later preschool years, socialization and preparation for
schooling take on greater importance, and the circle of caregivers widens.<p>
<p>
	However, this division of organizational responsibility also hides the need
for continuous attention of a coordinated nature.  It reinforces the
unfortunate tendency to omit psychosocial components prior to age three and to
think of child development programs as essentially educational programs
beginning at age three or four.  In order to counteract the tendency to
restrict programming for school development to one particular age group (for
example, the immediate preschool period) and to provide continuity for the
changing child, a comprehensive program framework must distinguish, but
include, all of the several period described above.<p>
<p>
<p>
	<b>Environments and related program approaches.</b>  Following Bronfenbrenner
(1979), the environment of the developing child can be examined at several
different levels.  The most immediate en-vironment is that provided by the
child's mother and other family members within the home.  The family or home
environment is set within the community environment.  Communities and families
are affected by a broader social and institutional environment, including
social laws and organizations.  Finally the way in which institutions and
families function is influenced by more general conditions which include
geographic, economic, and demographic circumstances as well as a general
cultural ethos guiding behavior for the society as a whole.  These different
"levels" of environ-ment will all affect the way in which a child is brought up
and learns.  Consequently, an overall strategy for child develop-ment and
learning should include not only programs that provide direct attention to the
child, but also programs directed toward families, communities, social
institutions and broader cultural norms.<p>
<p>
	From the above we can derive <b>five complementary program approaches</b> to
enhancing early childhood care and development.  Although all five approaches
are intended to enhance early childhood development and are therefore directed
in the last analysis toward improvements in the child, each approach is
directed, initially, towards a different audience or program participants.
Table 1 sets out these different participants (or in the unfortunate language
of some programming, "target groups").  The table also summarizes objectives
and suggests variations in the models that might be applied within each of the
general approaches.  <p>
<p>
	Table 1.  Complementary Approaches to programming for early 		  childhood care
and development<p>
_________________________________________________________________ <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
	Briefly described, the five complementary approaches are as follows:<p>
<p>
	1.  <b>Attending to children in centers.</b>  The immediate goal of this
direct approach, focussing on the <b>CHILD</b> is to enhance child development
by attending to the immediate needs of children in centers organized outside
the home.<p>
<p>
	2.  <b>Educating and enabling caregivers.</b>  This approach focuses on
<b>FAMILY</b> members and is intended to educate and "empower" parents and
other family members in ways that improve their care and interaction with the
child and enrich the immediate environment in which child development is
occurring rather than provide a substitute for it.<p>
<p>
	3.  <b>Promoting child-centered community development.</b>  Here, emphasis is
on working to change <b>COMMUNITY</b> conditions that may ad-versely affect
child development.  This approach stresses community initiative, organization,
and participation in a range of interre-lated activities, to improve the
physical environment, the know-ledge and practices of community members, and
the organizational structure, allowing common action and improving the base for
political and social negotiations.<p>
<p>
	4.  <b>Strengthening institutional resources and capacities.</b>  There are
many <b>INSTITUTIONS</b> involved in setting the climate for programs and in
carrying out the three approaches mentioned above.  These include governmental
and non-governmental institutions.  Included in this category programs that set
national policies and <p>
provide the legal underpinnings for functioning of institutions.  Also included
are programs of training, provision of materials, and experimentation with
innovative techniques and models (improving the available "technology."<p>
<p>
	5.  <b>Increasing awareness and demand.</b>  This program approach
concentrates on the production and distribution of <b>KNOWLEDGE</b>.  It may
function at the level of policymakers and planners, or be directed broadly
towards changing the cultural ethos that affects child development and/or the
participation in programs.<p>
	<p>
	Bringing together the two dimensions of the program framework, gives us
Diagram 1.  In theory, all of categories defined in the diagram should be
attended to.  Rarely, however, will it be possible for any one program to cover
all the categories and multiple efforts will be required for maximum effect.
<b>This framework allows us to locate where present programs are concentrated
and to see where the gaps are in programming.</b><p>
<p>
	<b>Program Guidelines.</b>  A third dimension could be added to the program
framework dealing with program guidelines.  A detailed discussion of guidelines
will not be offered here.  However, in Appendix A of the paper, seven
guidelines are set out which, taken together, could provide a litmus test for
programs found in any of the categories of the framework.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
	<b>Diagram 1.  Programming for Early Childhood Development: A
Comprehensive Framework</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>III  COUNTRY CONTEXTS</b><p>
<p>
	At the most general level of environment influencing the early development and
learning of children are a number of cultural,  social, economic and
demographic conditions, some of which are shared among countries of the
Convenio, some of which are very different from country to country.  <p>
	 <p>
<b>Common elements</b><p>
<p>
	The countries of the Convenio Andres Bello are subject to a number of common
influences and changes affecting child development that should be taken into
account when examining existing programs or when looking to the future.  These
common influences include:<p>
<p>
	<b>1.  500 years of cultural hegemony.</b>  Even the most resistant native
cultures of Latin America have been influenced to some degree by the Conquest
and its long aftermath.  In the sierran countries of the Convenio, the tensions
between indigenous and Spanish cultures endure seen, for instance, in the
controversy over using the mother tongue or Spanish for teaching in primary
schools and pre-school programs.  Also enduring is the influence of the Roman
Catholic church which, over the centuries, has helped to establish particular
beliefs and values, including those affecting childrearing (CELAM, 1992).
Against this background and fore-ground, <b>special consideration of indigenous
groups and of their practices and beliefs must be included when formulating
programs.</b> <p>
This holds for all the countries of the Convenio, but in differing degrees.<p>
<p>
	<b>2.  The advance of technology on many fronts</b> -- in transportation,
communication, education as well as in industry and commerce -- has not only
brought new ways of doing things, including raise children; it has also helped
to provoke a general clash of values.  That advance, with origins in "science"
and an occidental culture places competition, individualism and consumerism
against cooperation, solidarity, and spiritualism.  It has helped to dampen the
force of tradition and experience.  It has brought bottle feeding and plastic
toys and television other accoutrements of childrearing that were not available
in the past and which often substitute today for more traditional childrearing
technologies.  In programming, it is imperative not to forget or prejudge
traditional wisdom and experience.<p>
<p>
	At the same time, technological growth is providing opportunities for new
forms of learning.  For instance, the percentages of families that now have
access to television as well as radio is extremely high in most countries of
the region.  <b>The mass media, must be considered as a separate learning
channel, reinforcing or working against learning that occurs in the home, the
school and the community at large.</b><p>
<p>
	<b>3.  Urbanization.</b>  All countries in the Convenio can now be termed
"urban" countries, including Bolivia which, according to the most recent
statistics has just crossed the line to become 50% urban.  This long term trend
toward urbanization has been accelerated by economic declines and civil
disturbances over the last decade or more.  With the move to urban areas, old
ways of doing things do not always apply.  The space and conditions in which
children are reared change markedly requiring shifts in policy and practice.
With this growth and associated changes, <b>much more attention to marginal
groups in urban areas appears to be imperative.  </b><p>
<b></b><p>
	<b>4.  Economic decline during the "lost decade" of the 1980s.</b>  Without
exception, the countries included in the study suffered major economic declines
during the 1980's, affecting employment levels, increasing the number of people
living in poverty (IDB, 1990).  Of the seven countries, only two, Chile and
Colombia, show a positive average rate of growth in per capita income during
the decade.  In Bolivia, Panama, Peru and Venezuela, the average rate of
<b>decline</b> was 2% or greater.  <b>These declines make more urgent the need
for actions benefitting women and children who have been the hardest hit.</b><p>
<p>
	<b>5.  The impact of the neo-liberal economic policies</b> applied in an
attempt to overcome the economic problems of the 1980s.  The so-called
neo-liberal economic policy has been characterized by economic programs
providing incentives to attract local and foreign investment, and favoring
large scale industry and a shift to cash cropping, while increasing economic
inequalities, placing additional burdens on the poor and reducing social
spending.<p>
<p>
	The combination of the economic recession and of the neo-liberal policies has
led to a marked increase in the level of poverty in the region and has forced
more and more families to pursue survival strategies.  Economic pressures not
only lower the level of resources available to meet daily needs, but also
affect livelihood and work patterns, family structures and relationships, and
childrearing practices and patterns.  <b>These realities suggest that some
"compensatory" programs may be necessary even while working to construct new
opportunities together with the most affected groups.</b>   <p>
<p>
	<b>6.  The continuing move of women into the paid labor force and into
non-formal employment</b>.  Associated with economic pressures and changes,
urban growth and shifting values is an increase in the participation by women
in the paid labor force.  The percentage of the paid labor force that are women
varies from 19.3 percent in Ecuador to 28.5 percent in Chile (see Table 1).  In
all countries, however, there has been an appreciable increase in that
participa-tion over the last three decades.<p>
<p>
	Because societies still assign primary responsibility for childrearing to
mothers, this shift, when combined with a decrease in extended families and
with longer periods of children in school has brought with it a demand for
alternative forms of childcare and rearing outside the home.  Or, it has forced
adjustments in practices and patterns of child care which allow women to
combine work and care.  <b>Recognizing this trend makes more urgent the need to
respond to the intersecting needs of women and children in programs of child
care and development.</b><p>
<p>
	<b>7.  An impressive reduction has occurred in the rate of infant mortality
--</b> even in a time of economic difficulties.  With this reduction has come
an increasing shift from a cultural orientation focussed on accepting death and
promoting the survival of children, with its harsh tone based on a high
probability of an early death, to a more optimistic and open cultural
orientation toward growth and development.  This change needs, however, to be
reinforced and <b>the two approaches -- survival and development -- need to be
linked in action as well as in rhetoric.</b><p>
<p>
<b>Differences</b><p>
<p>
	For all these similarities, policy makers and programmers in countries of the
Convenio are confronted by very different constellations of demographic,
cultural, social and economic characteristics (see Table 2).  There are, for
instance, 13 times as many children under the age of 5 in Colombia as there are
in Panama.  Per capita incomes range from US$620 (Bolivia) to US$2560
(Venezuela).  The percentage of people living in rural areas ranges from 50%
(Bolivia) to 10% (Venezuela).   Cultural diversity is extraordinary, within as
well as among countries.  Literacy rates for adult women range from 43%
(Bolivia) to 93% (Chile).<p>
<p>
	There are, as well, major variations in the access to services and in the
distribution of services between urban and rural areas.  Whereas Venezuela and
Chile provide potable water to 90 and 89 percent, respectively of their
populations, Bolivia and Ecuador report serving only 53 and 58 percent
respectively.  In Peru, 61 percent of the population has access to water, but
in rural areas that percentage drops to 10 percent.  This contrasts with
Colombia which reports almost equal percentages for urban (88) and rural (87).
Access to health services runs from 36% in rural Bolivia to virtually 100% in
urban Chile.<p>
<p>
	Obviously, planning to promote the healthy development of young children will
be heavily conditioned by these differences.  If the bulk of children have no
access to health services, the option of linking developmental programming to
the activities of the health sector is not a very good option, at least in the
short run.  <p>
<p>
	In brief, all of the above similarities and differences have had their
influence on child development by affecting the immediate physical and social
environments in which children are reared, by affecting the values toward which
childrearing is directed and some of the beliefs that underpin traditional
practices, and by affecting the technologies available to be applied in the
process of childrearing.  An obvious conclusion is <b>that although there may
some general strategies that are pertinent for the region as a whole, some
options will not be pertinent to particular countries and important differences
will have to be respected as these are operationalized.</b><p>
<p>
<p>
	Table 2.  A Comparison of Convenio Andres Bello Countries: Selected
