<p>
	Notes:<p>
<p>
	 *UNICEF, <b>The State of the World's Children, 1993</b>.  New York, Oxford
University Press, 1993.<p>
<p>
	**Organizaci&oacute;n Panamericana de la Salud (OPS), "Primera Reuni&oacute;n
Interagencial para el Desarrollo de un Plan Regional de Salud Mental del
Ni&ntilde;o, Washington, D.C., 25-26 de enero de 1993,"  Washington, D.C., OPS,
Programa de Salud Materno Infantil, n.d.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
	From Table 3, it is clear that:<p>
<p>
	1.  With respect to the mortality rates, Bolivia, Peru and Ecuador are well
above the average for Latin America and the Caribbean; Chile, Colombia, and
Panama are well below; and Venezuela is somewhat below the average.<p>
<p>
	2.  Low weight for age (moderate and severe malnutrition) is greatest in
Bolivia, Peru and Ecuador, less so in Colombia and Venezuela, and virtually
eliminated in Chile.<p>
 <p>
	These basic figures reinforce the common sense conclusion that the situation
of children is worse in the poorer Andean countries of Bolivia, Peru and
Ecuador than in other, better-off Convenio countries.  If one were to use the
relative situation of children as a basis for establishing priorities about
where to work, these three countries would seem to be the obvious candidates.<p>
<p>
	Missing from Table 3 is an idea of the psycho-social condition of children in
the various countries.  <b>This is because there is no commonly accepted and
incorporated form of measuring and monitoring psycho-social development at a
national level.</b><p>
<p>
	Only in Chile is there an established system of monitoring psycho-social
development based on a measurement instrument developed in the country.<b>[4]</b>  Continuous monitoring in Chile over more
than 10 years shows that although the nutritional status of children improved
markedly during the period, the psycho-social status did not improve.
Moreover, the psycho-social monitoring shows clearly and consistently a
divergence in development as of approximately 18 months between children of
middle and upper classes and children living in conditions of poverty.<b>[5]</b>  <b>The clear conclusion is that it is not
enough to provide support for health and nutrition; support for psycho-social
development is also needed.</b>  <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>V  PROGRAMS FOR YOUNG CHILDREN</b><p>
<p>
	In this section, we will concentrate on programs that have (or are supposed to
have) a component directed toward improving the learning and/or psycho-social
development of young children.<b></b><p>
<b>	</b><p>
<b>	A.  Center-based programs</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>	Formal Preschools.</b>  The best documented of the programs that include a
stimulation or learning component are formal pre-school programs.  Table 4
provides the most recent figures available from the regional office of UNESCO
for enrollments in preschool in the Convenio countries.  The table also shows
trends in these countries over the past few years, disaggregates figures by
gender and shows the percentage enrollment in private institutions.  Appendix B
provides additional tables, on a country basis, disaggregating figures by
age.<p>
<p>
	It is evident from these tables that:<p>
<p>
	1.  A slow but steady growth from 1988 to 1991 has occurred in most countries,
with significant increases registered between 1990 and 1991 for Venezuela and
Colombia.  In the early 1980s, the growth was even greater.   (For the Latin
American region as a whole, it was estimated by UNESCO that from 1980 to 1986,
coverage more than doubled.  Tedesco, 1989.)<p>
<p>
	2.  Comparing the preschool enrollment figures with the estimated population
of children under 6 years of age (making an estimate based on the figures
presented in Table 2 which give figures for children under the age of 5) for
each country, the coverage appears to be relatively low with only Venezuela
reaching more than one-fourth of the children.<p>
<p>
	3.  If enrollment figures for five-year olds are compared with the number of
children estimated to be age five, the percentages are much higher, ranging
from 20 percent to 56 percent.  Coverage for children ages 3 and 4 is less and
has not grown as much over the same period.<p>
<p>
	4.  Coverage for children under the age of 3 remains very low.<p>
<p>
	5.  Girls are only slightly under-represented in the enrollment figures,
constituting about 49% of the total.<p>
<p>
	6.  Private pre-schools account for about 50% of the enrollments in Chile and
Colombia, with lower, but significant representation of the private sector in
Peru and Bolivia.<p>
<p>
	7.  There is a relatively high concentration of pre-schools in urban areas --
over two-thirds.<p>
<p>
	Points 6 and 7, taken together, suggest that the formal pre-school system is
heavily biased toward the wealthier and toward urban children.  Poorer and
rural children, if in any system at all, are in non-formal education or day
care arrangements.  <b>This raises questions of quality and equity.  It also
suggests that if the Convenio wishes to direct its support toward children most
in need, it would not do so through the formal pre-school system.  Or, it would
do so in selected portions of that system that are directed toward children in
rural and urban marginal areas.</b><p>
  <p>
<p>
	<b>Non-formal Pre-schools and Programs of Child Care and Development.  </b>The
preschool figures that have been presented in Table 4 provided by UNESCO do not
reflect accurately the partici-pation of children in programs of care and
development that contain an education component.  It seems reasonably clear
from the figures that both non-formal preschool programs and programs of child
care (which have an educational component) have been left out.  That may
because these programs lie outside the responsibility of ministries of
education or are not considered within the standard definition of
"pre-school."<p>
<p>
	Although no systematic information seems to be available across countries
about non-formal preschool systems or about center-based child care programs,
it is clear that these programs are a significant force in several of the
countries, particularly in Venezuela, Colombia, Peru and Chile.  In Venezuela,
for instance, a major program of home day care is being mounted through the
Ministry of Education, in conjunction with non-governmental organizations.
Coverage is estimated at somewhere in the neighborhood of 200,000, with
projections to much higher levels.  <p>
<p>
	In Colombia, the Instituto Colombiano de Bienestar Familiar extends to
approximately 800,000 children (as of January, 1992), ages 2 to 7 years of age
and another program covers approximately 800,000 children.  At least 250,000
additional children are enrolled in Pre-school Child Care Centers.  If these
figures were included, the coverage for programs of early childhood would be
about four times higher than that reported in Table 4.  Moreover, the age
distribution would change; more younger children would be included.  A bias
toward urban areas would remain.  The private sector's share in providing care
and development for young children would be reduced from more than one-half
(when only formal pre-schools are considered) to about one-ninth. <p>
<p>
	The non-formal education system in Peru (PRONOEI)  at one point reached almost
250,000 children.  (Current figures were not available at the time of this
writing.)  Plans are now being discussed to extend the non-formal system to
600,000 or more children.<p>
<p>
	In Chile in 1990, approximately 110,000 children, ages 2 to 6, were estimated
to be in programs run by the Junta Nacional de Jardines Infantiles (55,000),
the Fundaci&oacute;n de Jardines Infantiles (41,000) the Fundaci&oacute;n de
Jardines Infantiles y Navidad (4,000) and assorted non-governmental
organization (10,000) (Comisi&oacute;n de Educaci&oacute;n Parvularia, 1990).<p>
<p>
	In addition to the above, a major program of home day care has been funded for
Bolivia which is projected to include more children than the current preschool
program.  Ecuador is in transition to a new early childhood program in which it
is to place much greater responsibility on non-governmental organizations.<p>
 <p>
	<b>The above suggests that the decision to take "child care and development"
as the focus of discussion rather than "pre-school education" is not a trivial
decision.</b><p>
<p>
<p>
	<b>B.  Programs of Parental Education and Enablement.</b><p>
<p>
	Even less information is available for programs that approach early childhood
care and development through work with parents or other family members.  In
general, the education sector does not register programs of adult education
that include a parental education component; nor do they register specific
programs of parental education.  We have little idea, therefore, to what extent
parents are being reached with educational programs that will enable them to
improve their parenting.  Colombia has carried out a significant experiment in
a program called PEFADI.  In Chile,<p>
the Padres e Hijos Project has shown excellent results and a broader program of
parental education is being mounted, but with less attention to a community
dimension.<p>
<p>
	Various health and nutrition programs in the region include adult education
components, but at the time of writing no inventory of such programs was
discovered. <p>
<p>
	Although the statistics are not solid, the following conclusions are ventured
on the basis of informal discussions:<p>
<p>
	1.  Parental education has not been pursued vigorously.<p>
<p>
	2.  Most program efforts are relatively small scale.  <p>
<p>
	3.  Exceptions are the occasional programs of mass communication directed to
parents, through newspapers or television or special publications such as
"Facts for Life" created by UNICEF.  What these open programs lack is a link to
group discussions that will make the information come alive, that will allow it
to be internalized, and will provide the kind of social support needed for the
information to be acted upon.  For these reasons, such programs might more
logically be classified under the final strategy -- increasing public
awareness.<p>
<p>
	4.  There has been very little done to evaluate systematically the effects of
parental education programs.  Nevertheless, <b>this approach seems to hold
promise for the important task of improving the care and development of
children in their earliest years (0-3) at a reasonable cost and with integrated
content.</b><p>
<p>
 <p>
	<b>C.  Child-centered Community-Based Programs.</b>  Community-based programs
may include within them both attention to children in centers and programs of
parental education and empowerment, but should go beyond them to change
conditions at the community level that affect the development of children.
This includes changes in both the physical environment of the community and in
the ability of communities to organize for action and for negotiation with the
rest of the society of which they are a part.<p>
<p>
	As with the parental education approach, comments on child-centered
community-based programs, as carried out in the Convenio region must be
impressionistic.  A systematic inventory is not at hand.  My impressions are as
follows:<p>
<p>
	1.  Many child-centered community-based programs have been carried out on an
experimental, pilot or demonstration basis.  For the most part, these have been
projects of non-governmental organizations, often funded by foundations or by
international NGOs.  Many of these projects have been "successful" but are
difficult to duplicate on a large scale because they require continuing
dedication, a long term view, tolerance of local differences, and a willingness
to allow local participation in planning and implementation -- all of which is
difficult to obtain as programs grow large.<p>
<p>
	2.  Most governmental programs that are classified as community-based are so
in name only.  Community participation is often defined in terms of one-time
contributions such as the construction of a building and does not include
on-going participation in planning and implementation.  Or, community
committees are controlled politically from the center and do not include
representation of that part of local communities who are most in need.<p>
<p>
	If these impressions are correct, then adopting a truly community-based
strategy that empowers communities, taking the child as a starting point.<p>
<p>
	<b>D.  Institutional Strengthening Programs.</b>  With few exceptions,
institutional support for programs of early childhood care, development and
education are weak.  Training is often provided for program staff, but in short
term courses at the outset of a program, with an occasional "refresher" course,
seldom linked to work on the job.  Or, training is in formal institutions that
are long on theory and short on practice, more oriented to middle-class and
formal pre-schools than to community-based programs or to reaching those most
in need.  Little attention has been given to the training of planners or
program evaluators.  Supervision is probably the weakest link in most programs,
receiving very little support if it exists at all.<p>
<p>
	Materials are continually being created but are often produced in small
numbers and are not accompanied by the training needed to be able to do them
well.  And, adjustments are seldom made for cultural differences.   <p>
<p>
	<b>E.  Increasing Awareness and Demand.</b>  In Ecuador and Chile and
elsewhere, inserts in national newspapers have apparently been effective means
for communicating to the public.  A great deal more could be done through the
training of journalists to exploit this resource.  To create program demand,
popular theater has been used in Bolivia.  A best seller titled "Early
Stimulation" was published in Chile. <p>
<p>
	In brief, there seems to be no lack of "targets of opportunity" to improve the
quality of early childhood care and development programs.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>VI - SOURCES OF PROGRAM SUPPORT</b><p>
<p>
	Just as in the discussion of programs in the previous section, we will
concentrate in this section on support directed to programs that are education
programs (integrated or not) or are integrated child care and development
programs.  No attempt will be made to try and characterize sources of support
for sectoral programs in health and nutrition programs, although these will
have important potential effects on early childhood development and on rare
occasions may include a psycho-social component.<p>
<p>
	Even with this limit placed, the discussion must continue to be
impressionistic and will be incomplete.  To do a complete job would involve
detailed analyses of government laws and budgets and a more complete knowledge
of non-governmental, inter-governmental, bi-lateral and multi-lateral
organizations activities and budgets than we could possibly do in writing this
paper.  Nevertheless, the effort to characterize what is being done by others
is crucial to the desire of the Convenio to, on one hand, avoid repeating what
others are doing and, on the other hand, to look for possible partnerships.<p>
<p>
	The discussion will deal separately with national and international sources of
support.  Appendix C provides considerably more detail about support being
provided within the region by particular organizations: The World Bank, UNICEF,
the Bernard van Leer Foundation and international NGOs.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>National Sources</b><p>
<p>
	A proper analysis remains to be done of national sources of support for
programs of early childhood care, development and learning.  A better
understanding of national programs and of support, particularly by governments,
should be forthcoming from the scheduled meeting in September under the
auspices of the Organization of American States. <p>
<p>
	<b>Governments.</b>  Governments appear to be the main source of support for
programs of early childhood care and development.  They provide legal and
regulatory support as well as financial support.  <p>
	In some cases, the legal and regulatory support surpasses the ability of
governments, or of the institutions outside the government that it is hoped
will be affected, to live up to the law.  In other cases, laws are outdated.
Or, the ability and willingness to enforce laws is lacking.  <b>A systematic
analysis of laws and regulations remains to be done in various countries.</b><p>
	Some of the financial support provided by governments comes from the regular
budgets of Ministries of Education, usually under the category of pre-school or
initial education.  However, within education budgets, support for pre-school
education is, to take an educated guess, typically less than one percent of the
total education budget.  If this is so, it suggests that <b>education
bureaucracies and planning offices remain to be convinced that early childhood
education is a good educational investment.</b><p>
<p>
	Other government funding is found in family welfare budgets, usually for day
care and/or non-formal programs.  As suggested by the discussion of statistics,
these programs often have a greater coverage than pre-school programs.  In the
cases of Venezuela and Colombia  and Chile (and in the future, in Bolivia),
these contributions are significant.  In the case of Colombia, the family
welfare contribution from the government is linked to a payroll tax so that, in
a sense, the funds are contributed by the private sector.  Still, that same tax
money could presumably appropriated by government for another purpose.<p>
<p>
	Occasionally, government contributions occur in less obvious places, such as
the Central Bank in Ecuador or as part of the general system of social
security.<p>
<p>
	But appearances may be deceiving.  The contributions of governments are often
more visible than those of the civil society.  We do not know how large the
total support for early childhood programs would be if we added together all
the support from the civil institutions, including such diverse organizations
as: non-profit NGOs operating in the social sector, grass-roots organizations,
communities, churches, universities and labor unions. <p>
<p>
<p>
	<b>Non-governmental Organizations and other organizations of the civil
society.</b>  An inventory of involvement in the field of early childhood care
and development by non-governmental organizations remains to be carried out.
However, it appears that it is increasingly common for a wide range of civil
organizations to establish pre-schools or child care programs for young
children.  For instance, many church groups set up child care centers.  In
several Convenio countries, a national "Pastoral de la Infancia" has been
established by the Roman Catholic Church which should increase attention to
young children, often through programs of family education.<p>
<p>
	In the Human Development Report for 1993, issued by the United Nations
Development Fund, a case is made for greater non-govern-mental organizations
because they are often better able that governments to reach the poorest and to
empower marginal groups (UNDP, 1993).<p>
<p>
	<b>A careful examination would be valuable of efforts by governments to work
with and through non-governmental organiza-tions, as is beginning to occur in
Venezuela and Bolivia in the home day care program and as is being vigorously
discussed in Ecuador under the new government.</b>  <p>
<p>
<b>	Private Enterprise.</b>  In general, corporate enterprise has shirked its
duty with respect to provision of child care and development.  In Colombia,
that responsibility is shouldered through a payroll tax rather than by
provision of child care at work sites.  In other countries of the Convenio,
with laws requiring enterprises employing over a certain number of women to
provide child care for employees, little is done to enforce the laws.  And
there is a strong suggestion that such laws work to the detriment of the
employment of women.  Companies either stay under the legislated number or
employ women on a part time basis or for short periods only.<p>
<p>
	But even if private enterprise took its responsibility seriously, there would
be little effect on the welfare of children most in need whose parents are
likely to be unemployed, or working in the non-formal sector or in rural,
non-industrialized settings.<p>
<p>
	Another form of private enterprise that is not well documented or regulated is
that of setting up private venture pre-schools or day care programs.  Some of
these programs are outstanding models but can only be afforded by wealthy
families.  Others are local responses to day care needs that result in
custodial programs of such poor quality that they may be of more harm than good
to the children in them.  The home day care movement seeks to build on this
local solution, extending and upgrading care.  Whether or not this solution is
viable in the long term remains to be seen, but sufficient experimentation has
occurred and is occurring in the Convenio countries (in Venezuela, Colombia,
Ecuador, Peru and Bolivia) to make it a natural focus of attention.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>International Assistance in the Convenio Countries</b><p>
<p>
	There is no centralized source of information about the current international
support being provided to countries of the Convenio Andres Bello for activities
and programs in the area of early childhood care and development.  Moreover,
many organizations are not set up to be able to provide that information.
Early childhood is not only a relatively new area that has not yet found its
way into the standard statistical and accounting channels, but it is also a
field that cuts across the areas of health, nutrition, education and social
welfare, at a minimum, making tabulations of participation and support
difficult.<p>
<p>
	In order to get some idea of current support being provided, it was necessary
to make inquiries with individual agencies.  Results of these inquiries are
presented in Appendix C.  In most cases, it was difficult to put a dollar
figure on the activities so no attempt will be made to aggregate funds being
provided for early childhood care and development in the Convenio countries.<p>
<p>
	Additional information about international support for early childhood
programs should be forthcoming from both the OAS meeting in Chile mentioned
above and from an inter-agency, inter-sectoral meeting to be held in Colombia
in late August, bringing together representatives from a range of regional
networks, each approaching problems of early childhood from different
perspectives.<p>
<p>
	Several general comments seem appropriate in light of the preliminary
exploration of international financing.<p>
<p>
	1.  Although the level of international funding, given outside the health
sector for child survival, has not been high, international attention to this
area is increasing.  This is particularly notable within multi-lateral
agencies, and even more concretely, within the World Bank which has provided
loans containing a pre-school or early childhood component to five of the seven
Convenio countries within the last four years.  However, international NGOs and
the Catholic Church are also rediscovering the young child and are providing
new support.  Bi-lateral organizations are reconsidering their policy within
the context of support for "basic education."<p>
<p>
	2.  Support enters through many windows -- through education, nutrition, rural
or community development, women's programs.<p>
<p>
	3.  European bi-lateral funds and funds provided through international NGOs or
foundations are more likely to be directed toward community-based, grass roots
programs than are funds provided through multilateral agencies.<p>
<p>
	4.  Relatively few funds are being provided for systematic research, program
analysis and evaluation.  More funds are put into the buildings, equipment,
training and provision of materials (by multi-laterals) or into action programs
(by international NGOs and European bi-laterals) than into research or
evaluation.<p>
<p>
	5.  Multi-lateral and bi-lateral organizations must work mainly with
governments while foundations and international NGOs can work more easily with
non-governmental organizations.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>VII  OPENINGS FOR WORK BY SECAB</b><p>
<p>
	From the above it is clear that there are many possible ways to strengthen
support within the region for programs aimed at improving early childhood care
and development, without tripping over other organizations.  The challenge is
to look for manageable projects that can hope for more than an immediate and
possibly fleeting effect.<p>
<p>
	The suggestions that follow are based in part on the previous analysis.  They
also try to take into account the general lines of action that have been
emphasized by SECAB in its programming in other areas.  It is my understanding
that these are:<p>
<p>
   	training of human resources,<p>
   	strengthening information and exchange,<p>
   	organizing activities in selected areas (such as the development and
production of materials),<p>
   	carrying out research in support of the three main lines of activity just
mentioned.<p>
<p>
	It is also my understanding that SECAB has shown special interest in:<p>
<p>
   	promoting national appropriation of responsibility,<p>
   	facilitating inter-sectorial concertation, and <p>
   	articulating international cooperation.<p>
<p>
<b>Suggestions</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>	1.  A project dealing with the education and enablement of parents.</b><p>
<p>
	As suggested in the analysis of the situation of children and programs, few
children in the 0 to 3 age group are involved in organized programs of day care
or early education and the main responsibility for care continues to fall to
families.  Efforts to "empower" parents with knowledge and social organization
that would help them to improve the care they provide to their young children
have generally been limited in scope, sporadic and uncoordinated or have looked
at empowerment as an individual matter to be achieved through the simple
dissemination of knowledge.<p>
<p>
	Nevertheless, considerable experience with programs intended to sensitize,
educate, and even empower parents is accumulating in the region.  These include
such experiences as the Venezuelan Proyecto Familia and the recent work being
supported by the Bernard van Leer Foundation, Colombia's PEFADI, Peru's work
through women's programs, Ecuador's program "El Ecuador Estudia," Chile's
Padres e Hijos, etc.  A recent project to derive "lessons learned" from
programs of parental education and support in Mexico might be drawn upon
(Linares, 1992).  This growing experience needs to be evaluated, systematized,
and repackaged or disseminated.  It needs to be brought together with lessons
learned from health and nutrition education.<p>
<p>
	Focussing on parental education provides an excellent opportunity to work
across areas of education, health, nutrition, and family welfare, seeking the
kind of inter-sectoral concertation that is of interest to SECAB.  It would
allow pulling together of efforts by various other organizations.<p>
<p>
	A parental education project might be framed to focus on particular groups
that have not been properly brought into such education efforts such as
indigenous groups who have, in the main, been treated to outside "truths" about
childrearing and whose traditional wisdom has often been prejudged negatively.
Or, a project might be focussed on urban marginal parenting, on single parent
families, on the role of fathers, or on teenage parents, all areas that have
been neglected.<p>
<p>
<b>2.  A Children's Literature project.</b><p>
<p>
	Pursuing the SECAB process of sensitizing leaders and others to the idea that
educational materials are (or can be) strategic in the promotion of learning,
attention could be given to strengthening the production and use of literature
for children in the early years.  The project could build on the current
"concurso" for educators of children, ages 3 to 9 -- of experiences that relate
specifically to literature.  It could involve a broad process of bringing
together various groups (pre-school teachers, lower primary school teachers,
parents, publishers, writers and illustrators) to examine and discuss how
children's literature is produced in particular countries.  Is it left to
commercial publishers?  What are the human resources dedicated to illustration?
Do children's books show cultural sensitivity?  Where are the collections of
traditional stories and how widely are they available?  How much is imported
literature?  How are children involved in the process of producing stories and
socialized to reading, writing and appreciation of literature in the process?
How are story books used in homes, pre-schools and schools and how can they
help articulate these learning environments?<p>
<p>
	Training workshops could be held for budding writers and illustrators.
Technical expertise from such publishers as Norma might be drawn upon.<p>
<p>
	The project could be linked to the idea of a "canasta de aprendizaje" (rather
than a "canasta escolar").<p>
<p>
<b>3.  Mobilizing the health sector in support of early childhood care and
development.</b><p>
<p>
	At present, the health sector has focussed its attention on survival and
growth.  It has not turned its attention to development.  It continues, for the
most part to take a "disease" approach to health.  Materials for training
medical doctors have little to do with the social and mental health of young
children.  the psycho-social dimension of early development is not present in
programs of primary health care or in the training of midwives (from whom we
may have more to learn on this subject that to teach).<p>
<p>
	Such a project would involve intersectoral collaboration.  It could be linked
to parental education by demonstrating ways in which psychosocial content can
be integrated into health and nutrition education projects.<p>
<p>
	The project might be done in collaboration with the Pan American Health
Organization or professional organizations of pediatricians in particular
countries of the region.<p>
<p>
  <p>
<b>4.  Developing a Child Status Profile.</b><p>
<p>
	Missing from the descriptions of the status of children in most countries of
the region is a description of the psycho-social developmental status prior to
entering school.  Policy makers and planners must confront and try to improve
indicators of infant mortality and malnutrition, but need not deal with
problems of delayed or debilitated social and mental development.  School
policies do not have adequate data on the current and changing condition of the
children they receive to be able to do an adequate job of adjusting programs to
that reality.<p>
<p>
	A move is developing to try describe, as a profile, the health, nutritional
and psychosocial status of children in Colombia and Bolivia.  This would serve
both as a check on the effectiveness of programs designed to affect different
parts of the profile (or all of it).  SECAB might consider promoting the
development and institutionalizing of such indicators in other Convenio
countries.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>5.  Examining the Government-NGO connection.</b><p>
<p>
	As the move toward greater collaboration between governments and NGOs
develops, there will be a need to monitor the ways in which that process might
undercut the effectiveness of NGOs rather than increase their effectiveness.
SECAB could monitor the Venezuelan, Bolivian and Ecuadorian experiences and
bring together the interested parties to discuss results of the findings.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>A Closing Note</b><p>
<p>
	This paper will be considerably strengthened if it is put together with the
results that will be forthcoming from the regional meeting of networks to be
held in Colombia at the end of August and with the OAS seminar to be held in
Chile at the end of September.  From these meetings will come more recent (and
perhaps more accurate) data about the situation of children in the Convenio
countries as well as about new program efforts to improve that situation.
Undoubtedly, new suggestions will be made to fill in important program gaps.
It is suggested therefore, that SECAB take into consideration results of those
meetings in its deliberations.<p>
<p>
<a name="fn0">[1]</a>This approximate total was arrived
at by extrapolating the figure of 14 million young children under the age of of
5 years, as reported in UNICEF, <b>The State of the World's Children: 1993</b>,
New York: Published for UNICEF by the Oxford University Press, 1993,  Table 5,
p. 76.<p>
<a name="fn1">[2]</a>In this paper, the emphasis is taken off the key concepts
of "survival" and "growth" in order to concentrate on "care and development."
Child survival is often defined negatively as not dying before a certain age.
However, survival might more aptly be defined along a continuum running from
death to healthy development.  The further one is toward the healthy end of the
continuum, the greater the chances for survival.  "Growth" refers simply to
increasing in size.  That contrasts with "development" which involves ever
increasing levels of complexity.  For a more complete discussion of the
concepts of child survival, growth, development and care, see: Robert Myers,
<b>The Twelve Who Survive</b>, London: Routledge, 1992, Chapter 3.<p>
<sup>3</sup>This section draws heavily on: Robert Myers, <b>The Twelve Who
Survive</b>. London: Routledge, 1992, Chapter 5.<p>
<a name="fn2">[4]</a>In Colombia, a nationally normed scale now exists and an
attempt is being made to introduce use of the scale into the procedures used by
the health sector in monitoring health and nutrition.  This is, however, a very
recent development.  In other countries of the region various instruments for
measuring the psycho-social condition of children have been created locally or
appropriated from abroad and adjusted, but these have not been validated or
normed or accepted for use at a national level.  See: Atkin, L., "Analysis of
Instruments Used in Latin America to Measure Psychosocial Development and
Environmental Risk in Children from 0 to 6 Years of Age," A paper prepared for
the Consultative Group on Early Childhood Care and Development, New York,
1988.<p>
<a name="fn3">[5]</a>Comisi&oacute;n de Educaci&oacute;n Parvularia, "Proyecto
para Mejorar la Calidad y Ampliar la Covertura de la Educaci&oacute;n
Parvularia en Chile," Santiago, Chile, Ministerio de Educaci&oacute;n, Agosto
de 1990.



<p>

<b>REFERENCES</b><p>
