<p>
<p>
<b>APPENDIX A</b><p>
<b>PROGRAM GUIDELINES</b><p>
<p>
	The following is one set of principles and guidelines that might be followed
when developing and evaluating early childhood programs.<p>
<p>
	<b>1.  Priority should be given to families and communities living in
conditions that put their children "at risk" of delayed or debilitated
development.</b><p>
<p>
	If programming is to be guided by a principle of social justice, then emphasis
must be given to those most in need or "at risk."  Selecting those deemed to be
most in need or at risk will involve some combination of information about:<p>
<p>
   -	the condition of children (birth weight, nutritional and health status);<p>
   -	the condition of women (educational levels, health and nutritional status,
age at first pregnancy, work demands and earnings);<p>
   -	family and support systems (size and composition, employment and income,
the availability of adequate alternative child care);<p>
   -	childrearing beliefs and practices (feeding, health habits, nurturing,
communication); and <p>
   -	more general socioeconomic conditions (earnings and income distribution,
literacy rates, availability of potable water, access to health and other
services,m conditions of rapid social or economic change).<p>
	<p>
<p>
	<b>2.  Programs should form part of a comprehensive, multifaceted
strategy.</b><p>
<p>
	A programming strategy must begin with a set of objectives.  Often mentioned
as a starting point for child developments programs is the right of each child
to realize his or her potential.  What it means to realize one's potential is
defined somewhat differently in different cultures so the specific objectives
flowing from this goal will be different for different societies.  For this
reason it seems appropriate to take as the main goal for child development, and
hence of child development programs, the competence of children in adjusting
to, performing in, and transforming their own surroundings.  In some cultures
that will mean greater emphasis on independence; in others greater emphasis on
group solidarity.  In some cases, physical coordination will be central; in
others abstract reasoning.  In all, however, there will be physical,
intellectual and social dimension s of development.<p>
<p>
	<b>3.  Programs should be participatory and community-based.</b><p>
<p>
	Community participation is sometimes encouraged for its own sake, as a basis
for developing solidarity and greater control over one's own life.  More often,
however, participation is viewed instrumentally -- as a means of making
programs more effective by engaging potential recipients actively so that usage
will increase and so that the program will respond appropriately to local
needs.  A growing body of experience shows that community participation
increases the effectiveness of most programs.  And, community participation
allows extension of services beyond what would be possible using only the
budgets and resources of the public sector.<p>
<p>
	Community participation, to be authentic, should go beyond use or donation of
materials and time to include direct involvement in all phases of programming
activity -- in design, implementation and evaluation.  This implies the
existence and growth of organizational mechanisms through which participation
can be expressed.  It means involving the community at large, not just a
selected few individuals, in a process of discussion and action on a continuing
basis.<p>
<p>
	<b>4.  Programs should be flexible and adjusted to different sociocultural
contexts.</b><p>
<p>
	Nations, communities and cultures differ widely in the particular needs of
their children.  Unless programs can identify varying needs of diverse
communities and respond accordingly, programs run the risk of being irrelevant
to the prevailing conditions and needs.  Moreover, achieving real participation
will be difficult.  Arriving with a standard package of solutions to
preconceived problems does not favor participation or achieving the desired
outcomes.  If, however, community participation is to include consultation at
all stages, programs must be flexible enough to incorporate the results of that
consultation.  Nevertheless, there is a natural tendency for programmers to
seek standard solutions that can be spread widely (see also Guideline 7).<p>
<p>
	<b>5.  Programs should support and build upon local ways that have been
devised to cope effectively with problems of child care and development.</b><p>
<p>
	This guideline is based on the assumption that programs are more likely to
work if they begin with solutions devised and tried out locally rather than
with solutions imposed from outside.  It places an important value on coping
skills and on innovative measures born of necessity.  The position contrasts
with one in which knowledge is assumed to reside in the heads of outside
"experts" without, however, denying the potential role of outsiders in helping
communities see and experiment with new ways to enhance early childhood
development.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>6.  Programs should be financially feasible and cost-effective.</b><p>
<p>
	Clearly, programs must be possible to implement within recognized resource
constraints, and they should be economically feasible beyond an initial period
when costs may be borne by an outside source.  The economic "feasibility" of a
program, however, is only partly a matter of available funds -- it is also a
matter of priorities and of how funds are divided up.  If a program has been
assigned a high priority, it can be afforded and made feasible by giving up
something of lower priority.<p>
<p>
	This guideline is not couched in terms of "los-cost" programs.  The objective
is not to seek the lowest possible cost for a program.  Some cost-cutting
measures will also lead to a cut in effectiveness.  A low-cost project that has
little or no effect is a waste, more so than a program with higher costs that
is an effective program.<p>
<p>
	<b>7.  Programs should try to reach the largest possible number of children
living in conditions that put them at risk.</b><p>
<p>
	Because the need is so great in most countries, programmers should give
priority to those programs that offer the best prospect of reaching the most
children who are at risk, with an effective solution.  That means looking
beyond demonstration and pilot projects to the possibility of implementation on
a large scale.<p>
<p>
	The "scale" of each approach may be pictured simplistically as running from
very low coverage to a figure of 100%.  However, that is simplistic.  Not all
children may need to be reached, for instance.<p>
<p>
	"Scale" is often pictured as extending one model of coverage to all children.
Another way of viewing scale, however, is by adding together the results of
several different actions, each based on a different model, and each reaching a
different segment of the population.  Scale emerges as the puzzle pieces are
brought together.  This view allows high coverage to be increased by
encouraging a series of smaller initiatives as well as by launching national
programs.  Adopting this approach to scale is crucial in order to reconcile the
desire for community participation with the desire for broad coverage.<p>
   <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>APPENDIX B:  PRESCHOOL ENROLLMENTS</b><p>
<b>SELECTED COUNTRIES, BY AGE</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>APPENDIX C:  INTERNATIONAL ASSISTANCE</b><p>
<b>FOR PROGRAMS OF EARLY CHILDHOOD DEVELOPMENT</b><p>
<b>IN COUNTRIES OF THE CONVENIO ANDRES BELLO</b><p>
<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>	</b>International assistance for programs of early childhood care and
development in the Convenio countries should be seen against a more general
backdrop of trends in technical assistance related to early childhood.<p>
<p>
	<b>A dormant period.</b>  Prior to the 1980s, very little international
assistance was provided for early childhood programs.  The support that was
provided was, for the most part, directed toward small pilot or demonstration
projects.  Within education, emphasis was still being placed on assistance for
secondary (often technical) and university programs with, however, the
beginnings of a shift toward support for primary school education.  Health
programs were still oriented in the main toward hospitals and larger health
campaigns, with increasing attention to primary health care.  Food assistance
was about the only large scale assistance provided for children.  That
assistance was almost exclusively assistance in kind -- providing surplus food
in programs of food supplementation, some of which were targeted on pre-school
children and/or on pregnant and lactating mothers.  In these programs, an
integrated view of child development was lacking. <p>
<p>
	UNICEF provided some assistance for pre-school education, mostly for
facilities or for the training of pre-school teachers.  For the earlier ages,
attention was given also by UNICEF to early stimulation.  The development of
manuals and booklets for the education of parents and other caregivers was
funded, with a concentration of efforts in the Central American region.<p>
<p>
	Bi-lateral organizations provided few funds.  Here and there an isolated
project was supported as, for instance, in the case of Peru where USAID
provided assistance for experimentation with a home visiting program directed
toward improving the ability of families to provide their young children (ages
0 to 3) with a healthier and more adequate learning environment.<p>
<p>
	The support of major Foundations was focussed on research that included some
important research linking nutrition to cognitive development, but little
attention was given to practical applications of the research results or to
action projects in early childhood development.  An exception was that the
Bernard van Leer Foundation which, even during the 1970s, concentrated its
assistance on experimental community-based programs of early childhood care and
education.<p>
<p>
	The rather dramatic growth of international non-governmental organizations,
such as Christian Childrens' Fund and the Alliance of Save the Children, had
not yet occurred and the support provided through such programs was largely
directed toward children who had already passed beyond their pre-school
years.<p>
<p>
	Loan agencies, including the World Bank and the Inter-American Development
Bank had not begun to include attention to the early years in programming,
although some attention to health issues was beginning to grow prior to 1980.<p>
<p>
	<b>A small awakening.</b>  In 1978, the Alma Ata Conference gave an enormous
push to primary health care.  However, mental and social health was not among
the main lines of action emerging form Alma Ata.  With the International Year
of the Child in 1979, an up-swing occurred in the support for integrated
programs of early childhood care and development that included health and
nutrition as well as attention to the psycho-social development of young
children.   This support was, however, still in the main for small-scale
exper-imental programs.  Rather than gain momentum, early childhood programs
containing a psycho-social component were relegated to the background and
attention to child survival took center stage, promoted by UNICEF and the World
Health Organization working together.  The abundant funding for the health and
nutrition programs aimed at reducing infant mortality may have had an effect on
child development as well, but the main effect was on physical development.
Work in Chile, for instance, showed that although a dramatic drop in
malnutrition occurred from 1978 to 1990, measures of child development remained
constant over the period.<p>
<p>
	While international organizations were not putting much money into the early
childhood years during the 1980s, governments did begin to expand significantly
their pre-school programs, as indi-cated above in Table 3.  This was occurring
in spite of economic pressures in the region that began to mount with the
passing of the "lost decade" of the 1980s.<p>
<p>
	<b>Changing times.</b>  With the arrival of the 1990s, the climate for support
of early childhood programs began to change.  Three international events helped
to produce this change in climate.  The first was the approval of the
Convention on the Rights of the Child which led to approval by the United
Nations Assembly at the end of 1989.  The Convention, now approved by more than
150 countries, urged signatories to "...insure to the maximum extent possible
child survival and development (Article 6)  It also indicated that, while
placing primary responsibility for a child's upbringing with parents and
families, states must "insure the development of institutions, facilities and
services for the care of children (Article 18.2). <p>
<p>
	The second international event of importance was the World Conference on
Education for All which was held in Thailand in March of 1990, organized by
UNICEF, UNESCO, the World Bank, and UNDP.  The Declaration approved at the
Conference included the following statement:  "Learning begins at birth.  This
calls for early childhood care and initial education.  These can be provided
through arrangements involving families, communities or institutional programs,
as appropriate." (Article 5)  As indicated at the outset, The Framework for
Action also set expansion of early childhood care and development activities as
one of the targets to be considered in plans for the 1990's.<p>
<p>
	A World Summit for Children occurred in September 1990 that brought together
seventy heads of state to discuss the plight of children and to commit
themselves to improvements.  The Summit endorsed the conclusions of the World
Conference on Education for All and promoted the signing of the Convention on
the Rights of the Child.<p>
<p>
	It is not clear whether the subsequent increases in assistance to early
childhood care, development and education during these first years of the 1990s
can be attributed to a new visibility for children or to pressures from
national governments or to the natural evolution of events or to all of these
causes.  But some increases have occurred and, most importantly, some funds are
now available to help support larger scale programs.<p>
The World Bank <p>
<p>
	World Bank loans are negotiated with governments and most funds are provided
for government ministries, agencies and programs.  On occasion, however, the
funds are used by governments to help support efforts of NGOs as, for instance,
in the case of the Venezuelan loan listed below.<p>
<p>
	Prior to 1990, the World Bank had made no loans in Convenio countries that
could be considered in part or in whole as, "child care and development" loans.
Since 1990, however, the World Bank has made five loans that are either
focussed on, or include, early childhood care and development activities.
These are:<p>
<p>
	1.  <b>Colombia</b>.  In 1990, a loan of 24 million dollars was approved for
use over six years in the "Community Child Care and Nutrition Project."  Funds
are being used by the Colombian Institute of Family Welfare to strengthen the
on-going program of home-based child care which caters to the nutrition, health
and psycho-social development needs of children aged two through six in
low-income urban communities.  Included in the loan were funds for: equipment
and materials to introduce a regular system of training for community as well
as ICBF staff, credits to be used for up-grading the day care homes, the
development of a Management Information System, an impact evaluation, policy
development and program coordination.  (This loan represented less than 2% of
the total expenditures projected for the home day care program over the 6-year
period.)<p>
<p>
 	2.  <b>Venezuela</b>.  Also in 1990, a loan of 100 million dollars was
approved for use over seven years in a "Social Development Project."  The loan
represented 31% of the overall expenses of 320.9 million dollars projected for
the project over the seven years.  The loan was intended to help the GOV to
develop a social sector strategy, target its spending, cushion effects of
economic adjustment and promote institutional development in the Ministries of
Health, Education, and Family.  More specifically, the project supports:  (a)
rehabilitation and development of the primary health care network, including
provision of basic health and nutrition services for pregnant and nursing women
and children under six years of age ($60,500,000); (b) development and
expansion of pre-school education, focussed on the lower-income urban and rural
areas ($10,900,000); (c) information, education and communications services for
health, nutrition and education promotion ($8,200,000); and (d) improvement of
the GOV's capacity to design, plan and implement social programs and to monitor
the effect of such programs ($1,600,000).  When "contingency" funds and
anticipated national expenditures are added together, the total cost of the
childcare/pre-school component of the social development program was estimated
at 57.6 million dollars.<p>
<p>
	The pre-school component of the project anticipates expansion of the
community-based child day care program from 3,000 homes to 42,000 homes so as
to reach about half a million children from poor families, expansion of
pre-school enrollments by 96,000 children in conventional pre-schools and by
16,000 in non-conventional pre-schools, and introduction of a feeding program
in pre-schools.  The main support provided to pre-schools under the loan is for
construction of pre-schools, provision of furniture and materials, teacher and
staff training and supervision.  Some administrative costs of project
management units are also included.  The communications component of the loan
also includes elements directed toward improved child development, including
cognitive development.  For instance, funds are provided to the Ministry of the
Family to negotiate the rights to relevant television programs for pre-school
aged children.<p>
<p>
	Although it is clear that the health component of the loan also supports child
care and development, it is not possible to sort out what part of that
component assists development as well as survival.  Moreover, no provision was
made in the health part of the loan for specific attention to early stimulation
or to the psycho-social development of children in the earliest ages.  Impact,
therefore is most likely to be on physical development.<p>
 <p>
	3.  <b>Chile</b>.  In late 1991, a loan of 170 million dollars was approved,
for use over seven years, for a "Primary Education Improvement Project."  The
loan covers 74% of the projected 243 million dollar cost of the project.
Included in this project is an amount of 32.4 million dollars to expand
coverage and improve the quality of both formal and non-formal pre-school
programs.  When contingencies and local contributions to the project are
included, the estimated cost of this pre-school component is 39.3 million
dollars.<p>
<p>
	The loan specifies funding in the pre-school component to hire supervisors,
teachers and para-professionals, construct or refurbish facilities, provide
food rations design, produce and distribute materials, promote parent
involvement in the stimulation of their children, mount a mass media campaign
and carry out an evaluation.  Funds are targeted for 46,000 children (mostly
5-year olds) in areas of urban and rural poverty.<p>
<p>
	4.  <b>Ecuador</b>.  Also in late 1991, a loan of 89 million dollars was
approved, for use over 8 years, for a Social Development Project directed
specifically toward Education and Training.  The loan represents 75% of the
total project cost of 118.7 million dollars.  Included within the "urban basic
education" component of the project is support for a pilot pre-school component
to construct 60 pre-school classrooms attached to central primary schools in a
nuclear school system.  A high-quality formal pre-school model is indicated
which is to serve as an example for other pre-schools.  Short training courses
and materials are to be provided under the project.  Personnel from all types
of pre-schools have access to the training and materials.  Funds are also
provided for evaluation of this pre-school alternative, as compared with less
formal models.<p>
<p>
	5.  <b>Bolivia</b>.  In June 1993, a loan for 50 million dollars was approved,
for use over 5 years, for an "Integrated Child Develop-ment Program."  The loan
will support the extension of a home day care system to 9 major cities,
expecting to reach 130,000 children who are living in sections of those cities
where they are most at risk of delayed or debilitated development.  Funds will
help to strengthen the ability of the responsible government organization, the
National Organization for Minors, Women and Families (ONAMFA), to design and
manage the program, provide initial operational support (on a declining basis),
assist evaluation, look toward the expansion of programming to rural areas in
another phase of the project.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>UNICEF</b><p>
<p>
	In order to get an idea of UNICEF activities, annual reports for 1992 were
obtained for all of the Convenio countries.  These reports do not put dollar
figures on particular projects but do give a general idea of the kinds of
activities supported with UNICEF funds (or with the funds of others channeled
through UNICEF).  UNICEF has an office in each one of the Convenio countries.
<p>
<p>
	The bulk of UNICEF program funds are directed toward activities related to
child survival and growth.  In each country, attention is given to assisting
governments with plans and actions that help to meet commitments to the
Convention on the Rights of the Child, in light of the Declaration made at the
Summit for Children.  Child care and development activities are found in all
countries.  These activities vary considerably from place to place and include
support for experimental field projects, training, materials, advocacy,
diagnoses, and evaluation and research.  A unifying theme for much of the
UNICEF work in this area is attention to children through "informal" models.<p>
<p>
	Although most UNICEF funds are provided to governmental institutions for
governmental programs, a small portion of the available monies go to NGOs and
to universities or to individual researchers.<p>
<p>
	1.  <b>Bolivia.</b>  Support is provided to establish and run community-based
child care centers as part of a broader rural community development project in
selected villages in Norther Potos&iacute; and Southern Cochabamba.  The model
being tried out is unusual in that the centers are family enterprises (not run
only by mothers).  This project is funded through PROANDES, a regional project
which is financed by Italian government funds.<p>
<p>
	A bi-lingual education project carried out with Guarani- speaking children
includes a pre-school component and a follow-up evaluation of children in
primary schools.<p>
<p>
	UNICEF also provides materials and some training for educators in rural
non-formal pre-schools.<p>
<p>
	2.  <b>Colombia.</b>  Some funds were provided for the recently-completed
evaluation of the home day-care system.  UNICEF helped the Colombian government
formulate its national plan of action for children for the period 1991-94 and
supports social mobilization efforts in line with the plan.  Special projects
have been contracted out dealing with social indicators, identifying children
of high risk, and evaluating the "Year O" pilot project.<p>
<p>
<p>
	3.  <b>Chile.</b>  Direct support is provided to assist the implementation of
non-conventional low-cost forms of extending attention to pre-school children
through family day care centers, rural mini-centers and family creches.  A
series of evaluations have been supported as has work on child rearing
practices and patterns.<p>
<p>
	4.  <b>Ecuador.</b>  UNICEF support in Ecuador has assisted the National
Family Institute to evaluate and restructure its programs.  A study of
childrearing practices in rural and urban marginal areas was financed.<p>
<p>
	5.  <b>Panama.</b>  With UNICEF support an
inter-institutional/inter-disciplinary group has been formed to set up a
National Plan for Human Development.  Studies have been financed to: identify
oppor-tunities for technical support to the Panamanian Institute for Special
Training in the area of early childhood development, sexist practices in
pre-school centers, and child-rearing practices.  The last of these studies is
to be used in creating training materials for the Ministry of Education.<p>
<p>
	6.  <b>Peru.</b>  Studies have been supported of: the situation of day care
services in Metropolitan Lima, the effects of a national evaluation system on
learning achievement, the links between pre-schooling and primary education,
and the impact of a regulation authorizing enrollment of 5-year olds in the
first year of primary school.<p>
<p>
	7.  <b>Venezuela.</b>  Funding is provided for an evaluation of training
financed under the World Bank Loan to agents in programs of pre-school
education.<p>
<p>
	Other more general activities of UNICEF within the region provide assistance
that is available to Convenio countries.  For instance, a publication called
Facts for Life has been published that provides basic messages to be used for
education of parents and the public.  Most countries have made local adaptions
of this basic documents.  UNICEF carries out "Situation Analyses" as a part of
its general programming process.  Together with other institutions, UNICEF has
taken an active role in establishing a monitoring commitments made as a result
of signing the Convention on the Rights of the Child and made at the Summit for
Children.  Often this involves working with governments to develop National
Plans for Children incorporating the goals of the Summit and attending to the
provisions of the Convention. <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>The Bernard van Leer Foundation (BvLF)</b><p>
<p>
	According to its 1993 annual report, The BvLF has provided a total of 7.2
million dollars for projects in 4 Convenio countries in the three-year period
from 1989 to 1991.<p>
<p>
	1.  <b>Colombia (1.6 million).</b>  For almost a decade, the Foundation has
provided support to the Universidad del Norte to develop, implement and
evaluate a child-centered community development program in several villages
along the Northern coast.  Its 1989-91 support also included assistance to
CINDE to strengthen its resource and documentation center.  A third project,
with funding to the Department of Social Welfare in Cuidad Bolivar, supports a
community day care program.<p>
<p>
	2.  <b>Chile (2.9 million).</b>  Five projects were supported during the
period, four of which were NGO projects focusing, respectively on: an
experimental alternative early education model involving parents directly in
that education, operational research on the transition in early education,
community day-care centers for rural families in Southern Chile, and the
dissemination of innovative practices.  The national Foundation for the
Integrated Development of the Child has also received support to upgrade its
day care centers in urban and rural areas, concentrating on curriculum
development, parental involvement, a feeding program and staff training.  More
recently, the Foundation has also provided support to the Pastoral Social of
the Vicaria de Solidaridad within the Catholic Church, to the Junta Nacional of
Jardines Infantiles for a radio project in the South, to the Quakers to work
with a community organization in the improvement of peri-natal care and to an
organization called Opci&oacute;n to experiment with a program of home-based
care. <p>
<p>
	3.  <b>Peru (1.5 million).</b>   Within Peru, support has been focussed on the
governmental institution, INIDE, for the training of early education
"animators," using a system that the BvLF helped to develop through its support
to an experimental project carried out in conjunction with the Ministry of
Education over many years.<p>
<p>
	4.  <b>Venezuela (1.2 million).</b>  Here, support has gone to 1) the Ministry
of Education for child development workshops, 2) an NGO for a community
development project to meet the developmental and health needs of young
children and their families in a large town in the Paraguan&aacute; Peninsula
through parental education and training of community "promotores," and 3) an
NGO for a series of workshops for 120 community workers from 60 organizations
around the country on matters related directly to early childhood development
and for the production of child development materials aimed at parents,
community organizations and "animadores."<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>The Christian Childrens Fund (CCF)</b><p>
<p>
	The CCF works in only three Convenio countries: Bolivia, Colombia and Ecuador.
The CCF support has been focussed more on general community development
projects in rural areas and on activities affecting children older than age
five than on child development per se or on younger children.  Nevertheless, in
Bolivia, of 64 projects, five are for child development centers, and 10 are for
"social service centers.  In Colombia, the 54 projects include 10 child
development centers, 4 day care centers and 10 social service centers.  Work is
in both rural and urban areas.  Some attention is given to parental counseling
which includes sensitizing parents to developmental needs of their children and
to cultural preservation programs with indigenous peoples.  In Ecuador, only
one of 36 projects is specifically a child development project, but elements of
child survival and development are evident in support for immunization,
promotion of health education, food production programs, nutritional monitoring
and pre-and post natal care and education.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>The Interamerican Institute of the Child (IIN).</b><p>
<p>
	A great deal of the support provided by the IIN is directed toward provision
of information to institutions in the region.  A child information system is
being set up.  In addition to acting as a documentation center serving the
region as a whole, the IIN seeks to make its information systems live through
the participation in and organization of regional meetings and by involving
local institutions in a general process of collecting and disseminating
information.  In Colombia, the IIN works closely with the Rafael Pombo
Foundation, in Ecuador with the National Institute of the Family.  A
cooperative agreement is being developed with a center in Chile.<p>
<b>The United States Agency for International Development (USAID).</b><p>
<p>
	In the recent past, USAID has provided as great deal of support within the
region to programs directed to child survival but has done very little to
support child development or early education programs.  Recently, a sum of
$250,000 was provided to bolster the communications component within the
budding child development program in Bolivia.  In 1989, funds were provided for
a pilot evaluation of the home day care program in Colombia.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
