<p>
<center><b>MALAYSIAN EARLY CHILDHOOD DEVELOPMENT STUDY</b></center><p>
  <p>
<p>
Malaysia, a country rich in culture and resources, is projected to have a
population of nearly 20 million people by 1995.  It consists of two land
masses, separated by the South China Sea.  Peninsular (or Western) Malaysia,
which holds 82.3% of the population has  40% of the land.  Sabah and Sarawak,
on the other hand, with 60% of the land, are the home to 17.7% of the
population.<p>
<p>
The population of Malaysia is relatively young.  According to population
projections, at the present time the 0-15 age groups constitutes approximately
39% of the population (18% are in the birth through 6 age group), and 57% in
the 16-64 working-age group. Nearly 4% of the population is 65 or older (EPU,
1991). The population growth rate was 2.3% in 1990. (Yusof &amp; Zulkifil,
1992)<p>
<p>
In terms of health indicators, Malaysia has an infant mortality rate of 11/1000
live births, with a maternal mortality rate of 2/1000 live births.  The child
immunization rates are high: more than 90% of all children have been immunized
against BCG, DPT and Polio, with nearly 80% of all children immunized against
measles.  In terms of nutritional status, 75.5% of all children are in the
normal range; only .5% are severely malnourished.<p>
<p>
In the 1970s, Malaysia implemented the First Outline Perspective Plan (OPP1),
which embodied the New Economic Policy (NEP).  The NEP focused on eradicating
poverty and the restructuring of society. The Second Outline Perspective Plan
(OPP2), covers the years 1991 - 2000 and embodies the National Development
Policy (NDP)  It aims at balanced and sustainable development.  It also aims at
promoting human resource development and gives priority to the role of the
private sector as the engine of growth. <p>
<p>
The Sixth Malaysia Plan: 1991-1995 has as its <i>main thrust</i>, "to sustain
the growth and momentum and manage it successfully so as to achieve a more
balanced development of the economy".  One of the specific strategies
undertaken to achieve balanced development is to "enhance human resource
development".  <p>
<p>
The goals of balanced development are based on the following: <p>
<p>
<ul>Firstly, the principle of growth with equity is fundamental to ensure the
realization of a fair and equitable distribution of national wealth.  Secondly,
a balanced societal development is conducive to the maintenance of social and
political stability. Thirdly, the nurturing and moulding of a Malaysian society
with high moral values and ethics as well as positive attitudes are fundamental
towards the creation of a responsible, resilient, progressive and caring
society...The balanced development of the economy is essential to ensure stable
growth, minimize social conflicts, promote racial harmony and enhance national
unity.  (Sixth Malaysia Plan: 1991-1995, pg. 5)</ul><p>
<p>
With the above as some of the parameters of national development, Malaysia has
in the last twenty years experienced rapid changes economically and socially.
There have been increasing education and employment opportunities for women.
For example, the proportion of women classified as unpaid family workers fell
from 39.7% in 1970 to 21.6% in 1990.  This was largely due to the absorption of
women into the modern sector.  The proportion of women classified as 'employee'
rose from 38.9% in 1970 to 62.9% in 1990. (Sixth Malaysia Plan: 991-1995, pg.
415.  Women's participation in the labour force has increased significantly
since the Sixth Plan began.  Between 1970 and 1990 women's participation rate
increased slowly, from 31% in 1970 to 32.7% in 1980, 34.6% in 1985 and 35% in
1990.  In 1993 it was 47%.  (Mid-Term Review of the Sixth Malaysia Plan:
1991-1995, pg. 239)   Thus, increasingly women are entering the labour force.
This has impacted on their role within the family.<p>
<p>
There have been other changes which have influenced family life.  Over the past
twenty years there has been a significant rural-urban migration and
resettlement programmes of rural communities in land development and
rehabilitation schemes.  These have disrupted the traditional extended family
structure; many families now live as nuclear families.  This means that women
lack the traditional supports in terms of child care, thus creating an increase
in the  demand for alternative care of young children. <p>
<p>
Since the 1970s, and due to the emphasis given to the importance of education,
there has also been an increased awareness among parents, government and
non-governmental agencies (NGOs) of the importance of pre-school education for
five and six year old children. Given parental demand, there is a rapidly
increasing involvement of the private sector in providing pre-school
programmes, particularly in terms of bringing in "imported" models and
materials.  In addition, there is a tendency for many in the private sector to
provide `commercialised' programs which are appealing to parents, pre-school
teachers and caregivers, but which may not be sound in terms of child
development principles.<p>
<p>
Besides the increasing demand for programmes for children from 0 to six years
old, there is now a demand for after school care for children of working
parents.<p>
<p>
It is in relation to this changing situation in Malaysia that this study was
undertaken.<p>
<p>
<b><center>AIMS AND OBJECTIVES:</b></center><p>
<p>
Specifically, the purpose of this review was to assist the Government of
Malaysia in formulating a comprehensive and cost-effective ECD policy and
strategy linked to overall national development priorities.  Thus the
recommendations from the review focus on arrangements for effective
implementation, monitoring, management and coordination of ECD activities, and
the identification of broad policy and strategy options for strengthening ECD's
contribution to national development.<p>
<p>
What follows is a listing of the aims and specific objectives of the review and
a summary of how they were accomplished.  Further detail in relation to each of
the aims is provided in the main text of the document. <p>
<p>
AIMS<p>
<p>
<ol>	(1)	<b>to examine current ECD programme coordination mechanisms, including
existing legal provisions;</b><p>
<p>
	All agreed that this is an area of primary concern.  Thus considerable effort
was put into recommendations regarding coordination of ECD activities, and the
legislation required to support the recommendations.<p>
<p>
	(2)	<b>to inform key ECD managers of relevant experiences from other countries
in the formulation and implementation of ECD policy;</b><p>
<p>
As data on ECD provision were gathered in Malaysia, the situation of young
children and ECD programming was compared with other countries.  As part of
discussions during the Phase 1 workshop, and in the Phase 3 Workshop,
experiences from elsewhere were highlighted to provide examples of
alternatives.  Thus as the recommendations were formulated, this was done with
an understanding of how other countries have addressed similar concerns. <p>
<p>
	(3)	<b>to propose arrangements for the effective implementation, monitoring,
management and coordination of ECD programmes;</b><p>
  <p>
	The recommendations include proposed arrangements for the effective
implementation, monitoring, management and coordination of ECD programmes.
These were derived from the studies and the various workshop experiences.  <p>
<p>
	(4)	<b>to identify broad policy and strategy options for strengthening ECD's
contribution to national development; </b><p>
  <p>
Through the workshops and sub-studies the broad policy issues and strategy
options were described and discussed. These have been included in the
conclusions, the policy and recommendation sections.<p>
<p>
	(5)	<b>to review the nature and extent of current linkages between ECD
programmes, parents and the community and suggest ways in which such linkages
might be extended. </b><p>
  <p>
The study revealed that parent and community involvement is seriously lacking
in relation to ECD provision.  With the Government expectation that the
community will take increasing responsibility for ECD provision, it is critical
that parent and community involvement be defined in terms of empowerment. It is
important in continue to educate ECD managers regarding the experience of other
countries in mobilizing parents and the community in relation to ECD.</ol><p>
<p>
<p>
SPECIFIC OBJECTIVES<p>
<p>
<ol>	(1)	<b>to prepare a profile of existing ECD programmes in relation to
needs;</b><p>
  <p>
A mapping was done of those currently providing ECD services, in relation to
different populations in Malaysia. (See Part II)  The mapping includes basic
data on institutional based pre-school and child care centres provided by
government, non-governmental agencies and the private sector.<p>
<p>
	(2)	<b>to undertake selected case-studies of the non-institutional
home/family-based and after school care services;</b><p>
  <p>
As a part of the three sub-studies (on curriculum, parent/community involvement
and training), the various models of ECD provision in Malaysia were included.
This provides a picture of the strengths and weaknesses of the various
approaches - institutional and well as non-institutional.  <p>
<p>
	(3)	<b>to establish a comprehensive ECD data base;</b><p>
  <p>
	We are interpreting `data base' to mean gaining an understanding of the needs
for ECD services (i.e. how the population of children 0-9 is distributed
(geographically and by socio-economic grouping), what populations are currently
being served, where are the gaps in services, etc.), along with a comprehensive
understanding of the resources available to support the development and
promotion of ECD in Malaysia. In terms of the former, more work needs to be
done, particularly in terms of the identification of groups most in need of
services.  In terms of the latter, that has been accomplished within the study.
<p>
<p>
	(4)	<b>to analyze overall ECD programme costs;</b><p>
<p>
This aspect of the study is the least well developed. While we were able to get
some cost data regarding the actual operation of a given ECD programme, we were
unable to get data related to administrative costs from the various Ministries
involved in ECD programming.  Within the text of this report we suggest a
strategy that could be used to obtain more accurate cost information.<p>
<p>
	(5)	<b>to review existing research findings;	</b><p>
	<p>
The studies which have been undertaken in Malaysia in relation to ECD were
reviewed.  The primary focus of these studies has been on either child
development in Malaysia or pre-school education.  Very little has been done in
terms of research in relation to programmes for children under the age of 4,
and there have been little research on the impact of various ECD programme
models on children's later development. In order to understand whether or not
ECD programmes are having a positive impact, and if so, in what ways, funds
should be allocated to this kind of research. <p>
<p>
	(6)	<b>to review the status of ECD curriculum, teaching and learning methods,
materials production and training as related to the delivery of programmes of
satisfactory quality;</b><p>
  <p>
	Because programme quality is so important in terms of determining whether or
not there are positive outcomes for children in ECD programmes, three
sub-studies (one on curriculum, one on parent/community involvement, and one on
training) were conducted.  The results are reported on in this study.</ol><p>
<p>
<center><b> A NATIONAL ECD POLICY</b></center><p>
<p>
It is known that:<p>
<p>
<ul>the foundation for children's growth and development is established within the
first few years of life and that learning begins at birth;</ul><p>
<p>
Further, it has been demonstrated that:<p>
<p>
<ul>conducive and stimulating environments that enhance young children's physical,
mental, social, emotional and spiritual development lead to holistic and
balanced individuals; and that <p>
<p>
investments in early childhood development modify social and economic
inequalities, addressing the issues of accessibility, equity and equality; and
that <p>
<p>
quality early childhood programmes provide an environment which supports the
transmission of cultural, moral and religious values that are the underpinnings
of a fully moral and ethical society.</ul><p>
<p>
Thus, with a focus on Vision 2020 and the nine central strategic challenges,
the Government of Malaysia has made a commitment to the promotion of the
importance of early childhood years, from conception through the early primary
grades.  Further, in accordance with government policy, close collaboration
will be sought with the private sector in the implementation of appropriate
early childhood programmes.  <p>
<p>
<center><b>RECOMMENDATIONS</b></center><p>
<p>
The study undertaken provided an understanding of the strengths of ECD
provision within Malaysia.  It also indicated issues to be addressed to enhance
the capacity of Government, non-governmental agencies, the private sector and
the public to promote the well-being of all young children.  Within this
section of the report there is a delineation of the overall findings, with
specific recommendations for action.<p>
<p>
<ol>1.	At the present time Malaysia lacks a comprehensive policy to support the
overall development of young children as they make the transition from home to
care outside the home, to preschool and then into the primary school.  Current
services are fragmented  and there is a lack of interface among the agencies
currently serving young children and their families.<p>
<p>
<b>Therefore it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>a comprehensive and integrated ECD policy for Malaysia be adopted to meet
the needs of children from conception through the early primary school years.
The policy should:</b><p>
  <p>
<ol><b>	1)	be related to Vision 2020, and the National Development Policy </b><br>
<b>	2)	address important national issues, for example:</b><br>
<b>-  challenges associated with the quality of life desired for Malaysians,
including the strengthening of the family and moral, ethical and spiritual
values.</b><br>
<b>-  the support and enhancement of the National Plan of Action related to the
World Summit on the Survival, Protection and Development of Children.</b><br>
<b>-  challenges associated with increasing the labour force participation
among women for the industrialization programme, and the implications for the
family.</b><br>
<b>Thereby, ECD contributes to Human Resources Development.</b></ol></ul><p>
  <p>
2.  	Currently ECD services are fragmented, addessing only selected ECD needs<p>
<p>
<b>Therefore, it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>a review of current legislation affecting young children and their families
be undertaken. </b></ul><p>
  <p>
3.	There is a lack of data about what happens to children who are not in
registered child care and preschool programmes, and what happens for children
when they are not attending child care, preschool or lower primary school.
There is also a lack of data on children who are not attending lower primary
school and also children with special needs<p>
<p>
<b>Therefore, it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
  <ul>a study be undertaken to more completely document the situation and
needs of young children.</ul><p>
<p>
4.	There are well-developed Preschool Curriculum Guidelines for children 4-6
years of age.  There is no equivalent curriculum guideline for children under
the age of four.  <p>
<p>
<b>Therefore it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>comprehensive, integrated Curriculum Guidelines be developed for children
from birth to six years of age that interface with the Primary School
Curriculum. </b></ul><p>
   <p>
<p>
5.	ECD planning and practice must rest on a comprehensive and integrated data
base.  At the present time there is no comprehensive data bank on ECD needs and
provision.  It is important to have a better understanding of needs as related
to provision.<p>
<p>
<b>Therefore, it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>the Ministry of Health, through additions to their Home-based Child Health
Card, collect relevant data on children (0-6 years) and through the school
health records data on children (6-9 years).  There is also a need to compile
Malaysian-based child development indicators. </b></ul><p>
  <p>
<b>Further, it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>the Ministry of Education maintain responsibility for the data base for
children aged 4-9.  Agencies providing services to this age group should
channel their data to this Ministry.</b></ul><p>
  <p>
<b>Further, it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>data for target groups like immigrant children should be collected by the
Ministry of Home Affairs and channelled to the Ministry of Health or the
Ministry of Education for the respective age group.</b></ul><p>
  <p>
  <p>
6.	A cornerstone of effective early childhood programmes internationally is
parent and community involvement in all aspects of the programme.  The study
revealed that this in lacking in most programmes.  <p>
<p>
<b>Therefore it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>the concept of parent involvement be broadened to a concept of parent
participation which respects and strengthens the parent's role in the child's
development and establishes linkages between the home, early childhood
programmes and children's transition into the primary school.</b></ul><p>
  <p>
<b>Further, it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>parent and community support and involvement be mobilized in creating
awareness, planning, implementing, and sharing the cost of ECD
programmes.</b></ul><p>
  <p>
<b>Further, it is also recommended that:</b><p>
  <ul>media be involved in promoting a greater understanding of child
development, and the responsibility and role of the private sector in ECD
provision.</ul><p>
  <p>
  7.	Training is a key component in the successful implementation of any
curriculum.  The study revealed that current training, for the most part is
inadequate.<p>
<p>
<b>Therefore it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>a national ECD Training System be established which provides a framework for
the development of training packages, certification for trainees, accreditation
of trainers and training centres, decentralized resource centres, and
mechanisms for monitoring and evaluating training programmes.</b></ul><p>
  <p>
  
8.	Research and evaluation provide data important in the planning process.
Across ECD programmes there is a lack of evaluation of programme effectiveness
and impact.  Further, there is a gap between academic research and its
application in terms of programming. <p>
<p>
<b>Therefore it is recommended that the following research be pursued:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>-  the impact of available models (e.g. home and community based as well as
centre-based) on children's later growth and development.</b><br>
 
<b>-  the cost-effectiveness of different programme approaches.</b></ul><p>
  <p>
9.	At the present time government provision of ECD is heavily subsidized.  <p>
<p>
<b>Therefore, it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>in line with government policy to increase the private sector participation
in all public services, strategies be developed which will shift the financing
of ECD from Government to the private sector, the community and parents.</b></ul><p>
  <p>
<b>Further, it is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>alternative models of financing ECD be explored, including taxation, the
development of Trusts, and philanthropic initiatives.  The 1994 Budget includes
a tax benefit for businesses offering ECD services.  The effectiveness of the
approach needs to be evaluated.</b></ul><p>
  <p>
To address the issues identified and the recommendations made thus far,<p>
<p>
<b>It is recommended that:</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>as an interim measure, a National Early Childhood Development Council be
created within the Prime Minister's Department for the purpose of formulating,
conceptualizing and overseeing ECD programmes in the various sectors
(government, non-governmental and private).  The Council should be supported by
a strong Secretariat with technical skills related to ECD.  In the long term
the Council should be institutionalised within a major Ministry. </b></ul></ol><p>
  <p>
  
<center><b>PART I:  MAIN STUDY</b></center><p>
<p>
<p>
<b>SCOPE OF THE STUDY</b><p>
<p>
This study consisted of three phases.  The first phase was a workshop, held in
Kuala Lumpur, July, 1994.  All government agencies currently providing some
type of ECD programme were in attendance.  At the workshop, Phase 2 was
developed.  Phase 2 involved the mapping of what exists in terms of current
service provision and the supports for such provision (e.g. curriculum,
materials, and training); the legislation/ policies in place related to ECD
programmes; and coordination of services. While the focus of the Phase 2 review
was primarily on what is being offered by various government departments, where
there is a significant contribution to ECD by non-governmental agencies (NGOs),
the private sector and those involved in ECD provision for commercial reasons,
these were also included in the study.  Phase 3 consisted of another workshop.
At that workshop, held November 21-22 in Kuala Lumpur, the results of Phase 2
were presented and the recommendations were formulated. <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>DEFINITION OF TERMS:</b><p>
<p>
Early Childhood Development (ECD)<p>
<p>
Early on in the study it was realized that we needed to have a common
understanding of what is meant by the term Early Childhood Development (ECD).
There are two parts to the phrase, <i>early childhood</i> and
<i>development</i>.  As it is currently used internationally, <i>early
childhood</i> is defined as the period of a child's life from conception to age
9. <p>
<p>
The inclusion of children from conception through age 8 in a definition of
early childhood development is consistent with the way developmental
psychologists view the continuum of children's development. Children below the
age of 9 learn best when they have objects they can manipulate; when they have
chances to explore the world around them; when they can experiment and learn
from trial-and-error within a safe and stimulating environment.  At about the
age of nine they begin to view the world differently.  They can manipulate
ideas and learn concepts mentally and are less dependent on objects.  Thus in
terms of learning theory, the birth through age 8 time period presents a
developmental continuum.<p>
 <p>
Another reason for including children in the early primary grades in a
definition of early childhood development is that there is often a difficult
transition for children either from home or from a preschool programme into the
primary school, due to the radical differences in expectations.  Thus, if
programmes for children before they enter the primary school are to be
effective, there needs to be interface between what happens in the preschool
and lower primary school.  This does not mean that early childhood programmes
for the children under the age of 6 have to accommodate to the requirements of
the primary school.  It means that the primary school also needs to be examined
in terms of its readiness to receive children.<p>
<p>
In the definition of ECD <i>development</i> is being defined as a process of
change in which the child comes to master more and more complex levels of
moving, thinking, feeling and interacting with people and objects in the
environment.  Development involves both a gradual unfolding of biologically
determined characteristics and the learning process. <p>
<p>
<i>Learning</i> is the process of acquiring knowledge, skills, habits and
values through experience and experimentation, observation, reflection, and/or
study and instruction.  Both the child's physical growth (the child's health
and nutrition history and current health and nutritional status) are crucial in
the child's overall development.  Where the child is developmentally either
facilitates or inhibits future learning.  Thus learning is part of the
development process. And, learning begins at birth; it is not something that
happens once the child is exposed to the 3Rs or enters primary school. <p>
<p>
To further clarify the relationship between development and learning, it is
important to define the basic principles of child development and learning that
were brought to this study. <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>CHILD DEVELOPMENT PRINCIPLES</b><p>
<p>
<ul><li>   	<b>Development begins pre-natally and learning is occurring at birth.</b><p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Attention to the developmental and learning needs of children
should begin with pre- and post-natal interventions and be continued
thereafter.<p>
<p>
   	<li><b>Development and learning occur continuously as a result of the child
interacting with the environment.</b><p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Interventions can focus on changing the child and/or on changing
the environment (which includes the immediate family, the community, social and
political institutions).  <p>
<p>
   	<li><b>Development has several inter-related dimensions within which learning
occurs. </b> These include physical, cognitive, social, spiritual and emotional
dimensions (each of which affects the other and all of which are developing
simultaneously).<p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Development and learning must be seen holistically and
interventions should provide integrated attention to the child, including
attention to needs for protection, food, health care, affection, interaction
and stimulation, security provided through consistency and predictability, and
play allowing exploration. All of these elements should be present to support
the child' development.<p>
<p>
   	<li><b>Development proceeds in predictable steps and learning occurs in
recognized sequences.</b><p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Interventions should follow an appropriate sequence. Activities
should provide the child with a developmentally appropriate challenge.  There
is no value in presenting them before a child is developmentally ready for
them.<p>
<p>
   	<li><b>There is a great deal of individual and social variability in children's
rates and styles of development and of learning.</b><p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Interventions should be able to identify and adjust to varying
individual and social needs of children.<p>
<p>
   	<li><b>Children are active participants in their own development and
learning.</b> Learning and related development involves the child's
construction of knowledge, not an adult's imposition of information.  The
skills which are the basis for constructing knowledge improve with practice.<p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Interventions should include opportunities for children to learn
by doing, to be engaged in problem-solving, and the develop language and
communication skills. They should not put undue emphasis on cognitive/mental
development.<p>
<p>
   	<li><b>Children learn in many ways:</b> by playing and exploring, by using all
their senses, by imagining, by imitating, by interacting socially with
others.<p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Integrated interventions promoting social, emotional and spiritual
development as well as cognitive learning can take advantage of varied forms of
learning, consistent with cultural ways even while taking into account that
there are recognized sequences and activities that facilitate learning. <p>
<p>
   	<li><b>It helps a child to develop and learn when adults (parents, teachers and
community members</b>:<p>
<p>
<ul>	  -	are emotionally responsive and involved<br>
	  -	talk to children<br>
	  -	provide appropriate and varied play materials<br>
	  -	are supportive of the child's learning</ul><p>
<p>
	Therefore: Interventions should include ways to address the needs of children
within the context of the family and community.  Attention should be given to
adults as well as to children in programme planning and implementation.</ul><p>
<p>
<p>
In addition to some principles about child development, it is useful to also
outline some of the programming principles which have provided the framework
for the analysis of current ECD programming in Malaysia.  <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>PROGRAMMING PRINCIPLES</b><p>
  <p>
  	Some of the following operational principles are directly related to
the principles of development and learning set out previously.  Others are
general principles of programming that apply to ECD programmes as well as to
other kinds of programmes. Behind all of the principles is the desire to mount
effective and sustainable programmes.<p>
<p>
<ul><li>   	<b>Seek programme integration in conceptualizing, planning, delivering
services, establishing content and promoting use.</b></ul><p>
<p>
	This principle derives in part from the holistic nature of child development
in which physical, mental, social and emotional and spiritual dimensions of
development interact with and affect each other.  Hence, effectiveness requires
integrated attention to children.  In addition, there is a maximization of
resources when programmes are multi-dimensional, combining health, nutrition,
educational and social actions.   <p>
  <p>
<ul><li>   	<b>Foster participation by individuals, families and communities who are to
be the primary beneficiaries.</b></ul><p>
<p>
	A principle of active participation is consistent with the basic principles of
learning and development described above.  Sustained human and social
development and the sustainability of programmes all depend on enhancing
people's capacities to improve their own lives and to take greater control over
their own destinies.<p>
<p>
<p>
   	<ul><li><b>Build child-focused partnerships by expanding existing collaboration and
bringing together new partners supportive of development.</b></ul><p>
<p>
	Neither governments nor communities nor a wide range of non-governmental
organizations can easily maintain an effective programme without help.  The
principle of developing partnerships between government, non-governmental
agencies, the private sector and the community arises from social as well as
financial needs.<p>
<p>
   	<ul><li><b>Build on inherent strengths and local childrearing practices that are
beneficial to child and social development.</b></ul><p>
<p>
	Knowledge about solutions to child development problems can be found in
experience and traditional wisdom as well as in academic wisdom or new
technologies. Childrearing practices that are supportive of children's growth
and development should be encouraged and built upon in programming.<p>
<p>
   <ul><li>	<b>Take an inter-generational view; seek ways of involving children, youth
and adults.</b></ul><p>
<p>
	Programmes of early childhood development can and should benefit parents,
other caregivers and community members as well as children.  Child care, for
instance, is generally the responsibility of various family members (older
siblings and extended family members in addition to fathers and mother).
Programmes should take into account the needs of families as well as the needs
of children. <p>
<p>
<ul><li>   	<b>Be open to diversity and to complementary approaches.</b></ul><p>
<p>
	This principle derives in part from the social and individual variation in
children' needs.  It is also derived from a recognition of the cultural
diversity which exists within and across nations. Programmes which respect this
diversity will necessarily differ. <p>
<p>
<ul><li>   	<b>Be aware of the total environment and its impact on the child's
life.</b></ul><p>
<p>
	A child does not exist on his/her own.  The child's development in affected by
the environment with which the child interacts.  This includes the home, the
community, social institutions and legal frameworks, and a cultural ethos.  A
comprehensive programme to improve child development should function
simultaneously at these different levels, focusing respectively on the child,
caregivers, national institutions and policies, and the knowledge base of the
society. <p>
<p>
<ul><li>   	<b>Seek quality.</b></ul><p>
<p>
	Low quality programmes are ineffective, depriving children of benefits, and
represent a waste of resources.  In seeking quality, recognize that it is
affected by the motivation and training of programme personnel, the physical
environment, the materials used, and the form of the curriculum.  A quality
programme is appropriate to the stage of development and addresses the needs of
the child involved while respecting individual differences in development.
Quality cannot be legislated.  Setting norms and standards does not guarantee
quality.  Neither is quality defined by expenditure level.<p>
<p>
   	<ul><li><b>Aim at universal attention to children, but with special recognition of
children living in conditions that put them at increased risk of delayed or
debilitated development.</b></ul><p>
	<p>
	This principle recognizes the need for all children to be supported as they
grow and develop, while stressing the urgency of attending to children living
in poverty or those who are discriminated against as a result of ethnic
diversity.  <p>
 <p>
<ul><li><b>Coverage is best achieved by combining a variety of approaches rather
than developing a single national model meant to apply to all.</b></ul><p>
  <p>
	Attention to all the children can be sought through a series of different
programmes responding to distinct needs.  There need not be one national
programme that is extended to all children, parents or communities.<p>
<p>
<ul><li>   	<b>Seek cost-effectiveness.</b></ul><p>
<p>
	This principle recognizes the importance of using scarce resources efficiently
and effectively.  This does not mean that "low-cost" programmes are necessarily
the best. If they are not effective they represent a waste of resources. In
general, strategies that stress prevention are more cost-effective than
compensatory strategies.<p>
<p>
   <ul><li>	<b>Incorporate monitoring and evaluation into programmes from the
outset.</b></ul><p>
<p>
	This principle recognizes that many programmes are not effective or are not
sustained because they do not include the capacity to analyze strengths and
weaknesses and to adjust accordingly.  It is with these principles and
guidelines in mind that the review of early childhood development programmes in
Malaysia was undertaken. Before reviewing the findings of the study, however,
it is important to clarify how ECD terminology is used in Malaysia.<p>
<p>
  <p>
<b>ECD TERMS IN MALAYSIA </b><p>
<p>
What is important in the Malaysian context is to realise that the pre-school
years (in this instance ages 5 and 6) are only a part of the early childhood
continuum.  Thus pre-school and ECD are not interchangeable terms.<p>
<p>
In Malaysia, the term <i>kindergarten</i> has been used to refer to a half-day
programme for children 5 &amp; 6 years of age.  However, there has been a
recent shift in terminology.  These are now called <i>preschools</i>.  Children
below the age of 4 are provided for in <i>child care</i> centres.  Children are
also taken care of in homes by childminders.  This is known as <i>home-based
child care</i>.  <i>Community-based</i> generally refers to parent education
programmes.<p>
<p>

<center><b>PART II: FINDINGS</b></center><p>
<p>
<b>RESEARCH ON ECD</b><p>
<p>
The research on ECD in Malaysia has been focused primarily on various aspects
of pre-school education.  A major study was undertaken in November 1980 when
the Educational Planning Committee commissioned the educational Planning and
Research Division (EPRD) of the Ministry of Education to undertake a study of
preschool education in Malaysia.  The study was designed to provide data that
could be used in the formulation of policy.  The study received support from
the Economic Planning Unit as well, as they were seeking a comprehensive
understanding of preschool education in Malaysia.  Financial support for the
study was received from UNICEF.  <p>
<p>
In relation to the study a series of seminars was held in different parts of
Malaysia.  The first occurred in December 1981. Within this seminar the areas
to be covered in the study were outlined.  The second seminar, held in
September 1983, focused specifically on preschool curriculum.  The third and
final seminar was held in December 1984. At that seminar the findings from the
study were presented and discussed. (UNICEF, undated - circa 1985, pg.3)<p>
<p>
Within the December 1984 Seminar, there were a series of papers presented that
focused on the impact of preschool education on primary school performance. One
paper in particular, "Major Findings of the Correlational Study" (Zainal,
1984), looked at children's performance in primary school at Standard I and II
in relation to their preschool experience.  The results indicated that there is
a "head start" advantage for those who have had preschool.  However, the amount
of advantage gained by attending preschool depends on the type of preschool
centres attended and the type of primary schools attended, as well as the
location of both.  <p>
<p>
There was also a relationship between socio-economic status and the extent to
which children benefitted from preschool.  Those children from more
disadvantaged areas gained more than children from higher socio-economic
groups. (UNICEF, circa 1985, pg. 20-21)  Thus the argument can be made that any
government provision of ECD services should be targeted to the more
disadvantaged strata of society.  And, by and large, ECD programmes supported
by the government of Malaysia have focused on reaching children in rural and
low-income urban areas who could benefit most from an ECD programme. <p>
<p>
An important aspect of the Zainal study was that it focused on the nature of
the primary school that children entered as well as the type of preschool
experience children had.  Too often studies focus only on the impact of the
preschool experience on children's later achievement, not taking into account
the fact that primary schools are very different and that what the child brings
to the primary school in terms of knowledge, skills and competencies is only
part of the equation for success.  The other critical feature is the school's
capacity and readiness to build on what the child brings. <p>
A research project reported on in the preschool study focused on dropouts
(1973).  At the time of the study there was an `express' class within the
primary school.  In essence this amounted to a double promotion.  It was
discovered that 90% of the children who were put into the express class were
those who had a preschool experience. (UNICEF, circa 1984, pg.3) In other
words, those with preschool were better prepared for school than their peers
and this was immediately evident when they reached the primary school. <p>
<p>
Within the Third National Seminar there was also a paper on the impact of care
being provided outside the home during the early years on children's later
achievement. (Yusof, 1984)  The study indicated that some children who are left
in childcare centres and preschools because their mothers work full-time may
face developmental problems.  He noted that the reason for this was that most
childcare centres do not provide `adequate facilities both physical and human
to nurture the child at such  tender age.'  (UNICEF, circa 1985, pg. 21)
Frequently custodial care facilities, while keeping the child safe, do not
provide children with the stimulation they need to develop fully.  <p>
<p>
The relationship between poor quality programmes and children's later
development are echoed in other countries.  When children do not have a
stimulating environment within the centre-based programme, their development
suffers.  Thus, when we are promoting the importance of early childhood
programmes to foster the growth and development of children, we must be clear
that we are advocating for QUALITY programmes, not simply any programme. <p>
<p>
The preschool study undertaken by EPRD focused primarily on the structure of
the pre-school programme -- how many children were being reached, and where.
In addition it looked at the teaching force involved in preschool programmes
and the administrative and organisational structure in place to support the
programme. It also looked at the issue of costs (fees charged, staff salaries
and sources of income).  The results of the study were compiled and
recommendations for action were put forward. <p>
<p>
Beyond the specific research related to pre-school, Malaysia is rich in studies
on child development, particularly from across-cultural perspective (Chiam,
1991).  However, the results of this kind of academic research has seldom been
applied programmatically. There are a few studies available on the health,
hygiene and nutritional status of young children which highlight useful data
for health programming and education. <p>
<p>
Other than the attempt by the Department of Welfare to compile traditional
parenting practices among the different ethnic groups, none of the other
government agencies involved in ECD provision has seriously undertaken
empirical/applied research relating to ECD issues beyond studies of the
preschool. Further, few of the ECD programmes have incorporated action-research
as an integral component of its data-based planning and programming.  An
exception is a recent study commissioned by KEMAS to assess parent involvement
in the KEMAS preschool programme. The results of the study showed that KEMAS
parents who send their children to the preschool (TBK) have little knowledge
about the TBK objectives, children's daily  activities and curriculum.  In
addition, both parents and community members stated that their involvement in
the programme was important (85% and 76% respectively), yet they report that
their input is very low. (Putri, Bahaman and Ariffin, 1994) <p>
<p>
Evaluation of programme impact and effectiveness are almost negligible. If at
all available, these are mostly done in-house in the form of summative and
status reports and therefore lack independent and objective assessment. No
longitudinal studies have been carried out on any current ECD model.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>REVIEW OF CURRENT ECD ACTIVITIES</b><p>
<p>
To understand the position of ECD activities in Malaysia today it is important
to get some sense of trends over the last 20 years.  For example, in Table 1 it
is possible to see the growth in the number of preschools during that time
period.  As can be seen, there has been tremendous growth in terms of preschool
provision.<p>
<p>
<p>
<center><b>TABLE 1</b><p>
  <p>
<b>EXPANSION OF PRE-SCHOOL CENTRES AND ENROLMENT </b><p>
<b>1970-1994</b></center><p>
  <p>

<pre>
Year     Number of     Increase      Number of     Increase      Children/     
         Centres       across yrs    Children      across yrs    centre        
                         (%)                         (%)                         
1970        349                        24,801                       71         
                         752%                         589%                     
1980      2,974                       170,955                       57         
                         103.3                        92.3                    
1990      6,046                       328,813                       54         
                          54.0                        26.1                    
1994      9,311                       414,670                       44         

</pre>
<p>
Source:	<b>Development of and Issues in Pre-school and Primary Education</b>,
Dr. Leong Yin Ching, Situation Analysis Paper, UNICEF, 1992, pg. 14<br>
		Ministry of Education, 1994<p>
<p>
There has also been an interesting change in the number of children in
preschool centres.  The average number of children in a centre has decreased
over the years, from 71 children in 1970,  to 44 children in 1994. <p>
<p>
Another way to look at the increase is in terms of the percentage of the age
cohort that is served in an ECD programme.  In Table 2 there is a presentation
of the number of preschool centres, the number of children served in these
centres and the percentage of the age cohort that is in preschool from 1986 to
1994.<p>
<p>
What Table 2 indicates is that for nearly 10 years the percentage of the age
cohort being served by kindergartens has remained more or less the same -
between 34 and 41%.  At the same time, there has been a 59% increase in the
number of preschool centres, and a 33% increase in the number of children
served. This finding reinforces the fact that the number of children per centre
is decreasing.  It also suggests that the creation of preschools is only
marginally ahead of the population growth rate (20% between 1986 and 1994).
<p>
<p>
<p>
<center><b>TABLE 2</b><p>
  <p>
