<b>OF THE AGE COHORT BEING SERVED*</b><br>
<b>1986 - 1994</b></center><p>


<pre>
             Number of       Number of      Population       Percentage of    
             Centres         Children       children         cohort in        
                             enroled        5-6 years*       Centre           
 
   1986        5,847          310,926         837,647          37.1%          
   1990        6,046          328,813         955,599          34.4%          
   1991        6,442          372,768         973,147          38.3%          
   1992        7,483          385,201         985,428          39.1%          
   1994        9,311          414,670       1,002,288          41.3%          

</pre>
<p>
* 	Since no one source had data on each year, these data were taken from
different sources.  Thus the accounting may have been different across the
years.<br>
**	It should be noted that some children in the 6 year old cohort are in
primary school (Entrance into primary school is based on the year in which you
were born, not your actual age.)  It is also true that there are some children
aged 3 &amp; 4 in the preschool. However, since it is not possible to determine
either the number of 6 year olds already in primary school, or the number of
children under the age of five in the preschools, we are simply taking the 5 %
6 year old age cohort as the basis for the calculation.<p>
<p>
Sources:	<b>Population by Age and Sex (1985-2020)</b>, EPU, 1991<br>
<b>Development of and Issues in Pre-school and Primary Education</b>, Dr. Leong
Yin Ching, Situation Analysis Paper, UNICEF, 1992, pg. 18.<br>
		<b>Education Statistics</b>, January 1992, Ministry of Education 		<p>
		Ministry of Education, 1994<br>
<b>Role of NGOs in Social Services in Malaysia</b>, Datin Ann Majeed, Situation
Analysis, UNICEF, 1992, pg. 7.<p>
		<p>
<p>
The data in terms of ECD services for children under the age of four are
significant in that there are little data. (See Table 3.)  The earliest there
is recorded data on child care centres is 1992, primarily because child care
centres were not required to register before then. Even now if we look only at
registered centres it does not provide an accurate picture of provision.  There
are a known 600 centres that are on the waiting list to be registered, and it
is estimated that for every known centre there are at least 3 others.  Using
that rough calculation, it can be estimated that roughly 5% of the under five
population is being served in a child care centre.  This does not take into
account the large amount of non-formal care that happens within families and
neighbourhoods. The only way to get accurate numbers on this kind of care is
through a census or door-to-door survey.  <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<center><b>TABLE 3</b><p>
  <p>
