<p>
<p>
Since the primary focus of this study is on government providers, what follows
is a description of the various government agencies, their roles and functions
in relation to ECD provision. <p>
<p>
<b>GOVERNMENT PROVIDERS OF ECD SERVICES</b><p>
<p>
There are a number of government departments responsible for the provision of
care and/or education of children under the age of six.  Each has a slightly
different mandate and/or population that it serves.  In this report each of six
Malaysian Government programmes is reviewed.  To some degree, the <b>Sixth
Malaysia Plan (1991-1995)</b> and the <b>Mid-Term Review of the Sixth Malaysia
Plan: 1991-1995,</b> have provided the framework for the development of early
childhood programmes.  Where there is a relevant reference to early childhood
within either of these documents, that is noted. <p>
<p>
What follows is a listing of the Ministries and Departments involved in ECD
activities in one form or another.  <p>
<p>
<ol>1.	Ministry of Education <p>
<p>
2.	Ministry of Rural Development<p>
<p>
	<Ul>	KEMAS<br>
		FELCRA - Federal Land Consolidation and Rehabilitation Authority<br>
		FELDA - Federal Land Development Authority<p></ul>
<p>
3.	Ministry of Health <p>
		<p>
4.	Ministry of National Unity and Social Development <p>
		<ul>Department of Social Welfare<br>
		Department of National Unity</ul><p>
<p>
5.	Ministry of Human Resources<p>
		<ul>Department of Labour</ul><p>
<p>
6.	Ministry of Local Government and Housing<p>
	<ul>	Kuala Lumpur City Hall</ul></ol><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>THE SPECIFICS:</b><p>
<p>
<b>1.   The Ministry of Education</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>     The SIXTH MALAYSIA PLAN 1991-1995 : EDUCATION</b></ul><p>
<p>
5.06   Pre-school education which was aimed at preparing the child for primary
school, was provided by both the public and private sectors.  The role of the
Ministry of Education (MOE) was limited to the preparation of the curriculum
and the registration of pre-school centres.  <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>PROSPECTS, 1991-1995</b><p>
<p>
<b>Pre-school Education</b><p>
  <p>
<b>5.37 	During the Sixth Plan period, pre-school education will be expanded
gradually to those areas not served by pre-school facilities.  The Government
aims to supplement existing pre-school facilities by having classes for
children aged five as part of the Government primary schools through a
pre-school annex system.  This is necessary as participation in well-organized
pre-school facilities will give the opportunity for children from low-income
families to have the same head start as others.</b><p>
  <p>
<b>5.38 	The implementation of this new programme by MOE will be undertaken in
three phases.  The first two phases will be implemented in areas where
pre-school facilities are non-existent, while the third phase will be in areas
where facilities are available but benefit only certain sections of the
population.  It is expected that by the end of 1995, the combined efforts of
MOE, other Government agencies and the private sector will ensure that all
children entering standard one in the primary schools would have had at least
one year of pre-school education.  To ensure the success of this programme,
more specialist teachers for pre-school education will be trained. (pgs
170-171)</b><p>
  <p>
<b>Role of the Private Sector in Education and training</b><p>
  <p>
<b>5.83 	The demand for education has resulted in the proliferation of private
institutions offering pre-school to tertiary level education.  The expansion of
private sector education will be encouraged as this will supplement public
sector efforts... A more effective monitoring of these institutions will be
undertaken in order to ensure acceptable standards and quality. (pg 181)</b><p>
  <p>
  <p>
<b>MID-TERM REVIEW OF THE SIXTH MALAYSIAN PLAN: 1991-1995</b><p>
  <p>
<b>8.05    With the increasing number of preschool centres and the need to
ensure safety of children and quality of services provided by these schools, a
coordinating mechanism was established.  In this regard, the Ministry of
Education was responsibility for coordinating the implementation of preschool
programmes which included the registration of centres, development of
curriculum guidelines, and the training of trainers.   (pg. 204)</b><p>
  <p>
<b>Preschool Education</b><p>
  <p>
<b>8.40		As preschool education is important in giving children a head start
and preparing them for formal schooling, facilities in preschools will be
expanded.  While the participation of the private sector and community
organisations is encouraged,the Government will continue to provide these
facilities,particularly to children from low-income families and rural areas,
so that they have equal educational opportunities. (pg.216)</b><p>
  <p>
<p>
<b>The REALITY</b>: <b> A Review of What exists</b><p>
<p>
The Ministry of Education is an important actor when it comes to preschool
education.  They have developed the basic preschool curriculum, and they have
trained the trainers who train teachers in other government-operated preschool
programmes (e.g. KEMAS and National Unity).<p>
<p>
Even so, it was not until 1992 that the Ministry of education became involved
in implementation of preschool programmes.  The Educational Planning and
Research Division within the Ministry, conceptualized and promoted what has
been called the "Annex" preschool program, begun in 1992.  The Annex programme
was designed to help make poor children more `school-ready'.  In the Annex
programme a preschool for 6-year-olds <b>[1]</b> is
implemented on the grounds of the primary school grounds.  The Ministry issued
clear guidelines to the State Department of Education in terms of the criteria
that should be used to admit children into these classes  Responsibility for
applying the criteria is delegated to the state. <p>
<p>
At present, the Annex programme is being implemented in 1131 classes in 1043
schools and 26 teacher training colleges, and currently serves 26,090 children.
It was planned that an addition 870 annex pre-schools would be added to the
programme each year.  However, after only one year of operation, the proposed
expansion of the programme was withheld and the present number of 1131 classes
was mantained. So, while the MOE continues to provide support to the original
Preschool Annex, no additional schools have been added to the system.<p>
<p>
The great majority of the teachers for the Annex schools were recruited from
among the current teaching force.  Teachers were selected by their Heads; they
did not necessarily have an interest in becoming a kindergarten teacher.  These
teachers were then provided with a one-month training.  Some teachers were
drawn from a group provided with a one-year specialised training course on
pre-school education. <p>
<p>
In addition to the teacher, there is an assistant in each class. The assistant
receives no training and is paid on a daily basis for her work ($10/day).  In
instances where the lead teacher is good, the assistant has learned quite a bit
from the modelling done by the teacher, but these teachers need to be given
training and, at a minimum, they need to be under contract rather than on daily
wages.<p>
<p>
Discussion: <p>
<p>
<ol>1.	The Education Act of 1961 does not include adequate provisions for preschool
education, so the Ministry of Education does not currently have a mandate to be
involved in preschool education.  While a new Act has been drafted that would
make the Ministry of Education responsible for preschool education, the Act has
not yet been legislated into law.<p>
<p>
2.	Conceptually the preschool programme should come under the Ministry of
Education, given the age of the children and the linkages that should be
established between preschool and the primary school.  However, in reality,
those within the Ministry of Education who are interested in promoting
preschool education do not have enough internal or external support to develop
and coordinate the implementation of a solid programme.<p>
<p>
3. 	The Annex schools were developed by the Educational Planning and Research
Division (EPRD).  However, they are not an implementing branch of the Ministry
of Education.  In fact, the School Division is responsible for implementation.
As the program has been transferred from EPRD to the School Division, the
commitment to and belief in the efficacy of the preschool programme has not
been conveyed.  There were also difficulties in the design of the programme
which have made it difficult to implement. This has led to problems in relation
to acceptance of the programme at the primary school level.</ol>  <p>
<p>
Conclusion:<p>
<p>
Although there has been no formal evaluation of the Preschool Annex programme,
a generally expressed concern is that the educational approach is too close to
formal primary schooling.  This is probably the result of the fact that many
Annex teachers were formerly primary school teachers.  Also, the location of
the preschool on the primary school compound reinforces a more formal approach
to preschool.<p>
<p>
Several considerations appear to argue against an increased preschool
implementation role for the Ministry of Education.  First, the Ministry is not
currently in a position to expand the Annex programme.  Second, with its
traditional pedagogical approach, the Ministry of Education has no particular
comparative advantage in the development of a broader concept of integrated ECD
services for young children from conception up to school entry. <p>
<p>
2.	<b>Ministry of Community Development - KEMAS</b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>The SIXTH MALAYSIA PLAN:  Community Development</b></ul><p>
  <p>
<b>14.33   The main objective of the community development programme is to
inculcate positive values oriented towards development and self-reliance
amongst the rural and sub-urban population. Various agencies such as the
Community Development Division of the Ministry of Rural Development (KEMAS),
Federal Land Development Authority (FELDA), Rubber Industry Smallholder
Development Authority (RISDA) and Farmers Organization Authority (FOA) carried
out community development activities.  The activities of KEMAS included family
development, nutrition, family health, hygiene, home economics as well as
provision of services, such as the establishment of rural libraries and
pre-school centres.  (pg. 373-374)</b><p>
  <p>
<p>
<b>PROSPECTS 1991-1995</b><p>
  <p>
<b>14.69  KEMAS will continue to undertake programmes to develop values
oriented towards the development of self-reliance.  The focus of activities
will be on the rural population whose activities will be supported and guided
by KEMAS social workers.</b><p>
  <p>
<b>14.70 	During the Plan period, the construction of three family development
training centres and various community service centres will be continued.
KEMAS will also expand its programme for the rural population by providing more
rural libraries and pre-school centres.  The training and manpower development
capabilities of KEMAS will be upgraded through the improvement and renovation
of existing training centres.  (pg.383)</b><p>
  <p>
<p>
<b>The REALITY:  KEMAS - A review of what exists</b><p>
<p>
KEMAS began in 1957 with an adult literacy program.  In 1960 Community
Education was added to their portfolio.  By 1963 it was felt that basic
literacy had been obtained, so they shifted to more general home economics
activities to sustain literacy and they added religious education.  In 1970
they created the Community Development Division.  Within this, pre-school was
added as a component of Family Life education.  It was reasoned that the
Ministry of Health works with children pre-natally through the age of 4 (see
comments on the Ministry of Health), and that the Ministry of Education took up
children at age 7, leaving the 4-6 year olds without services.  Thus KEMAS
decided to focus their services on this age group. Now the pre-school program
is a major part of what KEMAS offers.<p>
<p>
Before 1992, any community could request a KEMAS preschool. At that point KEMAS
realized that preschools were mushrooming in urban areas, particularly among
private providers.  They felt that these preschools were further widening the
gap between urban and rural children.  Thus KEMAS decided to operate in the
rural areas.  However, where KEMAS had opened preschools in urban areas before
1992 they maintain the centre. <p>
<p>
The KEMAS preschool is a joint venture between of the community and the
government.  A local committee is formed, with the president being a community
member, the teacher is the Secretary and the Assistant teacher is the
Treasurer. The committee chooses the candidate for training.  Thus whenever
possible the teacher is someone from the community itself who is already known
to the parents.<p>
<p>
The committee is responsible for identifying an appropriate building to house
the preschool.  In housing estates this is not difficult. When housing
complexes are built the architect is required to provide a space for a
community hall.  This is generally able to accommodate the preschool.  In
instances where there is no suitable building, government will provide the
funds for the program. The community is then responsible for the maintenance of
the facility.<p>
<p>
The basic curriculum for the KEMAS preschools is the one developed by the
Ministry of Education, but with heavier emphasis on the 3Rs.  With regards the
spiritual education, in addition to religion in the Preschool Curriculum
Guidelines, KEMAS has added more content to religious education.  Recently
KEMAS has also added Islamic Education and the teaching of English to the
preschool curriculum.  Children are taught the English alphabet and learn to
recognize a set of English words and their Bahasa Malaysia equivalent. <p>
<p>
Conclusions:<p>
<p>
In terms of having responsibility for actually implementing preschool
programmes, KEMAS is the largest government provider. Today KEMAS operates
nearly 7,000 centres (6819 in 1993).  They calculate that 10,000 are required
to provide full coverage.  The mandate states that the teacher/child ratio
should be 1:25.  They try to hold to this, but in some cases they go to 30+
children in one class.<p>
<p>
In terms of positioning KEMAS in relation to the other Ministries and agencies
involved in ECD, it is important to understand that because of the structure
and mandate of KEMAS, it stands outside the rules and regulations that govern
other Government programs. While they have the best developed infrastructure to
support ECD provision, they need to develop an integrated curriculum that is
more developmentally appropriate for preschool-aged children.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>3.</b>	<b>Ministry of Health </b><p>
<p>
The Ministry of Health has taken a broad definition of health.  Health is "a
state of complete physical, mental and social well-being, and not merely the
absence of infirmity."  Thus the Ministry of Health emphasises both preventive
and curative medicine.<p>
<p>
Organizationally, policy is developed at the national level.  Implementation of
policy is coordinated at the state level.  Services are delivered at the
district level through a two-tiered system.  The primary contact point for the
community is the Community Clinic, which ultimately will be staffed by 2
Community Nurses.  These clinics are served by a team from a Main health
centre, where a doctor is based.  Referrals from a Community Clinic go to the
Main Clinic and then if necessary, a referral is made to the District Hospital.
<p>
<p>
The health infrastructure in Malaysia provides coverage throughout the country.
In Table 8 is a listing of the types and numbers of health care facilities that
can be found in the various parts of Malaysia.<p>
<p>
What is more important, however, than simply the kinds and numbers of health
care facilities that are available, is the type of coverage these facilities
provide for the population.  Table 9 presents the numbers and percentage of the
age population that is covered, with a focus on infants and young children.
The data are impressive.  Clearly health is seen as a priority in Malaysia.<p>
  
  <p>
<center><b>TABLE 8</b><p>
<b>PRIMARY HEALTH CARE FACILITIES</b></center><p>
  

<pre>
   Facilities           Peninsular      Sabah       Sarawak      
                        Malaysia                                 
  
  Health Centres             421           87           98       
  Village Clinics          1,715          191          100       
  MCH Clinics                 58                        24       
  Mobile Clinics             230            6                    
  Flying Service                            2           12       
  Village Teams                                        122       
         Totals            2,424          286          356       

</pre>

	Source:  Ministry of Health, 1994<p>
<p>
<p>
<center><b>TABLE 9</b><p>
  <p>
<b>COVERAGE BY CHILD HEALTH CLINICS</b></center><p>


<pre>
                               Infant                  Toddler  
                         (birth to 1 year)         (2 to 5 years)            
 
P. Malaysia               549,661 (88.2%)          676,554 (44.6%)      
(average # visits)             (3.9)                    (2.5)                  
 Sabah                     95,626 (93.2%)           60,974 (23.0%)      
(average # visits)             (4.1)                    (3.4)                  
 Sarawak                   80,928 (&gt;100%)          116,761 (59.1%)      
(average # visits)             (5.1)                    (4.2%)                 
 MALAYSIA                 726,215 (90.2%)          854,289 (43.2%)      
(average # visits)             (4.1)                    (2.8)                  

</pre>

  Source:  Ministry of Health, 1994<p>
<p>
<p>
The health infrastructure that has been developed means that nearly all
children are seen on a fairly regular basis during the first two years of life.
This presents an opportunity to provide the mother with child development as
well as health information.<p>
<p>
The programme within the Ministry of Health that can be seen as an integral
part of early childhood development programming is the Primary Care and Family
Development Programme, which includes:<p>
<p>
1.	 Antenatal care of pregnant women.  Approximately 600,000 are pregnant at
any one time.  At this point 80% of these women receive pre-natal care.
However, there are regional differences in coverage. In the Peninsula coverage
is closer to 96%.  In Sabah/Sarawak it is closer to 75%  To improve antenatal
care in Sabah/Sarawak, two programmes have been undertaken: High Risk Approach
and Safe Motherhood.<p>
<p>
2.	 Intranatal services (birth).  35% of births occur at home.  This is
encouraged in situations where it is anticipated that there is no risk to the
mother or infant.  The birth is assisted by mid-wives or staff nurses.  A new
category of provider is being trained.  This is a Community Nurse.  This is a
person who has more training than a mid-wife, but less than a staff nurse.  Two
years of training is required for this position (6 months for those currently
serving as mid-wives).<p>
<p>
Traditional Birth nurses still exist in some areas.  While they are not
encouraged to assist in deliveries, they are given training in case they are
the ones responsible.  They are also given training in how to identify high
risk births.<p>
<p>
3. 	 Postnatal care.  There is follow-up for both the mother and the child.
For home births a visit is made on days 1,2,3,4,6,10, and 20. For children born
in the hospital the follow-up is slightly less intensive. <p>
<p>
4.	 Care of newborns and infants - The components of health provided at this
time are nutrition (coupled with growth monitoring), immunizations
(poliomyelitis, tuberculosis, diphtheria, tetanus, pertussis, measles and
Hepatitis B), and developmental monitoring.<p>
<p>
There is a strong emphasis on breastfeeding. Infant formula is not provided in
the hospital, nor is it for sale at a reduced rate<p>
<p>
5.  	Child (1-6).  Services for children in this age group focus on nutrition,
physical and developmental growth monitoring.  A growth card has been created,
launched nationally November, 1994, that is to be used by and with mothers.
Children are routinely given health check-ups only once a year between the ages
of 2 and 5. <p>
<p>
6.	 School Health programme. This includes screening in Std. I, VI and Form
III, school dental services, school feeding and nutrition and a healthy school
environment. These services are undertaken by the Ministry of Health, but
delivered through the school.  Health education is the responsibility of the
Ministry of Education.  <p>
<p>
The Ministry of Health also works with children with special needs, children in
poor families through the distribution of a food basket to families containing
specialized foods for undernourished children, and some work with abused
children. The latter are served predominantly by NGOs and the Ministry of
National Unity and Social Development.<p>
<p>
Plantations have their own curative services, but they lack prevention
services.  Legally the  Ministry of Health cannot provide preventative or
curative services to plantations.  In situation where there are 20+ children
who should be immunized, the health services is allowed to do that on the
plantation.  Otherwise parents must bring their children to local clinics.
Where there is a recognized need, clinics have been established  near
plantations and they have adjusted their hours to accommodate those who work on
plantations.<p>
<p>
<p>
Conclusions:<p>
<p>
While the Ministry of Health does not see itself as providing early childhood
development services, in fact they are.  Health services are a critical part of
an overall early childhood effort. The Home-based Child Health Card that was
introduced to the country in November, 1994 (for implementation in January
1995) is an extremely useful way to help parents better understand children's
growth and development.  By using the card as an entry point, other information
can be introduced to parents as well, information that they can use as they
support the child's development. Thus the Ministry of Health, through their
Primary Care and Family Development Programme, is clearly a partner in the
overall approach to early childhood development <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>4.	Ministry of National Unity and Social Development </b><p>
  <p>
<ul><b>	A. National Unity</b></ul><p>
  <p>
The Department of National Unity was created in 1969. The specific purpose of
the Department is to strengthen and promote integration and national unity.
Today one of the activities of the Department is to provide opportunities for
positive inter-racial contact.  One of the primary vehicles that the Department
has chosen for this is preschools in the urban and suburban areas. Thus the
Department provides multi-cultural preschools for children aged 5 &amp; 6 (with
some four-year-olds in attendance), living in low-income housing areas.<p>
<p>
The Department of National Unity has Organizers who work within a housing area.
These operate under District officers who are under State Unity officers, with
final responsibility for the activities being at the national level.  The local
organizers promote the creation of what is known as a Self-reliance Committee
within a housing area, whether that be a housing block, or a squatter
settlement, or a Kampung (village).  The Rukun Tetangga (Neighbourhood
Committee) is formed along guidelines provided by the Department.  When a
neighbourhood group is ready to form a committee they make application to the
Department.  When approved, the Committee can undertake activities with
financial support from the national government. <p>
<p>
The preschools created within the Self-Reliance activities have their own
committee, known as the Unity Kindergarten Welfare Committee. (Other Committees
include the Women's Wing and the Youth Wing, each of which is geared to develop
appropriate activities for their constituent group.) The Kindergarten Committee
is chaired by a parent, and the teacher serves as the Secretary while the
Assistant Teacher is the Treasurer.  The committee is responsible for
organizing activities related to the preschool -- sports days, field trips,
contests, graduations, etc. However, it does not take on any real
decision-making in terms of the preschool.<p>
<p>
The teachers are on contract with the Department of National Unity.  And while
it is desirable that they come from the community where they work, this is not
the usual case. Generally teachers have completed Secondary School, with the
Assistant teachers having completed Form III.  The Trainers have been trained
by the Ministry of Education. Once trained, these trainers then train the
teachers.  After being trained, teachers are visited regularly (as often as
once a month) by a Supervisor hired by the Department.  However, in most
instances the Supervisor has not been trained to provide substantive feedback
to the teachers in terms of their work with children.  More often than not, her
feedback focuses on administrative and/or infrastructure concerns.  When the
Supervisor has been a teacher herself, then she is able to facilitate the
teaching/learning process within the preschool.<p>
<p>
The preschool programme consumes 40% of the Department of National Unity's
annual budget, with the majority of the costs being teacher salaries.  At the
present time there are 485 centres, serving 17,523 children. The department
hopes to add another 100 classes in 1995.  The ultimate goal is to have a
preschool associated with every Self-reliance Committee. At the present time
this would mean 2300 preschools. <p>
<p>
The population distribution in most pre-school centres has one dominant racial
group due to the reality of housing and population distribution. <p>
The preschool is taught in Bahasa Malaysia, and the curriculum developed by the
Ministry of Education is being implemented.  When Malays are in the majority
Islamic Education is included within the preschool curriculum  Children are
introduced to Arabic letters and basic words, as well as Islamic practices in
terms of prayers, manners, etc.<p>
<p>
Preschools run for 3 hours a day.  The preferable timings are in the morning
(8:30-11:30).  However, in some areas there is so much demand that an afternoon
class is also provided (1:30-4:30). In some instances the Kindergarten
Committee has created its own classes to meet the need, but the Department does
not encourage this as the same standards may not be met.  So, to the extent
possible, the Department covers the costs of the preschool and it is brought
under their umbrella.<p>
Other activities undertaken by the Department include socio-ethnic research on
inter-ethnic relations and issues related to it. This is in line with the
Department's objective of inculcating, promoting and strengthening national
unity and national integration.  Accordingly the functions of the Department
are as follow: <p>
<p>
<ul>o	To promote national unity and national integration.<p>
<p>
o	To prevent conflicts amongst the various races, communities and states.<p>
<p>
o	To instill good citizenship values towards the creation of a united<br>
	 Malaysian nation.<p>
<p>
o	To monitor and evaluate racial and community relations.<p>
<p>
o	To co-ordinate national unity programmes and activities with government and<br>
	 non-governmental organisations.</ul><p>
<p>
Conclusions:<p>
<p>
While the current structures within the National Unity Programme provide
considerable administrative support to teachers, mechanisms are lacking to
provide substantive support in terms of the teaching/learning process.<p>
<p>
The Department has expressed an interest in:  conducting basic research on the
impact of the preschools (the programme has been in operation for 18 years and
there has never been an evaluation of the effort to know whether or not it is
working); developing training for the supervisors so that they are able to give
more substantive feedback to teachers; and developing programs that would
increase parental involvement. <p>
<p>
  <p>
<b>	B. Department of  Social Welfare</b><p>
<p>
While the role of the Department of Social Welfare in ECD programmes is not
addressed directly in the Sixth Malaysia Plan: 1991-1995, there are references
to the importance of the family.  Since these were elaborated on in the
Mid-Term Review, the relevant sections from that document are quoted.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Family Development and Welfare</b><p>
  <p>
<b>9.33	 ... Recognising that the family is the core institution which can
effectively nurture and instill more and ethical values in the young as well as
provide care and support for the sick, disabled and the aged, focus was thus
given to the strengthening of the family as the basic unit of society.  Towards
this end, the family development programme emphasized the improvement of health
and welfare of the family through family life education, parenting courses and
marriage/family counselling, and inculcation of positive values in the
individuals, family and society... (pg 239)</b><p>
  <p>
<b>9.34	In view of the increased labour force participation rate of women at
47% in 1993, various programmes were implemented to help women cope with the
challenging responsibilities they face at home and at the workplace...  (pg
239)</b><p>
  <p>
<b>9.35	Programmes and projects to ensure the optimum development of children
continued to be undertaken during the period.  This commitment was further
recognized when Malaysia became one of the signatories of the World Declaration
for the Survival, Protection and Development of Children on 18 July 1991.  This
Declaration arose from the World Summit for Children in October 1990 which
called for the achievement of specific goals for children in the fields of
health, education, welfare and environment. (pg 240)</b><p>
  <p>
<b>9.36	To provide better legal protection for the well-being of children, the
Child Protection Act was enacted in 1991... In addition, the Child Care Centre
Act, 1984 which provides for proper child care practices was further
enforced.... (pg. 240)</b><p>
  <p>
<b>9.78	Child development programmes will be guided by the National Plan of
Action for the Survival, Protection and Development of Children.  This Plan
will enable a more comprehensive approach towards optimizing the potential of
children through the implementation of various programmes such as child health,
nutrition and basic education and literacy. (pg. 248)</b><p>
  <p>
<p>
The Mid-Term Review clearly endorses the creation of child care alternatives,
both for the benefit of working women and for the direct benefit of the
child.<p>
<p>
Historically the Department of Social Welfare has developed its services in
response to social needs, and to some extent that continues to be true.
However, like the other Departments they are also developing preventive
services.  While their function is to monitor and enforce standards, they are
also aware of the kinds of programmes that might be developed.  For example,
the department is aware of the child care demands of working women and have
seen the need to develop full-day child care for children from soon after birth
through the early primary grades. <p>
<p>
In the early 1980s a survey of provision was conducted with support from
UNICEF.  A total of 537 centres were surveyed.  These included the formal
centres and home-based child care.  The study looked at issues related to
physical safety, the programme for children, materials available, the
qualifications of the providers, and parent involvement.  The results showed
that plantations had the poorest facilities and overall programme.  In the
urban areas the problem was the promotion of `accelerated learning'.  The study
led to a drafting of the first legislation to govern the operation of child
care centres. This resulted in the Child Care Centre Act of 1984. This was
enforced in 1985.  The Act was amended in 1993 to allow the Department of
Social Welfare to accredit training centres.  <p>
Within the Act child care facilities with less than 4 children do not need to
register.  Those taking care of 4-9 children are registered as home-based
programmes and those with more than 10 children are classified as
`institutional' programmes.  The teacher child ratio should be 1:5 for children
under 3, 1:10 for 3-4 year olds.  Other requirements include basic teacher
qualifications, a programme of daily activities, and the need for parents to
have a clear understanding of what the centres provide.  <p>
<p>
The Department of Social Welfare is responsible for registering all child care
centres.  To develop a comprehensive set of guidelines, they have collaborated
with the Local Authorities, the Fire Department, and Health.  When the others
have approved the application, based on their criteria, Social Welfare issues
the registration.  It costs $50 for a license, which needs to be renewed every
year.<p>
<p>
The Bernard van Leer Foundation has funded several projects within the
Department of Social Welfare. This Foundation has been a very important partner
in supporting the development of early childhood programmes in Malaysia.  They
funded the Alternative Child Care project which led to the development of the
curriculum for ECD programmes and the creation of materials to support teachers
in implementing programmes.  In addition, training packages have been created
at three levels:  Preliminary (primarily for those with low levels of
education); Basic Child Care Course; and the Supervisors Course.  These courses
are offered by staff of the Department.<p>
<p>
In addition to creating curriculum and training packages, one of the objectives
of the van Leer project was to create a Division within the Department of
Social welfare that would support early childhood initiatives.  This did not
come about, so child care training has been incorporated into the Training
Division.  This puts great demand on the Training Division.  As a result, the
quality of the training has been affected, and the Basic Training has been
shortened from 4 to 2 weeks. <p>
<p>
The way the Department of Social Welfare is responding to the demand is through
identifying potential trainers and upgrading their skills so that they can
become trainers. They were co-opted as co-trainers and were paid for their
services. However, with the moral support of the Department of Social Welfare,
this group of trainers and other care-providers formed the Association of Child
Care Providers (PPBM), which has become a registered body. Now Kuala Lumpur,
Selangor, Sabah and Sarawak have their own set of trainers, and the PPBM has a
much wider scope and coverage. (See section on NGOs.)<p>
<p>
Conclusions:<p>
<p>
The Department of Social Welfare operates from an integrated approach and has
an infrastructure in place, that with appropriate training and support, can be
used to explore alternative approaches to ECD.<p>
<p>
<b>5.	Ministry of Human Resources</b><p>
<p>
	<ul>	<b>Department of Labour</b></ul><p>
<p>
The Department of Labour is within the Ministry of Human Resources. When the
Department of Labour began, the focus was on protecting the needs of the
workers.  Thus they served as an enforcement agency.  Within the last five
years they have taken a more proactive role in the promotion of workers'
welfare.   They come into a discussion of ECD because they are responsible for
the services provided for young children on the estates and plantations, and
more recently in factories and industries. There are more than 1 million people
living on estates and plantations (the majority are Indians and Malays).<p>
<p>
Within the Workers Minimum Standards Housing and Amenities Act (1966) it is
stated that employers must provide nurseries for the children of their workers.
When these began they were seen only as a safe place to keep children and
provide them with some nutritional food.  They are free to the workers (as is
everything on the estates) and they are staffed by "ayahs" who, because of
their title, are seen as housemaids.<p>
<p>
In 1990 the Labour Department amended the 1966 Act to be in line with the Child
Care Centre Act 1984, issued by the Welfare Department.  The new Act states
that those centres that are classified as 'nurseries' (i.e. they serve more
than 10 children between the ages of 0-4) must employ qualified (i.e. trained)
workers. Since the implementation of the amended Act, the Department of Labour
has been seeking ways to train those working in estate child care centres. More
than 800 of these centres exist within the 1500+ estates that have housing for
their employees.  (There may be home-based centres on some estates since the
management has to provide and to register the centre only if they have 10 or
more children between the ages of 0 and 4).<p>
<p>
In 1994, the Department of Labour was given an allocation of $1 million that
was to be used to provide some toys to the child care centres.  However, the
Department decided this was not the best use of the funds since teachers do not
know how to use the materials they are given.  So, they are using some of this
money for training since they feel this would be a better investment of the $1
million.<p>
<p>
A newer venture for the Department of Labour is working with industry and
factories to establish child care centres.  Three projects have already begun
and 40 different factories have made application to create child care centres.
An integrated model centre has been created by INTEL.<p>
<p>
There is both an <i>incentive</i> and a <i>motivation</i> for employers to
create child care facilities, whether it be on the plantations and estates or
in industry.  The <i>incentive</i> comes from the fact that industries are
given a tax break if they provide child care for the children of their workers.
This is an important policy decision in terms of strategies to meet the
intersecting needs of women and children.<p>
<p>
The <i>motivation</i> comes from the fact that they want to make their workers
happy.  There is a shortage of labour in Malaysia.  At the present time labour
for the factories and estates is being brought in from Indonesia and Bangladesh
primarily, although there are workers for other countries as well.  These
workers are costly to the country in that they send all their earnings home.
Thus employers want to hire Malaysians and because they are in high demand, the
employers need to find ways to attract and keep their work force.  Child care
is seen as a benefit that is attractive to women workers. <p>
<p>
At the national level an umbrella committee was created to develop guidelines
for the establishment of child care centres.  (These have been developed but
not yet printed)  The committee consists of members from Treasury, Income Tax,
Welfare, Education, Local government, Housing, and Labour.  The Department of
Labour coordinates this committee.<p>
<p>
<p>
Conclusions:<p>
<p>
In terms of the mandate of the Department of Labour it is possible to see why
they would be concerned about child care issues.  And, it is important to have
people other than those traditionally involved with children's issues promoting
ECD service. However, given that the Department lacks experience and expertise
in ECD provision, a question can legitimately be raised about the
appropriateness of the Department providing training and supervision.  <p>
<p>
An alternative would be to train the Community Services Officer (CSO), who is
hired by the management to oversee the services provided to families on the
estate. She is a key person in terms of overseeing the child care centres.  If
trained appropriately, she can offer training and support to women working in
plantation child care centres.   <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>NON-GOVERNMENTAL ORGANIZATIONS (NGOs)</b><p>
<p>
The mandate of the study is to map out government provision of ECD services and
make recommendations as to the government's role in that provision.  However,
government will never be able to (nor should it) provide 100% of the needed
provision.  Other partners need to be found.  Within most countries there is a
partnership between government, non-governmental agencies (NGOs) and the
private sector in the provision of ECD services.  This is already true in
Malaysia as well.  Thus in making recommendations that build on what already
exists, it is important to know what the NGO community is currently providing
and how that might interface with what the government can provide.  Therefore
in the study design, the major  NGOs with an ECD focus were surveyed.<p>
<p>
At the present time there are two NGOs that are providing considerable support
to the government in terms of ECD, in that they are providing training to those
working in government-sponsored ECD programmes.  The two NGOs are the Malaysian
Kindergarten Association (PTM) and the Association of Child Care Providers
(PPBM).<p>
<p>
<b>Malaysian Kindergarten Association (PTM)   </b><p>
	<p>
The Kindergarten Association (PTM) has been in existence since 1975/76.  There
are currently 3000 members (paying annual dues of $10), all of whom are trained
kindergarten teachers.  Over the years they have provided training to some
10,000 teachers. (They provide training for the Ministry of Education as well
as the private sector.) There are more than 100 people attending each of the
various training courses.  Training is set up in Steps.  There are 6 steps to
complete to get a certificate. Two steps are taught in a ten-day period.  The
courses are offered during school holidays, twice a year.  Thus it would take
someone a year and a half to complete the 6 steps.  <p>
<p>
<b>The Association of Child Care Providers (PPBM)</b><p>
<p>
The PPBM is a group equivalent to the PTM, but with a focus on child care
rather than preschool. This NGO provides training across the age spectrum
included in ECD programmes -- for child care providers and government preschool
teachers, as well as providing training for the private sector.  However,
instead of being linked with the Ministry of Education, they have provided
support to the Department of Social Welfare.  In 1986 a group of 20 providers
were identified to be trained as Trainers.  This was done in two-weeks and
since then 10-12 of these women have both worked with Social Welfare Trainers
in the training of child care workers, and they have offered training on their
own. These trainers have received no additional training and they are now
asking to have their own skills and knowledge upgraded.<p>
<p>
There are some individuals who belong to both PTM and PPBM. There is some
consideration being given to combining the two groups under an umbrella
organisation, in order to provide continuity of curriculum and training for
those working with children from birth up until the child enters the formal
school.   <p>
<p>
There are two other NGOs that are involved in training: Education Welfare
Research Foundation (ERWF) which began with an interest in training preschool
teachers, but now they are interested in services for children under 4,
particularly on estates.  They work closely with the Department of Social
Welfare.  <p>
<p>
The other group is CHILD, which originally focused more on health issues, but
today it has a broader development mandate.  CHILD is working on capacity
building within NGOs, and have taken an interest in ECD issues. <p>
<p>

<center><b>PART III: SUB-STUDIES</b></center><p>
<p>
<p>
Within the larger study, three sub-studies were conducted.  The first was on
curriculum across the 0-6 age range. The second focused on parent and community
involvement, and the third looked at current training systems in place.  The
curriculum and parent involvement sub-studies included the same basic sample.
Sixteen different settings were selected, ranging from government preschools,
to child care centres, to programmes operated by non-governmental agencies and
the private sector. There were both urban and rural programmes included in the
sample.  Specifically the 16 types of programmes selected included the
following:<p>
<p>
<ul>o	The Ministry of National Unity and Social Development<p>
<p>
<ol>1.	The National Unity pre-schools (urban)<p>
<p>
2.	Child care centres registered with the Department of Social Welfare (urban,
rural)</ol><p>
<p>
o	Ministry of Education's Annex Pre-school Programme (urban, rural)<p>
<p>
o	The Ministry of Community Development - KEMAS (urban squatters and rural)<p>
<p>
o	Ministry of Health (rural, Kuala Lumpur City - Urban Health Programme)<p>
<p>
o	Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs) - PTM - urban;  ERWF - plantation<p>
<p>
o	Religious-sponsors - ABIM (urban, rural)<p>
<p>
o	Home-based programmes (urban, rural)<p>
<p>
o	Commercial ECD programmes (urban)</ul><p>
<p>
In essence, this sample includes the range of ECD programme models found in
Malaysia.<p>
<p>
Included in this section of the report is a summary of each of the studies.
The complete reports from each of the studies can be found in Annex A for the
Curriculum Study, Annex B for the Parent Involvement Study and Annex C for the
Training Study.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>CURRICULUM</b><p>
<p>
For each of the agencies/organizations included in the study, the curriculum
was reviewed in terms of its quality, as evaluated against the principles of
child development listed above.  In addition, the support materials available
to the teachers and children were evaluated. The basic review allowed for the
identification of both strengths and gaps in the curriculum and materials
available to teachers and children.<p>
<p>
The subjects of the Review included teachers and principals of the respective
preschools and child care centres, as well as supervisors of home-based
centres. A total of 32 individuals (including teachers, principals and
supervisors), were interviewed. They were selected because they were considered
key figures in the teaching-learning environment and thus they are the best
informants for the purposes of the Review. <p>
<p>
Specifically, the focus was on the:<p>
<p>
<ul>o	objectives of the curriculum<br>
o	type of curriculum used<br>
o	modifications that had been made in the curriculum<br>
o	teaching-learning aids used by teachers<br>
o	type of teacher preparation<br>
o	activities implemented<br>
o	physical quality of the centres<br>
o	child-teacher interactions<br>
o	teaching-learning climate.<br>
o	parental support for curriculum development and implementation<br>
o	child evaluation or assessment supported by the curriculum</ul><p>
<p>
Classroom observations were conducted to gauge implementation of the
curriculum, to assess the teaching - learning processes in the setting, and to
obtain data on the educational setting. <p>
<p>
The findings indicate that generally, regardless of the type of preschool or
child care programme, the majority of programmes have as a major objective the
<i>total development of the child</i>. This may be because the primary
curriculum source for the majority of the programmes are the <i>Garis Panduan
Pra Sekolah Malaysia,</i> or Preschool Curriculum Guidelines, developed by the
Curriculum Development Centre (CDC) within the Ministry of Education. The
guidelines emphasize the total and well balanced development of the
preschool-aged (4-6 year old) child. <p>
<p>
The Preschool Curriculum Guidelines emphasize the total development of the
child: physical, social, emotional, mental, spiritual, civic responsibility,
language development, aesthetics and creative skills.  In 1993 the curriculum
was revised to include a greater emphasis on Islam, the introduction of English
and the introduction of objectives in relation to Vision 2020.  <p>
<p>
The Preschool Curriculum Guidelines include modules and activity books to
assist teachers in implementing the curriculum.  The Curriculum package
consists of a Teacher Resource Manual, activity books, learning materials for
preschoolers, and pictures.  The package also describes and prescribes the
preschool teacher's role, and includes an evaluation guideline for assessing
children's performance and development. <p>
<p>
The private preschools and the religious programmes, such as ABIM, are aware of
the CDC's guidelines, but they have developed their own curriculum.  <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Summary of the Findings</b><p>
<p>
The Preschool Curriculum Guidelines are very comprehensive and well-grounded in
child development theory.  They provide an excellent framework for the
development of programmes for children 4-6 years of age.  In sum, there is a
solid Malaysian preschool curriculum available.<p>
<p>
In terms of curriculum for children under the age of four, a package has been
developed by the Department of Social Welfare.  This includes a set of 28
modules and support materials - activity sheets, a manual on child development
and parental involvement, training manuals, cassettes containing children's
songs, posters, etc.  However, the conceptual/theoretical framework that has
guided the development of these materials has not been elaborated. The
activities and materials are generic.  There is little attempt to utilise
culturally-relevant materials and experiences from the environment.<p>
<p>
In general, the issue is not the quality of the curriculum available;
difficulties are encountered in curriculum implementation.  Difficulties in
implementation are mainly the result of inadequate training and supervision.
These difficulties are compounded where there have been additions made to the
Preschool Curriculum Guidelines, making it difficult to adequately implement
the curriculum within the current 3 or 3 1/2 hour preschool programme.<p>
<p>
<p>
<center><b>TABLE 10</b><p>
  <p>
<b>CURRICULUM PRESENTLY USED BY</b><br>
<b>PRESCHOOLS/CHILD CARE CENTRES</b></center><p>


<pre>
      Types of preschools                    Curriculum used              

National Unity (Perpaduan)        Preschool Curriculum Guidelines         
Preschool Annex                   Preschool Curriculum Guidelines         
KEMAS                             Preschool Curriculum Guidelines with    
                                  additional emphasis on the 3Rs          
Ministry of Health - Sang         Sukatan Pelajaran Taman Sang Kancil     
Kancil                            (early reading, writing, language,      
                                  experiences, music, play).              
Plantation EWRF                   EWRF'S self-developed Preschool         
                                  Curriculum                              
Commercial                        Montessori based, adapted for Malaysia  
Child care centres                Modules developed by Department of      
                                  Social Welfare, emphasis on health,     
                                  physical, growth and total              
                                  development.                            
Religious based: ABIM             Curriculum developed by ABIM, Biro      
                                  Pendidikan Awam' emphasis on            
                                  religious knowledge; Arabic language;   
                                  content areas blended with religious    
                                  2teachings                              
Home based                        Curriculum developed by the director    
                                  of the programme                        

</pre>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>PARENT/COMMUNITY INVOLVEMENT</b><p>
<p>
An important principle of effective child development programmes is that they
include significant community and parent involvement.  Thus each of the
programmes visited in the review, an assessment was made of the current level
of parent and community involvement.  <p>
<p>
As in the curriculum sub-study, a sample of sixteen settings provided the basic
data on parental involvement.  Data were gathered through a parent interview.
The programme was informed when the interviewers would be visiting, and parents
were invited to meet with the interviewers.  What this meant was that parents
self-selected to be included in the study.  It can be surmised that this is a
biased sample.  Parents who came to be interviewed i) were not involved in
full-time employment outside the home, and ii) were likely to be the parents
who were the most involved in the programme since they were comfortable coming
for the interview; and iii) were probably the parents most satisfied with the
programme.  Those whose time did not allow them to come, or who were not
regularly involved in the programme or those, who, for whatever reason, were
unhappy with the programme, were not included in the sample.<p>
<p>
Where it was not possible to interview parents, a questionnaire was sent home.
The rate of return of these questionnaires differed by setting.<p>
<p>
The interview and questionnaires focused on <p>
<p>
<ul>o	why parents sent their children to the programme,<br>
o	what parents perceived that the child received as a result of the
programme,<br>
o	the parent's understanding of what actually happened in the programme<br>
o	the extent of the parent's involvement in class activities,<br>
o	the extent to which parents were actively involved in implementing programme
activities with their children at home,<br>
o	parent's involvement in special activities,<br>
o	the kind of interaction parents have with teachers,<br>
o	how the programme fits into the child's day,<br>
o	fees - what the parents paid and what they are willing to pay</ul><p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Findings</b><p>
<p>
What was interesting about the results of this study is that within the
settings included, there was a very narrow definition of parent involvement.
Essentially the nature and extent of a parent's involvement in the programme
was determined by those implementing the programme.  (This was true even in the
parent education programme.)  While it was considered important for parents to
participate in the extra-curricular activities (sports day, festivals, etc),
parents were not expected to be actively involved in the daily programme.  In
some instances parents were given instruction in terms of the kinds of
activities they should be doing with their children at home.  The assumption
being that parents need to be told what to do with their children.  <p>
<p>
In essence there is a uni-directional, top-down approach to parent involvement.
No information is sought from the parents regarding the child's growth and
development.  There is no exchange of information between teacher and parent
that would either help the teacher provide appropriate support for the child in
the programme, nor prepare the parent to understand his/her role in supporting
the child's development.  In summary, there is no linkage or continuity between
the centre and the home.<p>
<p>
If one were to draw a continuum of parent involvement that went from parent
initiated to teacher initiated, the programme included in this sample would
fall toward the programme-initiated end of the continuum (represented by the
X).<p>
<p>
<p>
<center>parent initiated  &lt;---------------------------XXXXX--&gt; programme
initiated</center><p>
<p>
Even those programmes which have an infrastructure in place that would allow
for considerable community and parent involvement in the ECD programme, dictate
the nature of that involvement. <p>
<p>
There are some important implications of this finding.  First, the expectation
-- on both the part of programme implementers and parents -- is that parents
need to be educated about what to do.  The parents' perceptions and values
about children and cultural practices are not respected. Their knowledge about
the child's growth and development is not considered valuable.  Second, the
expectation is that ECD programmes are alternatives to child care and
parenting.  Parents have to take no responsibility, other than allowing their
children to attend the programme, for the development and implementation of the
programme.  What this means is that if the government expectation is for
parents and the community to take greater responsibility for ECD provision, a
different approach is going to have to be taken to parent involvement.  A much
more participatory approach is required.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>TRAINING </b>     <p>
<p>
The objective of this study was to examine the status of existing early
childhood development (ECD) training as provided by government,
non-governmental agencies and the private sector.  Specifically, the study
provided a review of the type of training available, the number of
teachers/caregivers trained, aspects of the training such as content,
methodology, structure, resources, personnel, evaluation, certification, costs,
inter-agency cooperation and linkages and identification of future training
needs. The study was also to assess whether the training had generated adequate
awareness, skills and interest among teachers and caregivers to implement the
Malaysian Preschool Curriculum Guidelines. Finally, it tried to assess to what
extent the skills related to initiating parent involvement and education had
been incorporated in the training programmes.<p>
<p>
  <p>
<b>Sample</b><p>
<p>
Fourteen training programmes were selected for review in this study. For each
programme, one to three trained teachers/caregivers were interviewed to get
their views on the training they had undergone. Trainers, consisting of
managerial/supervisory staff who were involved in the training programme, and
teachers and caregivers who had been selected and trained as trainers, were
also interviewed. <p>
<p>
The sample included six training programmes offered by government and four from
non-government agencies, all of whom were providing training mainly for
institution-based teachers and caregivers. One private sector training was
included. One community and one home-based model were also included in order to
gain some understanding of the kind of training the teachers and caregivers had
undergone.<p>
<p>
Data were collected by using the following instruments:<p>
<p>
<ul>o	observation checklist used for observing trainer-trainee interactions and the
training materials used during the training sessions;<p>
<p>
o	interview questionnaire for programme managers, trainers, and trained
teachers;<p>
<p>
o	a discussion guideline for the focus group discussion.</ul> <p>
<p>
In order to understand some of the issues related to training, it important to
know the status of the current teaching force.  In Table 11 is a summary of the
number of trained and untrained teachers and the number of assistant teachers,
by agency providing ECD services.    <p>
  <p>
  While Table 11 would suggest that less than half of those classified as
teachers are trained, this study revealed that even to be <i>trained</i> may
have little significance in terms of the teacher's knowledge skills and
competencies in working with young children.<p>
  <p>
  <p>
  <p>
  <p>
<center><b>TABLE 11</b><p>
  <p>
<b>NUMBER OF PRE-SCHOOL TEACHERS </b><br>
<b>AND ASSISTANT TEACHERS BY AGENCY</b></center><p>
<pre>
      	   	 NO. OF TRAINED    NO. OF UNTRAINED    NO. OF ASSISTANT 
AGENCY            TEACHERS           TEACHERS           TEACHERS

================================================================================
KEMAS                 4,059                 998                2,149
FELCRA           15                    3                  10
FELDA                   106                  22                   54
NATIONAL UNITY          449                  17                  425
PLANTATION       23                   29                  10
JAIS                     61                 149                   48
PRIVATE               3,043               2,060                1,179
ABIM                    201                  91                   56       
UNIVERSITY        6                           -                    -

=================================================================================
TOTAL                 7,963               3,369                3,933
</pre>
<p>
Note:  This does not include the Ministry of Education Annex Programme.<p>
Source: <b>Education Statistics</b>, January 1992, Ministry of Education<p>
<p>
The findings of the study can be summarised as follows:<p>
<p>
<b>1.	The Training Programme</b><p>
<p>
<ul>o	all government agencies that deliver ECD programmes are involved in providing
training to their own ECD personnel. Thus, the opportunity to link between
training and programme implementation experiences was available and could be
maximized.<p>
<p>
o	Except for the Ministry of Education and KEMAS, which was undertaking the
one-year, and five and half months training, respectively, the main concern
among government and NGO programmes was primarily to train as many teachers and
caregivers as possible through short training courses of about one to two-week
duration.  Expediency rather than an understanding of what teachers require is
the driving force.<p>
<p>
o	Except for the community-based parent education project in Kelantan, agencies
are focusing on either the training of institution-based preschool teachers and
personnel or child care centre caregivers and personnel. Only EWRF was
conducting both types of training, but as separate programmes.<p>
<p>
o	Except for the Department of Welfare and PPBM, and more recently EWRF, there
is no coordination, nor much collaboration and mutual support among and between
government and NGO training agencies.  Nonetheless, coordination and
collaboration is considered by most NGOs and trained teachers as very
important.<p>
<p>
o	Except for minimal efforts by the child care training programmes and PPBM,
the pre-school training programmes are not much concerned with reinforcing and
integrating parent/home/culture-based learning opportunities for the child. A
few programmes, all targeting one ethnic group, were imparting ways of getting
parents to teach the 3Rs to children, mainly through flash cards.  <p>
<p>
o	There is no coordination in terms of certification of training programmes
among government and NGOs.<p>
<p>
o	Training in the NGO and private sectors has not been monitored and certified
by any government agency. Misconceptions prevail among trained teachers/
caregivers in as far as certification and recognition of the training is
concerned. Most teachers and caregivers tended and wanted to believe that their
training was being recognised by the government.   <p>
<p>
o	There is no systematic way to train and certify trainers. Thus there is a
need to develop and provide a certified training of trainers system.<p>
<p>
o	There is no long-term and comprehensive ECD training system that can be
applied nation-wide.</ul><p>
<p>
<b>2.	Training content</b><p>
<p>
<ul>o	The training content and process are not based on an assessment of what
trainees already know and the knowledge, skills and abilities they need to
develop. An assumption is made that they know very little.<p>
<p>
o	Most of the training courses were found to be theoretical in approach. The
training lacks balance as well as linkage between theory and practice. The
emphasis tends to be more on content rather than the process of learning/
training.<p>
<p>
o	Teachers/caregivers self-motivation and attitudes, and parent/community
empowerment are not included in all the training courses.</ul> <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>3.	Training strategy</b><p>
<p>
<ul>o	One strategy for integrating theory and practice/experiences (i.e. by
involving trained caregivers and teachers), was used by the child care training
programmes and a few preschool training programmes. However, the
teacher/caregiver-cum-trainers need training in facilitative skills. <p>
<p>
o	The accreditation of decentralised training centres could be used as a
strategy by many agencies to implement massive and rapid training for large
numbers of teachers/caregivers.</ul><p>
 <p>
<p>
<b>4.	The Training methodology</b><p>
<p>
<ul>o	Locally relevant and culture-based learning/training methodologies both for
children and teachers/caregivers were not drawn into the training programmes.
FELCRA had tried to identify and use some of these. This was found to be well
received by the communities and an effective training technique.<p>
<p>
o	Most of the practicum components emphasise teacher-initiated activities
rather than child-initiated activities.      <p>
<p>
o	Almost none of the training programmes use highly interactive, learning by
doing, and experiential training/learning methodologies and processes.</ul><p>
<p>

<b>5.	Training materials</b><p>
<p>
<ul>o	The Preschool Curriculum Guidelines tend to be taught as a subject rather
than as a training/learning guide which should be used and referred to during
the training. The package is considered expensive (RM450). Most teachers and
trainers feel it is not presented in an interesting and facilitative way. In
fact it is seen as too structured. <p>
<p>
o	There are no curriculum guidelines for children under four years of age. <p>
<p>
o	Most training programmes lack audio-visuals, such as videos, taped songs and
stories, and materials such as posters and case-studies.<p>
<p>
o	Most materials made and demonstrated during the training were teacher
initiated. Practice in using these materials was too short and did not lead to
much process learning. It was also common to see sessions on material
production which focused more on the making of handicrafts than play materials.
<p>
 <p>
o	Almost all teachers felt there were not enough materials and examples drawn
from the local culture and home environments of the child.</ul> <p>
<p>

<b>6.	Evaluation of Training</b><p>
<p>
<ul>o	Process evaluation was not emphasized in most training, and many teachers and
caregivers thought that it would be equally if not more useful for them to be
able to examine the process aspects of the training, if they were to acquire
skills and attitudes that were positive in relation to child development and
parenting practices.<p>
<p>
o	While trainers had trainees evaluate the training at the end of the session
or course, no evaluations have been conducted on the impact of training on
teacher/caregiver knowledge, skills and practice.</ul><p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendations</b><p>
<p>
In view of the above, the recommendations of this study in relation to training
are as follows:<p>
<p>
<ul>o	Training strategies which incorporate and integrate ECD content and practice,
relevant to various socio-economic contexts, encompass both institutional and
home-based models, and which are cost-effective, should be adopted.          <p>
<p>
o	Resource networking among all agencies in the government and NGOs should be
fostered.  The network should include both institutional and home-based
programmes in all sectors.<p>
<p>
o	In the NGO sector, there should be an umbrella body to coordinate NGO ECD
training and resource networking, empirical and applied research and evaluation
of ECD programmes in all sectors.         <p>
<p>
o	Existing ECD training programmes by local universities, such as Universiti
Pertanian's Diploma training course, should be reinforced and become part of
the ECD comprehensive training system.<p>
<p>
o	The need for capacity-building for programming personnel in the respective
government agencies dealing with ECD should be reviewed. <p>
<p>
o 	Local universities should undertake longitudinal studies of ECD programme
models, and disseminate the data to all agencies dealing with ECD programmes.<p>
<p>
o	Innovative ECD projects relating to curriculum for children below four years
of age, participatory training packages and methodologies, and strategies for
parent empowerment should be identified and developed.<p>
<p>
o	Monitoring and evaluation of ECD programmes should be integrated into all
aspects of the programme.</ul> <p>
<p>

<center><b>PART IV: COSTS AND FINANCING</center></b><p>
<p>

In order to make recommendations in terms of the Government's future
involvement in ECD, it is necessary to have some understanding of the costs of
such programmes, and the Government's current level of investment in ECD.
Data on costs were collected in relation to programme implementation and in
terms of training costs. It was not possible to obtain information on the
infrastructure and administrative costs of the various Ministries that have
resources devoted to ECD activities.  To some extent this is due to the fact
that each of the Ministries concerned is involved in a range of activities and
thus it is difficult to determine precisely what resources are allocated to
ECD.  However, it is important to note that because there are six Government
bodies involved in one way or another with ECD provision, the administrative
and supervisory costs, as compared to the costs of on-the-ground programmes, is
disproportionately high.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>PROGRAMME IMPLEMENTATION COSTS</b><p>
<p>
In collecting data on programme costs we were able to obtain information from
the three main Government providers of preschool programmes.  Specifically data
were provided on the costs of <p>
<p>
<ul><ul>	- facilities<br>
	- materials<br>
	- teacher salaries/benefits<br>
	- support staff (cooks,cleaners)	<br>
	- food<br>
	- maintenance</ul></ul><p>
	<p>
These data are presented in Table 12.<p>
<p>
In essence the three agencies estimate the costs of a preschool centre somewhat
differently, ranging from $16,000 to $40,000.  While the Ministry of Education
uses existing classrooms for the Preschool Annex classrooms, neither KEMAS nor
National Unity do so.  The community is to identify a building that is
suitable.  All three agencies provide a grant to cover the initial costs of
equipping the preschool.<p>
<p>
All three programmes also provide food for the children at the rate of .50
cents/child/day.  Kemas and National Unity provide $10/month for materials
and/or training expenses for the teacher. (1 Semester is equivalent to 5
months.) All agencies provide per capita grants of $50/child/year.<p>
<p>
TABLE 12 is unavailable.
  <p>

<b>TRAINING COSTS</b><p>
<p>
One of the costs not included in the set-up costs presented, is the cost of
teacher training.  However, this is a very real cost and needs to be taken into
consideration in a discussion of expansion of ECD provision.  <p>
<p>
As a part of the Training sub-study, one of the questions asked was in relation
to the costs of training.  It was difficult to sort out equivalencies since
each of the agencies offers its own training, and each agency has its own way
of calculating costs.  Nonetheless what we attempted was to estimate the number
of days for the various training courses and divide that into the costs of the
course to get a per/day cost for training.  These data are presented in Table
13.<p>
<p>
As can be seen, training costs are varied, and ranged from low to high cost
programmes. The private sector training was the most expensive, due to costs of
its own prescribed books, play materials and equipment.   Nonetheless, there
are some trends.  First, decentralised training appears to be lower in cost
mainly because of its non-residential nature. While not a part of the figures
presented, decentralised training is also cheaper for the trainees since they
have lower transportation costs. <p>
<p>
Second, there are some economies of scale: the longer the programme, the
cheaper the per day costs.  Thus, the most expensive kind of training are the
2-3 day workshops offered in a centralized setting. <p>
<p>
A significant problem in trying to estimate a per day cost for training is that
the amount spent does not necessarily correlate with the quality of the
training.  Nor is there an ideal training package among the current training
efforts.  Thus we cannot estimate the total costs of adequately training an
individual. <p>
<p>
<center><b>TABLE 13</b><p>
  <p>
<b>TRAINING COSTS BY TOTAL, COSTS/DAY </b><br>
<b>AND CENTRALIZED (c) VS. DECENTRALIZED (d) TRAINING</b></center><p>
  <p>


<pre>
  Agency         Title          Duration        Cost         Costs/day     
                                 (days)                                      
Welfare       Preliminary          10                       *c = 71.82     
                                              $718 - c       d = 31.70  
              Basic                12                        c = 59.83  
                                              $317 - d       d = 26.42  
              Supervisor           13                        c = 55.23              
                                                             d = 24.38  
FELCRA                              6         $720 - c       c = 120.      

                                    3         $150 - d       d =  50.       

KEMAS         Teachers            120 +/-     $2635.75         21.96       

              Asst.Tchrs           24           356.15         14.84          

              Trainers             18          1600.00         88.89          

              Follow-up             6           697.00        116.17         
  
PTM           6 Steps              30           480.00         16.00       

*  c = centralised training costs, d = decentralised training costs
</pre>

<p>
FINANCING<p>
<p>
After determining the costs associated with establishing and operating a
preschool programme, the next question is, who pays for what?  <p>
<p>
One source of funds is parent fees/contributions to the programme.  As a part
of the sub-study on parent involvement, parents were asked what they paid
currently in terms of fees.  They were also asked if they were willing to pay
more, and if so, how much more.  Table 14 presents a summary of the
responses.<p>
<p>
<center><b>TABLE 14</b><p>
  <p>
<b>FEES BEING PAID BY PARENTS AND THE WHAT THEY ARE</b><br>
<b>WILLING TO PAY IN ADDITION, BY SPONSORING AGENCY - 1994</b></center><p>
  

<pre>
           Sponsor           Parent               Additional           
                            Contributions        Parents will Pay      
   
        National Unity         $10/mo                $10/mo           
        Education            50/Semester              10/mo           
        KEMAS                 5-10/mo                 15/mo           
        Health                   8/mo              up to 20           
        Labour                  15/mo                 - 0 -           
        Welfare              15-400/mo                20/mo            
                            sliding scale                              
        Private                160/mo                 - 0 -           
        Home-Based             110/mo                  More            
        ABIM                    40/mo                                

</pre>

	Source: <b>Review of Early Childhood Development in Malaysia: Parent and Community Involvement</b>. Putri Zabariah Rahman,  November, 1994<p>

<p>
It is interesting to note that, for the most part, parents are willing to pay
double what they are currently paying.  Currently they are paying approximately
20% of the running costs of the preschool  (see Table 15).  If they were to
double their payment, it would increase their contribution to nearly 40% of the
on-going costs.<p>
<p>
Who pays the other costs?  The answer is, the Government.  Table 15 summarizes
the way in which the various components of the programme are financed.  <p>
<p>
While the table would suggest that the parents and community pay a substantial
amount of the set-up costs, this figure is misleading.  While the initial
building costs are not paid by KEMAS and National Unity, for the most part the
building used to house the preschool is a Government building, in that it is
frequently part of a community centre which the Government has built.  Thus the
community has not had to put its own money into building a preschool. However,
the community is responsible for maintaining the building.<p>
<p>

<center><b>TABLE 15</b><p>
  <p>
<b>PRE-SCHOOL COSTS AND HOW THEY ARE PAID</b></center><p>
  

<pre>
  Agency                  TOTAL  Government    %    Parents/   %     Costs/    
                                                     Comm.*          child/    
                                                                      year**    
  KEMAS    Set up -EST   32,000    12,000    37.5%   20,000  52.5%             
           Recurrent     13,740    11,240    81.8%    2,500  18.2%     549     
  Unity    Set up        16,000    16,000    100%                               
           Recurrent     18,500    16,000    86.5%    2,500  13.5%     740     
           Repairs***   156,000                                                  
           Set up        40,000    40,000   100%                                
Education               new bldg.                                                  
                         16,000    16,000   100%                                
                        refurbish                                                  
           Recurrent     14,960    12,960    86.6%    2,500  16.7%     598     

</pre>
<p>
*	The calculations are based on the assumption that there are 25
children/centre, and that parent fees are $10/mo over a 10 month period.<br>
**	The costs do not include any of the setup or teacher training costs and are
based on the assumption that there are 25 children/classroom<br>
***	This amount is to provide repairs across all centres<br>
<p>
<p>
The last column in Table 15 is important.  It presents the cost/child/year in a
Government supported preschool.  In order to evaluate these costs, it is
important to know how they compare with costs in other parts of the system.  In
Table 15 are the costs of children in the primary and secondary schools.  As
can be noted, the costs of a half-day preschool are not significantly less.
They are 62%-68% of the costs of primary school.<p>
<p>
<center><b>TABLE 16</b><p>
  <p>
<b>PRIMARY AND SECONDARY EDUCATION EXPENDITURE</b><br>
<b>AND COST PER STUDENT 1980-1989</b></center><p>
  			

<pre>
       Year        Total $       as % of Ed.        Cost/pupil      
                   (000)           Budget            RM                
   
       1980         1,714           61.5              557           
       1984         2,531           60.4              745           
       1989         3,264           61.7              868           

</pre>
<p>
	Source:  <b>Development of and Issues in Pre-school and Primary Education</b>,
Dr.
	         Leong Yin Ching, Situation Analysis Paper, UNICEF, 1992, pg. 9<p>
<p>
As was noted earlier in the report, currently about 41% of the children 4-6
years of age are enroled in a preschool programme.  If 100% coverage is to be
achieved, it would be very costly for the Government.  There are several ways
that Government expenditure could be decreased.  One would be for the preschool
programme to be consolidated within only one Ministry so that rather than
duplicating administrative and bureaucratic staff, there would be one set of
infrastructure costs.  This would allow current resources allocated to
preschool programmes to be extended to more children.<p>
<p>
Another option is for lower-costs models of ECD provision to be explored.  One
such option is home-based programmes.  These could be established as satellites
of current preschool centres.  While the Government would be responsible for
providing training and supervision to the home-based programmes, the government
would not pay teacher salaries.  They would be paid by parent fees.  In
instances where parents are not able to pay the fees, the Government could pay
a per child subsidy to the teacher/caregiver.  This way teachers do not become
a part of the Government payroll. This model has been quite successful in Latin
America, in particular in Colombia and Venezuela.<p>
<p>
In terms of Government funding for ECD programmes, it is only from the Ministry
of Education that we have any data on what has been allocated to preschool.
Table 17 presents a summary of the allocation for preschool education within
the original Sixth Malaysian Plan and the Mid-Term Review.  While 140 million
was allocated as the Plan was formulated, this was revised downward, as noted
in the Mid-Term Review.  It is important to note that even in the original
allocation, the monies for preschool education amounted to only 1.8% of the
total Education Budget.  It is now less than 1% of the Education Budget.<p>
<p>
<center><b>TABLE 17</b><p>
  <p>
<b>ALLOCATION FOR PRESCHOOL WITHIN THE EDUCATION BUDGET</b><br>
<b>(RM Million)</b></center><p>
  

<pre>
                          Sixth        % for      Sixth       % for      
                          Plan         Pre        Plan        Pre        
                          Original     School     Revised     School     
    Preschool                140        1.8%         23        .33%     
    Education Total        7,724                  7,018.7                

</pre>
<p>
	Note, there has been no provision for pre-school education in previous<p>
	  Plans.  <p>
	Source:  (Sixth Malaysia Plan: 1991-1995, pg 183, and Mid-Term Review of<p>
	         Sixth Malaysian Plan: 1991-1995, pg. 225)<p>
<p>
It is interesting to compare the Ministry of Education expenditure figure with
what the Ministry of Education in Kenya allocates to preschool education.  In
their budget only .13% (one-tenth of one percent) is for preschool education.
(Myers, 1992, pg. 25)  Yet with this amount they are able to serve
approximately 800,000 children, (i.e. almost 30% of the estimated 2.8 million
children ages 3-5 in the country).  That is because of the high level of parent
and community participation. The community is responsible for constructing the
preschool and, in many communities, they are responsible for paying the
teacher's salary.  Government funds pay for teacher training and on-going
Supervision.<p>
<p>
We are not arguing that the Ministry of Education's budget for preschool remain
at less than 1% of the Education budget, particularly since the Ministry of
Education is not currently a major provider of ECD services.  We are suggesting
that there are more cost-effective ways of investing in preschool education
than is currently being done.<p>
<p>
An important variable in a discussion of financing of ECD in Malaysia is
current Government policy which promotes privatization.  In all sectors the
Government is seeking to reduce its subsidisation of services.  Services are
being taken over by the private sector.  While it can well be imagined that the
private sector can provide ECD services, particularly in the form of preschools
and child care centres, for those who are able to pay, there is a strata within
society that will be unable to pay the full costs of the services.  Thus
alternative funding will have to be sought for these programmes.<p>
<p>
There are a variety of alternatives.  In Colombia, for example, a payroll tax
levied on all Colombian businesses provides the funding for the Colombian
Institute of Family Welfare (ICBF), a quasi-governmental body responsible for
ECD provision.  This helps subsidise ECD programmes in areas where families are
unable to pay.  In Mauritius, a Trust has been established, the income from
which is used to fund ECD programmes.<p>
<p>
Another partner in the effort is business.  At the present time there is a
policy in effect in Malaysia which provides businesses with a tax break if they
provide child care for the children of their workers.  At this point the policy
has not been in effect long enough to know if it is effective.  Clearly the
impact of this policy should be monitored in terms of its cost-effectiveness as
a strategy for financing ECD.<p>
<p>
<center><b>PART V:  CONCLUSIONS</b></center><p>
  <p>
<p>
<b>Defining Roles and relationships</b><p>
<p>
A key question is, what is the role of government in early childhood
development, particularly in relation to preschool education and child care,
the areas that require significant capital investment and recurrent
expenditure. In principle, government investment in preschool and child care
centres which require dedicated buildings and staff, is justified if it meets
four tests:<p>
<p>
<ol>1.	The private market is failing to provide services in adequate quantity or
quality.<p>
<p>
2.	The private market does not operate in locations where children are in
greatest needs of services.<p>
<p>
3.	The intervention is cost-effective. <p>
<p>
4.	The intervention is more cost-effective than other interventions that
government might make to achieve similar goals.</ol> <p>
<p>
With regard to the second test, the Dropout Study (1973) demonstrated that
preschooling has a more significant impact on reducing the dropouts among
children of poor families than among rich families.  Thus a theoretical case
can be made for government financing of ECD programmes for the poor, provided
that ECD approaches are appropriately designed and that they are used as
convergence points for an integrated set of ECD services, so as to maximise
their benefits.<p>
<p>
With regard to the third and fourth tests, the research available in  Malaysia
on the impact of preschool of primary performance did not: 1) calculate the
cost of the approach; 2) look at the cost-effectiveness of alternative
approaches; or 3) look at the cost of preschool compared to other investments
that might be made to improve educational outcomes.  A longitudinal
cost-effectiveness study of different approaches to ECD (i.e. centre-based and
home-based, full-day and a half-day, parent education) should be undertaken to
determine whether there is a case for universal provision and the extent to
which government should be involved. <p>
<p>
Internationally, the biggest drain on Government financed ECD programmes is the
recurrent costs of staff.  Over time these costs absorb an increasing
percentage of the budget, giving government less flexibility to develop
innovative projects and to increase coverage. Thus, as the Government of
Malaysia is developing its own ECD policy, it is wise to define its role in
terms of policy and the development of curriculum and training systems,
coordination and monitoring -- setting the standard for what should be provided
-- rather than being engaged in large-scale provision.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Coverage, access and equity.  </b><p>
<p>
Coverage and equity concerns can be raised at two levels -- within a given
village/community and nationally.  The UNICEF study (circa 1984) looked at the
relationship between family variables and attendance in preschool centres. The
study indicated that parent income influences the type of preschool the
children attend.  Parents who can afford to do so, send their children to
private preschools.  <p>
<p>
If the public sector is going to provide ECD services, these must reach the
poor and the hard core poverty groups.  While it is recommended that additional
effort be put into reaching the poorest, it is not being recommended that
preschool centres be established in hard core poverty areas.  Rather,
appropriate cost-effective approaches should be developed to reach this
population. For example, satellite home-based centres linked to current
preschool programmes, community-based child care, parent education, and/or home
visiting programmes.<p>
<p>
Further, there should be exploration of the ways in which current Government
programmes can be enhanced to meet the broader ECD objectives.  For example,
parent education can readily be combined, at minimal additional costs, with the
health and nutrition outreach services, such as the Home-Based Child Health
Card.   <p>
<p>
<b>Impact and Quality Issues</b><p>
<p>
In the absence of a thorough evaluation of ECD programmes in Malaysia, it is
impossible to assess the impact of the various programmes. However, there is
general agreement, which was supported by this study, that quality is low.  <p>
<p>
Several factors contribute to low quality.  First, the length and focus of
training does not prepare teachers to appropriately support children's
development. Teachers and caregivers lack appropriate child stimulation and
teaching skills. There is a tendency to over-emphasise the teaching of the 3Rs,
rather than organising the child's environment in a way that would support
exploration, problem-solving, curiosity and the foundations for the 3Rs -- all
features of appropriate child development programmes. <p>
<p>
Second, the current supervision system does not provide substantive and regular
support to teacher/caregivers in the field.<p>
<p>
Bringing the preschool programme to an acceptable quality would require:<p>
<p>
<ol>1.  An expansion of the concept of quality to include the dimensions of
teacher/child, child/child, and teacher/parent interactions, rather than
focusing only on quantifiable dimensions that may or may not be related to the
quality of the experience for children in the ECD programme.<p>
<p>
2.  The creation of a training package that provides trainees
(teachers/caregivers and supervisors) with a curriculum framework that allows
them to make appropriate curricular decision, an adequate balance between
theory and practical experience to understand how theoretical principles can be
applied, and incorporating culturally-relevant teaching and learning
strategies.</ol><p>
<p>
<b>The Intersecting Needs of Women and Children.</b><p>
<p>
It is hypothesized that the current child care and preschool programmes do not
actually address the child care needs of working women, primarily because of
the limited hours of operations. (The exception to this is the plantation child
care centres.)  However, there are increasing numbers of women in the work
force, most of whom are in occupations where it would be inappropriate to bring
the child to the workplace.  In addition, many of these women now live in
nuclear families and lack the full-time support provided by extended family
members.  The demand for care, which combines attending to children's health
and safety with appropriate education and stimulation, is rising.<p>
<p>
The Department of Labour has been mandated to respond to this issue.  In
addition to the child care centres which are established on plantations, the
Ministry most recently has been working to establish industry-based childcare
in urban areas. <p>
<p>
However, most poor women do not work in factories and cannot afford the costs
of institutionalised child care.  At the present time there are no commercially
based systems of child care that are affordable to poor women.  There seems to
be a case on equity grounds for government to take a lead role in creating
alternative systems of child care supported by government, the community and
parents. <p>
<p>
Internationally there is considerable experience in the development and
implementation of home-based child care, particularly in Latin America.  This
experience might well be brought to Malaysia.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Programmatically</b><p>
<p>
ECD programmes should not focus only on children.  There is a need to focus on
the family in order to increase the family's capacity to provide for the
development of their own children. While it is important to focus primarily on
mothers, both because the mother's health and nutrition during pregnancy
determine the child's health and nutrition at birth, and because mothers are
the primary providers of care to young children, it is also important to look
at the family as a unit.  A  child's advantages or disadvantages stem from the
situation of the family as a whole.  Further, not just mothers but fathers, and
members of the extended family are important caregivers.<p>
<p>
Just as it is important to empower the family to provide for the child's full
developmental needs, it is also important to empower the community, as far as
possible, to provide for the welfare of all its children.  Well designed ECD
programmes, like well designed development programmes in general, foster
community participation in the assessment of needs, and the monitoring,
planning or implementation of interventions.  As with other development
programmes, participation is often best fostered through strengthening and
drawing on the resources of community organisations and NGOs.<p>
<p>
The KEMAS mandate and structure<i> allow for </i>greater parent involvement and
greater community participation at various levels than the other
pre-school/kindergarten programmes.  However, this has not been maximized.  <p>
<p>
<b>Organizationally:</b><p>
<p>
Currently there is a lack of coordination across and between the various ECD
programmes.  There is clearly a need for a mechanism to bring together those
serving children under 4, those serving children over 4, and those serving
children over 6 years of age.  The break and shift in programming that happens
at age 4 and at age 6 causes problems of continuity for the child and family.
Further, in some places this has led to the building of separate facilities in
areas which can barely afford one facility. <p>
<p>
In sum, continued government investment in preschool appears to be justified,
provided that its beneficiaries include the children of the poorest families
who do not have the resources to pay for private sector preschools even when
they are available.  Within Malaysia there is not sufficient research evidence
to suggest that current ECD programmes offer the most cost-effective approach
to early childhood provision.  However, the data do suggest that, from an
equity perspective, the already established programme narrows the differential
between rich and poor.  Thus these programmes should not be discontinued until
there is hard evidence regarding the cost-effectiveness of alternatives.  Given
the resources already allocated by government in various programmes mandated by
law, there will be high returns to investment at the margin to improve the
quality of current programmes.  A key in increasing effectiveness will be the
coordination of activities, both within the government and in establishing
appropriate linkages between government, non-governmental agencies and the
private sector.<p>
<p>
