<html><head>
</head>
<title>SURVEY OF ECD PROVISION IN MALAYSIA</title><body>
<b>ANNEX C</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>SURVEY OF ECD PROVISION IN MALAYSIA</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Aims and Objectives:<p>
<p>
The review aims to assist the Government of Malaysia in formulating a
comprehensive and cost-effective ECD policy and strategy linked to overall
national development priorities.  Thus the review will lead to proposals
regarding arrangements for effective implementation, monitoring, management and
coordination of the programme, and subsequent identification of broad policy
and strategy options for strengthening ECD's contribution to national
development.<p>
<p>
More specifically, the objectives of the review are:<p>
<p>
	(1)	to prepare a profile of existing ECD programmes in relation to needs;<p>
<p>
	(2)	to undertake selected case-studies of the non-institutional
home/family-based and after school care services;<p>
<p>
	(3)	to establish a comprehensive ECD data base;<p>
<p>
	(4)	to analyze overall ECD programme costs;<p>
<p>
	(5)	to examine current ECD programme coordination mechanisms, including
existing legal provisions;<p>
<p>
	(6)	to review existing research findings;<p>
<p>
	(7)	to review the status of ECD curriculum, teaching and learning methods,
materials production and training as related to the delivery of programmes of
satisfactory quality;<p>
<p>
	(8)	to inform key ECD managers of relevant experiences from other countries in
the formulation and implementation of ECD policy;<p>
<p>
	(9)	to propose arrangements for the effective implementation, monitoring,
management and coordination of ECD programmes;<p>
<p>
	(10)	to identify broad policy and strategy options for strengthening ECD's
contribution to national development; and<p>
<p>
	(11)	to review the nature and extent of current linkages between ECD
programmes, parents and the community and suggest ways in which such linkages
might be extended. <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>DEFINITION OF TERMS:</b><p>
<p>
Early Childhood Development (ECD)<p>
<p>
There are two parts to the phrase, 'early childhood' and 'development'.  Early
childhood is the period of a child's life from conception through the age 8.
'<b>Development'</b> is a process of change in which the child comes to master
more and more complex levels of moving, thinking, feeling and interacting with
people and objects in the environment.  Development, which involves changes in
complexity and function, is different from growth, which refers to changes in
size. (Myers, 1992)<p>
<p>
<b>Learning</b>, on the other hand, is a process of acquiring knowledge,
skills, habits and values through experience and experimentation, observation,
reflection, and/or study and instruction. Learning is a crucial part of
development.  General development involves both a gradual unfolding of
biologically determined characteristics and the learning process.
Developmental progress facilitates or inhibits learning which, in turn, helps
to define the progress of future development. Thus learning is part of the
development process. <p>
<p>
Beyond simply defining development and learning, it is important to define the
basic principles of child development and learning that underlay the review and
the operational principles that should be respected when establishing early
childhood programmes.<p>
<p>
<b>CHILD DEVELOPMENT PRINCIPLES</b><p>
<p>
   	<b>Development begins pre-natally and learning is occurring at birth.</b><p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Attention to the developmental and learning needs of children
should begin with pre- and post-natal interventions and be continued
thereafter.<p>
<p>
   	<b>Development and learning occur continuously as a result of the child
interacting with the environment.</b><p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Interventions can focus on changing the child and/or on changing
the environment (which includes the immediate family, the community, social and
political institutions).  <p>
<p>
   	<b>Development has several inter-related dimensions within which learning
occurs. </b> These include physical, cognitive, social, spiritual and emotional
dimensions (each of which affects the other and all of which are developing
simultaneously).<p>
	Therefore:  Development and learning must be seen holistically and
interventions should provide integrated attention to the child, including
attention to needs for protection, food, health care, affection, interaction
and stimulation, security provided through consistency and predictability, and
play allowing exploration. All of these elements should be present to support
the child' development.<p>
<p>
   	<b>Development proceeds in predictable steps and learning occurs in
recognized sequences.</b><p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Interventions should follow an appropriate sequence. Activities
should provide the child with a developmentally appropriate challenge.  There
is no value in presenting them before a child is developmentally ready for
them.<p>
<p>
   	<b>There is a great deal of individual and social variability in children's
rates and styles of development and of learning.</b><p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Interventions should be able to identify and adjust to varying
individual and social needs of children.<p>
<p>
   	<b>Children are active participants in their own development and
learning.</b> Learning and related development involves the child's
construction of knowledge, not an adult's imposition of information.  The
skills which are the basis for constructing knowledge improve with practice.<p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Interventions should include opportunities for children to learn
by doing, to be engaged in problem-solving, and the develop language and
communication skills. They should not put undue emphasis on cognitive/mental
development.<p>
<p>
   	<b>Children learn in many ways:</b> by playing and exploring, by using all
their senses, by imagining, by imitating, by interacting socially with
others.<p>
<p>
	Therefore:  Integrated interventions promoting social, emotional and spiritual
development as well as cognitive learning can take advantage of varied forms of
learning, consistent with cultural ways even while taking into account that
there are recognized sequences and activities that facilitate learning. <p>
<p>
   	<b>It helps a child to develop and learn when adults (parents, teachers and
community members</b>:<p>
<p>
	  -	are emotionally responsive and involved<p>
	  -	talk to children<p>
	  -	provide appropriate and varied play materials<p>
	  -	are supportive of the child's learning<p>
<p>
	Therefore: Interventions should include ways to address the needs of children
within the context of the family and community.  Attention should be given to
adults as well as to children in programme planning and implementation.<p>
<p>
<b>PROGRAMMING PRINCIPLES</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>	Some of the following operational principles are directly related to
the principles of development and learning set out previously.  Others are
general principles of programming that apply to programmes of early childhood
development as well as to other kinds of programmes. Behind all of the
principles is the desire to mount effective and sustainable programmes.<p>
<p>
   	<b>Seek programme integration in conceptualizing, planning, delivering
services, establishing content and promoting use.</b><p>
<p>
	This principle derives in part from the holistic nature of child development
in which physical, mental, social and emotional and spiritual dimensions of
development interact with and affect each other.  Hence, effectiveness requires
integrated attention to children.  In addition, there is a maximization of
resources when programmes are multi-dimensional, combining health, nutrition,
educational and social actions.   <p>
  <p>
   	<b>Foster participation by individuals, families and communities who are to
be the primary beneficiaries.</b><p>
<p>
	A principle of active participation is consistent with the basic principles of
learning and development described above.  Sustained human and social
development and the sustainability of programmes all depend on enhancing
people's capacities to improve their own lives and to take greater control over
their own destinies.<p>
<p>
   	<b>Build child-focused partnerships by expanding existing collaboration and
bringing together new partners supportive of development.</b><p>
<p>
	Neither governments nor communities nor a wide range of non-governmental
organizations can easily maintain an effective programme without help.  The
principle of developing partnerships between government, non-governmental
agencies, the private sector and the community arises from social as well as
financial needs.<p>
<p>
   	<b>Build on inherent strengths and local childrearing practices that are
beneficial to child and social development.</b><p>
<p>
	Knowledge about solutions to child development problems can be found in
experience and traditional wisdom as well as in academic wisdom or new
technologies. Childrearing practices that are supportive of children's growth
and development should be encouraged and built upon in programming.<p>
   	<b>Take an inter-generational view; seek ways of involving children, youth
and adults.</b><p>
<p>
	Programmes of early childhood development can and should benefit parents,
other caregivers and community members as well as children.  Child care, for
instance, is generally the responsibility of various family members (older
siblings and extended family members in addition to fathers and mother).
Programmes should take into account the needs of families as well as the needs
of children. <p>
<p>
     <b>Be open to diversity and to complementary approaches.</b><p>
<p>
	This principle derives in part from the social and individual variation in
children' needs.  It is also derived from a recognition of the cultural
diversity which exists within and across nations. Programmes which respect this
diversity will necessarily differ. <p>
<p>
   	<b>Be aware of the total environment and its impact on the child's
life.</b><p>
<p>
	A child does not exist on his/her own.  The child's development in affected by
the environment with which the child interacts.  This includes the home, the
community, social institutions and legal frameworks, and a cultural ethos.  A
comprehensive programme to improve child development should function
simultaneously at these different levels, focusing respectively on the child,
caregivers, national institutions and policies, and the knowledge base of the
society. <p>
<p>
   	<b>Seek quality.</b><p>
<p>
	Low quality programmes are ineffective, depriving children of benefits, and
represent a waste of resources.  In seeking quality, recognize that it is
affected by the motivation and training of programme personnel, the physical
environment, the materials used, and the form of the curriculum.  A quality
programme is appropriate to the stage of development and addresses the needs of
the child involved while respecting individual differences in development.
Quality cannot be legislated.  Setting norms and standards does not guarantee
quality.  Neither is quality defined by expenditure level.<p>
<p>
   	<b>Aim at universal attention to children, but with special recognition of
children living in conditions that put them at increased risk of delayed or
debilitated development.</b><p>
	<p>
	This principle recognizes the need for all children to be supported as they
grow and develop, while stressing the urgency of attending to children living
in poverty or those who are discriminated against as a result of ethnic
diversity.  <p>
 <p>
   	Coverage is best achieved by combining a variety of approaches rather than
developing a single national model meant to apply to all.<p>
<p>
	Attention to all the children can be sought through a series of different
programmes responding to distinct needs.  There need not be one national
programme that is extended to all children, parents or communities.<p>
   	<b>Seek cost-effectiveness.</b><p>
<p>
	This principle recognizes the importance of using scarce resources efficiently
and effectively.  This does not mean that "low-cost" programmes are necessarily
the best. If they are not effective they represent a waste of resources. In
general, strategies that stress prevention are more cost-effective than
compensatory strategies.<p>
<p>
   	<b>Incorporate monitoring and evaluation into programmes from the
outset.</b><p>
<p>
	This principle recognizes that many programmes are not effective or are not
sustained because they do not include the capacity to analyze strengths and
weaknesses and to adjust accordingly.<p>
<p>
It is with these principles and guidelines in mind that the review of early
childhood development programmes in Malaysia was undertaken. <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>ECD IN MALAYSIA - A REVIEW</b><p>
<p>
In Malaysia a number of terms have been used to refer to the care of children
of different age groups in various settings.  For example, the term
'kindergarten' has been used to refer to a half-day programme for children 5
&amp; 6 years of age. (There has been a recent shift in terminology.  These are
now called 'pre-schools'.) Children below the age of 4 are provided for in
'nurseries' or 'child care' centres.  Children are also taken care of in homes
by childminders.  This is known as 'home-based child care'.  For the purposes
of this review, Early Childhood Development programmes includes all these
programmes and more.  It includes the full range of programmes, services and
experiences that have been developed to support young children and their
families. <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>SCOPE OF THE REVIEW</b><p>
<p>
1.   The review will begin with a mapping of what exists in terms of current
service provision and the supports for such provision (e.g. curriculum,
materials, and training); the legislation/ policies in place related to ECD
programmes; and coordination of services. While the focus of the review is
primarily on what is being offered by various government departments, where
they is a significant contribution to ECD by non-governmental agencies (NGOs),
the private sector and those involved in ECD provision for commercial reasons,
these are also described.<p>
<p>
The review will begin by looking specifically at the activities of the
following agencies and organizations:<p>
<p>
	The Ministry of National Unity and Social development<p>
		The National Unity pre-schools <p>
		The Department of Social Welfare's nurseries and  child care programmes<p>
	The Ministry of Education's Annex Pre-school Programme<p>
	The Ministry of Land Development<p>
		Community Development Division - KEMAS <p>
	Ministry of Health <p>
 	Non-governmental agencies (NGOs) <p>
	Religious sponsors <p>
	Home-based programmes<p>
	Commercial ECD programmes<p>
<p>
<p>
For each agency/organization data will be gathered on:<p>
<p>
	Legislation/policies and objectives that guide the<p>
	   programme<p>
Location of the programme (distribution by state,  urban/rural)<p>
	Number of children attending, by age group (0-4,5-6)<p>
Profile of the children (age, ethnicity, family income level)<p>
Profile of teachers in programme (age, ethnicity, qualifications, number of
trained and untrained)<p>
	Programme costs - to the sponsoring agency, to the community  and to parents<p>
	Problems they face<p>
	Future plans<p>
<p>
<p>
From this mapping it will be possible to determine where there are gaps in
service - for age groups, for income groups, for ethnic groups, and by
geographic location. <p>
<p>
<p>
2.  Once the basic models have been defined in terms of their coverage, then it
will be possible to focus on CURRICULUM issues.  For the purposes of this
review, curriculum is defined as <i>the set of experiences planned for the
children, family and community.  </i><p>
<p>
<p>
SAMPLE:<p>
<p>
There will be 16 types of programmes surveyed. This includes:<p>
<p>
	The Ministry of National Unity and Social development<p>
		The National Unity pre-schools (urban)<p>
		The Department of Social Welfare's nurseries and<p>
		 child care programmes (urban, rural)<p>
	The Ministry of Education's Annex Pre-school Programme<p>
		(urban, rural)<p>
	The Ministry of Land Development<p>
		Community Development Division KEMAS (urban squatters and rural)<p>
	Ministry of Health (urban, rural)<p>
	Non-governmental agencies (NGOs) (PTM - urban:  ERWF - plantation)<p>
	Religious sponsors (ABIM)  (urban, rural)<p>
	Home-based programmes (urban, rural)<p>
	Commercial ECD programmes (urban)<p>
<p>
<p>
For each of the agencies/organizations included in the study, the curriculum
will be reviewed in terms of its quality (as evaluated against the principles
of child development listed above).  In addition the support materials
available to the teachers and children will be described and evaluated.<p>
<p>
Once again, the basic review should allow for the identification of both
strengths and gaps in the curriculum and materials available to teachers and
children.<p>
<p>
METHODOLOGY:<p>
<p>
	Review of existing materials as provided by each group.<p>
	Interview of Programme Managers at Headquarters<p>
<p>
Questions:<p>
<p>
	1. 	What curriculum are you using?<p>
	2.	What modifications have been made to the curriculum?<p>
	3.	What difficulties do you have in using the curriculum <p>
		and materials?<p>
	4. 	What suggestions do you have for improving the<p>
		curriculum? <p>
	5. 	Do you have any plans for the future in terms of curriculum development?<p>
<p>
3.  The next issue to be addressed is how well is the curriculum being
implemented?  In other words, what is happening on-the-ground?  What is the
experience like in the setting for both the child and the teacher?<p>
<p>
SAMPLE:<p>
<p>
	Classroom/service setting for each of the 16 sites.<p>
Programme Managers will be asked to select a site. They will be as how they
rate this site in terms of its quality.<p>
<p>
Methodology:   Interview of teachers/local Supervisors and Observation<p>
<p>
Teacher/Supervisor Interview:<p>
<p>
	1. 	In what ways do children benefit from the programme?<p>
	2. 	What curriculum are you using?<p>
	3. 	What modifications have you made in the curriculum?<p>
	4.	What difficulties do you have in using the curriculum and materials?<p>
	5. 	What suggestions do you have for improving the curriculum?<p>
	6. 	How much time does it take you to prepare each day?<p>
	7. 	What kind of activities do you plan for children?<p>
	8.	What materials are available?<p>
			Which ones have you made?<p>
			Which ones have the children made?	<p>
	9.	Are you given money to buy materials for the classroom?<p>
			If yes, how much?<p>
			If no, what do you do?<p>
	10. 	How do you use the outside space?<p>
	11.	How do you evaluate or assess children?<p>
		  	How do you use the information?<p>
	12.	What kind of contact do you have with parents?<p>
	13.	How do parents support your work with the children?<p>
	14. 	Why did you decide to become a teacher?<p>
	15.  	What is your own background in terms of experience?<p>
	16. 	What kind of training have you received?<p>
	17.	What additional training would you like?<p>
	18.	Is there anything else you would like us to know about your centre?<p>
<p>
From the teacher or manager the interviewer will gather data on the costs of
running the centre - teacher salary, maintenance costs, materials, activities,
food, etc.<p>
<p>
Request copy of timetable for review<p>
<p>
Take a video of the classroom. <p>
	scan room, scan outdoor space (if available)<p>
	room arrangement, storage space, kitchen, etc.<p>
	Interactions - teacher/child, child/child<p>
	What activities do children like most?<p>
<p>
4.  In order for teachers to implement the training they need to be given
adequate training. Thus a focus within the review is on training.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
SAMPLE:<p>
<p>
	Agencies providing training<p>
		Health (on-ground and home visitor)<p>
		FELCRA, Kelantan (home-based)<p>
		KEMAS<p>
		UNITY<p>
		Education  (Vocational, Annex)<p>
		NGO - PTM, EWRF<p>
		ABIM<p>
		Social Welfare<p>
		Commercial<p>
		University<p>
		<p>
	<p>
METHODOLOGY<p>
<p>
	Review materials<p>
	Interview Training Programme Manager<p>
	Interview trainers<p>
	Observe actual training, if available<p>
<p>
Interview of Trainer<p>
<p>
Training content<p>
<p>
	1.	What percentage of your curriculum	is devoted to providing the trainee
with:<p>
		- child development theory<p>
		- teaching methodology<p>
		- communication skills and attitudes related to work<p>
			 with parents<p>
		- self-development of teacher (motivation, values)<p>
	2.	What is the balance between teaching theory and providing trainees with
practice skills?  getting practice?<p>
<p>
	3. 	What methods do you use in training teachers/ Supervisors/Managers?<p>
	<p>
Structure<p>
<p>
	1.	What are the various types of courses that you offer?<p>
		(basic/follow-up/in-house/enrichment, etc)<p>
	2.	What is the duration of these courses?<p>
	<p>
Resources<p>
<p>
	1.	What materials do you have available for the trainer to use in training?<p>
	2.	Where does training take place?<p>
	3.	Is there overnight accommodation available and/or provided?<p>
<p>
Personnel<p>
<p>
	1.	Who are the trainers/facilitator?<p>
			(experience, qualifications?	<p>
	2.	Who are the trainees? (teachers/supervisors/managers)<p>
			(previous training)<p>
<p>
Evaluation <p>
<p>
	1.	What kind of evaluation is conducted on the training?<p>
	2.	Who does it?  How often?<p>
	3.	How are the data used?<p>
	<p>
Certification<p>
<p>
	1.	What kind of certification are you able to provide?<p>
	2.	What would your recommendation be in terms of a national certification
process?  Should there be one? If yes, how should it be developed?  Who should
issue the certificate?<p>
	<p>
Costs<p>
<p>
	1.	What are the costs of your training?<p>
			Trainers<p>
			Facilities (initial and maintenance)<p>
			Support staff<p>
			Teaching Materials<p>
			Office supplies<p>
			Food<p>
			Other<p>
<p>
	2.  	How are these costs financed?  How much is contributed by:<p>
		- government<p>
		- trainees<p>
		- private sector<p>
		- other<p>
<p>
Inter-agency cooperation/linkages<p>
<p>
	1.	Do you offer training to others?<p>
			If yes, what type of training?<p>
			How is that financed?<p>
	2.	Do other agencies assist in your training?<p>
			If yes, in what ways?<p>
			How are the costs covered? <p>
<p>
Needs<p>
<p>
	1.	What do you see as the greatest training needs?<p>
<p>
	2.	What would recommend in terms of the future development of training
opportunities for those involved in ECD programmes?<p>
<p>
Training of Trainers courses will also be reviewed and the questions listed
above will be asked of those training trainers. <p>
<p>
5.  An important principle of effective child development programmes is that
they include significant community and parent involvement.  Within each of the
16 centres to be visited in the review an assessment will be made of the
current level of parent and community involvement.  <p>
<p>
SAMPLE<p>
<p>
	16 centres <p>
	<p>
METHODOLOGY<p>
	<p>
	Focus group discussion at parent meeting with 10-15 parents<p>
	<p>
	1.	Why do you send your child to this centre?<p>
	2.	What has your child gained from being here?<p>
	3.	What kinds of things do they during the day?	<p>
	4. 	What do you like best about the centre?<p>
	5.	What do you like least?<p>
	6.	What do you see as your role in supporting your child's development?<p>
	7.	Are the activities that you have seen at the centre that you do at home?
If so, what?<p>
	8.	Have you created any of your own activities for your child?  If so, what?<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Parent Activities<p>
<p>
	1. 	Why do you come to the centre?<p>
	2. 	What kinds of activities do you do at the centre?<p>
			how often?<p>
			how much time do you give? <p>
	3.	How many parents usually come?   fathers?  mothers?<p>
	4.	How do you decide what you will do? <p>
	5.	Are you able to be involved in all the activities you would like to at the
centre?  If not, why not?<p>
	6. 	Is your spouse also involved? If not why?<p>
	<p>
Parent/Teacher interaction<p>
<p>
	1. 	How often do you meet with the teacher?<p>
	2. 	What information do you get from the teacher about your child?<p>
	3. 	What other information do you get from the teacher?<p>
	<p>
Structure<p>
<p>
	1.	Are the centre hours for your child appropriate?<p>
	2. 	What does your child do after school?<p>
		 If they go elsewhere, what does it cost?<p>
	3.  	 Does this work for you?  <p>
			If no, why not?<p>
Costs<p>
	<p>
	1.	What does it cost to send your child to this centre?<p>
		fees, uniform, registration fee, materials, others<p>
	2. 	How much more do you think you could pay?  $20?  30?  etc. <p>
	3. 	In what ways does the community provide support to the centre?)<p>
		(e.g.  financial, in-kind, maintenance of facilities)<p>
<p>
Get list of the things parents do within the programme from the teacher. <p>
	<p>
<p>
6. Costs/financing<p>
<p>
Before any government can invest in ECD programmes it has to have a clear
understanding of the costs involved.  Thus a cost analysis needs to be done in
relation to each of the models being reviewed.<p>
<p>
<p>
METHODOLOGY<p>
<p>
Collect information from government departments in terms of the costs of
operating their programme.  Costs include:<p>
<p>
	- facilities<p>
	- materials<p>
	- teacher salaries/benefits<p>
	- support staff (cooks,cleaners)	<p>
	- food<p>
	- maintenance<p>
	<p>
Infrastructure costs<p>
<p>
	- training<p>
	- supervision<p>
	- management<p>
<p>
	2.  How are the costs covered?  <p>
<p>
	- government expenditure<p>
	- parental fees<p>
	- community contribution (in-kind services)<p>
<p>
<p>
*  *  *  *  *  *  *<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
TIMELINE for Review<p>
<p>
