<b>I   INTRODUCTION</b><p>
<p>
<p>
	The main purpose of this paper is to stimulate informed discussion and debate
about preschool policy and programming in Mexico with the intention of
improving the care and development and preparation for school of children
during their immediate pre-school years.<b>[1]</b>
The paper will take as its base for looking ahead Mexican program experience
since approximately 1970, with special attention to the most recent years and
to 1993/4.  It will take a broad view of "pre-schools" (institutionalized
settings that provide and facilitate learning in the years prior to entering
school) that goes beyond the formal pre-school system, incorporating
information about complementary initiatives lying outside public preschool
education.<p>
<p>
	Information for the paper was gathered in several ways:<p>
<p>
 Descriptive information was sought from official governmental sources<p>
<p>
 Within the restrictive time limits set for the review, relevant literature was
located and consulted.<p>
<p>
 Interviews were obtained with people involved directly in planning or
implementing preschool programs.<p>
<p>
 A reanalysis was carried out of preschool information obtained during an
evaluation of the Programa de Abatir el Rezago Educativo.<p>
<p>
 Two case studies of preschools were carried out in the Alta Mixteca of Oaxaca
and several other preschools were visited in order to get a qualitative flavor
of preschooling in operation.<p>
<p>
	After setting the stage with a brief description of the context within which
the analysis must proceed, the recent evolution, present status, and costs of
preschool programs will be presented, followed by a section identifying and
discussion key issues for policy and programming.  In a final section,
conclusions will be drawn and recommendations made.<p>
<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>The Changing Context</b><p>
<p>
	<b>Demographic changes</b>.  Mexico was and is a predominantly young country
in spite of a  reduction in its fertility rate (from 3.2% in 1970 to 2.6% in
1990).  Approximately one-quarter of the more than 90 million inhabitants of
Mexico are under age 10, with about 13% under age 6, a percentage that is now
declining slightly.  The Mexican population is mobile as well as young.
Rural-urban migration has increased markedly during the last 15 years.  In
addition, there has been a relatively high level of temporary migration from
Mexico to the United States and to selected agricultural areas within Mexico in
search of employment.  Ironically, while urbanization has increased, the number
of small communities with less than 500 inhabitants has risen from 82,705
communities in 1970 to 140,551 in 1990.  These simple demographics affect
pre-school policy and programming in several ways:  1) although falling
fertility rates mean that less energy must be put into expansion in order to
simply keep pace with population growth, the sheer size still places
considerable pressure on social services;  2) rural-urban migration has created
new needs in urban areas even while major gaps in coverage of programs continue
to appear in rural areas, including in small communities; 3)  temporary
migration for work has often disrupted or split families and has prejudiced
many children left behind while creating a challenge with respect to care and
development of those young children who accompany their migrating parents.<p>
<p>
	<b>Economic changes.</b>  A combination of worldwide recession and of debts
accumulated by Mexico led to a major policy of economic adjustment during the
1980's.  Economic hardships, inflation and the adjustment policy reduced
purchasing power, increased unemployment and had particularly severe short term
economic effects, increasing the number of people living in poverty and in
extreme poverty.   The economic adjustment policy was accompanied by a drop in
social and educational investment, relative to Gross National Product.<b>[2]</b>  Following a renegotiation of the debt, a
major shift to privatization, the negotiation of an internal agreement among
government, labor and industry, and an opening to world markets, the economy of
Mexico began to recover during the 1990 to 1994 period.  Inflation was
controlled and the purchasing power of workers began to rise, falling well
short, however, of their 1980 levels.  Moreover, immense economic disparities
continued to characterize with an unacceptably high proportion of the
population living in conditions of extreme poverty.  Unfortunately, the
recovery proved short-lived as Mexico suffered a major economic setback at the
end of 1994.  A serious commercial deficit and capital flight forced
devaluation which, in turn, has again adversely affected employment and
purchasing power, particularly among the poor.  Whether or not the prodigious
efforts by the present government to bail out the economy with massive
international help will be successful, and at what level, remains to be seen.
An inflation rate of 42% and a negative growth rate of approximately 5% are
projected for 1995.  In the meantime, the recovery policy implies, again, a
worsening income distribution.<p>
<p>
	The present discussion of pre-school policy must take into account both
current pressures to decrease government expenditures and the continuing
pressures on the poor sectors of society that are a product of difficult
economic times.  Although an effort is being made to preserve the education
budget, it is not realistic to expect new or increased funding.  The high level
of poverty makes it difficult to expect poor families to increase their
contributions to support the education of their children.  The high poverty
level also magnifies the effects of out-of-school variables (malnutrition, the
need for young children to work, migration) on pre-school as well as on school
progress and performance.<p>
<p>
	<b>Social and political changes</b>.  After almost 7 decades of one-party
government, the political situation was modified at the end of the 1980 decade
as other political parties and the civil society have emerged as important
political forces.  Opposition included armed opposition in Chiapas,
representing at once an unsettling eruption of pent-up social and economic
frustrations and a challenge for a government anxious to both maintain
stability and build a new image.  The case of Chiapas, the poorest state in
Mexico on almost any indicator chosen, highlights the importance of taking into
account vast differences among (and within) states as well as the importance of
issues related to ethnic origin.  The recognition of and respect for cultural
differences continues to be a central issue within a social and political
policy agenda that seeks justice and democracy.  And, the political turmoil
that frames the current study seems to give a different tone to the phrase
"participation."  It accelerates the search for democratic structures and
solutions allowing civic organizations as well as the government to play
important roles in the political and social life of the country.<p>
<p>
	<b>Educational changes.</b>   A process of decentralization, begun in 1978,
was given new life in 1992 with the transfer to the states of administrative
responsibility for educational programs.  This complex and prolonged process
has had to contend with existing economic and educational inequalities among
states, educational zones, municipalities and localities.  For the time being
at least, financing of education and influence over the norms and content of
education have continued to function in a centralized way.  Several
"compensatory" programs, including those educational programs administered by
the National Council for Educational Promotion (CONAFE) and those that appear
under Solidaridad, continue to be controlled directly from the center.   A
discussion of pre-school education must take into account the tension between
the decentralized administration and centralized control over the collection of
finances as well as over norms.  The discussion must recognize at the same time
the growing pressure for popular participation in education and the barriers to
such participation that are a product of continuing economic and political
inequalities.  Accordingly, it will be important to try and look outside as
well as inside the present educational options and structures for new solutions
and forms of participation if, as proposed in the National Agreement for
Educational Modernization (1992) and in the National Plan for 1995-2000, there
is to be greater participation by parents and the community in general in
educational activities, including their participation in decision-making and
implementation.<p>
<p>
	<b>The National Plan of Development , 1995-2000.</b>  Against this background,
the present government has prepared a 5-year development plan organized around
five basic objectives.  These are: 1) strengthening national sovereignty; 2)
consolidating citizens rights and rule by law; 3) constructing a complete
democracy with social participation; 4) extending and sustaining social
development, and 5) fostering economic growth.<p>
<p>
	In the National Plan, a social strategy is proposed that is to be "national,
integral, federal and participatory, inclusive and effective" (National Plan,
p. xii).  Combatting inequality is central to the Plan and a mutual
relationship is recognized among social, political and economic inequality.
Accordingly, the social development program is focussed on "eradication of
poverty, giving privileged attention to groups, communities and geographic
zones that are at the greatest social and economic disadvantages" (ibid., p.
xiii) and on "...families in conditions of extreme poverty, on marginal
populations, on indigenous communities and on groups at a disadvantage in
integrating themselves into the process of development" (ibid., p. 74).
Moreover, the social policy proposed in the plan anticipates a new national
effort that would not only promote concurrent efforts by municipal, state and
federal entities, but would also seek the participation of non-governmental
organizations, public assistance institutions and organizations of
beneficiaries as "co-responsibles" in the developmental process.<p>
<p>
	The five general strategies that organize the social policy presented in the
Plan are: 1) increase coverage and improve the quality of basic services; 2) an
integrated approach to population growth and distribution; 3) promote equality
in development among regions; 4) give privileged attention to populations with
the greatest economic and social disadvantages; and 5) approach social
development in an integrated manner implying co-responsibility of the State and
the society.  As part of an effort to guarantee all children and youth a basic
education that is free, secular, democratic, nationalistic and based on
scientific knowledge, the Plan proposes "...to design and apply programs and
actions that guarantee access at the preschool, primary school and secondary
school levels, increasing substantially the "terminal efficiency" in all of
basic education, and reducing disparities in coverage and quality within public
education" (ibid., p. 85).  Increased attention is to be given to acquisition
of the basic capacities of reading, oral and written expression and
mathematics.  The Plan proposes improvements in the contents, methods and
materials of basic education, the development of initiatives and projects
originating in schools, the revaluating of supervision and school
administration, continued attention to improving the infrastructure, timely
evaluations of the educational system, integration of educational activities
with other social sector programs, the consolidation of federal and local
participation in education, and the establishment of a national system of
training and professional improvements for teachers.   <p>
<p>
	The social policy makes special mention of the need for programs that can
reach the poor in rural areas where the population is dispersed population (p.
114) and that are directed toward indigenous communities (pp. 117-18).  With
respect to indigenous communities, the Plan seeks:  "...to achieve full
integration of ethnic groups into the process of national development without
having to renounce their rich cultural history, their language or their
traditions (p. 117)." <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>	The Condition of Pre-School Children</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>	Any discussion of preschool education must take into account the
condition of the children to be served.  That condition is reported in Table 1,
based on the State of the World's Children published by UNICEF and on official
statistics taken from the October 1994 "Fourth Evaluation" of the National
Program of Action set out by Mexico in relation to its signing of the
Convention on the Rights of the Child and its participation in the Children's
Summit  (Secretar&iacute;a de Salud 1994).  The table does not try to describe
differences among the various federal entities which, in some cases are very
significant.  For example, in Chiapas, "terminal efficiency" for primary school
is estimated at 34% vs. a national figure of 61% and the failure rate in
primary school is reported at 13% in Chiapas vs. 8% nationally. <p>
