<p>
<b>II -- PRESCHOOL EDUCATION IN MEXICO, 1995</b><p>
<p>
	<p>
<b>The Legal Basis for Pre-School Education in Mexico</b>  <p>
<p>
	Article 3 of the Mexican Constitution provides the right to an education and
indicates that the State has the responsibility for providing basic education.
Basic education includes pre-schooling as well as primary  and secondary
schooling.  The Constitution also mentions (Apartado "A", Fracci&oacute;n XXIX)
that child care centers are a benefit of great public utility and their
provision corresponds to the Social Security system.  <p>
<p>
	The most recent interpretation of the right to education is contained in the
General Law of Education promulgated in 1993  Although the General Law
recognizes the importance of preschooling for children by indicating that
parents have a right to enroll their children in preschool (Part I of Article
59),  Article 37 of the law states explicitly that "Preschool education is not
a pre-requisite for primary school."  (Programa para la Modernizaci&oacute;n
Educativa, 1989-1994).   Moreover, legislation pertaining explicitly to the
preschool level is almost absent from the General Law which, rather,
incorporates preschool into basic education.  It is assumed, therefore, that
legal provisions set for Basic Education will apply to preschooling.  For
instance, Articles 38 and 42 of the General Law state, respectively:<p>
<p>
Article 38. Basic Education, in its three levels, should include the
adaptations required in order to respond to the cultural and linguistic
characteristics of each of the diverse indigenous groups in the country as well
as to dispersed populations and migratory groups.<p>
<p>
Article 42.  In imparting education for minors, methods will be used to assure
that the protection and necessary care needed to preserve physical,
psychological and social integrity based on dignity and the application of
discipline will be compatible with a student's age.<p>
<p>
Article 59 is somewhat more specific, stating that those institutions that
impart preschool education should contract accredited personnel with an
adequate preparation.  Moreover, the article says the "...installations should
satisfy hygienic, pedagogic and security conditions that the educational
authorities determine..."  One assumes that these conditions are meant to apply
to public as well as private preschools.<p>
<p>
	Also relevant to preschooling in its broad sense is the legal base for the
support of Child Development Centers (CENDIs) that is found in Article 123 of
the Constitution.  This care, which includes care and education for children
ages 4 and 5, is mandated as a right for working mothers and is applied, in the
main, to workers in the governmental sector.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Preschool Programs :  Present Variations on the Theme</b><p>
<p>
	There are several ways in which preschools can be classified, including: by
the population served, by their organization and pedagogical methods, by their
administrative jurisdiction, or be combinations of these.  The discussion that
follows will be divided into two parts according to whether the preschool forms
are supported and administered through the public sector or whether the
preschools are private or social initiatives that do not depend financially or
administratively on the government..<p>
<p>
	<b>Preschools in the Public Sector</b><p>
<p>
	In its presentation of educational statistics, the SEP recognizes three main
forms of preschooling managed within the education sector: 1) General
preschools (previously referred to as Jardines de Ni&ntilde;os), 2) Bi-lingual,
or Indigenous preschools, and 3) Community preschools.  As shown in Table 2
(with further information provided in Appendix A), these preschool programs are
different in terms of the populations they serve, their coverage, their locus
of administrative control, the their hours of operation and norms governing
such matters as the number of students required to establish a preschool and
the qualifications required to be a teacher.   These three general categories
are commonly used for programming purposes within the education sector (see,
for instance, SEP, July 1994, "Strategies for generalizing basic education").<p>
<p>
	There are variations within the three general categories of public education.
For instance, General preschools are administered nationally in the case of the
Federal District but  in other cases are administered at the State level.  In
addition, two "alternative" programs are hidden within the general preschool
statistics, one of which is similar to the community preschools of CONAFE
programs (because it relies on secondary school graduates or community women
trained as "promotoras" and takes a non-formal approach).  The other
alternative program is an urban program called the "Mixed" preschool that
extends the operation of general preschools to a full day, involving community
mothers as well as regular preschool teachers.  <p>
<p>
	Community preschools run by CONAFE include four main variants.  In addition to
the most prominent program, which is labeled the Community Preschool, CONAFE
also runs a small program in which community mothers become the teachers
(Centros Infantiles Comunitarias) and with childcare linked to productive
projects for women, an experimental preschool program for migrant children, and
a program attending to indigenous children.<p>
 .<p>
<p>
	The educational statistics of the SEP also include information about Centers
for Integrated Development (CENDI), a preschool/child care option that is
intended to provide attention to children between the ages of 42 days and 5
years, 11 months, of working mothers.  This child care modality is subject to
educational norms set by the SEP.  CENDIs may be run at a national (now only
those in the D.F.) or state level.   In addition, some CENDIs are run on a
private basis.<p>
<p>
	Not falling into any of these categories, nor reported in the preschool
statistics is another small public childcare program called "Day Care Homes."
This program, which also includes attention to children ages 3 to 5, was run by
the a national system of volunteers, headed by the President's wife, but has
now being taken over by the Family Institute (DIF):<p>
   <p>
********<p>
<p>
	Although public preschool programs are administered by different entities
within the government and are run by people with different levels of training
and experience, the specific objectives of the different preschool modalities
are more or less similar.  In addition, the fact that programs are supposed to
follow norms set by the Ministry of Education, means that the curricula overlap
a great deal, and even the methods applied show similarities.  In 1992/3, a new
preschool program was put in place involving a major reorganization of content.
This program has been adapted by Indigenous preshool education for work in
indigenous communities.<p>
<p>
	In general, preschool education is described as child centered, active
(children are expected to take an active part in the process, constructing
their ow knowledge), integral (in the sense of including attention to
cognitive, social, emotional and physical development) and directed toward
building personal and social autonomy, a critical capacity, creativity,
language skills, identification with both nation and local cultures, and a
healthier relationship with the environment.  The methodology is built around
the experience of the child, usually organized around a "project" or "theme"
which children are expected to help choose and which is used to organize and
link activities.  Preschool teachers are expected to act as coordinators and
promotors of learning situations, assisting the child to construct his or her
own knowledge.  Explicitly teaching children to read and write and cipher in
preschool falls outside the norms, but children are expected to acquire basic
concepts and skills that will help them with these tasks when they enter
primary school.<p>
<p>
	In the case of indigenous preschools, the expectation is that children will be
taught in their mother tongue and that the activities will be closely related
to the particular indigenous culture (SEP, Programa de Educaci&oacute;n
Preescolar para zonas Ind&iacute;genas, 1994).  Experience and observation
suggests that these stipulations are frequently disregarded in practice so that
it may be difficult to distinguish a "general" from an "indigenous" classroom
(see case study 2 in Appendix E).  The PAEPI program, run by CONAFE, seeks to
develop bilingualism and recommends the use of Spanish and the indigenous
language according to the degree to which both languages are used in the
community.<p>
<p>
	The obvious differences among the different public sector programs tend to be
more organizational or structural than methodological or in content.  Norms
differ with respect to the minimum number of children required for a preschool
to be set up (a minimum of 5 in the case of CONAFE's community preschools  vs.
18 for indigenous preschools vs. 25 for general preschools).  Thus, community
preschools or the alternative preschool program must serve very small
communities and general preschool education is reserved for larger ones.  Hours
differ.  In <p>
<pre>
