</pre>
the case of the CENDIs and the "mixed preschool service," children are present
during a full day rather than during a 3 or 4-hour period in the morning which
characterizes most programs.  Programs also differ in the extent to which
health and nutrition are directly incorporated in the programs.  Only the CENDI
programs provide health attention on the premises.  The full-day CENDIs and the
Mixta programs provide food whereas other programs depend on the children to
bring their own snacks.<p>
<p>
	The backgrounds and training of teachers also differ considerably among the
programs:  <p>
<p>
   -  General preschool teachers are supposed to be at least normal school
graduates with training in preschool education.  Presumably they arrive on the
job as trained teachers.<p>
<p>
   -  Indigenous preschool teachers are also supposed to enter service with a
minimum qualification of a secondary schooling certificate, but with the
understanding that they will upgrade themselves in the coming years by taking
courses provided by the National Pedagogical University or a normal school.
Bi-lingual teachers must also speak an indigenous language.  The initial
training for bi-lingual teachers has varied from 2 months to 6 months,
depending in part on the budget available for such training.  The official
supervision they receive during the year is minimal.<p>
<p>
   -  Community Instructors in the CONAFE program, on the other hand, are young
people between the ages of 15 and 21 who have completed secondary school (9
years of schooling).  These youth are provided with a 2-month initial training
program and are assisted during the year by a supervisor who also meets monthly
with the group to continue the training and to handle problems that may have
been encountered.<p>
<p>
   -  The Alternative Preschool Program for Rural Areas operates on principles
similar to that of CONAFE and has two variants.  In one variant, the education
agents are community members, usually with a secondary school degree, who have
successfully completed an initial training of two months.  The second variant
takes youth who have completed a bachillerato who must also pass through a
2-month training.  The initial training is backed by a relatively intensive
system of continued orientation in which trainer/supervisors are responsible
for preschools in a limited number of communities (in Oaxaca, for instance the
number was between 7 and 12 communities, depending on the time necessary to
reach the communities).<p>
 <p>
	It is not clear what the effect of these differences is on the development of
children because we do not have studies that make the comparison, for instance,
between normalistas with three years of preschool training and secondary school
graduates with a minimum of training.  Further, we do not know what differences
may be attributed to the fact that the CONAFE program, by recruiting young
people, incorporates more young men as teachers than do other programs.<p>
<p>
	The level of financial and other support for teachers in the different
programs also varies.<p>
   -  General preschool teachers enter the regular pay scale and receive social
security and retirement benefits.  Pay hovers around three or four minimum
salaries.<p>
<p>
   -  The bilingual teachers also enter the preschool pay scale and receive
benefits as well as a salary.  In general, the pay they receive is only
somewhat lower than general preschool teachers, reflecting the difference in
academic qualifications..<p>
<p>
   -  CONAFE Community Instructors  are provided with a very low maintenance
stipend (less than a minimum salary) during the year they teach and are paid
also to return for training one day of each month.  They are provided with
lodging and food by the community in which they work.  They are also assured
support to study for three years afterward to complete their preparatory school
studies. <p>
<p>
   -  The promoters or bachilleres in the Rural Alternative programs receive
stipends similar to those of the CONAFE Instructors and are provided with
access to study at the next level of education.  They are also provided with
food and lodging by the communities in which they work.<p>
<p>
From this brief description, it is clear that the per child costs to the State
of formal (general and indigenous) preschooling will be much higher than the
costs of non-formal (Cursos comunitarios and the alternative rural modalities)
preschooling.  Again, we do not know how these differences relate to effects on
the preschool child.<p>
<p>
<p>
	<b>Private and Social Sector Preschool Initiatives</b><p>
<p>
	To obtain a fuller picture of the preschool scene in Mexico, preschool
initiatives should be included which lie outside the Public Sector.  This
includes private sector initiatives in which preschools are run by industries
or are set up as "for profit" private preschools or as CENDIs.  They include
social sector initiatives in which preschools are set up and run by NGOs, by
church groups or by community organizations.  And finally, they include
experiments associated with universities or other research settings.  Examples
of programs within each of these categories are described in Appendix A.<p>
<p>
	Unfortunately, very little information is available about preschool programs
that are operated outside the public sector.  The official statistics tell us
that in 1993/4  some 251,958 children were enrolled in private preschools,
accounting for 8.4% of the total preschool enrollment.  Of these, 10,441
children were in privately run CENDIs and the rest were in general preschools.
This number for the private sector is probably an underestimate; an unknown
number of unregistered private preschools exist.<b>[3]</b>  Because pre-school is not a requirement for
entrance into primary school at this point in time, there has not been much
attention paid to assuring that private preschools are registered, provide
statistics to the SEP or operate in an adequate manner.  Should preschooling
for 5-year olds become mandatory, this situation will have to change.  The lack
of information about these programs extends to the training of the educational
agents and the quality of their offerings.<p>
<p>
	Nevertheless, some general comments about preschooling outside the public
sector can be made, based on general conversations.  For instance:<p>
<p>
   -   It seems that only rarely are preschools set up in relation to a
business enterprise; rather, preschool needs of  workers children are seen as
being satisfied through the CENDIs.<p>
<p>
   -   Rarely are private preschools found in a rural setting.<p>
<p>
   -   Usually preschools are set up to respond to one of two demands that it
is felt are not being met by public programs: quality or the need for
flexibility associated with alternative child care.   Private preschools often
advertise themselves as providing quality attention to children based on the
academic qualifications of their teachers, the available of an excellent
facility and materials, and/ or their link to a particular curriculum that is
not the same as that of the SEP, such as, for instance, the Montessori method
or the High/Scope Cognitive curriculum.  In most cases, these private schools
charge substantial fees that restrict attention to children of the middle and
upper classes.  There are, however, many examples of popular and
community-based preschools that are of good quality  but cater to families with
few resources and do not (cannot) charge large sums (see examples of Cerro de
Judio and Nezahuapilli in Appendix A).  In these cases it is not unusual for
the popular preschool program to count, at least initially, on the outside help
of a non-governmental organization providing training, technical advice and
even some financial support.  As a result, a cadre of trained (but uncertified)
preschool teachers has grown up outside the official system.  These teachers
usually receive less than a minimum wage and do not receive benefits.
Sometimes they are forced to leave their positions in order to earn a living
wage elsewhere.  As the government looks ahead, it might ask how, at relatively
little cost, it might provide support to help sustain and expand such community
programs, in line with its desire to extend coverage to marginal groups at a
time of extreme budget pressures. <p>
<p>
	A second reason private preschools open is to provide <b>flexibility</b> and
convenience associated with the need for <b>alternative child care</b>.  The
half-day schedule of general preschools is not intended to meet child care
needs of families in which both parents must work or where a single mother
works outside the home, where hiring help in the home is not an option.  It
does not serve well many parents employed in the informal sector (which now
accounts for about 40% of the labor force) who cannot count on extended family
for care, and who are not eligible to put their children in a CENDI (where in
any event the number of places is very limited in relation to the demand).
General preschools were not designed taking into account the increasing
participation of women in remunerated activities, now estimated at 34% or
higher.<b>[4]</b>  The Jardines Mixta program of the
SEP which begins to respond to this need by  extending normal preschool hours
into the afternoon, combining child care and preschool education, began only
recently, requires at least 60 children to organize a program, and is still
limited in coverage.  The government faces a challenge as the need to combine
preschooling and childcare grows apace.<p>
<p>
	<b>Because so little information is available about non-public preschools, a
logical procedure would be to create a systematic profile of the complementary
efforts being carried out by the private and social sectors.</b>  This seems
particularly important given the call in the National Plan for a national
alliance and for "co-responsibility" in programming to meet social needs.  <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>III  AN EVOLVING PROFILE OF PRESCHOOLING, 1970-71 TO 1993/94</b><p>
<p>
<p>
	Defining and tracking a profile of preschool education is Mexico is not easy
for several reasons.  First the models and administrative forms of providing
preschool education change from time to time.  Changes of  government,
decentralization, and a special program of educational modernization in recent
years have been accompanied by shifts in attention that influence statistical
series.  Second, a complete picture of preschool education involves collecting
information about programs that are handled by the Secretar&iacute;a de
Educaci&oacute;n P&uacute;blica (SEP), other governmental entities and the
private sector.  Some information about programs other than those run by the
SEP are included in the presentation of information by the SEP, but not all
extra-SEP programs are included and most of the analyses that have been made
refer to programs of the SEP.  The omissions are particularly clear with
respect to private educational initiatives, but also occur with respect to
lesser government-associated  programs as well.<b>[5]</b>  Third, the basis for categorizing preschool
programs in the statistics is based on administrative responsibility and not on
the model of preschool education being used.  Therefore, "non-formal" models
may be hidden within the statistics, requiring a special effort to pull them
out.  The official statistics, for instance, do not include information about
the rural or urban alternative preschool programs which fall under the general
preschool education department.  Nor do they include information about the
newer initiatives within the Consejo Nacional de Fomento Educativo (CONAFE).
Fourth, descriptions vary somewhat depending on whether one uses enrollment
figures at the beginning of the year vs. end-of-year figures.  Fifth, the
statistics themselves are sometimes inconsistent or difficult to interpret (in
appendix A more specific comments are provided on sources and problems
encountered in working with existing statistics).<p>
<p>
	In lieu of these problems it is well for the reader to take the following
descriptions and analyses as reasonable approximations of the preschool
situation in Mexico rather than as definitive descriptions.  It is our
impression that general orders of magnitude and the trends identified would
hold up even if greater precision were introduced into the statistics.  The
following analysis of enrollment, groups, teachers and schools is based on a
historical series provided by the Direcci&oacute;n de An&aacute;lisis y
Sistemas de Informaci&oacute;n within the Planning and Programming Department
of the SEP.  The figures reflect enrollments at the beginning of the school
year.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Enrolment/children</b><p>
<p>
	Table 3 presents information about enrollments (as counted at the beginning of
the school year) for the period from the school year 1970/71 to 1993/94.  From
the table we see that:<p>
<p>
	1.  <b>Total Enrolment in preschools has increased steadily,</b> with growth
registered in every year from 1970/1 to 1993/4, except 1989/90 when for all
intents and purposes there was no growth.   It would not be an exaggeration to
say that preschool education has grown dramatically over the last 25 years
during which time the total enrolment increased more than seven-fold.  However,
most of this growth occurred during the 10 years from 1975 to 1985 when
enrolment increased five-fold.<p>
<p>
	2.  <b>There are marked variations by year and sexenio.</b>  The rate of
growth in enrolment has varied markedly from sexenio to sexenio and sometimes
from year to year.  At one extreme is the minor drop of 0.2% that occurred
between 1989 and 1990; at the other, total enrolment increased at a rate of
28.4% between 1979 and 1980.   The differences by sexenio are:<p>
<pre>
			      Average	    Highest growth		Total growth
   Sexenio		growth per year	    rate in one year		 each sexenio


1970/1 - 1975/6	         7%		      7.8% (75-76)		        34%
1976/7 - 1981/2	        21%		     28.4% (80-81)		       126%
1982/3 - 1987/8	         9%		     13.0% (83-84)		         55%
1988/9 - 1993/4	         2%		      4.2% (92-93)		         12%
</pre>
<b>Table 3</b><p>
<b></b><p>
	<b>From the above it is clear that the increase in enrolment leveled out
during the most recent sexenio. </b>  This is particularly so for the growth in
enrollments for children in the third level (usually children age 5) where
almost no growth occurred during the sexenio.  When we take into account that,
until 1993/4 the number of children entering preschool age was continuing to
increase slightly (but since 1993/4 is declining), the growth rate during the
previous sexenio barely covers that growth.<p>
	<p>
	3.  <b>There are variations by preschool level.</b>  Enrolment growth spurts
have occurred at a different pace for the different levels within preschooling.
Enrollments for the first level (mostly children age 3) lag well behind
children in the third level (mostly age 5).  Enrollment in the first level has
grown only about a third as fast as enrollment in the third level over the 1970
- 1993 period.  Accordingly, during 1993/4, only 17% of all preschool children
were in the first level or 
grade whereas 53% were in the third grade.<p>
<p>
	<b>1979-81.</b>  As shown in Table 3, enrollments in the first level of
preschool decreased markedly in the period from 1979 to 1981.  This decrease
was caused by a decision to emphasize attention to children aged four and five
at that time.  As a result of this policy, enrolment in the first level of
preschool increased by only .6% during the 1976-82 sexenio at the same time
that enrollment in the second and third levels increased by 97% and 217%,
respectively.   <p>
<p>
	4.  <b>Variations by state.</b>   An enormous variation in growth rates at the
state level appears in the rates of growth in enrollment at the state level.
Table 4 consolidates state-level information by sexenio.  From Table 4 we see,
for instance, that whereas enrolment in the Federal District grew by 146% over
the entire period and enrollments actually decreased by 2.5% from 1990 to
1993), Chiapas enrollment grew 2075% and enrollments grew by 28% in the 1990-93
period.<p>
<p>
	Perhaps the most significant conclusion to be drawn from an examination of the
state-level data is that <b>poorer states, for the most part, have grown faster
than richer states during the period.  This suggests that some redistribution
of public funds is occurring and that important efforts have been made to help
lagging states to catch up.</b><p>
<p>
<p>
  <b>Groups, Teachers and Schools</b><p>
<p>
	<b>Groups</b>.  As is evident from a comparison of Tables 5 and 3, the
creation of new groups of children has occurred at a greater rate than the rate
of increase in enrolment.  This has allowed the average number of children per
group to drop from 37.5 in 1970 to 19.5 in 1993.  The average figure hides
considerable variation from group to group but indicates that for many, the
size of the group has been reduced significantly over time.<p>
<p>
	<b>Teachers.</b>  The rate of growth in the number of teachers has also been
greater than that of enrolment, beginning in 1976, so that, from 1976 to the
1993, the average number of students per preschool teacher has dropped from
38.1 to 24.5.  <p>
		Table 4.-- Percentage Changes in Preschool Enrollments, by State and
Sexenio,<p>
1970/71 - 1993/94
<pre>
=====================================================================
		       1970/71	        1976/77		1982/83	   1988/89	   Total
		       1975/76	        1981/82		1987/88	   1993/94	   Growth
____________________________________________________________________________

Fed.  Republic          34.2		126.3		    55.2	       11.6	    644.7

Aguascalientes          39.7		 90.0		    75.0	       14.2	    536.8
Baja California         48.7		117.3		    44.0	       20.2	    567.9
Baja California,S.      48.8		 70.5		    15.0	       13.3	    269.5
Campeche	        23.7		220.3		    46.9	       23.2	    948.2
Coahuila	        20.1		161.5		    45.9	       12.0	    717.3
Colima	                26.1		 44.1		    49.9	         9.6	    383.8
Chiapas	                81.9		293.7		    65.3	       36.7	  2074.8
Chihuahua	        17.0		105.8		    48.0	       15.2	    470.0
Distrito Federal        18.0		 37.8		    27.5	         2.7	    146.6
Durango	                19.1		360.3		    18.8	       10.7	  1224.0
Guanajuato	        43.4		611.4		    79.6	       21.6	  3668.6
Guerrero	        65.0		 73.5		    65.9	         9.7	    669.3
Hidalgo	                26.7		222.5		    33.3	       11.1	    799.5
Jalisco		        43.8		244.8		    72.1	         6.6	  1084.7
Estado de M&eacute;xico        49.8		110.7		   103.4	       12.7	    834.5
Michoac&aacute;n               24.2		185.2		    84.4		        8.7	    931.6
Morelos	                27.3		 23.9		    25.7		        4.4	    176.4
Nayarit	                36.8		 83.0		    51.3	 	        9.4	    464.7
Nuevo Leon	        59.9		122.6		    42.7		       11.1	    619.1
Oaxaca	                33.1		807.7		    59.5		        9.7	 2177.4 Puebla		        55.3
