Quintana Roo	       111.1		151.6		    83.9		      39.5	 1979.2
San Luis Potosi         91.6		261.5		    76.9		        7.8	 2076.4
Sinaloa	                42.0		188.8		    13.4		      11.0	   782.4
Sonora	                28.2		160.7		    54.1  	        8.0	   842.1
Tabasco	                75.7		227.8		   107.7		      10.2	 2431.3
Tamaulipas	        13.7		107.9		    35.7		        6.7	   879.6
Tlaxcala	        25.3		 53.8		    54.7		        2.1	   426.7
Veracruz	        27.4		109.5		    65.9		      11.7	   662.1
Yucatan	                52.3		262.6		    37.7		      19.1	 1026.1
Zacatecas	        78.6		 93.0		    64.0		      12.9	 1222.2
____________________________________________________________________________
</pre>
Source: Ibid.<p>
	Table 5<p>
<p>
	<b>Schools.</b>   The number of preschools has increased 16-fold over the
period since 1970 and the average size of schools has dropped from 130 children
to 58 children.  This reflects the increasing reach of preschool into rural
areas.<p>
<p>
 Growth Rates, by Sexenio:	Enrolment, Groups, Teachers and Schools<p>
<pre>
	      Sexenio			Enrolment	  Groups	Teachers	Schools

	1970/71 - 1975/76		      34%	     42%	    34%	     35%
	1976/77 - 1981/82		     126%	    156%	   170%	    276%
	1982/83 - 1987/88		      55%	     92%	    75%	     78%
	1988/89 - 1993/94		      12%	     31%	    26%	     28%
</pre>
	Looking at the rates of growth for groups, teachers and schools by year and
sexenio, similar variations and patterns to those described for enrolment are
found.  Growth is concentra-ted in the ten-year period from 1975 to 1985.
However, during the most recent sexenio, the average number of students per
group, teacher and school has continued to decrease in spite of the fact that
enrollments have leveled out.<p>
<p>
	 <b>In theory, the trends described in Table 5 should signal an important
improvement in the quality of preschools.  However, the following should be
kept in  mind:</b><p>
<p>
	1.  An average number of 25 children per teacher for the preschool years is
still high and may not yet permit major qualitative effects to appear.<p>
<p>
	2.  The reductions represent continued efforts to establish schools in rural
areas where the concentration of children is not as great.   We do not know
whether these rural schools have achieved a reasonable level of quality or not,
given the additional difficulties associated with serving a rural population.<p>
<p>
	3.  The continued growth of teachers and the change in numbers represent in
part a response to union pressures for better working conditions that may or
may not translate into changed performance in the preschool.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>An Analysis of Enrollments and Operational indicators, 1993/94</b><p>
<p>
	In order to obtain a picture of the current state of preschool education and
of its more recent development, an analysis is presented of the figures for
1993/94.  Tables supporting this analysis are found in Appendix C.  To make the
analysis more manageable, data are presented for the Federal Republic, for the
five states with the highest enrolment and the five states with the lowest
enrolment.  From these tables we can see the following:<p>
<p>
	1.  <b>Enrollment, by grade level</b> (Appendix C, Table 1).  At the national
level, 52.3% of all preschool children are enrolled in grade 3, with 31.6%
found in grade 2 and 16.1% in grade 1.  This pattern holds for most of the
states, with a major exception found in Veracruz where 53.5% are found in the
first level.<p>
<p>
	2.  <b>Enrollment, by "type" of preschool</b> (Appendix C, Table 2).  General
preschools account for 88.2% of all preschool enrollment and indigenous
preschools for 8.3%  Cursos Comunitarios and CENDIs account for 1.9% and 1.6%,
respectively.  This distribution of programs changed very little during the
previous sexenio (Appendix C, Table 3).  There are variations in the
distribution by type of preschool among states.  For instance, in Oaxaca,
indigenous preschools account for 44.1% of all enrollment (as contrasted with
the 8.2% national figure).  In no state do cursos comunitarios account for more
than 4% of total enrollment.  The distribution among programs in the Distrito
Federal is different from other states because it has a much higher percentage
of private enrollment (28.3%) and of CENDI enrollment (5.6%).  In general, the
percentage of enrollment accounted for by the CENDIs is below 2%.<p>
<p>
	3.  <b>Enrollment by Federal/State/Private.</b>  In 1991, the Federal
government was responsible for administering programs enrolling 72% of all
children in preschools (Appendix C, Table 3).  States administered 19% and the
private sector was responsible for 9%.  Following the decentralization in 1992,
all of the general preschools and the CENDIS located outside the Federal
District were transferred to the states.  Responsibility for all indigenous
preschools was also placed in the states.  Thus, in 1993/4, we see a dramatic
shift in the distribution so that the Federal government was now only
responsible directly for 9% (General preschools and CENDIs in the DF, and
Cursos Comunitarios, classified as compensatory programs and therefore kept at
the national level) whereas states administered 83% and the private sector 8%.
 <p>
	<p>
	4.  <b>Enrollment by formal/non-formal.  </b>Only about 4% of the enrollment
classified under General Preschooling is actually enrollment in "Alternative"
preschool programs (see Table 2) which follow a non-formal model but which are
administered by the general preschool department.  If the alternative programs
are put together with the non-formal programs administered by CONAFE, the
percentage of the total is 5.2% from which we can conclude that <b>non-formal
preschool programs account for a very small part of the total preschool
enrollment.</b><p>
<p>
	5.  <b>Correspondence between age and preschool level (grade).</b>  Although
there is some variation, children are more or less in the grade level
corresponding to age.  The data show (Appendix C, Table 4) that 98.1% of the
children age 3 are in the first level; 75% of the children aged 4 are in the
second level, and 89 % of the children aged 5 are in the 3rd level.  An
exception to this pattern appears in Veracruz were only 5% of the children aged
5 are in the third level.  The rest are distributed between the first (25%) and
the second (70%) levels.<p>
<p>
	6.  <b>Rate of "retention."  </b>This rate is calculated by comparing the year
end enrollments with inscription numbers.  This is a very rough comparison at
best because some children leave and others arrive during the year and because
there is migration across states.  With these cautions in mind, the figures
suggest (Appendix C, Table 5), that the rate of completion during the year is
relatively high, according to the statistics, but varies from state to state
with the lowest rates in the D.F.  <p>
.  <p>
	7.  <b>Coverage.</b>   In order to estimate coverage of the preschool system
it is necessary not only  to have a reasonable estimate of enrollment, but also
an estimate of the relevant age group (representing "potential social demand")
that is being served by preschools.   In a number of publications, the relevant
age group for which coverage figures are calculated has been defined as
children age five, and coverage has been calculated by relating the enrollment
of children in the third year of preschool to the estimate of the total
population of children aged 5.   Using this definition of coverage, it is
estimated that coverage grew from 13% in 1977 to 72% in 1990.<b>[6]</b><p>
<p>
	More recently, however, coverage figures have been reported as indicating
coverage for children ages 4 and 5 in the population.  An example is the Fourth
Evaluation of the National Plan in support of children presented in October
1994.  Here, a coverage figure of 75% is reported using figures for 1993/4.
It is not clear how this calculation was made but the figure seems to continue
to represent a comparison of the third level enrollment with estimates of the
children aged 5 in the Mexican population.  According to the population
projections provided by the census bureau, the estimated number of children
aged 5 in 1993 was 2,131,539 and the number aged 4 was 2,256,916.  If the third
level preschool enrollment for 1993 of 1,558,031 is compared with the estimate
for children aged 5, the coverage figure is 73%.  If we compare the total
enrollment in preschools for 1993 (2,980,024) with the sum of the projected
population figures for children aged 4 and 5 (4,388,455), then the coverage
figure would be 68%.  However, the total enrollment includes children ages 3,
as well as ages 6 and 7.  If we take only the enrollments of children in the
second and third levels of preschool (on the assumption that first level
children are mostly aged 3) and compare these enrollment figures (2,499,123)
with the sum of the population projections for children aged 4 and 5
(4,388,455) the coverage figure for children aged 4 and 5 turns out to be 57%,
considerably lower than the 75% reported.  If we compare total preschool
enrollment with the population projections for children ages 3 to 5, the
percentage is even lower: 45%.  <b>In brief, it would seem that the coverage
figures are considerably inflated unless they refer only to children age
5</b>.<p>
      <p>

<a name="fn0">[1]</a>The terms of reference for this
paper are roughly as follows:  a) describe preschool education programs; b)
identify and discuss the major issues pertaining to programs; c) describe the
Government's and NGO/Private sector's preschool education strategies and d)
make recommendations for improvements in the quality, efficiency and access to
preschool education.<p>
<a name="fn1">[2]</a>Later on in the paper we will see that relative reductions
in educational spending did not lead to decreases in the expansion of
pre-school education which ran counter to this general trend.<p>
<a name="fn2">[3]</a>When the topic of private preschools was brought up in
Oaxaca, we were told that only 18 schools were registered for all of Oaxaca and
that only 10 of these had provided statistical information about their
programs.<p>
<a name="fn3">[4]</a>This figure is a 1988 figure and probably understates the
actual participation.  The figure, as well as that for the level of the
informal economic, was taken from: Patricia Hernandez, et al., "Child Care in
Female Street Vendors in Mexico City: Needs and Policy Recommendations,"
Instituto Nacional de Salud P'ublica, Cuernavaca, Mexico, 1994.<p>
<a name="fn4">[5]</a>For instance, the official statistics do not include
children ages 3 to 5 who are participating in the small program of Day Care
Homes (Casas de Cuidado Diario) that was carried out under the auspices of the
El Patronato Nacional de Promotores Voluntarios and is now administered by
DIF.<p>
<a name="fn5">[6]</a>These estimates are reported in:  J. Prawda and G.
Psacharopoulos, "Educational Development and Costing in Mexico, 1977-1990.  A
Cross-state Time-series Analysis,"  <b>International Journal of Educational
Development</b>, Vol 13, No. 1 (1993), p.18.


