<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>NEPAL: FROM ENTRY POINT TO CONSOLIDATION</b> <br>
<p>
<p>
<b>AN ASSESSMENT OF EARLY CHILDHOOD PROVISION IN NEPAL</b><br>
<b>WITH RECOMMENDATIONS FOR</b><br>
<b>UNICEF'S INVOLVEMENT </b><br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b><u>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</u></b><p>
<p>
A three week mission was undertaken in September 1992 to assess the current
standard of early childhood provision in Nepal.  This involved meeting with
governmental and non-governmental agencies to ascertain their interest in and
commitment to implementation of programs for young children.  As a result of
the visit a set of recommendations has been made on how UNICEF might be
involved in upgrading the standard of current provision and enter into
partnership with government, donors and agencies to develop models of early
childhood provision.  <p>
<p>
Conclusions and recommendations in this report were based on discussions with
key individuals in the government.  Meetings were held with key individuals in
the Ministry of Education, Culture and Social Welfare (MOEC), including the
Curriculum, Textbooks, Supervisory Development Centre (CTSDC), and the Basic
Primary Education Project (BPEP).  Other government interviews included
discussions with the Women's Development Division (WDD) in the Ministry of
Local Development (MLD), and the Women's Training Center (WTC).  Discussions
were also held with people working in the Small Farmers Development Programme
(SFDP), and the Production Credit for Rural Women (PCRW) programme.  Both
international and local non-governmental agencies were also included in the
survey.  <p>
<p>
One week was spent in the field visiting a variety of programmes, from
home-based day care to child care centers, to pre-primary and primary education
classes.  Discussions were also held with personnel in UNICEF to gain a further
understanding of the history of the programmes and the parameters within which
new programmes might be developed.<p>
<p>
The findings suggest that Nepal has a rich and varied experience in early
childhood provision. These have been developed by governmental agencies and
international and local non-governmental agencies and organisations.  Models of
both home-based and centre-based programmes have been implemented, with varying
degrees of community support.  Some of these have been in place for as long as
10 years.  Some of them have already been terminated. <p>
<p>
There is an infrastructure in place which can provide support from the central
to the district to the local levels.  This is impressive.  The difficulty is
that at the present time there is a lacuna nationally in terms of intellectual
and technical support that could be provided to those who are attempting new
programmes and to those who are trying to sustain their current efforts.  If
Nepal is to maintain its current programming for young children and further
expand coverage, then aggressive action must be taken to develop appropriate
expertise within the country.   One way to do that would be for UNICEF to
implement the following recommendations:<p>
<p>
1.	Rather than contribute to individual efforts in early childhood provision,
UNICEF should support the development of human resources at the national level
that can provide technical assistance to governmental and non-governmental
agencies in the areas of curriculum development, training and related research
and evaluation.  The model developed for the training of Master Trainers in the
field of Adult Education might well be followed.<p>
<p>
2.	Current infrastructures should be supported to provide training and on-going
support to those currently providing early childhood care and education (e.g.
WDOs, WDAs, RP's)<p>
<p>
3.	Models of home-based care should be evaluated more closely in terms of
content and the quality of provision.  This is a very important model
internationally for the provision of care and education to children in isolated
rural areas.  Further experimentation with this model would be useful
nationally and internationally.<p>
<p>
4.	Non-governmental agencies (international and local) should be provided with
support in the development of community-based models of early childhood care
and development which are developed from the perspective of
self-sustainability. Organisations open for collaboration on such an effort
would be Save the Children USA and PLAN International.<p>
<p>
5.	Within current models of provision, particularly SFDP and PCRW, attempts
should be made to experiment with alternative models of funding the early
childhood components so that they can become self-sustaining.  <p>
<p>
6.	Currently there are several training systems which have been developed
nationally (the MLD has 5 training centres, WTC has 4 centres, and there is the
BPEP system).  The possibility should be explored that these centres also be
utilized for the training of early childhood personnel. <p>
<p>
7.	Strategies should be developed for working the content of early childhood
education (child development and the interaction of health, nutrition and
stimulation) into the content of current non-formal education and literacy
programmes.<p>
<p>
8.	Investments should be made in developing the capacity of local NGOs, not
only in terms of curriculum and training, but also in management and
sustainability.  Given UNDP's interest in developing the capacity of NGO's,
perhaps this could be a joint endeavor with them.<p>
<p>
9.	Several reports and commissions have recommended the development of a
national center to support early childhood care and development.  In documents
there is reference to a Pre-Primary Unit in the Ministry of Education and
Culture, a Child Study Center, and a Section for the implementation of Early
Child Education and Care (ECEC) programme within the Ministry of Education and
Culture.  In the private sector there is the Teaching Services Center. While
this is a worthy long-term goal, such a Unit/ Section placed within the MOEC or
a resource center based in an NGO should be undertaken cautiously.  Before
investing, an assessment should be made of the resources that would be required
to establish and maintain a resource centre since this is likely to be a costly
activity.  <p>
<p>
10.	It was recommended that a National Pre-Primary Council or National Board be
established for the purposes of providing direction to the Ministry of
Education in the development of its pre-primary education programme.  As a
result of this mission, it is being recommended that a <i>National Council on
Early Childhood Care and Education</i> be created which has a broader mandate.
It should work with the MOEC in the development of its pre-primary programmes
and also oversee the development of care for all children under the age of six
being provided for by both governmental and non-governmental agencies.<p>
<p>
11.	For the short term, the possibility of using volunteers trained in early
childhood provision should be considered and appropriate volunteers should be
actively recruited (e.g. VSO's and Peace Corps volunteers).<p>
<p>
12.	People in Nepal should become familiar with early childhood developments in
the region.  There are particularly strong  programmes in Thailand, India and
Sri Lanka.  Appropriate study tours should be created to maximize what can be
learned from these countries. <p>
<p>
13.	Advocacy efforts should be undertaken to promote a more widespread
understanding of the importance and value of the early years in terms of
children's later growth and development.<p>
<p>
14.	The early childhood position should be filled within UNICEF Nepal as soon
as possible in order to provide the appropriate coordination and backstopping.
The individual could be recruited from the region where there are some
individuals very experienced in early childhood care and education. <p>
<p>
15.	A linkage should be established with a reputable early childhood
organisation which could provide training and technical support over the next
five years. An example would be the High/Scope Foundation in the USA.  They
have the flexibility to design training specifically for Nepal and they have
developed a system for working with nationals to adapt the High/Scope
curriculum so that it is culturally appropriate.  Their curriculum has been
adapted for use in rural communities in Ecuador, Colombia, Bolivia, Peru, and
Iraq.     <p>
<p>
<p>
A number of these recommendations can be implemented through a national
in-country training programme outlined in the Action Plan (Section IV).  Others
could be addressed by the individual in the UNICEC ECEC position.  While in the
initial stages the Action Plan will require periodic input from experts outside
the country, over a three year time period there would be a core group of
individuals in Nepal trained to continue to provide appropriate support to
those committed to investing in the lives of young children. <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>NEPAL: FROM ENTRY POINT TO CONSOLIDATION</b> <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>AN ASSESSMENT OF EARLY CHILDHOOD PROVISION IN NEPAL</b><p>
<b>WITH RECOMMENDATIONS FOR</b><p>
<b>UNICEF'S INVOLVEMENT </b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
The focus of this report is on early childhood care and development in Nepal.
Section I provides a brief introduction to Nepal. Section II provides an
overview of governmental commitment to investment in early childhood provision.
In Section III there is a review of a range of programmes currently being
provided for children under the age of 5, particularly in rural settings.
Section IV presents a set of recommendations for how these efforts might be
built upon and strengthened to increase coverage of services to the youngest
population most at risk, and discusses what UNICEF's role might be in that
process, and Section V provides an Action Plan which could be undertaken in
support of the recommendations.<p>
<p>
<b>I.  INTRODUCTION</b><p>
<p>
The statistics on Nepal are daunting. Covering nearly 150,000 square
kilometers, Nepal has a population of approximately 18.5 million people, over
half of whom are under age 18; 43% are under the age of 14.  Thus the country
has a relatively young population.  In addition, the population is increasing
rapidly, despite a high infant mortality rate (107) and a high under five
mortality rate (165).  While the maternal mortality rate is the highest in the
region (850:100,000), Nepal also has a high fertility rate (5.8). All these
variables result in an annual growth rate of 2.08%  (Central Bureau of
Statistics, 1992)<p>
<p>
How does Nepal compare with other countries?  It has been described as one of
the poorest countries in the world.  It is one of the least developed nations
in South Asia, with a low GNP and a relatively high growth rate.  While the GNP
is only US 170, according to those in Nepal this figure is too high to
represent the reality of most people's lives.  They say it reflects the
relative wealth of a small minority.  According to the National Planning
Commission, nearly half of the population live in "absolute poverty". (1992, pg
1).  The World Bank has estimated that this is closer to 70%.<p>
<p>
Nepal is predominantly an agricultural country: 90% of the labor force is
involved in agricultural work.  This is surprising since only about 18% of the
total land area has been brought under cultivation.  The low percentage of
cultivatable land is understandable when taking into consideration the
topographical constraints. The country is divided into three regions: Mountain,
Hill and what is known as the Terai (plain).  The rugged topography
characterized by high mountains and deep valleys make many parts of the country
inaccessible.  The majority of the people live far (it can be several days
walk) from any road network.  <p>
<p>
While the Terai, covers a third of Nepal, it contains 57% of the total
cultivated land.  The distribution of the population parallels the availability
of cultivated land.  Only 8.7% of the population lives in the Mountain areas,
47.7 in the Hill area, and 43.6 % on the Terai. (Central Bureau of statistics,
1992, pg 4) <p>
<p>
The country contains a variety of ethnic and cultural groups.  While Nepali is
the official language, only about 58% of the people have Nepali as their mother
tongue.  Other prominent languages include Maithili (11%) and Bhojpuri (8%).
Somewhat less representative are Tharu (4%), Tamang (3%) and Newar (3%).
(Central Bureau of statistics, 1992, pg 3)  There are other languages as well,
but they are the mother tongue of less than 3% of the population.  <p>
<p>
While the official religion is Hindu, and about 90% of the population would be
classified as such, it is not the Hinduism of India.  The Hinduism of Nepal has
incorporated many of the rituals and practices prevalent before Hindus arrived
in Nepal, but Hinduism has introduced a caste system that has been imposed on
traditional ethnic cultures, making for a unique mix of beliefs and
practices.<p>
<p>
While most agree that the great majority of the population is still illiterate,
there is no agreement on the actual percentages.  The Central Bureau of
statistics (1992, pg. 5) state that the literacy rate was 23.3% in 1981, and
was estimated to be 35% in 1988.  But this gross estimate masks regional and
gender differences.  UNICEF documents describing the conditions in specific
areas help illuminate the situation.  In the Birathnagar district it is
estimated that only 18% of the women are literate compared with 74% of the men.
(Dhungana, 1990, pg 33)  In Lalitpur, the percentages are 13.5% for women and
52.6% for men.  The urban average is 37.45% for women and 62% for men.
(Presern, 1990 , pg. 46)  Regardless of who is quoted as a source on statistics
related to literacy, the data are powerful in indicating the overall lack of
literacy, and the disproportionate illiteracy among women.<p>
<p>
The situation for children is harsh.  The high dependence on agricultural
production requires intensive labor.  Much of this labor is provided by
children. A Nepali child between the ages of 6 and 9 will work 3 hours a day,
those between 10 and 14 work from 5 to 6 hours a day.  Girls work about twice
as many hours as boys. While legally girls cannot marry before age 16, it is
estimated that 22% of the girls are married before age 13, and 50% by age 16.
(Master Plan of Operations, 1992, pg. 3)<p>
<p>
Given the demographics it is not surprising that Nepal has the lowest school
completion rate in the region (27%)  (National Planning Commission, 1992, pg 3)
 The education system has been undergoing rapid change, yet the government is
being pushed to the limits in terms of providing the additional support
required to increase coverage and to assure quality education.  In 1987 about
40% of the primary school teachers were untrained, and that percentage remains
unchanged. (Educational Statistics of Nepal, 1990, pg.1)<p>
<p>
That is the context within which UNICEF and others are operating. <p>
One would expect that within this context there would be little or no
experience or interest in what happens to young children before they enter
primary school.  But that is precisely what makes Nepal such an interesting
country.  When one begins to delve into early childhood care and education --
in terms of what is being provided by the government and non-governmental
agencies -- there is a rich variety of early childhood offerings.  Many of
these efforts, particularly those developed through donor-supported rural
development projects, go back almost 10 years.  In addition there are a great
variety of private pre-schools which have been developed by individual
entrepreneurs in urban settings.  <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>II. THE POLITICAL WILL</b><p>
<p>
Within Nepal, in the government, donor and non-governmental community, there is
emphasis being given to early childhood provision.  As will be seen from the
discussion of individual efforts which follows, a range of interesting early
childhood initiatives has been developed during the past 10 years.  While many
of these were fairly isolated efforts, there is interest now in bringing them
together to learn from one another.<p>
<p>
A major impetus has been given to programmes in early childhood as a result of
the Education for All (EFA) conference in Jomtien Thailand in 1990.  There
early childhood education was put on the agenda and incorporated as an integral
part of Basic Education.  This has provided the policy framework within which
governments and donor agencies are able to make arguments for increased
investment in the early years.<p>
<p>
Within the <u>Master Plan of Operations 1992-1996</u> which presents the
country programme of cooperation between the government of Nepal and UNICEF
there are numerous references to the importance of investment in early
childhood provision. In that document it is stated:<p>
<p>
The obligation to protect a child's human right to develop to her full
potential is the most fundamental reason to invest in a programme which
enhances early childhood development.  Also, early childhood education lays the
foundation for successful transition to the often alien and difficult world of
the formal schools. (1992, pg.55)<p>
<p>
It goes on to state that the education programme being promoted through this
cooperative agreement, "seeks to lay a sound basis for expanding early
childhood care and education services in the country whereby parents and
communities are able to prepare children for learning and entry to school
(1992, pg. 56)  Thus there is a clear mandate and intention to invest in early
childhood provision.<p>
<p>
But how does a country as poor as Nepal enact such a plan?  The strategy being
developed is one which puts increasing emphasis on the role of the parents and
community in both the development and on-going support of appropriate early
childhood programmes.  In Figure 1 there is a representation of what is called
the <i>Strategic Triangle Empowering the Family</i> taken from the <u>Master
Plan of Operation </u>(1992, pg. 8).  In the figure there is an attempt to show
that the greatest power comes from the community itself, with support from the
agencies and organisations at the upper part of the triangle.<p>
<p>
What is impressive is to see the number of organisations (private and public)
that have developed strong infrastructures which begin at the grassroots level
and which then have supportive mechanisms all the way to the central level.
The focus on organising the community to meet its own needs is certainly well
established in Nepal.  This is one of the real strengths that can be built upon
in further promotion of early childhood programmes.<p>
<p>
In the <u>Master Plan of Operations</u> there is a discussion of the strategy
that will be used to build on this strong community base.<p>
<p>
Communities that want to establish Early Childhood Care/Education Centres will
provide most of the local requirements including the building, a locally
selected and remunerated child care worker and costs of upkeep.  The Ministry
of Education, other governmental offices, projects and NGO's will encourage and
support the communities in their efforts. (1992, pg. 68)<p>
<p>
In other words, the governmental and non-governmental agencies will provide the
technical inputs in communities that are willing and able to undertake the
costs of operating centres.  The question being raised is how to do this well.
In order to help answer that question it is important to have an understanding
of what is currently being provided, and the strengths and weaknesses which
current efforts demonstrate.<p>
<p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>III.  DEVELOPMENTS: A BRIEF REVIEW</b><p>
<p>
In preparation for the visit to Nepal, a number of articles on programs in
Nepal were reviewed, there were conversations with people who had experience
working in the country, meetings with nationals studying abroad, and
discussions with UNICEF New York.  This was done in order to understand early
childhood programming developments in Nepal.  The variety of initiatives that
have been undertaken over the years is impressive, as is the range of
organisations that have been involved in early childhood provision. (For a
guide to the various acronyms which will be used, see Annex A.)<p>
 <p>
Upon arrival in the country, visits were made to NGOs and governmental agencies
that have historically been involved in provision of care and/or education for
children under the age of 5. This was done in an attempt to identify what
currently exists--the accomplishments, problems and the strengths.  (For the
itinerary of the visit refer to Annex B.)  While there are a variety of
interesting models that have been created, many of these programs have either
ended or are on the brink of collapsing.<b>[1]</b>
<p>
<p>
The interventions which have been developed in Nepal tend to fall into two
distinct groups: those which cater to children from birth to three years of
age, and those which provide for the 3-5 year old--commonly considered the
"pre-school" child.  At age 6 the children in Nepal enter the primary school
system.  Table 1 presents an overview of current provision.<p>
<p>
Programmes for children in the birth to 3 age group have been developed in
conjunction with community development and women's programmes, where the
primary objective has been to alleviate women's <i>reproductive</i> role in
order for them to be engaged in more <i>productive</i> activities. When such
projects are a part of government programming they are likely to be found
within the Ministry of Local Development (MLD), under the Women's Development
Division (WDD).<p>
<p>
Children in the 3-5 age range are more likely to be catered to by the MOEC.
However, until recently this age group has not been recognized formally as part
of the education system.  <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
 <p>
<b>TABLE 1</b> <p>
<p>
<b>CURRENT ECEC PROVISION</b><p>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
Organization        Home-Based     Child Care    Pre-Primary
                     Centre         Centre        Class

SFDP                                 45/31 * 
PCRW                    22           91/90 **
NCO                                   5              75***
PLAN                                 39/40
Redd Barna              47            5
BPEP                                                  4(?)
Seto Gurans                           1
</pre>
<p>
<p>
*   We obtained 2 different numbers in relation to how many centres were in
operation.  This programme is going to end in 1992.  It is unclear what will
happen to the child care centres.<p>
**  Two different numbers were provided.<p>
*** The <i>Bal Mandir</i> schools frequently contain Nursery, Lower Kdg, and
Upper Kdg. classes for children 3, 4 and 5 years of age.<p>
<p>
Before proceeding much further it is important to define some terms.  In
conversations and in the literature people use the terms <i>early childhood
education, pre-school education, pre-primary education, early childhood care
and development, early childhood care and education, early childhood
development</i>.  These terms mean different things to different people.  While
research and experience would suggest that the term <b>early childhood care and
development</b> best represents an understanding of the needs of young children
(in terms of a continuity of provision and an emphasis on an integrated,
cross-sectoral approach to programming for young children), this phrase is not
commonly used in Nepal.  For the purposes of describing current activities for
young children in Nepal, the two most common terms used locally are defined
below.  These are used as the framework for categorising programmes in Nepal.<p>
<p>
<b>Early Childhood Education</b>.  In Nepal this stands for pre-school and
pre-primary education.  In the most conservative definition, it means the
provision of education within the formal education system for children at age
five.  Some people would also include the three- and four-year-old, but this is
not common.<p>
<p>
Pre-school education has been developed most fully by the private sector, most
commonly by individuals who have created pre-schools for children in urban
areas.  <p>
<p>
More recently, however, the development of pre-school education by the
government has been prompted by the fact that the government has begun to
acknowledge and address a phenomenon which has been going on for several years.
In grade 1, which is meant to provide education to six-year-olds, there are
frequently children ages 3, 4 and 5 as well.  This is the result of six year
old children bringing younger brothers and sisters along with them to school.
If they did not, the six year old would have to stay home and take care of
these children. The result is that grade 1 may have over 100 children in it,
although less than half of this number is the correct age to enter school.  It
is estimated that 30-40% of those who attend grade 1 are less than 6 years old.
(Action Plan, pg.1)<p>
The attendance of younger children in grade 1 is one of the factors
contributing to the very high <i>repeater</i> rate between grades 1 and 2.  In
fact the younger children have not needed to <i>repeat</i> grade 1, they are
simply a year older and now the right age for grade 1.  The age-appropriate
cohort moves on to grade 2.<p>
<p>
There is now a recognition of the fact that the youngest children in grade 1
should be catered for separately in a pre-school class, more commonly known as
the <b><i>Shishu</i></b> class.  Experimental pre-schools have been developed
in the governmental sector through the Basic Primary Education Project.  <p>
<p>
<b>Early Childhood Care and Education/Development</b>.  These terms are
generally used to refer to programmes for children under the age of three.
These programmes are not under the MOEC.  Rather, they tend to have been
developed in connection with other programmes operating in a given setting,
primarily those related to women and development efforts.  While it might be
imagined that these programmes focus primarily on care, in fact, where they
exist, they clearly have an educational as well as care component.  There is
also an emphasis on health and nutrition.<p>
<p>
Within the governmental sector these programmes are being offered as part of
the Production Credit for Rural Women (PCRW) and the Small Farmers Development
Programme (SFDP), both being offered through the Ministry of Local Development,
under the Women's Development Division.  In the international non-governmental
community, programmes for children under 3 are being developed by Save the
Children USA.  There is also a newly evolving NGO, Shreejana Vikas Kendra,
which has developed a child care programme that was an outgrowth of work with
women in carpet factories.  These and other efforts are described in more
detail in the section which follows.  <p>
<p>
<b>A.  Project Review</b><p>
<p>
In this section there is a brief summary of the current level of provision of
the organisations visited and interviewed, followed by a definition of some of
the challenges currently being faced by the organisation and an assessment of
the potential strengths of the activities currently being undertaken.  Given
that the consultancy was only three weeks in duration, there may well be
inaccuracies in the presentation. <p>
<p>
<b>1. Governmental organisations/agencies</b><p>
<p>
<b>	a. Ministry of Education and Culture (MOEC).  </b>Within its mandate, as
defined by the National Education Commission, the MOEC is to make provision for
pre-primary children (ages 4 &amp; 5).  At the present time the focus is on
provision for children age five.  MOEC is projecting the implementation of a
pre-primary classroom at every primary school by the year 2000.  However, this
is an unrealistic projection as it would require opening more than 3000 centers
and training more than 3000 teachers each year for the next 10 years. At the
present time the country lacks the capacity to undertake this kind of massive
expansion.<p>
<p>
Given constraints within the government, the MOEC is saying that the provision
of pre-primary education should be a shared responsibility.  The community
should provide the classroom and the teacher's salary and the MOEC will provide
materials, training and supervision.  This seems like a very sound approach.
At the present time nothing is being done to obtain these objectives.  This is
partially due to lack of financial resources, but more importantly, it has to
do with a lack of personnel with an understanding of how one would proceed to
get this kind of community/government collaboration underway. <p>
<p>
Within the MOEC there are two groups that are doing some work to meet the
government's commitment for pre-primary children.  These are the Curriculum
Textbooks and Supervision Development Center (CTSDC) and the Basic Primary
Education Project (BPEP)<p>
<p>
<b>1.  Curriculum, Textbooks and Supervision Development Centre (CTSDC)</b>.
This unit is responsible for the development of curriculum, textbooks and
supervisory systems, as its name implies.  It is this group that could develop
pre-primary education curriculum and materials.  Already it has been proposed
that a pre-primary unit be established at CTSDC.  Currently there is a person
at CTSDC who has been given responsibility for the pre-primary activities, but
in reality she is pulled in other directions and little has been created.  She
has offered a few training sessions for people operating pre-schools in the
private sector, but has not really devoted time and energy to focusing on
developing pre-primary education for the government schools.  <p>
<p>
<b>2. Basic Primary Education Project (BPEP)</b>.  The BPEP project, an
outgrowth of a Primary Education Project (PEP) (developed in 1982 and
implemented until earlier this year), is currently receiving support from
UNICEF, World Bank, DANIDA, UNDP and Japanese AID.  The BPEP project was set up
to create an innovative curriculum, teacher training and teacher support
process for the primary grades.  It is operating on a experimental basis in
several districts.  Within three BPEP schools we visited near Surkhet, the
Headmaster had taken the initiative to set up a separate classroom for the
under-aged children known as the <i>Shishu</i> class.  Teachers from the
primary school have been shifted to teach this class and given some very
rudimentary training by the Resource People (RP) at the district level to work
with these younger children.  Several of the national-level staff within the
BPEP project have shown an interest in developing a solid programme for the
<i>Shishu</i> class, but at the present time the BPEP Unit does not have a
mandate to proceed with curriculum development and training for this age
group.<p>
<p>
<u>The challenges</u>:  There are many for the MOEC.  While there is  political
will to invest in early childhood programming, there is a serious lack of
resources.  Further, curriculum development and the creation of the necessary
accompanying training and support schemes, have not been undertaken.  If CTSDC
were to become the home of pre-primary curriculum and training activities, it
would need to be strengthened considerably.  On the other hand, if BPEP were to
be given the responsibility for pre-primary education, then there would be the
issue of incorporating the pre-primary efforts into regular government
provision.  Currently BPEP remains a "project"; it has not been incorporated
into the MOEC as a "programme".  <p>
<p>
Another issue is the fact that currently the MOEC is defining pre-primary
education as the provision of education only for five-year- olds.  Given the
current pattern of attendance in grade 1, there is going to be a need to
address what happens for three- and four-year-olds as well.    <p>
<p>
<u>The Potential</u>:  BPEP staff, with appropriate support and training could
undertake to develop the pre-primary component.  They have the infrastructural
support systems required to provide training and on-going support for teachers
if they could develop the curriculum and appropriate training.  Further, there
is considerable staff interest within BPEP to undertake such a project.  This
same interest was not evident in CTSDC.<p>
<p>
<b>	b. Agricultural Development Bank - Small Farmers Development Programme
(SFDP)</b>  SFDP was created in 1975 and is operated by the Agricultural
Development Bank, with financial support from the Asian development Bank and
UNICEF.  The purpose of SFDP is to provide groups of small farmers with credit,
technology and the skills necessary to improve their agricultural production.
The community development process utilized in the project also includes
education, health, family planning and nutrition components.<p>
<p>
UNICEF began providing support to SFDP in 1981, with the specific mandate to
introduce basic services.  These have included  literacy, water, sanitation,
improvements of educational facilities, kitchen gardening and the introduction
of child care centers.  Currently there are 45 child care centers operating
within this project.  The teachers and assistants (<i>Sevikas)</i> are paid by
the project.  The community provides the space and food for the children.<p>
<p>
<u>The Challenges</u>:    In 1987 there was a review of the overall effort.  At
that point it was recommended that a national center for early childhood
education be created.  The MOEC was not willing/able to take this on, so UNICEF
did not pursue this recommendation.  Also as a result of the review UNICEF
encouraged community take-over of the child care centers.  This has not
happened.  Thus when there was a request for funds from UNICEF to expand the
system, UNICEF said no.  <p>
<p>
At the present time UNICEF is considering phasing out the child care centers.
This is primarily because UNICEF does not feel SFDP is able to provide the
necessary technical support to keep the centers operational.  In addition, SFDP
is finding it difficult to make these centers self-sustainable (i.e. have the
communities take them over completely).  One of the reasons is that the
teachers' salaries are extremely high compared to the salaries of teachers in
comparable programmes. <b>[2]</b>  The community
cannot afford to take over these salaries and they have not been provided with
technical assistance in the development of alternative ways of supporting the
centers.<p>
<u></u><p>
<u>The Potential</u>:  There is an excellent infrastructure in place that has
led to the development of a very viable system of child care. There are WGOs
(Women Group Organisers) who see the importance of continuing to promote early
child care provision, and mothers clearly have benefitted from these centers.
The challenge is to work with the communities to develop alternative ways of
sustaining the programme, through the creation of income-generating activities
to support the child care center, restructuring salaries so that they are in
line with local resources, not established in relation to national norms, etc.
<p>
<p>
<b>	3.  Ministry of Local Development (MLD)- Production Credit For Rural Women
(PCRW)</b>.  While the Ministry of Local Development does not have a mandate to
develop programmes for children below primary school age, through a major
development effort within the Women's Development Division (WDD) they are
involved in early childhood provision.  As a result of the Production Credit
for Rural Women (PCRW) project, there is now considerable expertise within the
WDD in relation to early childhood provision.<p>
 <p>
PCRW was begun in 1982 as a joint project between the Ministry of Local
Development (MLD) and UNICEF.  Within the MLD, the Women's Development Division
(WDD) has taken primary responsibility for project implementation.  While
similar in structure and process to the SFDP project, the focus is on women.
PCRW is the only large-scale national programme specifically directed toward
meeting the needs of rural women.  The project seeks to make small scale credit
available to women for agricultural production, livestock, and cottage
industries.  This work is facilitated by Women Development Officers (WDOs) and
Women Development Assistants (WDAs).<p>
<p>
This highly successful programme has received considerable recognition
internationally and currently receives support from a variety of donors
agencies, including UNICEF, USAID, UNDP, CIDA, GTZ, EEC and the Netherlands, as
well as from the Nepalese government.  <p>
<p>
Within this programme two forms of child care have been developed.  One is a
home-based system of child care for children under age 3 (widely known
internationally as Project Entry Point).  Within the programme 6 to 8 women
with young children form a child care group.  These women are given a four day
training in their village and then they rotate responsibility for taking care
of the children.   In some sites permanent rooms have been made available and
the mothers rotate.  In other villages the children rotate from one home to
another, depending on which mother is responsible for the children on a given
day.  A tin box of materials is given to the community and it is rotated with
the mothers.  At the present time PCRW is operating 22 home-based child care
centers.<p>
<p>
The second model of provision is more formal child cares centers for children
from 3-5 years of age.  Here, as in the SFDP programme, teachers and
<i>Sevikas</i> are paid by the project, with the community providing the
building and some food for the programme.  The salaries within the PCRW project
are lower (Rs. 700/teacher/ month and Rs 500/<i>sevika</i>/month.  However,
even this amount is too much for the community to support.  There are 90 of
these child care centers currently operating.<p>
<p>
<u>The Challenge</u>:  At the present time both of the child care models are
viewed primarily as a way of relieving women's work.  There is little
understanding of the ways in which the programmes can support children's
development.  What both the home-based and the center-based programme require
is technical support, in the form of additional curriculum inputs and on-going
training and supervision.  Some of these centers have been operational for 8-9
years.  The teachers were given training before they began their work and they
were provided with a set of materials.  They have received little or no
technical support since then.  They are ready for more training, but it is not
being provided.<p>
<p>
Within the home-based programme the services are essentially self-sustaining,
but the mothers/teachers need additional technical support in terms of
curriculum.  The challenge for the child care centers is the same one being
faced by SFDP, and that is that the centers are not moving toward
self-sustainability.  This is understandable given that they were not set up
with self-sustainability as a goal.  Now programme staff are pushing
communities to take on total responsibility for the centers.  The communities
are used to receiving the services; it is difficult to now change the structure
of the project.<p>
<p>
<u>The Potential</u>:  Both the home-based and the center-based models of
provision developed by PCRW are extremely valuable in the rural context,
particularly the home-based option.  This should be capitalised upon and
expanded, both in terms of geographic coverage and in terms of making the
programme available to children up to the age of five, if there is no
possibility for the child to attend a child care center.  The more informal
nature of the home-based programme makes it less costly to operate, but it does
require higher levels of technical support than is now being provided. <p>
	<p>
The field-based network of WDOs and WDAs provides an infrastructure already in
place that is extremely valuable.  These individuals could be trained to
provide training and on-going technical support to both the home-based and
center-based programmes.<p>
<p>
The Women's Training Center was established to provide support to the WDD in
terms of the work of the WDOs and WDAs.  At the present time the early
childhood training offered through this organisation is very weak. However,
with some technical support this organisation could be utilized as the vehicle
for on-going training within the PCRW system and they could offer training to
other governmental and non-governmental agencies as well.<p>
<p>
<b>2. Semi-governmental organisations</b><p>
<p>
<b>	a. National Children's Organisation.  </b>This group has a long history in
Nepal. Originally it was under the patronage of the Queen and was devoted to
the creation of orphanages and the development of care for under-privileged and
handicapped children.  The NCO centers which were created are known as <i>Bal
Mandirs</i>.  Because of the Queen's involvement there was a stability to the
organisation and an assurance of funding.  Since democracy that has changed.
The National Children's Organisation has become an NGO and no longer has the
necessary funds to continue its extensive programming.  <p>
<p>
Currently, in addition to operating several orphanages NCO supports <i>Bal
Mandirs</i> in the largest urban area in each of the 75 districts.  These
consist of primary schools, beginning with pre-primary classes in some cases.
(The most developed schools have nursery, Lower Kdg, and Higher Kdg. classes.)
While <i>Bal Mandirs</i> were initially designed to serve the poorest children,
due to economic necessity these schools are now charging relatively high fees
(in Pokhara this was Rs 85/mo for the 3 pre-primary years (nursery, lower KG
and Upper KG), and Rs 65/mo for the primary school).  Thus these schools now
serve a much more middle-class population.   <p>
<p>
In an attempt to bring their programme more in line with their original
purpose, NCO, with support from UNDP, has undertaken a pilot project which
involves the creation of community centers in five semi-urban settings (serving
2000-5000 families each).  Known as the Child Welfare Through Community
Development (CWTCD) project, it is designed to evolve in each setting, based on
local needs.  It was envisioned that the centers would develop income-
generating activities, early childhood centers, programmes for youths, literacy
classes, etc.  In the design it is the income-generating activities that are to
eventually make the centers self-sustaining.  This has happened in Pokhara
where there is a fisheries project. In the other four centers the
income-generating projects (goat keeping and wool refining) have not been as
successful. (It was unclear how many of these sites actually have a child care
programme.)<p>
<p>
Originally CWTCD was a 2-year project, but it has been extended for a
additional year and an evaluation is being undertaken.  If it appears to have
some potential, it is likely that UNDP will continue funding and expansion of
the effort.  <p>
<p>
At the present time the staff of the NCO are in the process of re-grouping.
They would like to undertake an extensive evaluation of their entire system and
then restructure it to more appropriately meet the needs it was originally
designed to serve. (UNDP and UNICEF have been requested to assist in this
effort.)<p>
<p>
<u>The challenges</u>:  Currently the organisation is struggling to survive.
(They receive approximately 20-25% of their funding from the government.) The
current structure is cumbersome and the <i>Bal Mandirs</i> are not serving the
population they were designed to serve. It will take some time and considerable
resources to restore NCO to a position where it can operate effectively.<p>
<u></u><p>
<u>The potential</u>:  NCO has a well established system of schools operating
in all 75 districts of the country.  There is no other organisation that has
such a wide-spread infrastructure, covering all the districts.  Since the
<i>Bal Mandirs</i> are located in the largest urban area in the district, NCO
has the potential to reach a large number of children.<p>
<p>
<b>	b.  Research Centre for Educational Innovation and Devlopment (CERID). </b>
While not strictly an implementing agency, the Research Centre for Educational
Innovation and Development is currently undertaking a community-based action
research project in 3 districts, with one center being developed in each of the
three topological areas (Mountain, Hill and Terai).  CERID has been interested
in early childhood provision since the early 80's.  In 1982 they undertook a
survey of early childhood provision in the country.  From the study they
concluded that what was being provided, mainly by private entrepreneurs in
Kathmandu Valley, was highly academic and that the concept of early childhood
care and development, in its broadest sense, was poorly understood.  <p>
<p>
With funding from IDRC, CERID is currently undertaking an action-research
project that will include an extensive baseline survey, followed by the
implementation of a community-based early childhood project focusing on the
development of children between the ages of three and five.  The total project
will take three years.<p>
<p>
<u>The Challenges</u>:  The structure of the model of provision being
implemented in the action-research project is one already implemented in Nepal,
where there have been difficulties in sustainability.  The project is building
the center and providing the salary for the teacher/facilitator and
<i>Sevika</i>.  They are implementing the current "curriculum" and utilizing
Seto Gurans (described below) for the training the teachers.<p>
<p>
<u>The Potential</u>:  This is an attempt to really understand the impact of
early provision for children ages 3-5.  The baseline study promises to generate
some very interesting data on the status of young children in the different
project villages.  Dr. Joshi, Director of the Project, is committed to early
childhood education and is an important advocate for increased government
investment in care and development for young children. <p>
<b>3. International non-governmental organisations</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b> 	a.  Save the Children USA</b>.  Save the Children USA has shown
considerable interest in developing child care provision.  A primary focus of
their work has been on the development of women's groups.  In their work they
see a progression of working within a community.  They begin with literacy
training.  This frequently leads to the creation of women's groups that then
turn their attention to a variety of community needs, one of which is child
care.  At the present time SCF USA is working with more than 60 women's groups.
One of these groups has developed a home day care.  Another group has visited
the day care programme and is interested in also starting their own.  Rather
than encouraging rapid expansion of the home-based child care model to other
women's groups, SCF wants to be sure that these groups have the right kind of
training and technical support and that, from the beginning, they are
structured to become self-sustaining.<p>
<p>
<u>The Challenge</u>:  At this point SCF USA has little experience in the
implementation of child care programmes.<p>
<p>
<u>The Potential</u>:  There is enormous potential within this organisation in
terms of the future development of early childhood provision in Nepal.  They
are an international partner that has considerable credibility in the country,
given their work to date.<p>
The organisation has made a commitment nationally and internationally to the
development of appropriate child care systems.  They are open to working with
government and other NGO's to develop appropriate models, curriculum and
training systems.  <p>
<p>
<b>	b.  PLAN International. </b>PLAN International is currently operating in 41
villages.  Within the villages they do fairly extensive family surveys to
assess needs and then develop programmes appropriately.<p>
<p>
Over the past several years they have developed 40 pre-school centers for 3-5
year olds.  The pre-school programme (now about 3 years old in some villages),
has evolved out of other activities PLAN is doing in communities.  <p>
<p>
From the beginning PLAN has been concerned about sustainability. What they are
attempting to implement is a child care center in collaboration with the
community.  The community provides the space and 'tiffin' (snack) for the
children.  The first year PLAN pays the teacher's and sevika's salaries (Rs.
700 and Rs 500, respectively). In subsequent years the proportion paid by PLAN
decreases as the amount paid by the community increases.  (This has just begun
so it is not possible to know if it will work.)  PLAN also provides some
educational materials for the centers.<p>
<p>
As a result of their experience, PLAN have concluded that rather than beginning
a child care center immediately upon entering the village, programming should
start with adult literacy.  PLAN sees the importance of then integrating the
literacy efforts with child care, nutrition, health and income-generating
activities.  At the present time they are developing income-generating
activities to support the child care center, and they have developed a linkage
programme connecting the pre-primary school with the primary schools in the
area.  <p>
  <p>
<u>The potential</u>:  Like SCF USA, PLAN is moving slowly in a very systematic
way.  They are interested in developing approaches and evaluating them
carefully before they move on full-scale.  They could be a good group to
include in the development and testing of a self-sustaining community-based
model and a national curriculum.  They appear to be willing to work with others
on these issues.  They, like Save the Children USA, have a good reputation in
the country and are a very viable partner in the future development of early
childhood efforts in Nepal.<p>
<p>
<b>	c. Redd Barna.  </b>This international NGO has been involved in a range of
community-based initiatives.  They have a well-developed system of home-based
child care programmes (currently 47 in number) and they have developed 5 child
care centers as well.  The model of provision is based on the programme
developed within PCRW. Teachers for these programmes receive training from Seto
Gurans.<p>
<p>
Redd Barna also has an extensive Child-to-Child programme involving some 2,000
children in a community programme focused on increasing health awareness and
improving the quality of care for younger children and the community.
Child-to-Child operates through community organisers and is not linked with the
formal school system.<p>
<p>
Another activity of Redd Barna is what is known as the Cheli-Beti programmes
for out-of-school girls.  The programme is an attempt to provide girls with
primary education, utilizing a non-formal methodology.<p>
<p>
<u>The Potential</u>:  This international NGO is highly respected in Nepal and
has both the resources and flexibility to experiment with models of provision.
They should be brought into any effort to develop national models of provision
that are self-sustainable. They also have a weekly radio programme (Hatimalo -
Hand-to-Hand) which is developed by and for children.  In the programme they
use dramas, songs, stories, etc. to convey a range of messages.  This could be
a very useful vehicle in the promotion of an understanding of child growth and
development and the importance of the early years to later growth and
development. <p>
<p>
<b>4. National non-governmental organisations</b><p>
<p>
<b>	a.  Seto Gurans.  </b>Seto Gurans was begun by Agatha Thapa, a woman who
has been involved in early childhood programming in Nepal for many years.
Having received training in Israel in early childhood provision, Mrs. Thapa
developed a curriculum and continues to develop materials for pre-school age
children. With support from UNICEF, Seto Gurans, the NGO created by Mrs Thapa,
became a major training resource within Nepal during the 80's, providing
training to the PCRW and SFDP programmes and to the majority of the
non-governmental agencies establishing programmes for young children.<p>
<p>
In 1988-89 UNICEF's core support for Seto Gurans came to an end. While UNICEF
continued to buy training from Seto Gurans, the lack of core support has made
Seto Gurans' survival tenuous.  <p>
<p>
In addition, the Women's Training Center was established.  Trainers from this
center, who were trained by Seto Gurans, established their own training
services.  The Women's Development Division, once a recipient of Seto Gurans
training, now receives training from the Women's Training Center rather than
from Seto Gurans.  Thus WDD, the group operating the largest early childhood
programme through PCRW, and thus the greatest purchaser of training services,
no longer requires training from Seto Gurans.  While WDD was not Seto Gurans'
only customer, it was a major contributor to the on-going support of the
training unit. <p>
<p>
At the present time, there does not appear to be a systematic approach to
training.  While an extensive examination of the training was not conducted, it
would appear that training packages are put together based on the time the
receiving agency feels it can allocate to training rather than the needs of the
trainees.  <p>
<p>
In essence, since 1990 Seto Gurans has declined considerably, both in terms of
its ability to perform and in terms of its reputation within Nepal.<p>
<p>
<u>The Challenge</u>:  Seto Gurans was supported almost exclusively by UNICEF
when it began.  During the time that UNICEF was providing core funding Seto
Gurans was not encouraged to seek other sources of support.  When UNICEF monies
ceased, Mrs Thapa lacked the appropriate skills and experience to seek
alternative funding.  Key staff left the organisation as funds decreased, and
while materials continue to be developed, there is a lack of on-going
curriculum development and the quality of the training has declined.  There is
also a lack of management capability within the organisation.<p>
<p>
<u>The Potential</u>:  Within Seto Gurans there is a wealth of experience that
could be utilized.  Seto Gurans is particularly strong in the development of
materials.  They could be a rich resource in the development of appropriate
play and learning materials for pre-school programmes.  This is one of the few
NGO's in Nepal that has a history of working with young children.  Explorations
should be made as to the viability of trying to revive this organisation.<p>
<p>
<b>	b.  Nepal Women's Association</b>.  Although relatively new in formation,
this group has a strong network of members throughout the country, and focus on
promoting the concerns of women.  They are seeking ways to go beyond advocacy
and awareness-raising.  They would like to develop projects for women but lack
the necessary skills to put viable projects together.  For example, they
applied to UNICEF to establish a revolving loan fund for women, but the project
was not well-enough conceived to warrant funding.  <p>
<p>
They are concerned about the conditions of women and children in carpet
factories, and would like to develop a project for them.  They operated 2
creche centers in Kathmandu, but could not sustain them.  They have also
attempted to develop some projects with the National Children's Organisation
(the <i>Bal Mandirs</i>), but again these efforts have been tentative and not
well developed. Clearly NWA is concerned about the issue of child care and
would like to get involved in some way, but they are unsure on how to proceed.
<p>
<p>
<u>The Challenge</u>:  Basically this is a very inexperienced group in terms of
programming.  At least the people we met appeared to lack the skills to
conceptualize a programme and take the steps necessary to get it funded. <p>
<p>
<u>The Potential</u>:  This group consists of women from all over the country,
and they have an established network.  They are committed to trying to make a
difference in women's lives.  With the right kind of training and support, they
could make a significant contribution.  Again, this might be an NGO worth
investing in to build their capacity.<p>
<p>
Recommendation:  It would be extremely valuable for a small group of women from
NWA to visit India and meet with Ila Bhatt and others at SEWA.  SEWA is a
dynamic women's organisation that has made a substantial difference in women's
lives.  Their strategy has been to address issues simultaneously at the
grassroots level to mobilize women and at the national policy level to put into
place supportive legislation.  They have also developed a strategy for the
implementation of child care programmes in conjunction with women's work.<p>
<p>
* * *<p>
<p>
While the focus of the review was on early childhood projects directed toward
poor children, primarily in the rural areas, there are some efforts being
undertaken in Kathmandu which focus on the underclass.  These have the
potential to provide viable models of provision for urban children.  These
projects need to be taken into consideration in terms of their experience and
what they can offer to the development of early childhood resources nationally.
<p>
<p>
<b>	c. Shreejana Vikas Kendra.  </b>This relatively new organisation was
created by a very active woman (Shanta Choudwry) who has developed this NGO to
alleviate the extremely negative conditions of rural women.  Beginning with
activities to help address women's legal issues, Shreejana Vikas Kendra now
also provides literacy classes in Kathmandu (bringing the women in from the
rural areas), training for the purpose of income-generating, and a child care
center for women working in carpet factories.<b>[3]</b><p>
<p>
<u>The Challenges</u>:  Shreejana Vikas Kendra is a very small organisation,
but it is thriving. While there is a child care center being operated, it is of
low quality.  The Director admits that she knows little about children, but she
saw the need for child care and has created a place where at least the children
are safe and they are being fed.<p>
<p>
<u>The Potential</u>:  The Director, Shanta Choudwry, is a women of strong
commitment, and she has considerable energy and enthusiasm.  She was a
recipient of an Ashoka Fellowship in 1989, and certainly demonstrates the
qualities of individuals chosen for that fellowship.  <p>
<p>
<b>	d. Madhyamik Vidayalaya.  </b>This private school has been organised for
lower caste children.  The Director, Stella Tamang, began by creating a
pre-school.  Then as she learned more about the poor quality of the primary
system into which graduates from her center entered, she decided to extend her
school into the primary grades, and finally into secondary school. She now
operates a high quality private school.  But Stella has not limited herself to
developing and operating her own school.  She has been actively involved in
early childhood education in the country.  She is a member of the national
advisory committee for the BPEP project and she has been active in promoting
early childhood awareness.<p>
<p>
In 1980 she helped found the <u>Teaching Services Center for Early Childhood
Education</u>.  Currently membership is primarily from among the
private-schools in Kathmandu, but this group has the potential to take on
advocacy and awareness-raising activities that would serve the nation.<p>
<p>
<u>The Challenges</u>:  At this point Stella Tamang's work has been focused
primarily on the development of her own school.  <p>
<p>
<u>The Potential</u>: Mrs. Tamang has a good understanding of early childhood
issues and would be a tremendous resource if she could be encouraged to move to
the national arena in some way.  The Teaching Services Center could be
developed as a national resource for curriculum development, material
development and the creation of appropriate training for urban and rural child
care teacher/facilitator. <p>
<p>
<b>5. Industrial day care</b><p>
<p>
While not an organisation as such, another vehicle for the development of child
care systems is industry-sponsored/supported child care.  We visited one such
center in Pokhara that had been developed out of the initiative of a local
Business Professional Women's Club (BPWC).  This club understood the needs of
working women for child care.  They organised and then sponsored such a center
within the industrial complex in Pokhara.  <p>
<p>
Initially BPWC provided some funding for the center.  The remainder was
supplied by the factory and the parents ( 2:1 proportionally).  BPWC has now
withdrawn funding.  The current level of parent and factory funding is not
sufficient to sustain the child care centre.  However, if costs were analysed
it might be possible to sustain the center if the factory would contribute
2/3rd of the required costs, while the women workers contribute 1/3.  <p>
<p>
<u>The Challenges</u>:  It requires an individual or organisation to work with
individual factories and industries to establish such child care centers,
although there may be some national business organisations that could be
approached to develop child care systems within their setting.  At this point
there is little experience in employer-sponsored child care in Nepal, but it is
certainly an avenue worth exploring.<p>
<p>
<u>The Potential</u>:  Clearly for a country where there are increasing numbers
of women involved in the more formal work sector, there will be an increasing
need for employer-sponsored child care.  The existing models could well be
built upon so that they can serve as examples of what can be developed and
implemented.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>B.  A Typology of Programme Approaches</b><p>
<p>
In order to get some perspective on the initiatives that have been developed in
Nepal, it is useful to put them within a typology of early childhood provision
that encompasses efforts internationally.  This topology, taken from the
<u>Coordinators' Notebook</u> (Issue 11, 1992, pg 8) is presented in Table 2
and summarized below:<p>
<p>
<b>	1.  Delivering a service.</b>  The goal of programmes in this category is
to meet the immediate needs of children.  The services provided can include
health care, nutrition and stimulation (education), and they are provided
outside the child's home. <p>
<p>
<b>	2.  Educating caregivers</b>.  This category of services focuses on parents
or other caregivers, providing them with information that will enhance their
parenting/caregiving abilities.  Interventions can include parental education
(literacy is one vehicle), and/or efforts that focus on older children who
provide care for their younger siblings (for example Child-to-Child). <p>
<p>
<b>	3.  Promoting community development.</b>  This strategy emphasizes working
with the community to define its needs and support the development of services
they see as beneficial.  When child care and development is a desired outcome,
the services are developed in line with community resources to help assure
sustainability. <p>
<p>
<b>	4.  Strengthening national resources and capabilities</b>.  The focus of
these strategies is on developing the organisational capacity of institutions
in order for them to be able to continue their services to children and their
families.  <p>
<p>
<b>	5.  Advocating to increase demand.</b>  An important support for the
development of services for children and families is increased public awareness
of the need for such services.  Advocacy is an important part of that
consciousness-raising process.  This requires pulling together relevant
knowledge and disseminating it in a variety of ways to reach multiple
audiences.<p>
<p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
