<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>	6.  Monitoring social, legal and regulatory dimensions.</b>  A critical
piece in developing programmes for families is to assure that legislation is in
place which is supportive of both women and children.  This includes monitoring
and reinforcement of labor regulations as well as assisting in the development
of appropriate programmes to demonstrate application of the legislation.<p>
<p>
<b>	7.  Developing national child care and family policies.</b>  At the
national level, it is important to have policy in place that provides an
<i>enabling environment</i> for the development of appropriate programmes for
families and children.  While policies can be directly related to provision for
women and children, tax and other incentives can indirectly benefit the quality
of children's lives.  Thus it is important to focus on developing a broad range
of social policies.<p>
<p>
What follows is a mapping of current efforts in Nepal within these seven
categories of provision.<p>
<p>
1.  Direct Service				PCRW<p>
							SFDP<p>
							BPEP - Shishu classes<p>
							Save the Children USA<p>
                                   Redd Barna<p>
							Shreejana Vikas Kendra<p>
<p>
2.  Educate Caregivers			Literacy classes<p>
							PCRW<p>
							SFDP<p>
							Redd Barna<p>
<p>
3.  Promote Community Development  PCRW<p>
							SFDP<p>
							Save the Children<p>
							PLAN International<p>
                                   Redd Barna<p>
4.  Strengthen National
	resources and capabilities<p>
<p>
5.  Advocate to increase demand    Redd Barna<p>
<p>
6.  Develop supportive 
     legal frameworks<p>
7.  Develop national child        Ministry of Education and Culture<p>
     care and family policies    UNICEF<p>
<p>
<p>
As can be seen, at the present time the majority of the efforts have been
directed toward the provision of care, educating caregivers and promoting
community development.  In the plan of action being proposed in this report,
emphasis will be given to the <b><i>strengthening of national resources and
capabilities</i></b>, which will help strengthen what has already been
developed in terms of the other strategies.  Emphasis will also be given to
advocating to increase demand.<p>
<p>
This strategy is being recommended because Nepal is at a turning point in terms
of its support of early childhood efforts.  Nepal has been involved in early
childhood provision for UNICEF's target population for the past 10 years in the
PCRW and SFDP programmes. Other experiments have been underway within the
international NGO community for nearly as long.  While this may not appear to
be very long, in fact it is a significant amount of time when compared to other
efforts internationally.  The 10 years have allowed the programmes to move
beyond the pilot/ experimentation stage.  They have been in place long enough
to have some stability. They have not achieved self-sustainability, but that is
not necessarily the fault of the community. It has more often been the result
of the ways in which the programmes were introduced initially into the
community.<p>
<p>
Again, it is useful to put Nepal's experience in perspective.  In a review of
early childhood programmes internationally, Robert Myers (1991) summarized some
of the current issues being faced by those who have been involved in early
childhood provision.  Several of his comments are applicable to Nepal.<p>
<p>
Many projects and programmes continue to be pilot and demonstration activities
that are innovative, effective and feasible to replicate, but have not been
extended in a significant way.  (pg.55)<p>
<p>
This is certainly true in Nepal.  The two largest projects, SFDP and PCRW, have
implemented well-conceived early childhood projects. And while it may well be
feasible to replicate the efforts (with some changes in the approach to
implementation) this has not happened.  In fact, child care centres within SFDP
will be phased out by UNICEF at the end of 1992. This is illustrative of
another point made by Myers.<p>
<p>
Many...programmes have now passed the point of initial enthusiasm and
the...spirit that was so critical in getting programmes underway is growing
thin.  And yet these programmes have not been recognized as bona fide claims on
the public purse; they are in danger of fading. (pg. 56)<p>
<p>
The programmes in Nepal are indeed in danger of fading.  The time is right for
some action by UNICEF, in collaboration with the government and NGO community,
to assure that the efforts do not fade and that appropriate technical support
is provided to some of the current initiatives. In the following section there
are a series of recommendations for action.<p>
<p>
<b>IV.  RECOMMENDATIONS AND ACTION PLAN</b><p>
<p>
In order to understand the rationale for the proposed recommendations and
Action Plan it is useful to take a step back and look at what happens over time
as projects develop.  There are stages or phases to projects.  These are common
across development efforts and provide a useful framework for assessing the
level of development of early childhood provision in Nepal.  What follows is a
brief description of the phases and an indication of where the various efforts
in Nepal fall within that framework.   From this, recommendations are made in
terms of a specific Action Plan that could be undertaken by UNICEF over the
next 3-5 years.<p>
<p>
<b>A.</b> <b> Phases in the life of development projects.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>	1.  An initial interest in developing a programme</b>.  Here staff of an
organisation or agency have seen the need to develop a programme and are
seeking models that might be implemented in their setting and/or they are in
the process of developing their own model.  <p>
<p>
	Save The Children USA<p>
	World Education (Family Literacy)<p>
National Women's Association <p>
	<p>
<b>	2. Experimental/pilot programme phase.   </b>This consists of designing a
model and testing it out in a few sites.<p>
<p>
	Research Centre for Educational Innovation and Development<p>
	  (CERID)<p>
	Ministry of Education and Culture (MOEC)<p>
	  Basic and Primary Education Project (BPEP)<p>
	  Curriculum, Textbooks, Supervisory Development Centre<p>
        (CTSDC)<p>
	Shreejana Vikas Kendra<p>
NCO's community center programme<p>
<p>
<b>	3. Evaluation/Review</b>.  Here the experimental model has been in place
for some time (a minimum of 3 years).  The agency/ organisation is making an
assessment of what has been accomplished and is looking to the future.<p>
	Production Credit for Rural Women (PCRW)<p>
     Small Farmers Development Programme (SFDP)<p>
     PLAN International<p>
	Redd Barna<p>
     National Children's Organisation (examining the <i>Bal Mandirs</i>)<p>
<p>
<b>	4. Redesign</b>.  For those who have determined that there are changes that
need to be made in the model, either in terms of the quality of the provision
or related to issues of sustainability, this is the time to make those
changes.<p>
<p>
This is the position of most of the groups listed in Phase 3. There is a
realization that the current model is not adequate and interest in receiving
assistance in terms of the future.<p>
<p>
<b>	5. Consolidation/dissemination</b>.  At this stage the organisation has
confidence in the model that has been developed and is in the process of
designing ways to take the model <i>to scale</i>.<p>
<p>
At the present time there is no group in Nepal at this stage.<p>
<p>
<p>
In sum, Nepal is rich in experience.  There are a number of early childhood
efforts that have been underway for almost 10 years.  It is at the point where
people are asking, now what?  The great difficulty in answering that question
is that despite the long history of involvement in early childhood provision
there is a lack of expertise in the country to assist those groups who are
beginning efforts.  More importantly there is lack of expertise to take the
more experienced groups to the next stage in their own development.  Nepal is
in danger of losing what has already been developed.<p>
<p>
<b>B.  What role can UNICEF play?</b><p>
<p>
UNICEF can play an extremely important role by helping to support the
development of human resources at the national level who would assist people
through Phase 4 (and provide assistance to those in the earlier Phases as
well).  Eventually this may lead into the development of a national Resource
Centre.  Specifically what people are requesting is assistance in:<p>
<p>
	<b>1. Curriculum development</b>.  At the present time what is passing as an
early childhood curriculum is merely a collection of activities that can be
undertaken with young children.  There is no framework that people are working
from to make curricular decisions.<p>
<p>
<b>	2. Training</b>.  The training that has been provided has not been
systematic.  People have taken what they could find in Nepal, and quite a
number have done short courses in Israel over the years, but again, there is no
overall training design that could be applied systematically.  Many of the
organisations which have already begun early childhood programmes are serving
the rural areas.  Thus a training system developed for rural, illiterate
teachers is required and could be applied across many of the organisations.<p>
<p>
	<b>3. Alternative approaches</b>.  <p>
<p>
a.	There is a need to develop a truly community-based approach that will lead
to self-sustainability.  The models that have been developed are reliant upon
external funding in order for the programme to be maintained in the community.
There is a need to re-work these models in order for them to achieve
self-sustainability.  There is also a need to provide support in the early
stages to those groups initiating early childhood programmes so that
sustainability is built in from the beginning.<p>
<p>
b.	There is a need to link early childhood provision with other programmes.
Literacy is a primary example.  There is an opportunity to bring together these
two efforts in a variety of ways: <p>
-  through the introduction of child development into literacy materials,<p>
-  through the creation of child care programmes that operate in conjunction
with the literacy classes, thus making it possible for more women to
participate.<p>
<p>
<b>	4.  Advocacy</b>.  There is a need to develop advocacy programmes to raise
awareness of the importance of early childhood provision. This
awareness-raising needs to be done with parents as well as with policy
makers.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>C. Recommendations and Strategy/Action Plan</b><p>
<b></b><p>
The recommendations which follow will allow UNICEF and HMG/Nepal to meet their
stated objectives in support of early childhood provision. Each set of
recommendations is followed by a suggested strategy or Action Plan designed to
allow for implementation of the recommendation.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendations 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6</b><p>
<p>
<i>1.	Rather than contribute to individual efforts in early childhood
provision, UNICEF should support the development of human resources at the
national level that can provide technical assistance to governmental and
non-governmental agencies in the areas of curriculum development, training and
related research and evaluation.  The model developed for the training of
Master Trainers in the field of Adult Education might well be followed.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i>2.	Current infrastructures should be supported to provide training and
on-going support to those currently providing early childhood care and
education (e.g. WDOs, WDAs, RP's)</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i>3.	Models of home-based care should be evaluated more closely in terms of
content and the quality of provision.  This is a very important model
internationally for the provision of care and education to children in isolated
rural areas.  Further experimentation with this model would be useful
nationally and internationally.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i>4.	Non-governmental agencies (international and local) should be provided
with support in the development of community-based models of early childhood
care and development which are developed from the perspective of
self-sustainability. Organisations open for collaboration on such an effort
would be Save the Children USA and PLAN International.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i>5.	Within current models of provision, particularly SFDP and PCRW, attempts
should be made to experiment with alternative models of funding the early
childhood components so that they can become self-sustaining.  </i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i>6.	Currently there are several training systems which have been developed
nationally (the MLD has 5 training centres, WTC has 4 centres, and there is the
BPEP system).  The possibility should be explored that these centres also be
utilized for the training of early childhood personnel. </i><p>
<i></i><p>
<b>Strategy/Action Plan:</b>  Among the recommendations given above, several
address the issue of human resource development at the national level in order
to support and promote early childhood activities in Nepal.  Action which
facilitates human resource development would support Recommendations, 1-6.
What follows is a proposal for how this might be done.  It is based on several
premises. <p>
<p>
	*  More than one or two people in the country should become early childhood
care and development experts.  In fact a core group -- minimum 12 people --
should have the skills and abilities to develop curriculum and train others in
its application.  With only 1 or 2 being trained there is the risk of their
leaving the country or changing their profession.  There needs to be a solid
core group that can provide on-going support to one another.<p>
<p>
	*  To the extent possible, they should acquire new skills and abilities
through in-country training.  It would be extremely costly to send this number
of people abroad for training. In addition, sending them abroad would increase
the risk of their not maintaining their involvement in early childhood
education.<p>
<p>
	*  Training should be structured in such a way that it allows people to
continue in their present position and not draw them away from their
responsibilities.  One of the possible outcomes of removing people from their
job in order to receive training is that someone else has to take on the
person's current responsibilities.  When no one else is available, then the job
does not get done.  When someone else is available, they may want to retain the
position when the individual being trained returns to the position.  This can
cause difficulties within the organisation.  Further, if the individual being
trained can remain on-the-job it provides them with an opportunity to apply
their training immediately and to know what will and will not work in their
context.  This provides extremely useful feedback to those doing the training.
<p>
<p>
	*  As new curricular ideas, materials and concepts are introduced, those
receiving the training should take maximum responsibility for adapting them to
the culture and conditions in Nepal.  No <i>package</i> should be imposed.  All
too often a curriculum or programme is imported without regard for its cultural
appropriateness.  Through the process being suggested below, while a well-known
curriculum would be introduced early on in the process, it would be for the
purposes of providing a framework for the development of a local curriculum.
From that framework an appropriate curriculum would be developed for Nepal.<p>
<p>
	*  In order to build up expertise within Nepal it is going to be necessary to
draw on experts outside the country.  The appropriate curriculum and training
expertise to support this Action Plan does not exist in-country.<p>
<p>
	*  At the present time a separate Resource Centre for Early Childhood Care and
Education should <u>not</u> be established due to the costs of such an
investment at a time when there are neither adequate personnel to staff the
centre nor a clear sense of the objectives and mandate of such a Centre.  Many
of the curricular ideas, materials and training packages that might be offered
through such a Centre will be developed in the proposed project, but a physical
centre will not be established.  If the need for such a centralized function
evolves in 3-5 years time then a separate proposal would be developed.  (See
Annex C for an analysis of some of the current agencies and organisation in
terms of their potential to house such a Resource Centre.)<p>
<p>
Given these premises, the following course of action is proposed, based on a
series of in-country workshops, developed in consultation with external
experts. <p>
<p>
	<u>A National Workshop</u> would be held with invitees from all the agencies
and organisations currently providing some kind of early childhood care and
education activities.  Two participants would be invited from each
organisation.  Given the numbers involved (there are at least 14 organisations
that should be included, in addition to the governmental offices), it is
proposed that two workshops be held, with half of the group attending one
workshop and the other half attending the second workshop.  Further, it is
proposed that these workshops be held outside Kathmandu, perhaps in Pokhara and
Ilam.  The workshop would be of four days duration.  Its purpose would be to
help <i>ground</i> people in what early childhood care and education is all
about.  (The material provided in the UNICEF Manual would be an excellent
resource.)  There would also be a discussion of whether or not the agencies
represented were willing to nominate 1-2 of their people to become curriculum
developers and trainers.  <p>
<p>
Criteria would be established for the participation in further training of
those with a strong interest in early childhood provision.  The
agency/organisation would have to submit an application for 1-2 people from
their staff to become Master Trainers, and the agency would have to make a
commitment to utilize these individuals in a training role once they completed
the course.<p>
<p>
	<u>Training Workshop I</u>. This two-week workshop would be offered to those
who had been accepted for the training course.  During the first training the
emphasis would be on curriculum development.  The participants would engage in
a discussion of what curriculum is, they would analyse the current early
childhood curriculum in terms of whether or not it meets the criteria of a
curriculum, and they would then be given the task of identifying gaps and
setting up working groups to fill in the gaps.  Following the training they
would return to their agency and work on implementing the curriculum as
designed, making changes as appropriate, and identifying gaps not yet filled.<p>
<p>
	<u>Training Workshop II</u>.  This two-week workshop would build on what the
participants had learned as they tried to utilize the curriculum in their
settings.  The group would then try to finalise a national curriculum framework
that could be offered to those interested in establishing early childhood
programmes.  It is important to note that curricula would have to be developed
for home-based programmes, for centre-based child care programmes and for the
pre-primary classes.  While there would be a great deal of overlap in these
curricula, they would have to be adapted for use in the various settings.<p>
<p>
	<u>Training Workshop III, IV and V</u>.  Within these two-week workshops the
participants would be trained to become trainers in the curriculum.  Between
each workshop the participants would be expected to apply what they are
learning, develop training materials, document their activities and progress,
etc.  During each of the trainings there would be an opportunity to discuss
what they had learned as they tried to apply their new skills, and there would
be an opportunity to address areas covered previously in order to reinforce
earlier learning. <p>
<p>
A major aspect of the training would also include how to work with communities
to gain their support for early childhood provision and ways of developing
resources within the community to establish and maintain appropriate
provision.<p>
<p>
After the fifth workshop there would be an assessment of the progress made by
the participants and a recommendation made in terms of additional training
and/or follow-up that might be required.<p>
<p>
At the end of the process there would be 12-20 individuals within the country
who would have expertise in early childhood care and education, in terms of
curriculum development and the ability to train others in the application of
that curriculum.  These individuals would remain within their own organisations
and would have the ability to provide training to teachers and supervisory
staff working in the child care programmes operated by their agency or
organisation.  In addition, it is anticipated that they could be made available
to provide training to new groups interested in starting early childhood
programmes.<p>
<p>
If after the training it is apparent that a centralized resource centre for
early childhood provision is required, then that would be proposed to the
government, UNICEF and other donors.<p>
<p>
A timeline for action in relation to this set of activities is included in
Table 3. The costs of this strategy would be approximately $100,000/year for 2
years.  This would include the costs of the external consultants, the travel
and stipend costs for the participants and workshop costs. <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
				<p>
