<p>
<p>
<b>Action Required</b>: As noted earlier, this set of activities would require
input from outside Nepal.  However, UNICEF would have to be responsible for
setting the activities in motion.  Following discussions with the government
and NGOs that might be included in the activities, an outside
consultant/organisation would need to be contracted to conceptualise and
conduct the trainings. <p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation 7 - </b><p>
<p>
<i>Strategies should be developed for working the content of early childhood
education (child development and the interaction of health, nutrition and
stimulation) into the content of current non-formal education and literacy
programmes.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<b>Strategy/Action Plan</b>:  By collaborating with non-formal education and
literacy programmes it would be possible to reach a wide spectrum of people.
The non-formal programmes address the needs of those 6-14, and literacy
programmes address the needs of adults. Both of these programmes are well
established in Nepal, and UNICEF has made a commitment to support these
efforts. <p>
<p>
One of the ways that early childhood could be strengthened through the
non-formal education programme is to include child development, health and
nutrition content as a part of the non-formal curriculum.  What might also be
useful is the inclusion of parenting education.  Many of these children are out
of school because they are caring for younger siblings.  The more they know
about how to care for them appropriately, the better.  A parenting curriculum
would also help prepare them for their role as parents.<p>
<p>
In terms of literacy programmes, there are many materials available for use in
teaching basic literacy.  What is being developed at this point are
post-literacy materials, reading materials for those who are now literate.
Many people we talked with were concerned about the content of post-literacy
materials.  They wanted to be sure that they were appropriate in terms of what
people needed, and they wanted to be sure that they were in a format that
people who are basically non-readers would find attractive.  There was
considerable interest in the development of materials that would address the
interaction of child development, nutrition and health and what that means for
children's growth and development. Another topic they felt was of interest is
the ways in which parents can support children's learning.  Many felt these
topics would be of interest to women and that there would be considerable value
in developing such post-literacy content.<p>
<p>
In order to link effectively with non-formal education and literacy programmes
it would be necessary to examine the current curricula to see to what extent
health, nutrition and child development are included.  Then it would be
necessary to identify someone who could help to add these components to the
curriculum. <p>
<p>
Given the large number of people being reached through these two systems, and
their relative flexibility, there is tremendous potential to get the right
messages out to this group of people through existing mechanisms.  This
strategy would be particularly important in terms of reaching girls and women.
<p>
<p>
<b>Action required:</b> Given UNICEF's in-house expertise in non-formal
education and the hiring of a new person for literacy, activities to integrate
early childhood into these programme could be begun as soon as the UNICEF ECEC
person is hired.  The activity of developing appropriate materials could also
be incorporated to some extent into the Workshops which are a part of the
Action Plan described above.  Literacy and non-formal education curriculum
developers could attend the workshops and take advantage of the expertise
available through them.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation 8 - </b><p>
<p>
<i>Investments should be made in developing the capacity of local NGOs, not
only in terms of curriculum and training, but also in management and
sustainability.  Given UNDP's interest in developing the capacity of NGO's,
perhaps this could be a joint endeavor with them.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<b>Strategy/Action Plan. </b> This is not a direct mandate for UNICEF at this
point in time. However, it is a part of helping to strengthen the organisations
currently providing early childhood programming.  Since there are other
development agencies and donors (e.g. UNDP), who are interested in
organisational development issues, the kind of cooperation that is being
proposed between UNDP and UNICEF to support the National Children's
Organisation is an excellent way to proceed. <p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation 9 - </b><p>
<p>
<i>Several reports and commissions have recommended the development of a
national center to support early childhood care and development.  In documents
there is reference to a Pre-Primary Unit in the Ministry of Education and
Culture, a Child Study Center, and a Section for the implementation of Early
Child Education and Care (ECEC) programme within the Ministry of Education and
Culture.  In the private sector there is the Teaching Services Center. While
this is a worthy long-term goal, such a Unit/ Section placed within the MOEC or
a resource center based in an NGO should be undertaken cautiously.  Before
investing, an assessment should be made of the resources that would be required
to establish and maintain a resource centre since this is likely to be a costly
activity.  </i><p>
<i></i><p>
<b>Action required: </b>There is no action required at this time since it is
being recommended that the idea of developing a Resource Centre for ECEC be
analysed over time to assess the viability of such an investment.  However,
over the next two years there should be further exploration of this
possibility.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation 10 -</b><p>
<p>
<i>It was recommended that a National Pre-Primary Council or National Board be
established for the purposes of providing direction to the Ministry of
Education in the development of its pre-primary education programme.  As a
result of this  mission it is being recommended that a</i><b> National Council
on Early Childhood Care and Education</b> <i>be created which has a broader
mandate.  It should work with the MOEC in the development of its pre-primary
programmes and also oversee the development of care for all children under the
age of six being provided for by both governmental and non-governmental
agencies.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<b>Strategy/Action Plan:</b>  This would be an important activity to undertake
in the near future.  The consultancy helped to stimulate renewed interest in
early childhood activities, and the discussions held would suggest that people
are willing and able to participate in such a Council.<p>
<p>
<b>Action required:</b>  UNICEF needs to take the initiative, but work closely
with the Ministry of Education and Culture, and perhaps the Ministry of Local
Development, who would appoint the National Council.  The National Council
should be comprised of individuals from governmental and non-governmental
agencies and organisations.  The National Council should be formed as soon as
possible so that they can be active participants in the design and
implementation of the Action Plan suggested in relation to recommendations 1-6.
<p>
One possibility would be for an Executive Committee of the National Council
(4-6) members to be part of the Planning Committee for the Workshops.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation 11 -</b><p>
<p>
<i>For the short term, the possibility of using volunteers trained in early
childhood provision should be considered and appropriate volunteers should be
actively recruited (e.g. VSO's and Peace Corps volunteers).</i><p>
<i></i><b></b><p>
<b></b>Clearly Nepal is open to having volunteers from a variety of countries.
This is potentially an important source of early childhood expertise.  <p>
<p>
<b>Strategy/Action Plan</b>:  Discussions with those associated with the VSO
programme expressed an interest in being involved in early childhood activities
in Nepal.  They assured us that they would be able to recruit volunteers with
appropriate experience.  This avenue should be explored further, and other
agencies that provide volunteers (e.g. Peace Corps) should be approached and
requested to provide volunteers with appropriate early childhood training and
experiences. <p>
<p>
<b>Action required:</b>  It is not necessary to undertake the task immediately.
When the new UNICEF ECEC staff person gets on-board, he/she should meet with
the various groups providing volunteers and develop a plan of action for
recruiting them to work in this sector.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation 12 -</b><p>
<p>
<i>People in Nepal should become familiar with early childhood developments in
the region.  There are particularly strong  programmes in Thailand, India and
Sri Lanka.  Appropriate study tours should be created to maximize what can be
learned from these countries. </i><p>
<i></i><p>
<b>Strategy/Action Plan:</b> <b> </b>There are a number of exemplary early
childhood programmes in the Region.  It would be worthwhile for a selected
number of people to visit such programmes, but they should do so with a very
clear agenda.  For example, there is a Teachers Resource Centre (TRC) in
Karachi, Pakistan that is designed to develop curriculum and materials, conduct
workshops for teachers, and work at the policy level to promote early childhood
concerns.  A study tour would allow participants to learn:  how the TRC
evolved; about the services it offers; about its organisational structure; and
how it is financed. <p>
<p>
Another programme it might be worth visiting is the Self Employed Women's
Association (SEWA) in India, which has a long and rich experience in working
with disenfranchised women.  One programme that they have developed which would
be of particular interest is the Creche (child care) programme developed for
women working in the rural areas.  The SEWA model would be of interest as
alternative programming for women and children in the rural areas is being
considered. <p>
<p>
There is a parent education programme in Thailand that is well worth visiting.
Within the programme materials have been developed that help stimulate parent
discussion groups.  The materials describe the stages of child development and
emphasise the interaction between health, nutrition, and stimulation.  The
materials being developed and the process of working with parents would be of
particular interest.<p>
<p>
<b>Action required:</b>  There should be a minimum of one study tour a year
(and a maximum of 2) for a group of 6-8 people, with a very particular focus
for each study tour (e.g. models of care for children under 3, or resource
centres, or community-supported child care, etc.)  The first study tour should
be set up toward the end of 1993 when those people participating in the
Workshops described above would have some ideas about what they would like to
learn from making such a study tour. <p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation 13 -</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<i>Advocacy efforts should be undertaken to promote a more widespread
understanding of the importance and value of the early years in terms of
children's later growth and development.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<b>Strategy/Action Plan:</b>  Redd Barna would be a good partner for UNICEF on
this activity.  They have media capacity within their staff and a strong
interest already in advocacy work.  The <i>Hatimalo</i> programme is one
vehicle for strengthening the messages that go to children and parents.<p>
<p>
<b>Action required:</b>  Rather than expending UNICEF staff time in advocacy
work, if funds were available, it would be advisable to work with Redd Barna to
develop a proposal that they could implement and that UNICEF would help fund.
Other donors could also be brought into the project. <p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation 14 -</b><p>
<p>
<i>The early childhood position should be filled within UNICEF Nepal as soon as
possible in order to provide the appropriate coordination and backstopping.
The individual could be recruited from the region where there are some
individuals very experienced in early childhood care and education. </i><p>
<i></i><p>
<b>Action required:</b>  If UNICEF is going to make a commitment to strengthen
and further support the development of early childhood initiatives in Nepal,
then the UNICEF office has to be strengthened in its capacity to backstop the
effort.  The activities listed above cannot be carried out by current personnel
given their responsibilities at the present time.  It would be advisable to
recruit someone for the position and to have them take up their
responsibilities as soon as possible.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation 15 -</b><p>
<p>
<i>A linkage should be established with a reputable early childhood
organisation which could provide training and technical support over the next
two to five years. </i><p>
<i></i><p>
<b>Strategy/Action Plan</b>:  As noted earlier, the recommendation is being
made that a linkage be established with the High/Scope Foundation in the USA.
High/Scope is known internationally for its commitment to young children.  The
research produced by High/Scope has demonstrated the importance of early
childhood education, not only in the present, but more importantly in terms of
the long-term benefits of investment in early childhood education.  High/Scope
also has a well-developed curriculum that has been adapted for use with the
rural poor in a variety of countries (e.g. Ecuador, Colombia, Bolivia, Peru,
and Iraq). <p>
<p>
High/Scope has developed a training process which provides for the training of
teachers, supervisory staff and the development of Master Trainers.  A linkage
with this institution would provide for two-way exchanges.  Through the
workshop process, a High/Scope consultant would travel to Nepal to conduct the
workshops.  At some point in time there might be individuals in Nepal who it
would be appropriate to send for advanced training. <p>
<p>
<b>Action required:</b>  If the Action Plan is accepted by UNICEF Nepal then
discussions should be undertaken with the High/Scope Foundation to develop the
Action Plan further and develop an appropriate contract.<p>
<p>
<b>D. Costs</b><p>
<p>
It is recognised that each of the recommendations needs to be developed further
to test their feasibility.  They also need to be costed.  While the Action Plan
detailed in Table 3 has been estimated to cost $100,000/year for 2 years, the
other recommendations and the proposed strategies/action plans have not been
elaborated in enough detail to attach a cost to them.  <p>
It should also be noted that some other options have been outlined for UNICEF's
consideration.  These are described briefly in Annex D.  Some of these have
cost estimates.<p>
<p>
* * *<p>
In sum, Nepal is at a turning point.  A considerable investment has been made
in early childhood provision in the country.  While the investment has provided
rich returns, there is a danger that the investment is going to be lost.
Organisations are at a point where professional support is required to keep
them moving ahead.  That support does not exist within Nepal.  It has to be
developed, and it can be, but it is going to take a real commitment on UNICEF's
part (financially and in terms of personnel) to make it happen.<p>
<p>
<p>
