<title>CULTURAL ASPECTS OF PSYCHO-SOCIAL DEVELOPMENT: AN EXAMINATION OF WEST AFRICAN CHILDREARING PRACTICES</title>
<body>
<h3 align=center>
<b>CULTURAL ASPECTS OF PSYCHO-
SOCIAL
DEVELOPMENT:</b><p>
<b>AN EXAMINATION OF WEST AFRICAN CHILDREARING PRACTICES</b><p>
<p>
<p>
Judith Timyan<p>
<p>
<p>
A report prepared for the Regional UNICEF Workshop:<p>
<p>
<p>
TOWARD A STRATEGY FOR ENHANCING EARLY CHILDHOOD<p>
DEVELOPMENT IN THE WEST AND CENTRAL AFRICA REGION<p>
<p>
<p>
January 18-

22,
1988<p>
Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire<p>
</h3>
<p>
<b>TABLE OF CONTENTS</b><p>
<p>
I. INTRODUCTION<p>								
II. BACKGROUND REMARKS<p>						
      A. Child-

rearing
during a time of rapid						
          social change.<p>
      B. The diversity of West African cultures<p>				
      C. Early prevention instead of later intervention				
<p>
      D. "Universal" evaluation of child development				<p>
      E. The identification of the child whose psyche-

social
		
         development is "at risk"<p>
<p>
III. CHILDREARING PRACTICES IN WEST AFRICA<p>
<p>
      A. Definition of child-

rearing
practices					<p>
<p>
      B. The context of child-

rearing
