<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
RAH96 Editorial: The Spree Is Over
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/grph/rahbkgd.gif">
<CENTER>
<!-- Commonwealth Broadcasting Network HTML Code Version 3.0 -->
<a target=_top href=http://commonwealth.riddler.com/Commonwealth/bin/statthru?214302><img height=60 width=460 border=0 src=http://commonwealth.riddler.com/Commonwealth/bin/statdeploy?214302></a>
<BR>
<H2>
Editorial: The Spree Is Over<BR>
by Dave Bealer
</H2>
<H3>
Irresponsible Behavior
</H3>
<P>
When I was but a wee tyke there was a game show on television that
ended in a shopping spree. The lucky winner would get to roll a 
shopping cart around a grocery store and stuff as much food into it
as possible during a one minute period.  For some reason the idea of
rolling a shopping cart around a grocery store and putting whatever
I wanted into it held a great fascination for me.  Bear in mind that 
I was extremely young at the time and prevented by parental authority
from having whatever I wanted when in a <i>real</i> grocery store.
</P>
<P>
What I didn't realize at that time was that a much larger, much more
sinister shopping spree was taking place on a national level. The
liberals had gained control of government and were spending money they
didn't have like there was no tomorrow. After a few decades of this it
became apparent to all but the most irretrievably liberal that there
really <i>was</i> no tomorrow for this nation unless the uncontrolled
spending was brought to a halt.
</P>
<H3>
Reality Check '94
</H3>
<P>
We all know that the liberal gravy train derailed in November 1994 in a 
wreck that made AMTRAK look safe by comparison. The Democratic Party
leaders, who were the sole occupants of the locomotive cab at the 
critical moment, have tried to blame the crash on Oliver North, Reagan/Bush, 
swamp gas, Rush Limbaugh, America's high fat content diet, Desert Storm, 
Hailey's Comet, sun spots, and (most of all) those angry, closed-minded, 
ignorant, non-pain-feeling citizens who were, for some strange reason, 
given the right to <b>vote</b> by some even stranger people a couple
hundred years ago. The idea that citizens who earn the wealth which is
collected by the government in the form of taxes should have some say
in how those taxes are spent is appalling to liberals. 
</P>
<P>
Most liberals would benefit from skipping one or two of the latest 
New Age I-feel-your-pain tomes and reading a little history. Perhaps 
if they knew what <b>real pain</b> can feel like they wouldn't be
so quickly impressed (or depressed) by a little everyday human misfortune.
This is not to say that there is no genuine need in this country - there
most certainly is. But the simple, brutal fact is that even America, the 
wealthiest nation on the planet, does not have unlimited wealth or resources.
</P>
<P>
The oh-so politically incorrect consequence of this critical fact is that 
the majority of voters in a democracy have the absolute right to allocate
the available resources as they see fit.  This includes the right to refuse 
financial (or other forms of) aid to anyone they want to exclude. The 
majority also has the right to impose conditions on the receipt of any such 
aid that is offered.
</P>
<P>
Ooo! Can you hear that whining? It's deafening. Those of you who are still
with us may want to throw some cold water on those who have fainted. They
may be happier remaining unconcious, but will have to face reality sooner 
or later. And the quicker they get started, the sooner they'll figure out 
what life is all about.
</P>
<P>
Don't get me wrong. I'm not condoning withholding aid from people because
of their race, religion, gender, fashion/social sense (or lack thereof),
or other affiliation or status. The folks footing the bills do have the
right to require work from those aid recipients capable of doing so, and
to place limits on the length of time that aid may be received.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of limits, term limits for elected officials are also a good
idea. A "ruling class" of professional legislators and executives is
not what the nations' founders had in mind. It is no accident that the
only lifetime appointments included in the constitution were for the
justices of the Supreme Court.
</P>
<H3>
Decision '96
</H3>
<P>
The national election this November will be one of those crucial
elections that determine, in a large way, the future course of American
history. We will have to decide whether to let the liberal kids loose in
the store again with an open line of credit, or whether to put someone
responsible in charge for a change. 
</P>
<P>
As you go to exercise your franchise on November 5th, please remember that 
although shopping sprees can be fun, especially for the young and 
irresponsible, the bills always come due eventually.  You, or your children, 
or their children will have to pay those bills. 
</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/grph/rah96bar.gif" ALT="______________________________">
</P>
<P>
