<TITLE>
RAH96: Lettuce To The Editor
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/grph/rahbkgd.gif">
<CENTER>
<!-- Commonwealth Broadcasting Network HTML Code Version 3.0 -->
<a target=_top href=http://commonwealth.riddler.com/Commonwealth/bin/statthru?21177><img height=60 width=460 border=0 src=http://commonwealth.riddler.com/Commonwealth/bin/statdeploy?21177></a>
<BR>
<H2>
RAH96: Lettuce To The Editor
</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
From: Paul Hays <wphays@scott.net><BR>
To: Dave Bealer <dave@rah96.com><BR>
Subject: Best of RAH Vol  0<BR>
Date: Sat, 1 Jun 1996 17:37:33 -0500
<BR><BR>
Dear Mr. Bealer:
<BR><BR>
I know you are a busy man so I'll make this short.  How can
I get a copy of <I>Command Line Cowboys: The Best of RAH Vol 0</I>?
<BR><BR>
The files I got from Dreamforge BBS, (The Last 12 issues of RAH)
didn't include the file RAHORDER.FRM
<BR><BR>
Paul Hays
wphays@scott.net
</P>
<HR>
<P>
Date: Sat, 01 Jun 1996 23:53:17 -0500<BR>
From: Dave Bealer <dave@rah96.com><BR>
To: Paul Hays <wphays@scott.net><BR>
Subject: Re: Best of RAH Vol  0
<BR><BR>
Hi Paul,
<BR><BR>
Unfortunately, you can't get a copy of <I>Command Line Cowboys:
The Best of RAH Vol 0</I> (CLCV0). I stopped promoting it because only a
few copies sold.  The real bite here is that during a hard disk
crash I lost the Hyperwriter setup (the hypertext product used to
create CLCV0) and never bothered to reinstall it because I never
needed it again.
<BR><BR>
Yes, I'm sure that the production release for CLCV0 (including the
Hyperwriter runtimes) exists on diskette here somewhere (I'm not quite
THAT irresponsible <g>).  The trouble is that we're talking a time lapse of
at least 18-24 months since the hard disk crash.  I have no idea where the
diskette containing this prize could be.  It would take far too much time
to try and find it.
<BR><BR>
One consolation is that CLCV0 wasn't too good, being my very first attempt 
at hypertext.  So quite honestly you didn't miss much.  If I ever become
famous, perhaps the Smithsonian folks will find it when searching through 
all my diskettes. <g>
<BR><BR>
I'll publish selected bits of your request and my response as the first 
"Lettuce to the Editor" for RAH96.  That way any other interested parties 
will know about this situation too.  Then if I ever encounter the magic 
CLCV0 diskette in my travels around my work area I'll announce that in 
RAH96 as well.  Whether I charge for it in that event depends on how broke 
I am at the time.  <g>
<BR><BR>
Sorry I couldn't be more helpful.
<BR><BR>
//Dave\\
</P>
<P>
Note that this set some kind of modern personal record for answering an 
e-mail message. I got that answer back to Paul just over six hours after
he wrote the original message.
</P>
<P>
I would like to publicly (and sincerely) apologize to anyone who attempted
to contact me during the February/March 1996 time frame.  I was working
through some personal problems at the time and couldn't bring myself to
even logon my BBS for several weeks. Things have settled down now, but
I am still extremely busy. I <B>am</b> answering my mail these days, but
it can take a while on occasion.
</P>
<CENTER>
<P>
RAH96 doesn't have a guestbook, so there's no need to worry about random
lame comments (except those made by the staff). We do want to have a 
dialog with our readers, however, and this is where it happens. Send
your comments, suggestions (please <I>try</I> to be constructive!) or
whatever to <A HREF="mailto:lettuce@rah96.com">lettuce@rah96.com</A>.
By sending e-mail to this address you are granting the publisher of
RAH96 the non-exclusive right to publish the contents of your message on 
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
Dave may send personal responses to some lettuce@rah96.com messages, but
don't expect him to do so. This applies whether the message in question
is published or not.
</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/grph/rah96bar.gif" ALT="______________________________">
