<HEAD>
<TITLE>
RAH96 Techno-Rant: Framed On The Web
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/grph/rahbkgd.gif">
<CENTER>
<!-- Commonwealth Broadcasting Network HTML Code Version 3.0 -->
<a target=_top href=http://commonwealth.riddler.com/Commonwealth/bin/statthru?214308><img height=60 width=460 border=0 src=http://commonwealth.riddler.com/Commonwealth/bin/statdeploy?214308></a>
<BR>
<H2>
Techno-Rant:<BR>
Framed On The Web
</H2>
<H3>
by Dave Bealer
</H3>
<P>
Copyright &#169; 1996 Dave Bealer, All Rights Reserved.
</P>
<P>
Oh, no! I've been framed! Such is the cry of the frames-capable browser
user as he falls victim to another runaway frame job. As a long-time Netscape 
user, I've got my own war stories to tell.
</P>
<P>
Sure, frames <i>can be</i> cool - though usually not the ones your
mother picks out for you. So can BLINK, and graphics, and even the 
occasional image map. I'd even go so far as to say that server push
may have its place, although not on any page of more than a few lines
that someone expects <i>me</i> to read.
</P>
<H3>
Framed Into A Corner
</H3>
<P>
The first time I ever cursed out frames was the day I tried to find
a network card driver on the Gateway Science Theater 2000 tech support 
website. As I descended through the levels of the GST2K site, the viewing 
area on my screen was being subdivided into smaller and smaller segments.
Eventually the active area of the browser screen was confined to a tiny 
frame (about 20 x 20 pixels) in the lower right corner. This screen was 
too small to hold any useful information, and I had a heck of a time
backing out of it.  (Did I mention that this was also my <i>first</i>
experience with frames?)
</P>
<P>
Since that bad first impression, I have seen some sites that put
frames to good use.  My favorites are the ones that place the site
menu in a narrow frame on the left side of the screen. The rest of the 
screen is the active area for whatever option I'm viewing/using at the 
time. The biggest advantage of this setup is that I can scan the menu
entries, and even scroll through the menu, while new information is
being downloaded into the option frame.
</P>
<P>
Another thing I don't care for is the link that launches an entire new
copy of the browser. Since I often go off and do something else while
waiting for any lengthy page download, I usually don't even notice
that another copy of Netscape has been started until I try to use
the "Back" button and nothing happens. Since I'm already fairly senile
(a bad thing at age 39), this can cause several minutes of fun and games 
each time it happens until I figure out what is "wrong."
</P>
<P>
So the moral of this story is that frames have their uses. Like most
things in life (and the web), frames are best used in moderation, and 
only then with sufficient planning and testing of the implementation.
Just don't look for them on RAH96 any time soon, unless I happen to
think of a really funny application for them.
</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/grph/rah96bar.gif" ALT="______________________________">
</P>
