<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
RAH96: Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<CENTER>
<!-- Commonwealth Broadcasting Network HTML Code Version 3.0 -->
<a target=_top href=http://commonwealth.riddler.com/Commonwealth/bin/statthru?26332><img height=60 width=460 border=0 src=http://commonwealth.riddler.com/Commonwealth/bin/statdeploy?26332></a>
<BR>
<H2>
<IMG SRC="/grph/rah96tm.gif" ALT="Random Access Humor 96 (tm)"><BR>
Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)
</H2>
<P>
Here is the definitive trove of official answers to the most frequently asked
questions about Random Access Humor 96 (RAH96). Please look through this 
document for answers to any questions you may have before asking a staff 
member via e-mail. If the answer to your question is contained herein you 
will simply be referred back to this document anyway. If you need further 
clarification on something feel free to write, but be prepared to be smacked
in the head with a rubber chicken if the answer to your question appears
three or more times in this FAQ document.
</P>
<P>
<A HREF="/rah96/rahfaq.html#Format">RAH96: Format and Availability</A><BR>
<A HREF="/rah96/rahfaq.html#Cost">RAH96: Cost</A><BR>
<A HREF="/rah96/rahfaq.html#Advert">RAH96: Advertising</A><BR>
<A HREF="/rah96/rahfaq.html#Submit">RAH96: Submissions</A><BR>
<A HREF="/rah96/rahfaq.html#Troubles">RAH96: Troubleshooting</A>
</P>
<A NAME="Format">
<H3>
RAH96: Format and Availability
</H3></A>
<P>
Q) What's all this, then? (i.e. What is the purpose of this site?)
</P>
<P>
A) Many people think of this site as a worthless pit of degradation. While 
these folks may be correct, the staff considers RAH96 to be the finest 
electronic humor magazine available online. It will probably require the
services of court-appointed psychiatrists to determine who is right.
</P>
<P>
Q) In what formats is RAH96 available?
</P>
<P>
A) RAH96 is available only in HTML format on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
Q) What about in plain ASCII text format?
</P>
<P>
A) Sorry. RAH96 is available only in HTML format on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
Q) How about in hardcopy? On newsstands?
</P>
<P>
A) You really don't get this, do you? RAH96 is available only in HTML format 
on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
Q) What about in Postscript, so I can print it myself?
</P>
<P>
A) RAH96 is available only in HTML format on the World Wide Web. This
is a recording.
</P>
<P>
Q) How do I change the text and background colors of the RAH96 pages?
</P>
<P>
A) RAH96 is available only in HTML format on th... no!  Wait!  Many browsers
allow you to override the colors defined in the HTML documents you are
viewing. The same goes for displaying/not displaying the graphics files
included in the pages. Check your browser documentation for details on
how to change these settings. (In other words Netscape and Microsoft
don't pay us to answer tech support questions on their products. We don't
pay them to write humor, mercifully, so it all works out best for everyone.)
</P>
<P>
Q) Why doesn't the RAH96 FAQ Page (i.e. this page) have the standard
RAH96 background?
</P>
<P>
A) So that folks who can't read the text when displayed on that background
can read the previous question and answer, which gives them help in 
overriding the default background. Clever, eh?
</P>
<P>
Q) The "Boob Shield" and "Table of Incontinence" pages seem awfully long.
Now that I've laughed at all the stock jokes a few times, is there any way
to skip right to the link part of those pages?
</P>
<P>
A) Yes.
</P>
<P>
Q) Well?  Are you gonna tell us how to do it?
</P>
<P>
A) Yes.
</P>
<P>
Q) Do it now!
</P>
<P>
A) Okay! Okay! Simply click on the "RAH96 tumbling letters" logo at the 
top of the page. This will take you to the link section of the page.
This feature will only be implemented on large pages with a single link
section near the bottom. Pages with multiple link sections (e.g. "The Best
of RAH" page - or this very page you are reading now) will have the classic 
table of section links located just below the title area of the page.  Note 
that the "stock jokes" in various parts of RAH96 <i>do</i> change from time 
to time. If you always take the shortcuts you might miss some good laughs.
</P>
<BR>
<A NAME="Cost">
<H3>
RAH96: Cost
</H3></A>
<P>
Q) Is there any kind of fee to access/read RAH96?
</P>
<P>
A) Our policy is to never charge the end user a fee to access the web edition 
of RAH96. This doesn't mean there is suddenly such a thing as a free lunch. 
We plan to make money from advertising which will appear on the RAH96 pages.
Eventually we may offer t-shirts, caps, sweatshirts, towels, shower curtains,
and stuffed hamsters emblazoned with the RAH96 logos for sale to our readers 
(that is, if more than six people ever show interest in the magazine).
</P>
<P>
Q) Will the stuffed hamsters be radioactive?
</P>
<P>
A) They can be, but that will cost extra. Lead-lined boxes require a lot
of postage.
</P>
<P>
Q) Will the stuffed hamsters be rabid?
</P>
<P>
A) What are you, some kind of nut? Rabid hamsters, even dead ones,
are incredibly dangerous!
</P>
<BR>
<A NAME="Advert">
<H3>
RAH96: Advertising
</H3></A>
<P>
Q) It is possible to buy advertising in RAH96?
</P>
<P>
A) Yes. Send an e-mail to: 
<A HREF="mailto:advert@rah96.com">advert@rah96.com</A> (message content
and subject can be anything) for an automated e-mail response containing the
current RAH96 advertising rates/policies.
</P>
<BR>
<A NAME="Submit">
<H3>
RAH96: Submissions
</H3></A>
<P>
Q) Does RAH96 accept submissions from freelance writers?
</P>
<P>
A) Yes. Send an e-mail to: 
<A HREF="mailto:submit@rah96.com">submit@rah96.com</A> (message content
and subject can be anything) for an automated e-mail response containing the
current RAH96 submission policy.
</P>
<BR>
<A NAME="Troubles">
<H3>
RAH96: Troubleshooting
</H3></A>
<P>
Q) Why do the RAH96 pages display correctly except for a single broken
graphic near the bottom of most pages?
</P>
<P>
A) The probable cause for this is that the RAH96 Admin Server is down
or disconnected from the net. Nearly every RAH96 page calls a usage counter
(for that page) whenever the page is loaded. The usage counter returns a
small invisible graphic which is "displayed" near the bottom of the page.
This is transparent to users except when the Admin Server is unavailable.
In that case the user sees a "broken graphic" symbol when using Netscape,
or whatever symbol the browser being used has for denoting a missing graphic.
</P>
<P>
Q) Why is the rest of RAH96 available when the Admin Server is down?
</P>
<P>
A) The HTML, graphics, and MIDI files that comprise RAH96 are served
through a T1 connection from a UNIX system in the office of our Internet 
Server Provider (ISP). The RAH Admin Server runs on a Windows 95 machine
located in the RAH96 offices and is connected to the ISP via a 28.8 KBPS 
dial-up modem connection which is supposed to stay up 24 hours/day, 7 days 
a week.  That is the theory, at any rate. In practice the phone circuit 
gets interrupted occasionally, and the system doesn't always dial back 
automatically like it should. Power outages in the office can also cause 
the server machine to shut down. Such outages usually last only a few 
minutes or hours. When the RAH96 staff is out of town (like for the Olympics
- July 21st through August 2nd) these outages can last for a few days. Don't
worry, the only things missing are the usage counts which are not displayed to 
the end user anyway. We decided that we would rather lose a few days worth of
usage data than spend loads of money on some "fail safe" solution for keeping
the Admin Server connected to the net.
</P>
<P>
Q) Why don't I receive an answer from any of the RAH96 infobots (automated
e-mail responders)?
</P>
<P>
A) You should receive a reply from the infobots within 2 - 24 hours.
If you don't, there are three possible reasons:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>The bots don't like you and are hoping you will go away.
<LI>The RAH96 mail server is down. It's located on the same Windows 95
machine in our offices as the Admin Web Server, so if the link (or
power) goes down, both servers are down until the link (or power) is
restored.
<LI>You sent your message to Tibet rather than our mail server. (And the
Tibetans aren't the least bit happy about it.)
</OL>
</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/grph/rah96bar.gif" ALT="______________________________">
</P>
