<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Book Review: IF YOU'RE FAT, IT'S NOT YOUR FAULT
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#091157 TEXT=#FFFFFF LINK=#FFFF00 VLINK=FF00FF>
<CENTER>
<H2>
Book Review: <I>If You're Fat, It's Not Your Fault</I><BR>
by Dave Bealer
</H2>
<P>
Diet books have been one of the fastest growing segments of
the book publishing market for the last decade or so. Two of 
the more popular diets have been the Scarsdale Diet, which was 
to die for, and the Rotation Diet, which tended to make people
dizzy if they went too fast. One of the most fad-laden segments
of a fad-driven society, the diet industry seems to benefit
everyone except the customers. All that is about to change.
</P>
<P>
<I>If You're Fat, It's Not Your Fault</I> by Paul Rivas, MD. and
E.A. Tremblay is a revolutionary weight loss book. Instead of 
placing the blame for obesity solely on the "weakness" or "lack 
of will power" of the patient, this book (and the medical weight 
loss program it describes) recognizes that obesity is a disease.
</P>
<P>
Paul Rivas, M.D. is a board certified internist who 
specializes in bariatric medicine (the treatment of obesity).
During the first ten years of his practice Rivas treated his 
patients using the tried and true method of sticking the poor
suckers on a diet and then sternly admonishing them when they
failed to lose weight as expected. The good doctor bought into
the standard belief that all it took to lose weight was a little
willpower. Everyone knew that, didn't they?
</P>
<P>
Of course a century ago everyone knew that man would never
find a way to achieve powered flight. All it took was a couple 
of bicycle mechanics from Ohio to prove everyone wrong. In the 
case of proving that obesity was actually a chronic medical 
disorder that could be treated with medication the breakthrough
was not nearly so obvious or dramatic as the <I>Wright Flyer</I>
soaring over the sands of Kitty Hawk.
</P>
<P>
Eventually one of Dr. Rivas' patients, who was certain that 
his intense cravings for Italian food were not caused by any 
lack of willpower, gave Rivas a copy of a research report by Dr. 
Michael Weintraub of the University of Rochester.  The report
described Weintraub's four year study of two new appetite
suppressants, phentermine and fenfluramine.  Rivas was interest-
ed, but still cautious.  Eventually he prescribed very low doses 
of the drugs for this patient.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Rivas consulted all the medical literature 
available on the new drugs.  For years virtually all appetite 
suppressants were amphetamines.  Those drugs work, but they are 
also dangerous and addictive.  Phentermine and fenfluramine are
not amphetamines.  More important, the new drugs don't just 
suppress the patient's appetite, they moderate the level of 
serotonin in the brain.  
</P>
<P>
Serotonin is a prime suspect as the cause of Obsessive-
Compulsive Disorder (OCD).  It is known that OCD patients have
an underlying biochemical abnormality which may or may not
involve serotonin.  Doctors do know that OCD can be success-
fully treated with serotonin modifying drugs like Prozac.  
</P>
<P>
Dr. Rivas began to understand that overweight people, at 
least those who suffer from irresistible food cravings, seem to 
be exhibiting a very specialized form of obsessive-compulsive
behavior.  Every study Rivas consulted showed impressive weight 
loss from the new drugs along with no major side effects and no 
addiction.  The clincher was that it worked for his patient.  
Then it worked for another patient, and another.
</P>
<P>
Eventually this reviewer became one of those patients.  I
will now describe my own personal experience with this system.
</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/grph/davewbar.gif" ALT="______________________________">
</P>
<P>
It was Sunday, September 10, 1995, the day before my 38th
birthday.  At well over 350 lbs (the highest weight I could
find a scale to measure), I weighed more than at any time in 
my life.  Recently I had started taking ibuprofen to kill the
pain in my worn-out knees just so that I could walk.  Not that
I could walk very far before my heart started pounding like a
jackhammer and my breath came in gasps.
</P>
<P>
It had been apparent for some time that this situation was
unsupportable.  Unless something was done - immediately - I
would probably not live to see my 40th birthday, and surely
not my 50th.  I began to consider liposuction as a means of 
getting the load off my knees and my heart.  Of course I knew 
that surgery wouldn't solve the long term problem.  I was just 
looking to buy some time in which to find a solution to my 
lifelong cravings for food.
</P>
<P>
I grew up in a Pennsylvania Dutch household in Pennsville,
a village about 15 miles north of Allentown, where I was born.
Food is very important in Pennsylvania Dutch culture.  In fact
food represents hospitality and even love in that culture.
</P>
<P>
The last time I weighed a normal amount for my height was 
a month before my 14th birthday.  I had just gotten out of a 
rehabilitation hospital after a six month stay for severe 
asthma (which had nearly ended my life several times in the 
previous year).  I was 4'10" tall and weighed about 100 lbs 
(the result of six months on a hospital diet - and let's face 
it, hospital food is nasty even if you're <i>not</i> on a diet).  
</P>
<P>
My parents got me home, took a look at their only child, 
and said, "you're so skinny!"  They proceeded to stuff me like 
a goose until I regained the rotund (and no doubt healthy, at 
least to their eyes) shape they were used to seeing.  Needless 
to say both my parents were overweight as well.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four years and numerous failed diet attempts later 
I found myself with a rapidly disintegrating body.  As I read
the Sunday <i>Baltimore Sun</i> that September day I happened upon 
a special medical advertising supplement.  It occurred to me 
that I might do better finding a plastic surgeon from that
supplement than from Yellow Pages ads (sorry, Mr. Jones).
</P>
<P>
The supplement did contain an ad from a plastic surgeon,
but it contained something even better.  Dr. Paul Rivas had
an ad that described his medical plan that treated "obesity
as a chronic biochemical problem".  Well, now.  This guy sure
sounded more sensible than any other doctor I had discussed my
weight problem with.
</P>
<P>
I had long suspected my problem was a lot more complicated
than a simple matter of "willpower".  For one thing, I'm one
of the most stubborn and willful people on the planet.  If I
really set my sights on something, I rarely fail to achieve my 
goal.  In fact weight loss was the only thing in my life I had
tried repeatedly and always failed to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
For another thing, I'm not stupid.  I knew intellectually 
that my eating habits were killing me.  I said that to myself 
time and time again as I raised another piece of pastry to my 
lips. "This thing will kill me."  Gulp.  Something just didn't 
add up.
</P>
<P>
Since about the age of six I've been a card carrying cynic,
so I realized that the Rivas ad could be another come on.  But 
I was getting desperate, and this WAS the first explanation of 
obesity I had seen that even came close to the way I felt about 
my problem.  I decided it was worth a look.
</P>
<P>
My "scam detector" went to yellow alert when the staff
person who gave me my initial appointment over the phone made 
a big deal about how much the first visit would cost and what 
forms of payment they accepted.  I kept the appointment anyway.
</P>
<P>
As soon as I opened the door to Dr. Rivas' office on 
Tuesday, October 12, 1995 I was slapped in the face by large 
signs proclaiming the "rate schedule" for various stages of the 
program and the "returned check fees" in effect.  Red alert!  
Still, I had come this far, and I remained desperate.  I might 
as well try the plan, or at least hear what the doctor had to 
say.  Even if this plan didn't work for me I might learn 
something which could be useful later.
</P>
<P>
So I spent half an hour filling out a thick sheaf of forms
detailing my medical history and promising not to hold Dr. 
Rivas personally responsible if the Washington Monument ever
caught fire.  Then came the moment of truth.  I weighed in at 
360.5 pounds according to their electronic scale.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Rivas spent about five minutes with me that day and
basically told me, "You need to lose that weight."  Duh.  I 
sure wish I had gone to medical school so that I could have 
figured that out!  Eventually I paid my money and received
two weeks worth of medication.
</P>
<P>
What the heck?  If the medication actually worked, the
rest of the nonsense wouldn't matter.  I waited until I was
safely at work before taking my first dose of medication.  It
had been decades since I last took prescription medication and
I didn't want to experience an adverse reaction while driving
on the Baltimore Beltway, the amateur demolition derby venue
which surrounds the city.
</P>
<P>
Phentermine and fenfluramine (commonly referred to as Phen/Fen) may 
not be amphetamines, but they sure speeded up my metabolism that night 
(I work evenings). A physical wreck, exhaustion had forced me to take a 
short nap at my desk nearly every night.  Not that night!  I was wide
awake, more so than I had been in a long time.  One interesting
thing, though - I made it through the entire evening without
hearing the siren call of the snack vending machines in the 
corner of the building.  It had been even longer since that had 
happened.
</P>
<P>
Sure enough, the blasted pills worked!  By following a low
fat diet and staying on the medication, I began to lose weight.
Sure, there were lapses, especially on my trip to Las Vegas 
and over the holidays.  But aside from those extra special
temptations, my weight was going down.  I didn't feel so tired
all the time, but I could go to sleep at the normal time every
night.  Side effects were limited to dry mouth, which I've 
always had anyway, so the added effect quickly faded into the 
background.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, April 16, 1996 I saw Dr. Rivas for my six
month checkup (I had seen nurse practitioners at a clinic
of the Rivas Weight Loss Program located much nearer my place
of employment during the intervening period).  I weighed in at
313.5 lbs, a loss of 47 pounds in six months.  I was off the
ibuprofen and my knees were healing.  I could walk around at
a normal pace without becoming winded after 50 feet.
</P>
<P>
I have dieted this long and this effectively before.  The
difference is in how I feel.  By the six month mark of previous
diets I was feeling good physically, but lousy mentally.  The
stress of resisting the constant urges to eat the wrong things,
in huge quantities, was getting to me.  Eventually I would eat
something I really shouldn't have.  Then my shattered willpower 
would collapse completely and it was off to the races (and the 
bakery) again.
</P>
<P>
Being a fallible human, I sometimes eat things I shouldn't while on 
this plan.  The difference is that I never even consider giving up.
I simply tell myself that I shouldn't do that again and keep right on
going with the plan.  Notice that I have never referred to the
Rivas plan as a diet.  That's because I don't even think of it
that way.  The medications I'm taking have allowed me to change 
my basic eating habits.  Quite frankly I eat nearly as much 
food as I did before (not counting the binges, of course).  I 
simply eat low fat food now, and I'm not left with the residual 
cravings for "bad food" that such actions saddled me with before 
starting on the medication.
</P>
<P>
Whenever someone notices you're losing weight they ask you
"what is your goal?"  This question confused me, and I wasn't
sure why.  Then it struck me - my goal is to make sure I don't
go back to the way I was!  I'm eating correctly, probably for
the first time in my life.  I will eventually lose the other
130 lbs or so I need to shed to reach a "normal weight" for my
height (5'7").  (Update: As of June 11, 1996 I was down to 300.5 lbs, 
for a loss of 60 lbs in 8 months.)
</P>
<P>
I'm not terribly concerned with how long all this takes, since I know 
that I'll get there eventually.  The critical thing is that I already 
feel good about myself in a way I never have.  The monkey is finally 
off my back, and in my case it was more like a gorilla.
</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/grph/davewbar.gif" ALT="______________________________">
</P>
<P>
If you are overweight and my story sounds even vaguely
like yours, this system is worth checking out.
</P>
<PRE>

              <I>If You're Fat, It's Not Your Fault</I>
             by Paul Rivas, M.D. and E.A. Tremblay
      ISBN 0-9647675-0-3    187 pages, hardcover   $19.95
               published by David-Paul Publishing
                               1205 York Road
                            Lutherville, MD. 21093
                                     USA
               to order, call: 1-800-247-6553


       You may contact Dr. Rivas directly at his office:

                 Rivas Medical Weight Loss Program
                         1205 York Road
                      Lutherville, MD. 21093
                          (410) 583-5677

        (Yes, the book does appear to be self-published.
           Who cares?  The information is worthwhile.)
</PRE>
<P>
Other information for overweight people:
<BR>
The Bariatric Society has a complete directory of U.S. 
bariatric physicians, state by state, and they will refer 
you to one if you call:  1-800-779-4833
</P>
<P>
USENET Newsgroup:  alt.support.obesity
</P>
<P>
World Wide Web Sites:
</P>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.loop.com/~bkrentzman/links/bzk.bookmarks.html">
Medical bookmarks, including several on obesity</A>
</P>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.loop.com/~bkrentzman/md/doctor.list.html">
List of U.S. bariatric specialists, by state</A>
</P>
<P>
<A HREF="http://pharminfo.com/pubs/msb/seroton.html">
An interesting report on Serotonin and Eating Disorders</A>
</P>
<P>
You can always do searches on words like "bariatric" or
"weight loss" in your favorite search engine. My favorite is 
<A HREF="http://www.altavista.digital.com/">Alta Vista</A>.
</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/grph/davewbar.gif" ALT="______________________________">
