</UL>
<CENTER>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/grph/davewbar.gif" ALT="______________________________">
</P>
<P>
Author's Addendum (July 18, 1996):<BR>
This review has garnered more feedback than any piece I've written 
in my career (which spans only four years, but I'm still amazed). 
Apparently more folks are interested in classic rock than I imagined.
I would like to publicly answer the main points that correspondents
have raised in e-mail:
<UL>
<LI>Apparently Rich Williams, the lead guitarist for Kansas, <i>is</i>
losing weight. This is excellent news!
<LI>It was not my intention to denigrate the violin playing of David
Ragsdale. The paragraph about Mr. Ragsdale still reads (to me) as a 
positive statement on his playing, which was intended. I love Robbie 
Steinhardt's playing, and basically equate Mr. Ragsdale's playing to
Robbie's.
<LI>No, I didn't care for Greg Robert's keyboard work on June 2nd. I 
did point out that what I heard may not represent the peak of his 
ability. One can only hope it doesn't. In any case his fans were most
eloquent in his defense, especially the gentleman who pointed out that 
Mr. Robert's keyboards are always "turned way down" in the studio and 
stage mix. I'm no musician, but this doesn't sound like the most
ringing testimonial for the man's contribution to the Kansas sound.
<LI>For those who think that classic rock fans are "wasting our time"
with "burned out artists" who are only "in it for the money" - why 
did you read this review in the first place? Allow those of us who
find meaning in old time rock to have our fun. Save your pity for
those people who haven't found any meaning in their lives. Sheesh!
</UL>
</P>
<P>
